<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS CHANGED, BUT DAVIS HASN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Away from a half-dozen or so pieces of pending
litigation and out of the eternal spotlight glaring off his curious
relationship with the rest of the NFL, Al Davis remains the most
single-minded of sports owners.
</P>
<P>
   He just wants his Raiders to win.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter where they win. It doesn't seem to matter how
anymore, either, and that's no small change. But there's no
mistaking: Davis still burns to win, to make the playoffs and find
that Super Bowl stage. Al Davis still wants to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since he has. The Los Angeles Raiders won
a Super Bowl in 1983 and contended the next two years. But since
1986, a span of two cities and 13 tumultuous seasons, the Raiders
have been to the playoffs just three times.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Oakland Raiders beat the dismal San Diego Chargers
17-10 to improve to 8-7, but their playoff hopes died out of town
with New England's win. Since separating from L.A. and launching
its second tour of the East Bay, the Raiders are 27-36 and have yet
to make the playoffs or post a winning season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Davis said Sunday. ``It's my life, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm looking for right now is a foundation. I think we've
got one here. We're doing some things well, things we can build on.
I thought we had a foundation back in 1993, I really did. You
remember. We were close. And I thought we had it turned around in
1995, too. Things happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have two more wins this season if we hadn't lost
(cornerback) Eric Allen (to a torn ACL). The defense alone would
have won us two more games.''
</P>
<P>
   On another day at another time, those comments could have
sounded as bitter as burnt coffee. Sunday, they sounded reflective,
like someone who has come to terms on matters which, in the past,
would have raised the blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room after the win, Davis wore an easy smile and
congratulated everyone. That was hardly the demeanor one would have
expected, say, five years ago in the same playoff-less
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Brown and Davis engaged in an animated, good-humor chat for
about 10 minutes, a fascinating thing to see since there were years
during the L.A. era when the two didn't say 10 words to each other.
</P>
<P>
   People who work for the Raiders say the organization recently
took a collective step back from its own reputation. After years of
turmoil and blown expectations, there was little to be arrogant
about.
</P>
<P>
   A fundamental change was needed, and the Raiders apparently got
it by hiring Jon Gruden as head coach. He's 35 and has cheeks pink
enough to get him carded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest change has been Gruden,'' said Brown. ``The
decline in penalties are all him. He won't take that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Gruden Raiders committed just three penalties, quite
a departure from the years (1994 and 1996) when the team averaged
almost 10 a game and set NFL records. On defense, the Gruden
Raiders play more base defense, smarter since the unit doesn't have
the star power of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the quarterbacks Gruden has had this year _ the lame
Jeff George, clipboard guy Donald Hollas and the ancient Wade
Wilson _ eight or nine wins is quite an achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always disappointing to not make the playoffs,'' said
Brown. ``If we win next week, we'll be 9-7 and improved five games
on last year (4-12). And a winning record is something that hasn't
been done around here since 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is always a relative term when it's the Raiders, of
course, and it wouldn't be a Raiders story if there were not some
speculation about their moving back to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Davis declined to discuss it, but he was interested in knowing a
grassroots letter-writing campaign is under way. Of the 60,716 in
Qualcomm on Sunday, about 20,000 of them were loud Raiders fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a shame,'' said Raiders chief exec Amy Trask,
``because if the Hollywood Park idea had been allowed to go
through, Los Angeles already would have a privately funded
stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. That's one of those pieces of litigation coming to a
courtroom near you. For now, L.A. remains unaffiliated, and Davis
still wants to just win. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
