<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE COMMIT TO PLAY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC continued to bolster its recruiting class as
kicker David Newberry and linebacker Chris Prosser committed to the
Trojans this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Newberry, a junior-college transfer from Corsicana, Texas, will
be a sophomore next season. Prosser (6-foot-2, 200 pounds) is from
Morse High School in San Diego, the alma mater of USC free safety
Rashard Cook.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have received 11 oral commitments. USC has received
commitments from defensive tackles Bernard Riley and Sagan Atuatasi
of Los Alamitos; linebacker Aaron Graham of Bakersfield; defensive
tackle Malcolm Woolridge of Boca Raton, Fla.; wide receiver Kareem
Kelly and defensive back Darrell Rideaux of Long Beach Poly; tight
end Jacob Rogers of Oxnard; offensive lineman Nate Steinbacher of
Anaheim Esperanza and linebacker Markus Steele of Long Beach City
College.
</P>
<P>
   USC also leads for two players close to making a decision:
offensive linemen Lenny Vandermade of Mater Dei and Courtney Morgan
of Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   This was the final recruiting weekend for the Trojans until they
return from the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Family affair: Linebacker Mark Cusano will be the most popular
Trojan at the Sun Bowl, with more than 20 relatives and friends
attending the game. Cusano grew up in The Colony, Texas, a suburb
of Dallas, but his mother's family lives about 30 minutes outside
El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're excited,'' Cusano said. ``They're all going to get to
see me play in person for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusano also has family coming from Dallas, but USC's appearance
in the Sun Bowl isn't as much of a break for them as one might
think. El Paso is actually closer to Los Angeles than Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to fly. They don't want to drive,'' Cusano said.
``It's a terrible drive. Once you get out of Dallas, there's
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMars returns: Defensive lineman Bobby DeMars of Westlake High
School resumed practicing after undergoing hernia surgery before
the UCLA game.
</P>
<P>
   DeMars practiced Saturday but quickly experienced pain and had
to rest. ``I wanted to come back slowly and then go full speed,''
DeMars said. ``But I came back too fast.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMars said he should be healthy for the Sun Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
