<HEADLINE>
HOW TO TEACH THE CHILDREN WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kids play sports. Kids need to learn the rules.
And kids love to watch videos.
</P>
<P>
   But who's kidding who? A plus B doesn't necessarily equal C.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to produce sports instructional tapes that hold
the attention of anyone under age 5 without including a stupid
purple dinosaur is as tough to make as one for someone older than
10 who won't be bored by something too simplistic.
</P>
<P>
   A new series of tapes with the ESPN label is worthy of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by Buena Vista Home Entertainment, the ESPN
Instructional series ($14.95 each) uses not just top-name athletes
and coaches on the box to sell the product, but ones who address
the audience without talking down to them. They find a way to
demonstrate the fundamentals and reinforce them with
easy-to-understand drills without giving in to elementary
entertainment devices.
</P>
<P>
   So, in this series, kids who want to improve will learn
something, and the adults who often find themselves thrust in as
coaches are shown the best way to go about teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Let's Play'' tapes include baseball (with Ozzie Smith),
soccer (with Mia Hamm, John Harkes and Zachary Ty Bryan), tennis
(with Tracy Austin, Fred Stolle and Cliff Drysdale) and skiing for
beginners (with Picabo Street, A.J. Kitt and Holly Flanders).
Basketball is demonstrated by Mike Krzyzewski, which can be a
little tedious for short attention spans. Maybe Dick Vitale would
have been a better choice.
</P>
<P>
   Younger kids can watch them over and over to absorb the
information and most of these tapes are in the 30-to-50 minute
range.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Teaching Kids'' series aimed at adults and older kids
includes the must-have basketball video (with John Wooden). There's
also football (with Bo Schembechler), tennis (with Nick
Bollettieri), golf (with Ben Sutton), swimming (with John Naber),
baseball (with Jerry Kindall), skiing (with Hank Kashiwa) and
bowling (with Gordon Vadakin). These run as long as 75 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Now the hard part _ tracking these gems down. The only reliable
option is a toll-free phone number (800-662-ESPN) since neither the
ESPN Store in Glendale nor the shopping area on the ESPN.com Web
site (http://store.espn.com/) are consistent with titles.
</P>
<P>
   The closest this series has to a roller hockey instructional
video is the NHLPA's Wayne Gretzky All-Star Hockey, which can be
ordered through 888-702-3776. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
