<HEADER>
A9768 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMTRAK-DERAILMENT-TEX     12-21 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-DERAILMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIN INVOLVED IN EARLIER FATALITY DERAILS IN NORTH TEXAS, 15 HURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRISTY GONZALES and MEDE NIX 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Amtrak's Texas Eagle, bound from Chicago to
Los Angeles with 199 holiday travelers, derailed near Six Flags
Over Texas in Arlington Sunday night, injuring at least 15 people.
</P>
<P>
   Nine cars of the 13-car train left the tracks about 7 p.m., 31/2
hours after the same train had hit and killed a deaf woman in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the 199 passengers were taken to area hospitals with
what were reported as minor injuries, and uninjured passengers were
evacuated to the Meadowbrook Recreation Center in Arlington, blocks
from the derailment. Later, the passengers were taken by Arlington
school buses to the Ramada Inn in downtown Fort Worth, where 175
rooms were reserved for them.
</P>
<P>
   John Wolf, an Amtrak spokesman in Washington, said Sunday night
there was no indication of what caused the derailment.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Railroad Administration and National Transportation
Safety Board are investigating. Union Pacific Railroad crews were
dispatched to help clear the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The train's silver cars sat crookedly off the tracks. Medical
crews stood by with stretchers, blankets and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Bionica Mullins, 16, walked out of the wreckage
carrying her baggage to a truck belonging to a friend who came to
pick her up. She was on her way to Fort Worth from Benton, Ark.,
when the train derailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just came off the track,'' she said. ``I was sitting there
and we felt a jerk and then it tipped over. I thought we were dead.
I was waiting the whole time for the thing to cave in. I held on. I
was still in the chair. It was dark, and everybody was
scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Brian O'Brien, who was headed to Tucson, Ariz., said
he had just finished dinner when he felt the train come to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the brakes hard,'' O'Brien said. ``You could feel him
put on the emergency brakes. It chattered a bit, and then you could
feel it go on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The derailment closed Division Street between Six Flags Drive
and Stadium Drive. Arlington fire Lt. Pat English said it may be up
to two days before Division is reopened while the wreckage is
cleared and investigators try to determine the derailment's cause.
Heavy equipment will be needed to clear wreckage, which also is
near power lines, English said.
</P>
<P>
   The superliner originated in Chicago, where passengers said an
electrical problem caused a 11/2-hour delay, and was headed for Los
Angeles via San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The speed limit was recently raised to 60 mph on the Union
Pacific tracks used by up to 25 trains a day through Arlington,
portions of Fort Worth and Grand Prairie in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Several passengers said the train was traveling very fast, but
English said the passenger train was going ``much slower'' than 60
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just had that two- or three-hour delay, so I figured he
was making up for lost time,'' said Bob Toney of Nappanee, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 injured were treated mostly for neck and back pain,
English said. One person was trapped in the train, but only because
a door was stuck, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been much, much worse,'' English said.
</P>
<P>
   Six people were taken to Dallas-Fort Worth Medical Center in
Grand Prairie. Six others went to Arlington Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours after the wreck, 150 passengers remained in
their seats on the train, as tow trucks and ambulances lined
Division Street.
</P>
<P>
   The same train ran over and killed a deaf woman earlier in the
day near Jim Miller Road and Redbud Street in Pleasant Grove, the
Dallas County Medical Examiner's Office said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Martinez, 33, was killed about 3:25 p.m. as she was
walking on the tracks, officials said. The death appeared to be
accidental, but an autopsy was not scheduled to be complete until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The train was delayed in Pleasant Grove for about three hours
for the medical examiner's investigation and to remove the woman's
body from beneath the train.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Autrey, Kimberly Durnan, Jeanne Graham and Angie
Summers contributed to this report, which includes material from
The Associated Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
