<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LANDS TOP RECRUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA capped its biggest recruiting weekend of the
season with five oral commitments, including two from players
considered among the best at their position in the state: Hart High
receiver Jerry Owens and Corona offensive lineman Shane Lehmann.
</P>
<P>
   Owens was so impressed with UCLA he plans to cancel visits to
Oregon, Ohio State, USC and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to take all my visits, but I got (to UCLA) and had
the feeling that this was something I needed to do,'' said Owens,
whose host for the weekend was freshman tailback DeShaun Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Owens topped UCLA's wish list at receiver, but don't count on
him stepping into the starting lineup next season because the
Bruins are loaded. Danny Farmer, Brad Melsby, Brian Poli-Dixon,
Freddie Mitchell, Jon Dubravac and Cody Joyce all return.
</P>
<P>
   If injuries strike, perhaps Owens will join the rotation. If
not, he has the option to redshirt, get stronger, recover from a
broken leg suffered in Hart's last regular-season game, and be
ready for 2000 with four years of eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches cannot comment on recruits until letters of intent are
signed Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Some recruiting analysts believe Owens is the state's best
receiver, while some prefer Long Beach Poly's Kareem Kelly, who has
committed to USC. But there's no doubt about Lehmann. He is
6-foot-5 and 280 pounds and chose UCLA over Notre Dame, Ohio State
and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA also received an oral commitment from Esperanza kicker Nate
Fikse, who will compete for Chris Sailer's vacant position with
current walk-on Chris Griffith. The Bruins are also in search of a
punter, since Sailer has performed both functions the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Bruins landed David and Matt Ball, twin defensive
ends from Dixon, a Sacramento suburb. The Balls are 6-5 and 230
pounds each and play with a controlled rage missing from the Webb
twins, Micah and Josh, who have not lived up to their billing in
the three years since they signed.
</P>
<P>
   Cal, Washington, Stanford and Oregon were recruiting the Balls.
</P>
<P>
   Where they stand: The weekend commitments increase UCLA's total
to nine. The others are Venice quarterback J.P. Losman, Temecula
safety Ryan Wikert, Anaheim linebacker Asi Faoa and Bakersfield
defensive lineman Rodney Leisle.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has 20 scholarships available.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell update: Mitchell's availability for the Rose Bowl
probably will be determined this week. He has made a breathtaking
recovery from a broken leg suffered at Houston on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mitchell had the second of two interlocking screws
removed from his left femur _ the stabilizing rod will remain for
the rest of his career _ and he recently ran the 40-yard dash in
5.3 seconds. If the time drops, as expected, he may be cleared to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The scholars: Sailer and center Shawn Stuart are among 35
players nationally who have been awarded $5,000 postgraduate
scholarships by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart, a sociology major from Saugus, had a 3.62 grade-point
average and currently attends graduate school. He has made the
director's honor roll (3.0 GPA or higher) in all 14 quarters at
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Sailer, from Burbank, is a communications major with a 3.32 GPA.
He has made the honor roll in eight of the last nine quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEWAY-HERO-LADN     12-21 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEWAY-HERO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN FACED OWN HORROR TO TRY TO SAVE A LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Slammed to a halt behind an exploding gas tanker
on the Ventura Freeway, 19-year-old Mike Daniel watched in horror
as fire snaked closer to a crashed Chevy Blazer. Trapped inside,
22-year-old Zaki Gordon screamed for help.
</P>
<P>
   Flames blazed 200 feet high and explosions sounded like gunfire.
Yet Daniel rushed into the inferno and tried to free Gordon, only
to find his legs pinned, his body immobile.
</P>
<P>
   As heat from the flames began to lick Daniel's face and arms, he
gave up hope and ran for safety. About four minutes after the
explosion, the flames engulfed the car with Gordon in it.
</P>
<P>
   For Daniel, with a past shaded by a juvenile record, that moment
Saturday afternoon on the freeway west of Los Angeles marked a
change of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be heavy into gangs and things like that when I was
younger,'' he said Sunday, from his home in suburban Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through that and see people getting killed, and
something like this happens and you try to save a life instead of
take one, it opens your mind to a whole different way.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Daniel gathered with his friends Keri Homan and Sito
Tupuola, who were with him Saturday, to come to grips with the
tragedy they had shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened all so quick,'' said Homan, who was driving
Saturday. ``Now that I think about it, I think we did everything we
can. The way that the Jeep was stuck, you would need the Jaws of
Life to get him out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel brooded over his inability to free Gordon from the
burning vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   When a firefighter who transported him to the hospital praised
his bravery, Daniel rejected the compliment.
</P>
<P>
   In the emergency room, he played the scene over and over,
reviewing rescue maneuvers he could have tried: He could have put
the truck in neutral and pushed it out of harm's way, he thought.
He could have gotten in the Blazer and loosened Gordon's wedged
legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so messed up because I thought I failed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, well, you did all you could. But you know what?
If I had been more aware of the situation, there could have been a
lot more done.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred when Gordon, entering the northbound Ventura
Freeway from the Lindero Canyon on-ramp, lost control of his
vehicle on the rain-slick roadway, the California Highway Patrol
reported.
</P>
<P>
   He swept into a Chevron gasoline tanker truck, which rolled on
its side and slid into the center divider. The Chevy Blazer landed
alongside it.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds after the crash, the rig exploded with a thunderous
boom, and gas gushed onto the freeway around Gordon's vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a bridge above us, and the flames were as huge as
that,'' Homan said. ``The flames ran across the whole entire
freeway.''
</P>
<P>
   Homan slowed to a stop about 20 feet before the crash site, and
leapt out with Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, John Legans, 48, of Lancaster, north of Los
Angeles, was taken to a hospital where he was treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   Zaki Gordon's brothers Yani, 11, and Adam, 14, leaped from the
sport-utility vehicle immediately, and Homan said she rushed over
to check their wounds. Both suffered minor injuries and were
treated at a hospital and released.
</P>
<P>
   But their older brother was pinned in the driver's seat, his
legs jammed by the crushed left side of the vehicle, Homan said.
</P>
<P>
   As he struggled to free himself, flames from the explosion were
spreading along the trail of spilled gasoline, creeping closer to
his vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor thing was trying to start the car after it was
crushed, to try and move it, because he saw the fire coming and he
couldn't do nothing about it,'' Homan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was scared, and then my friend Mike jumped in.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel lives with his grandparents and aspires to be a stuntman.
He's now looking for a job, he said. His current life, however, is
far from the one he left behind three years ago. Between ages 9 and
16, he said, he associated with gang members, and spent time in
juvenile hall. He renounced all gang connections at 16, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the problems of his past receded into the background
as he saw someone's life at stake and tried to save him.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel was airlifted to UCLA Medical Center and treated for
first-degree burns to his face and lungs, and second-degree burns
to his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   While he was unable to save Gordon's life, the experience opened
a new window in his own. ``I used to see things like that on the
news, and like well, truck blew up, that guy burned to death, well,
that happens,'' he said. ``But now it's a different thing. Wow,
that poor guy burned to death. His poor family. His holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel's grandmother, Joan DeHaven, acknowledges that the
incident gives her a shiver of fear when she imagines what might
have happened. But it's also testimony to how much he has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries me that he jumps in and does things without
thinking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said, ``I'm very proud of him. Not many people
jump into a burning car to try to help somebody. That's really
quite astounding that he did that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
