<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-49ERS-BO     12-21 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-49ERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE FIELD GOAL LIFTS PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The tumult of excited Patriots crashed onto
the playing field, amid a stadium of disbelieving fans who had
witnessed a fairy tale game led by the Wizard of Zo.
</P>
<P>
   Running contrary to the predictions of most prognosticators, the
Patriots defeated the San Francisco 49ers, 24-21, Sunday at Foxboro
Stadium. The unlikely win, combined with the Tennessee Oilers' loss
at Green Bay, lifted New England into the playoffs for the third
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   The game ball went to Scott Zolak. The inspiration for the win
went to Scott Zolak. The praise for leadership went to Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand,'' said receiver Shawn Jefferson, who
caught a 61-yard touchdown pass from Zolak in the second quarter.
``Zolak is a very confident player. He gives out that confidence in
practice and he gave it on the field today. When he was in the
huddle he kept clapping and said, `Let's go get 'em.' When the
quarterback is feeling that way, it spreads over to the whole team.
We rallied around him, there's no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers may not bear out Jefferson's comments. Zolak
completed 14 of 30 passes for 205 yards, two touchowns, and two
interceptions. He wasn't always sharp and could have had even more
interceptions, but that didn't matter. The fact is he made throws
when the Patriots needed them most. His passing led to the tying
touchdown in the fourth quarter, then he led a 23-yard drive that
set up Adam Vinatieri's winning 35-yard field goal with three
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw all that stuff on TV while I was watching the pregame
shows (Saturday) night, and some of the things being said really
pissed me off,'' said Zolak. ``When you hear all of that stuff, you
want to prove people wrong. That's the way I've always been.''
</P>
<P>
   If Zolak keeps it up, the Patriots may have even bigger
surprises ahead. He likely will lead the Patriots into the
Meadowlands to face Bill Parcells's New York Jets in a game that
may help determine whether New England will host a wild-card game
or if the AFC East champion Jets earn a first-round bye. Even with
a loss to the Jets, the Patriots could host a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   The win was emotional not only for Zolak and his teammates but
also for coach Pete Carroll, who was bypassed for the 49ers' head
coaching job two years ago after two years as their defensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big game for us to win. It's huge,'' said Carroll.
``The way we all stuck together and followed the game plan and
responded when we had so many players missing was remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak certainly had a lot of support. Rookie running back Robert
Edwards followed up his 196-yard effort against the St. Louis Rams
last week with 101 yards on 24 carries. He did some tough running
and, unlike last week, got the tough yards when they were needed.
And the offensive line pushed the 49ers around.
</P>
<P>
   The defense came up with big plays along the way _ big
fourth-quarter sacks by rookie Greg Spires and cornerback Steve
Israel as well as a fourth-quarter interception by Willie Clay,
which set the stage for the game-tying drive.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots trailing, 21-14, and 12:18 left, Clay got
things headed in the right direction by picking off a Steve Young
pass intended for Terrell Owens with a diving effort at the 49ers'
49-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game at that point called for someone to make a big play,
and I was in position to do it,'' said Clay.
</P>
<P>
   From there Zolak, methodically led the Patriots down field. He
completed a big third-and-17 play to Tony Simmons that went for 20
yards to the San Francisco 21. Moments later, Simmons made a
mistake when he caught a 13-yard pass on third down and went out of
bounds 2 yards short of the first-down marker.
</P>
<P>
   With 8:48 left, the Patriots decided to go for it on fourth
down. They came out in a shotgun and Zolak found Ben Coates for a
4-yard gain and a first down at the 9.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards did the rest, running up the middle for 4 yards, then
off Todd Rucci for 5 yards and the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last week, I wasn't about to be stopped there,'' said
Edwards, who was stopped on two series inside the 5-yard line in
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense responded from there, but after an Israel
sack forced a 49ers punt, San Francisco stiffened on defense as
well and got the ball back at its 11 with 3:29 left. Spires came up
with a huge play on a third-and-1, sacking Young for a 10-yard loss
that resulted in a punt and a 14-yard return by Troy Brown to the
49ers 41.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots took over with 1:48 remaining and stayed on the
ground with four running plays by Edwards and an important facemask
penalty by Winfred Tubbs, which put the ball at the 17. After Zolak
took a knee at the 18, Vinatieri, who had missed a 33-yarder in the
second quarter, nailed the winner.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, things looked bleak.
</P>
<P>
   On the final play of the half, the 49ers had botched a 40-yard
field goal attempt on a poor snap, but holder Ty Detmer, the backup
quarterback, gathered the ball and rolled to his left. Tight end
Irv Smith somehow got behind the Patriots' coverage into the end
zone, and Detmer hit him with a pass for 6 points and a 21-14 49ers
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers had tied it, 14-14, when Zolak threw a ball intended
for Coates that went into the arms of Tim McDonald, who ran it 18
yards to the Patriots 22. Three plays later, Young threw to a wide
open Owens for a 7-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots drew first blood, going 48 yards on six plays and
scoring on Zolak's 19-yard toss to Edwards, who got a big block
from Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   With 9:18 remaining in the second quarter, Young connected with
Jerry Rice on a short pass over the middle, and Rice beat Clay and
the rest of the Patriots secondary for a 75-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   But Zolak and the Patriots showed their resiliency _ and a deep
game of their own. Jefferson separated himself from defender Merton
Hanks at the 25, caught a Zolak long ball on the fly at the 15, and
went in for the 61-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn called that one. He told me, `I can beat him deep,' and
to watch for it, so I did,'' Zolak said. ``Shawn got free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
