<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9782 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SAINTS-AZR &LR;      12-21 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SAINTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKE'S LATE MAGIC KEEPS DREAMS ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Jake Plummer wasn't certain, but he thought he
saw a shadow of doubt on the faces of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Saints had just taken a one-point lead in the
closing 81 seconds of an emotion-charged, playoff-atmosphere battle
with the Cardinals, one that both teams needed to win Sunday to
keep postseason hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' fortunes appeared bleak when a holding penalty on
the kickoff return put the ball at their 8-yard line with 1:16 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the huddle and said to the guys, `I don't see the
look in your eyes,' '' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, as they had seven previous times since Plummer
became their quarterback last season, responded. Two passes to
Frank Sanders for 53 yards and a 21-yard scramble later, Plummer
positioned Chris Jacke to kick a 36-yard field goal as time
expired, giving the Cardinals a 19-17 win that vaults them to the
brink of their first playoff berth since moving to Arizona in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals (8-7) beat the San Diego Chargers (5-10) at Sun
Devil Stadium on Sunday in the season finale, the Cardinals are in.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of Plummer in late-game situations has been largely
responsible for their ascension from a four-win season in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being in that situation, although we've been in it
probably too many times,'' said Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Adrian Murrell became a 1,000-yard rusher for the
third straight season and the line did not allow a sack in 44
passing plays as the offense rolled to 513 total yards, the
Cardinals were in trouble late because they had scored in threes
rather than sevens.
</P>
<P>
   That left an injury-battered defense the chance to identify some
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Maddox, an eighth-year pro starting his third game at
middle linebacker in place of injured Ron McKinnon, made his first
career sack.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Sapp, a backup outside linebacker, forced a fumble on
another sack.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Wilson, who started in place of injured defensive tackle
Mark Smith, deflected a field goal. Wilson blocked one at
Washington on Nov. 22 that proved to be the difference in that
game, as well.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, the 318-pound Wilson, when describing his
vertical leap, quipped, ``I can dunk a doughnut.'' After this one,
Wilson said, ``Now I can dunk with two hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The big turning point, though, was a defensive stand early in
the fourth quarter after Murrell lost a fumble at the Arizona 18.
The Saints moved nine yards in three plays. On fourth-and-one,
Saints Coach Mike Ditka turned down a field-goal try that would
have tied the game at 13. Maddox, who was on three Super Bowl teams
at Buffalo, stuffed Aaron Craver for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had just gotten all the momentum with the sudden change,
and when that happens, we have to go make something happen quickly
to take it right back from them,'' Maddox said. ``Bernard and
Rashod (Swinger) did a good job tying up their guard and center,
and I got in scot-free. We just weren't going to let them get a
first down on us down there.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the Cardinals controlled the ball for more than
10 minutes in the first quarter with only 3 points to show for it,
until Jacke kicked his second straight game winner (his 32-yard
field goal beat Philadelphia in overtime Dec. 13), points were hard
to come by.
</P>
<P>
   The difference ultimately was that the Cardinals had Plummer and
the Saints didn't.
</P>
<P>
   And after this morning, the Cardinals are expected to have
Plummer, who is under contract through 1999, a lot longer. The
Cardinals have called a news conference and are expected to
announce a long-term extension. Plummer's agent, Leigh Steinberg,
was on the field after the game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to get it done tonight,'' Steinberg said. ``But I
don't think we're going to ask for a separate charter to take his
family to and from games.''
</P>
<P>
   If Plummer, who completed 32 of 44 passes for 394 yards,
continues to bail the Cardinals out of tight spots, team owner Bill
Bidwill might at least upgrade Plummer to first-class seating on
the new charter aircraft unveiled last week. After all, his
last-drive heroics assured the Cardinals of a non-losing season and
equaled the most wins they've had since they moved to the Valley.
If they beat San Diego, they will end the league's longest playoff
drought at 16 years and post their first winning record since going
9-7 in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   And while there were more than 20,000 empty seats in Sun Devil
Stadium for what many believed was the team's biggest game since
moving here, the crowd of 51,617 was strongly pro-Cardinals, which
often has not been the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you work for,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``I've
never liked having to depend on someone else do do things for me. I
like to carry my own weight. I want to get into the playoffs
because of what we do, not what someone else does.'' &QL; 
Staff writer Tim Tyers contributed to the report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
