<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-21 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, ZO GOOD FOR BACKUP QB TURNED STARTER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Only Zo knows.
</P>
<P>
   Drew can guess, but he doesn't know, because Drew is The Star
and the star simply cannot relate. Drew Bledsoe makes the big bucks
and gets all the headlines, and that's the way it should be since
he has the obvious God-given talent and the proven ability to win
games in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   So how could Drew know?
</P>
<P>
   How could Drew know what it's like to be 31 years old and be the
perennial backup quarterback to a man who has been both efficient
and amazingly durable? How could Drew know what it is like to go
through an entire season (1996) in which your two chances to play
consist of a game in which you throw one pass (completed) and one
in which you take three successive knees at the end of a 45-7 rout?
</P>
<P>
   How could Drew know what it's like to have gone more than three
full seasons without starting? How could Drew know what it's like
to walk the local streets knowing that people are pointing at you
and saying, ``Boy, I wish I had a cushy job like that guy has,'' or
``Drew Bledsoe's backup ... that's like being the Maytag
repairman,'' or ``Is that guy a football player or a football
watcher?'' or ``Hey, Zo, don't drop the clipboard, buddy''?
</P>
<P>
   No way Drew could know. Only some other team's Zo could know.
</P>
<P>
   Only another Zo somewhere in the National Football League could
relate to the satisfaction Scott Zolak felt Sunday afternoon when
he took the first snap, the last snap, and every Patriots snap in
between for a team whose dramatic and highly entertaining 24-21
victory over the San Francisco 49ers sent New England into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to the Super Bowl and did some other good
things,'' said Zolak, ``I was pretty much along for the ride. It's
nice to be able to put my stamp on one of these games. It was worth
staying around.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci said Zolak was as good as he
needed to be, but he was better than that. He was good, period. He
made a number of quality professional plays and he made one very
big play, airing it out for a 61-yard TD bomb to Shawn Jefferson
that let the Niners know he wasn't going to be some
pocket-protector nerdy custodian of perfunctory quarterback duties.
That pass let the San Francisco 49ers, and perhaps any future
Patriots opponents, know that Drew Bledsoe wasn't the only
legitimate professional quarterback in the organization's employ.
</P>
<P>
   This game was the textbook definition of pressure. If the
Patriots had lost _ even if they had lost, 50-47, in overtime _
where do you suppose the finger would have been pointed? This was
the biggest game of Scott Zolak's eight-year professional career.
It was a pass-fail exam, and he aced it; that's all there was to
it.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of happy fans in the doomed stadium Sunday
afternoon, but none more ecstatic than the occupant of Section 121,
Row 8, Seat 13. That would be his former high school coach, a Mr.
Paul Zolak, who, yes, also doubles as Scott Zolak's father. For the
past eight years the elder Zolak has attended every Patriots home
game, usually driving the 10 1/2 hours needed to make the trip from
his home outside of Pittsburgh. But for this game, one in which it
was certain that he would start, Scott Zolak had his dad flown in.
</P>
<P>
   And just as Drew could not know, neither could Mac Bledsoe,
another coaching dad, possibly know what it's been like to be Paul
Zolak, to come week after week, year after year, hoping to see your
son demonstrate his ability without wishing any harm to befall the
star quarterback who was making his son a career caddy. It would
have been one thing if Paul Zolak were just a cheerleading layman
of a father. But when you have coached the game, when, in fact, you
have coached a man some say was the Best Quarterback Ever _ does
the name Montana ring your chimes? _ and when you know enough about
the technicalities of the sport to know that your son really is a
capable professional quarterback, it cannot be easy to attend all
those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say I knew he could do this if he ever had a
chance to prepare,'' said Paul Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   With appropriate paternal pride, Paul Zolak ticked off some of
his son's long-ago accomplishments, starting with a title-winning
performance against Belle Vernon High School and concluding the
dissertation with a four-touchdown show that propelled the Maryland
Terrapins past hated Virginia and into the vaunted Poulan Weed
Eater Bowl (fabled in song and story). But with all deference to
the pair of Ws his son posted back in '92 (pre-Drew and pre-Tuna),
he had to acknowledge that what Scott did Sunday represented the
zenith of his professional career. Perhaps Zolak pere was confident
Zolak a fils could get the job done, but not everyone shared that
opinion, as Scott Zolak knew all too well.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe himself did his best to instill confidence, but there
was only so much anyone on the outside could do. This was not an
easy week. He was the center of unwelcome media attention, and he
did not sleep very well. He knew the stakes. He knew that if he
went onto the field and tossed out a stink bomb, his reputation
would never be salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   So how could anyone on this earth know what it felt like to be
Scott Zolak at approximately 4:10 Sundayafternoon, after he had
proven to the world and, most important, to the 44 players whose
fate he had held in his hands that he was someone they could rely
on?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about what Zo did today,'' saluted Chris
Slade. ``It is great to know you can lose your starting quarterback
and have someone come in and play the way he did today. We did not
lose a beat today with Zo in there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a great day to be Scott Zolak, but no one else knows how
great.
</P>
<P>
   Only Zo knows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
