<HEADER>
A9791 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-     12-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNT ON CARDS FOR THRILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The winner's locker room was quite a scene.
Cattle were mooing. Shepherds and wise men knelt in wonder around
the heaven-sent quarterback whose favorite receiver, Frank Sanders,
called ``an exciting little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bidwill bumped into a camel.
</P>
<P>
   Beaming like a new father, Bob Ferguson reached out and pumped
the hand of anyone and everyone, accepting congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't happened yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got one more,'' reminded Ferguson, vice president of
player personnel, after the Cardinals' 19-17 win over the New
Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   The most overdue team in professional sports still must beat the
San Diego Chargers at home Sunday in the last game of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cards (8-7) ``are'' going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they'll probably have three or four turnovers. Look for them
to blow a lead and fall behind late in the fourth quarter. Isn't it
always that way?
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer will come in and huddle the offense near his goal
line and take the team down the field, licking his fingers and
working his magic as he did again Sunday, when the Cardinals beat
the odds and the clock and kicked a 36-yard field goal on the last
play.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it is with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight and fight and fight. Finally, it pays off,'' Patrick
Sapp said. The backup linebacker grinned, exposing a gleaming row
of gold teeth. ``That's the story of our season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards are infuriating. Exasperating. Maddening.
</P>
<P>
   Delightfully entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   To my knowledge, not one fan has left Sun Devil Stadium this
season, after a win or a loss, and demanded a refund.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like ``this'' ticket, you don't like roller
coasters,'' said Dave McGinnis, the frazzled defensive coordinator.
``You hang onto the bar. Maybe it'll keep you in. Maybe it won't.
What a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   One more win.
</P>
<P>
   The blessed event is close now. The due date is almost here.
Cardinals fans must feel as if they're in the last week of an
11-year pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardiac Cards beat the Chargers, they will qualify for
the NFL playoffs for the first time since the team moved to the
Valley. The last time the franchise qualified for the postseason in
a non-strike year, Henry Hyde had dark hair. Monica Lewinsky was 1
year old.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they are going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are going to make the playoffs because their
quarterback is a leader and a winner. Ask Plummer how he does it,
how he scrambled for 21 yards on the game-winning drive, and he
shakes his head and gives a beats-me smile. ``Just playin' baby,''
he said. ``Just playin.' '' Just doing what comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   They're going to win because veterans like Aeneas Williams and
Larry Centers are determined to seize this long-dreamed-about
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, there was Centers catching a short pass,
then dropping his left hand to the ground to balance himself, then
running, weaving, legs churning like a bicyclist, and finally,
trying to hurdle a tackler for an extra yard.
</P>
<P>
   Centers worked as hard as Saints Coach Mike Ditka, who paced and
ranted, his jaw working furiously on a stick of chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   They are going to win because of young players like Pat Tillman.
To Tillman, the game of football is only a little more precious
than air. The rookie from Arizona State lost his job as starting
free safety a month ago. This week, Vince Tobin drew up a scheme
that placed Tillman in the thick of the action at middle
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like this?'' he asked McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hail, yes,'' his defensive coach said in his Texas drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman loved it. ``You should have seen his eyes light up,''
Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half, Tillman stood alongside McGinnis. ``Cub,
Cub,'' he said, whispering the code name for the alignment that
would get him off the sideline and into the game. The Cardinals
went to the formation in the second half. The Saints were caught by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Credit the coaching staff for finding a way to take advantage of
Tillman's aggressiveness. The Saints couldn't block him. All he did
was make plays.
</P>
<P>
   One more win.
</P>
<P>
   They should do it. Aeneas Williams looked around the locker room
and liked what he saw. ``We're getting close,'' he said, ``to what
I call harvest time.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
