A9797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      12-21 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKUP TALLAS GETS BACK UP AFTER LONG LAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He has won his last two games, earning a 5-4 overtime
victory over Washington and beating Tampa Bay, 4-1. Problem is,
those contests were eons ago. Backup netminder Rob Tallas, who has
a record of 3-2-0, a goals-against average of 1.85, and save
percentage of .926, hasn't set foot (or skate) in the Bruins' net
since Nov. 24. Because of the club's schedule, which had Boston
playing just nine games in the 25 days since Tallas's last start,
Byron Dafoe has had nearly all of the goaltending duties.
</P>
<P>
   But, with Tallas's unblemished record against the Tampa Bay
Lightning _ 4-0-0 for his career _ he will be back between the
pipes Monday night when the Bruins host Tampa at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be an easy assignment for Tallas. The Bruins are coming
off an emotional 4-1 win over the Stanley Cup champion Red Wings
Saturday and are subject to a letdown against the lowly Lightning.
Add to that the long layoff, and Tallas may be facing an uphill
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just basically stay positive,'' said Tallas, when asked how
he dealt with the idle time. ``You look around the league, and
other goalies are in the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   If truth be told, some backup goalies are in worse situations.
For example, former UMass-Lowell goalie Dwayne Roloson is the
backup in Buffalo behind warrior Dominik Hasek and has played just
60 minutes of a possible 1,583.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough but it's part of our job and you have to fight
through it,'' said Tallas. ``There was a time last year I got hurt
and then we had the Christmas holidays and I had about four weeks
off. I came back and got a shutout in the first game against
Washington, and you have to look back and be positive on that,
like, `You've done it before, you can do it again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a true challenge. We're coming off a high.
It's a Monday night crowd, and sometimes they're not the best. It's
a great challenge for me. I hope they come prepared and throw
everything my way and that I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas routinely is the last Bruin on the ice at practice,
getting in extra work.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Assistant coach) Bobby Francis has been great the last couple
of days,'' said Tallas. ``He told me you don't want to be playing
games too much after practice with the guys because you pick up bad
habits. Basically, relax and do some game situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby has always been great to me, even in Providence. I
respect him as a coach. When he tells me something, I totally
listen to him because he's right. He grew up with his father, Emile
Francis, the original Cat. Bobby knows what he's talking about; he
knows a lot about goaltending. (Saturday) we worked on game
situations, handling the puck. Sometimes you get away from that
because as the season goes on, the practices get shorter. In my
case, they have to get longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas has always been upbeat, but he said it has been difficult
to sit and watch every game, as he has the last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't deny it's frustrating because you really want to
feel like a part of the team,'' he said. ``You want to get out
there and prove something. You miss the excitement. We've got some
games coming up, and I just keep looking at that. I know what the
schedule reads in the future. I'm definitely always looking
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas said his frustration is mitigated by his strong
relationship with Dafoe. The two are friends and spend a lot of
time with each other, relating as only goaltenders can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for him,'' said Dafoe. ``I haven't really been in
that situation, so I can't know what is going through his mind. I
would love to play every game. I know it's not going to happen, but
as for Robbie, he's a very positive person and that's what is going
to keep him in this league for a long time. He works hard in
practice, and when he gets his opportunity, he takes advantage of
it. He is coming off two wins, let's not forget that, so he's on a
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tallas plans to keep that roll going Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not supposed to go in there and hit a home run,''
Tallas said. ``You just go in there to give your team a chance to
win. But me, I like to hit home runs. I like to go in and get a win
and do well and do everything right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
