</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ISLANDERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES MAKE MOST OF PIT STOP  
 TKACHUK'S FINAL-PERIOD GOAL BESTS ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Considering where the Coyotes have been and where
they're going, Sunday's game against the New York Islanders was
like an overnight stop at a businessman's hotel.
</P>
<P>
   You might say that all those clanging souvenir handbells that
were ringing non-stop at sold-out America West Arena were their
wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   After returning home from a four-game road trip, the Coyotes
stuck around long enough to stick it to the Islanders, 4-2, before
getting ready to head out of town again today for games at Detroit
on Tuesday and Chicago on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to finish these next two games and get back home
and play in front of our crowd,'' said Keith Tkachuk, who provided
the game winner for Phoenix on the power play by shuffling in Deron
Quint's shot toward net with 5:20 left to play. ``December's been a
tough month for us with all the travel, but I think we're battling
through and doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk apparently forgot that the Coyotes also must venture to
Los Angeles on Saturday _ their 11th time away from home in 13
games _ before returning to the Valley for a five-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Home has been good for the Coyotes (18-5-4), who pulled to
within three points of Dallas _ which has played two more games
than Phoenix _ for the best record in the league. Sunday's victory
ran the Coyotes' streak to 11 home games without a loss, which ties
a franchise record set in the 1983-84 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes haven't lost here since their opening-night 4-1
disaster against Ottawa. Since then, they're 10-0-1, haven't
allowed more than two goals in a single game and have outscored the
opposition, 37-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a big bonus for us,'' center Bob Corkum said.
``Especially when you get down to playoff time. If we can keep
streaks like this going, it's very imposing for other teams to come
in here and try to get a win when they know we haven't lost in so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Corkum sealed it for Phoenix with an empty-net goal shortly
after New York Coach Mike Milbury pulled goalie Tommy Salo for a
sixth attacker in the final frantic minute and a half.
</P>
<P>
   With a faceoff in front of Coyotes goalie Nikolai Khabibulin,
Islanders defenseman Eric Brewer lost the puck along the boards and
stumbled, allowing Corkum to race down the wing for the clinching
score with 31 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a wheel,'' said Brewer, who had tied the score at 2
with his third goal of the season midway through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Adams had a goal and an assist for the Coyotes, who also
got a goal from second-year pro Juha Ylonen, just his second of the
season and the third of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Mark Lawrence had a goal and an assist for the Islanders
in his 10th NHL game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game started out like the best of my life and ended as
the worst,'' Lawrence said. ``We had a lot of chances tonight and
didn't capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as many chances as the Coyotes, who had 34 shots and
seemingly could have racked up seven or eight goals had Salo not
stoned them on a few can't-miss attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their goaltender played real well,'' Quint said. ``It's a
different style than what we've seen. He comes out a lot and
challenges you. We didn't make many passes by him, so we kept
shooting it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes scored twice on the power play after an 0-for-15
stretch and failing to score with the man advantage on their recent
four-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Schoenfeld likened Sunday's pit stop to another road
game, a hockey one-night-stand, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost ``is'' like another road game,'' Schoenfeld said,
``when you only come back for one after playing games out East.
You're back for one game, and we're leaving again in the morning
for Detroit. It isn't like a home game where you get acclimated.
You're in town and out of town, so this was just like another road
game, which all of December pretty much has been.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
