<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES FELLED BY FEARSOME SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's been called the scariest shot in hockey. St.
Louis Blues defenseman &UR; Al MacInnis has a slap shot that's been
clocked at over 100 mph.  &UR; Mike Sullivan, the Coyotes' checking line
left wing, felt it Thursday night in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   A MacInnis blast hit his left skate so hard during the Coyotes'
3-2 loss that it broke Sullivan's big toe, forcing him to miss
Sunday's game against the New York Islanders, as well as upcoming
games at Detroit, Chicago and Los Angeles. He will be out anywhere
from a week to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an awfully hard shot,'' Sullivan said after the
Coyotes' 4-2 win over New York. ``I played the rest of the game and
it got progressively sorer and sorer, but I didn't know it was
broke. He's got one of the hardest shots in the league, and you
have a tendency to try and get to him faster (to block a shot)
because he poses such a threat to you.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of other Phoenix players found themselves in the way of
MacInnis slap shots Thursday, including  &UR; Dallas Drake, the right
wing on the team's No. 1 line. Drake played Sunday against New
York, but the shot he took in the foot likely will put him in a
walking cast off the ice while he continues to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a little,'' Drake said, ``but I didn't get it as bad
as Sully did.'' &QL; 
On the mend
</P>
<P>
   After missing two games because of a nagging groin injury,
 &UR; Keith
 &UR; Tkachuk returned to the Coyotes lineup and scored the game-winning
goal with 5:20 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great. My groin's much better. It just takes some time
to get into it, but I felt pretty good out there,'' said Tkachuk,
who netted his team-leading 16th goal. ``Obviously, at the end, it
gets a little tiring. But a couple more practices, a couple more
games . . . it feels almost like not being in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk missed camp this summer because of a holdout. It took
him a week or so, he said, before he got his legs under him. &QL; 
Ringing in the season
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes teamed up with the Salvation Army in an effort to
set a Guinness world record during the second intermission of
Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the sellout crowd of 16,210 purchased $2 holiday
hand bells and then, under the direction of Surf Dog recording
artist Gary Hoey, performed _ supposedly _ the world's largest hand
bell choir to the tune of ``Silver Bells,'' which originally was
written for the Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   According to a news release, there had to be at least 1,000
bells ringing to qualify for a record. &QL; 
Slap shots
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rick Tocchet had to be pulled away from Islanders goalie  &UR; Tommy
Salo after the two started yapping at each other during the first
period. Tkachuk then barged in and had a few choice words for Salo
before also getting led away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did something to Rick, that's why I came in,''
Tkachuk said. ``Usually, it's the other way around. Rick always
comes in there for me, so I wanted to come in there for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Right wing  &UR; Shane Doan was back in the lineup after missing
Thursday's game in St. Louis to be with his wife,  &UR; Andrea, who
delivered the couple's first child early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Doan couldn't get back to Phoenix in time for the birth of
7-pound, 3-ounce daughter  &UR; Gracie Shea, however.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he just missed scoring his first goal of the season.
He is the only forward on the team, other than  &UR; Louie DeBrusk, who
has appeared in just one game, without a goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
