<HEADER>
A9814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     12-21 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL STILL HASN'T WON OVER EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The coach was feeling his oats Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His team had just won the biggest game of the year when it was
outmanned and seemingly outgunned and had reached the playoffs for
the second straight season. Pete Carroll was feeling flush.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he believes in _ democracy in the locker room and the
players assuming responsibility for their team's future _ had
played out for him Sunday. Or so he thought, at least.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, they had been throttled by a team they should have
beaten even if the team plane had crashed on the way to St. Louis,
but this was a different week and a different team. While some see
that teeter-totter effect as a bad sign, Sunday all Pete Carroll
saw was a band of wounded warriors ambushing one of the best teams
around.
</P>
<P>
   He saw his team, the Patriots, hanging (as he would put it) and
hanging and hanging until they finally hung a 24-21 defeat on the
San Francisco 49ers. It was a win that when coupled with a loss by
the Tennessee Oilers put New England back in the playoffs. It was a
win that Carroll seemed to believe made a statement not only about
his team but also about himself and his methods.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two years, Carroll has felt that the local media has
been unfair to him. He complained last week to a West Coast
reporter that he has been unfairly labeled ``a California surfer''
even though he has never been on a surfboard in his life. Fact is,
no one in New England has ever said he has been, but let's not let
the facts get in the way of a pretty good line.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, that's the way Carroll sees it and so it has become
reality in his mind, just as the dark specter of the man he must
coach against next Sunday has stalked him from the shadows and will
continue to until his team does something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big win but until Pete beats the Jets ...''
linebacker Chris Slade said Sunday without finishing the thought.
He didn't have to finish it, because in New England the Jets mean
Bill Parcells and Bill Parcells means a headache for Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   That pudgy migraine exists in Carroll's head in part because he
feels that for the past two years his methods have been unfairly
compared to Parcells's by many in the media. He feels no one here
is capable of understanding his approach to football. We are
ignorant and he is smart and one day we'll all understand, but not
until it is as plain as the nose on Paula Jones's face. Until then
we must suffer in our ignorance and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When are you going to figure it out?'' Carroll asked Sunday,
less than an hour after his team's biggest win of the season.
``When are you going to figure out there's more than one way to do
this? The problem is with you, not me.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't saying that a week ago in St. Louis, of course, when
the Rams nearly butted his team out of the playoffs. But that was
last week and this was today and today had produced a big win by a
team that had rallied around him. So it was time to make his point,
which apparently is that it is not only Congress that needs to
develop a new sense of civility and open-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't say enough about the collective effort by so many
people to get this thing done,'' Carroll said. ``It took a bunch of
players that just wouldn't say die, that wouldn't listen to all of
the talk that they didn't have a chance against a great football
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about seeing people hang together and stay
with the coaches and believe in the coaches and believe in the game
plan and put it to work and make it come through and be successful.
I just can't say enough about the fact that it was a collective
effort by so many people to get this thing done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big win. That's a fine, fine football team (the
49ers) and they're hot. I'm darn proud of this whole thing today.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he was. He was proud his team had overcome injuries to
defensive end Willie McGinest, linebacker Ted Johnson, fullback
Tony Carter, quarterback Drew Bledsoe, and wide receiver Terry
Glenn. He was proud he had found a way to convince his team it was
still alive when it had good reason to feel otherwise with so many
of its top players in jeans and windbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   He felt proud that his methods had been vindicated against a
team he grew up cheering for, a team he once had coached, a team
that had chosen someone else to be its boss when he thought of
himself as a logical successor to George Seifert two years ago.
Proud to be alive for another couple of weeks, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' said Patriots cornerback Steve Israel.
``Pete has lived the Walton, John Boy, Wonder Years (life). He's
lived the picture perfect career. He grew up in San Francisco. He
cheered and rooted for the Niners. He got an opportunity to coach
for them. Then he comes here in a big game and we knock them off. I
mean, what more can you ask for?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, complete acceptance of his methods by the skeptical,
for one. It was not enough Sunday for Pete Carroll's team to win.
It was not even enough to have it coupled with an Oilers loss that
put the Patriots back into the playoffs. Carroll needed more than
that. He needed acknowledgment from those he perceives as unfair
critics that his ideas will play here in the Northeast, where
everything seems unnecessarily harsh to him.
</P>
<P>
   He needed acceptance that his way is the true way, or at least
an acceptable way, to long-term success in the NFL. A win over the
49ers was enough to get that team into postseason play, but it
wasn't enough to give him that acceptance because it is still a
long walk from 9-6 to Miami on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   A long walk to prove that democracy and good cheer are enough to
lead a team to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   What went on Sunday at Foxboro Stadium was something Pete
Carroll had every right to be proud of, as did his team. But before
he talks too much about that he should remember this Biblical
admonition:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pride cometh before a fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
