u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-     12-21 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS'S BIG GAIN: CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A smile crossed Robert Edwards's face, a
rare smile in front of the media, when he was reminded that a
certain other running back from the University of Georgia had
received virtually all the running back publicity before Sunday's
Patriots-49ers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we don't rub noses too much, me and Garrison,'' said
Edwards when asked if this victory was sweeter because it was
Edwards _ and not Hearst _ who made the key runs in the final
minutes to put his team in position to win. ``I had a good game,
Garrison had a good game, and we really don't compete to see who
had the best game.''
</P>
<P>
   But at game's end, when plays had to be made, it was Edwards who
made them. ``I've grown a lot as a runner in the last two weeks,''
said the rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Edwards appears much more confident, no longer thinking
first, last, and foremost of simply not fumbling the ball, but
instead focusing on reading his blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards made three late runs that were huge for the Patriots,
especially considering that their two most feared offensive
weapons, Drew Bledsoe and Terry Glenn, were out of the lineup. In
the final quarter, San Francisco and New England had virtually the
same offensive philosophy _ the 49ers gave the ball to Hearst, and
the Patriots gave the ball to Edwards. Time and again.
</P>
<P>
   It was Edwards who came through, first when the Patriots faced a
first-and-goal at the Niners 9-yard line with eight minutes to
play. Edwards gained 4 yards, setting up a situation that New
England's players, coaches, and fans knew all too well: Just last
week in St. Louis, Edwards and the Patriots had the ball inside the
5 and failed to get it into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down on ourselves for not scoring there last week,''
said Edwards. ``I know when the ball gets down that close, I should
be able to score, and I didn't. I didn't want that to happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Edwards's number was called on the second-down play, ``I
knew we had to have it. When I heard my number, the first thing I
was thinking was, `Don't fumble the ball,' and then I was thinking,
`Just get it in.'''
</P>
<P>
   The much-maligned offensive line did its part, ``and I had a big
lane to run through,'' said Edwards, who finished with 101 yards on
24 carries and broke the 1,000-yard mark (1,068) for the season.
The rookie has had to learn many lessons this year about running a
football in the NFL, but he has not had to learn what to do when
he's near the goal line _ he has an instinct for getting into the
end zone, the St. Louis game the glaring exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to score,'' said Edwards. Which he did, slicing
through the middle of a pliant San Francisco defense and lunging
the final _ and most important _ yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had that slump at midseason, it was all my fault,''
said Edwards. ``I wasn't reading (blocks) the way I should. But
I've learned what to do with my first read and then my second
read.'' And the result, said Patriots coach Pete Carroll, is that
he has become a back ``who ran like a warrior.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in St. Louis, when Edwards gained 196 yards, ``he had
a breakout week in terms of just being productive,'' said Carroll.
``But you noticed in practice this week there was a difference, and
I know it's just having confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was not finished running, however, because the game was
only tied. After the New England defense stifled the strangely
conservative San Francisco offense and the Patriots took over on
the 49ers 41 with 1:48 left, it was Edwards who carried the ball
into Adam Vinatieri's kicking range.
</P>
<P>
   On first down, Edwards gained 10 yards. Then he gained 3 more.
But his biggest run of the game came two plays later, when New
England faced a third-and-6 at the 27 with 23 seconds left, a
lengthy field goal attempt facing Vinatieri if Edwards did not come
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were trying to run the clock down for a field
goal,'' said the rookie, ``but I knew we had to make some more
yards.''
</P>
<P>
   So Edwards circled right end and gained 5 yards. Five more were
added on after linebacker Winfred Tubbs was flagged for grabbing
Edwards's face mask. Vinatieri was in prime position for the
winning kick.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was over, Robert Edwards and Garrison Hearst met
at midfield, two former Georgia running backs congratulating each
other for a game well played.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we talked about getting together after the season for more
workouts,'' said Edwards, who usually does not say much, but might
have something more to say when the two are back in Athens, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
