<HEADER>
A9816 &Cx1f; tth-z
r S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      12-21 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS RALLY, BUT MISS PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Before Sunday's game was three plays old, the Seahawks
had been eliminated from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They proceeded to make the Indianapolis Colts look like a
playoff team, falling behind by 13 points after three quarters at
the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Seahawks shook off the disappointment of being
eliminated from the postseason for the 10th straight year _ this
time because the New England Patriots had upset the San Francisco
49ers earlier in the day _ and surged past the Colts with 17
fourth-quarter points. The 27-23 victory marked the first time this
season they rallied to win after trailing going into the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way everybody fought to come back, that was impressive _
especially knowing the situation,'' running back Ricky Watters said
after running for a career-best 178 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Watters got the rally rolling, scoring on a 33-yard romp through
the Colts' defense that looked more like a slalom run the way he
juked, jived, eluded and finally stiff-armed would-be tacklers to
cut the Colts' lead to 23-17 with 9:19 left to play. Watters also
had a 38-yard run that set up a 30-yard field goal by Todd Peterson
with 1:57 left to give the Seahawks their final margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Pro Bowl cornerback Shawn Springs scooped up a
Marshall Faulk fumble that was forced by defensive end Phillip
Daniels and returned it 14 yards for a TD that gave the Seahawks a
24-23 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Seahawks' big-play defense withstood four throws
by rookie quarterback Peyton Manning into the end zone from the
Seattle 7-yard line to ice the win. Cornerback Willie Williams
tipped away Manning's first-down pass that was intended for E.G.
Green. Strong safety Jay Bellamy tipped Manning's second pass meant
for Ken Dilger and free safety Darryl Williams made sure the Colts'
tight end did not catch it by blasting him from behind just as the
ball arrived. Daniels hurried Manning into an incompletion on third
down. Manning's fourth-down throw to Torrance Small at the back for
the end zone was too long.
</P>
<P>
   As Watters said, everybody contributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the best game that we played,'' coach Dennis
Erickson said, ``but those guys fought to the end. There were
plenty of times in the fourth quarter when they could have hung it
up, but we just kept hanging in there, making plays and we ended up
winning a football game.''
</P>
<P>
   His players said they will give no less effort in Sunday's
season finale against the 13-1 Broncos in Denver. They will be
playing for pride, and probably under Erickson for the last time.
Despite being eliminated from the playoffs, the now 8-7 Seahawks
can post their first winning season since 1990 by upsetting the
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   It is less than what the Seahawks were expecting after they
loaded up on free-agent talent for the second consecutive offseason
and then started the season with three easy victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully when it's all said and done, we'll finish up at
9-7,'' linebacker Chad Brown said. ``You play every year for the
playoffs, but when you let it slip away like we did, the way we
came back is refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the game, the Seahawks appeared stale.
</P>
<P>
   The offense was having trouble moving the ball with any
consistency against a Colts' defense that ranked 28th in the league
and had surrendered at least 26 points in seven of its past nine
games.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, meanwhile, did a masterful job bottling up Marshall
Faulk, limiting the Colts' Pro Bowl running back to 19 yards on 13
carries. But Manning was something else. He completed 23 of 39
passes for 335 yards, spreading the ball to fellow rookie and
former Washington Husky Jerome Pathon (six catches for 66 yards),
Dilger (4 for 61), Small (3 for 120) and Green (3 for 52).
</P>
<P>
   That's how a Colts team that had won only three of its first 14
games came precariously close to pulling out this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of our main problem all year,'' Manning said
about blowing a fourth-quarter lead for the fourth time. ``In this
case, we jumped up on them in the second half and thought we had a
good lead ... . But we let it slip right out of hands. It's
extremely frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Seahawks used some monster plays from the oldest
Seahawk and one of the youngest to rip this one from the Colts'
clutches.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to Watters' TD run would not have happened if
quarterback Jon Kitna, making his fourth start this season, had not
scrambled for 17 yards on third-and-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Erickson said, ``was a huge play.''
</P>
<P>
   So was the 16-yard catch Brian Blades made two plays later.
Blades is in his 11th season and the only player left from the last
time the Seahawks were a playoff team _ 1988, his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive to Peterson's field goal, Kitna and Blades hooked
up again for an 11-yard gain on third-and-11. Watters' 38-yard run
came on the next play. Peterson's field goal came five plays later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody stepped up their games today,'' said Kitna,
who completed 16 of 29 passes for 177 yards and is now 3-1 in his
stint as the starter since replacing Warren Moon. ``Everybody did
their part today.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody except the 49ers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
