<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, PATRIOTS FANS HAVE REASON TO BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ So after six months, 20 games (including
preseason), 101 trips to the hospital, a couple of court
appearances, an answered prayer, the rise of the Tuna in New
Jersey, and the announcement that they are leaving town, it is
official: The New England Patriots are going to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots Sunday beat the vaunted San Francisco 49ers, 24-21,
on a closing-seconds field goal by Adam Vinatieri. With almost a
half ton of high-priced meat sitting on the sideline (Drew Bledsoe,
Ted Johnson, Terry Glenn, Willie McGinest), New England rallied
'round backup quarterback Scott Zolak and defeated the perennial
Super Bowl contenders.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time in five weeks that the Patriots beat a
quality team (Miami, Buffalo, Pittsburgh, San Francisco), and the
third straight last-minute home win for the Future Hartfords.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the I-84 Pats are the feel-good story of our Christmas
week. They were impeached by the local media and many of their own
fans, but they have survived their trials on the field. Beaten
down, ridiculed, counted out, the Patriots are going to the
playoffs. Not only that, but if Miami loses Monday night against
Denver or next week at Atlanta and the Patriots find a way to beat
the Jets Sunday, New England actually will host a playoff game
after New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how proud I am,'' said Daddy Pete Carroll,
who took home the game ball. ``We're real pleased that this has
come out of our season after all we've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll had reason to gloat. Most of us were calling for his
head when the Patriots staggered to 5-5 at mid-November, and his
wounded team was given little chance Sunday against the hot 49ers.
Let's not forget that northern California is home to Daddy Pete and
he did his best work as defensive coordinator of these 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't listen to all this talk that we didn't have a
chance against a great football team,'' said Carroll. ``This is
just getting the job done. It is great to beat these guys ... just
because it's home and it means so much. I can't tell you how proud
I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who was reduced to a clipboard-carrying Edward
Scissorhands, said, ``It's a great feeling. We've been through a
lot of stuff. Injuries. Setbacks. And now here we are _ we've got a
shot. We've just got a lot of guys that have a lot of heart.
Everybody counted us out. I don't think many people gave us a
chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The midseason slump, coupled with owner Bob Kraft's
intended defection to the suburbs of New York, soured New England
on this team. The Great Recovery started on ``Monday Night
Football'' against the Dolphins and continued (with an interruption
at St. Louis last week) through the final shopping weekend before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose Sunday, there was a high likelihood of a playoff
berth, but few fans wanted to wade into the postseason with an 8-8
record, a three-game losing streak, and a raft of players in the
infirmary.
</P>
<P>
   But everything changed with the victory over the 49ers. It still
seems unlikely New England will meet Denver for the AFC
Championship, but Sunday's victory gives our region's sports fans
something to follow at least into early January. (That ought to
hold you until pitchers, catchers, and peanut vendors report in
mid-February.)
</P>
<P>
   Winning with Zo gave this one extra meaning. Zolak would
probably be voted Most Popular and Class Clown if the Patriots
produced a high school yearbook, but he needed to remind his
teammates and the fandom that he is more than a stage-diving quote
machine. Now he can go into next week and maybe into free agency
with a win over the 49ers under his belt. He was 14 of 30 for 205
yards, including a 61-yard touchdown to Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was riled up, and other guys could feel that energy,'' said
Jefferson. Zo was riled up, and now Patriot Nation goes into the
holidays with a reason to believe in the hometown team again. With
any luck, there might even be one more traffic jam on Route 1
before the season is over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
