<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-JACKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET TALK ABOUT UNLUCKY NUMBER  
 JACKE COMBINES 13 WITH SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Maybe Chris Jacke has figured out this Cardinals
Jinx.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the number 13 is supposed to be bad luck. But that's
for those who otherwise have good luck. It only figures to be good
luck for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   And darned if it wasn't Sunday in a heart-thumping, 19-17
Arizona victory over the New Orleans Saints at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jacke, the Cardinals' interim place-kicker, wears No. 13 on his
jersey. And Sunday he hit the 13th game-winning field goal of his
career, this one from 36 yards out as time expired, to keep the
Cardinals' playoff heart beating.
</P>
<P>
   The former Green Bay Packer has been with the Cardinals for only
three weeks, and he has hit two game-winning field goals in the
past two games. Last week in Philadelphia, he missed one in
regulation but made up for it by winning the game in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost the identical kick,'' Jacke said. ``I think it was 35
this week (it was 36), and last week it was 36, the one we missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's probably why they brought me in here. They
brought me in knowing that I've been in this situation before.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all his experience, Jacke admitted that he was a little
shaky after quarterback Jake Plummer drove the Cardinals from their
own 10 to the New Orleans 19 to put Jacke in the middle of the
field for the decisive kick.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Saints called a timeout to ``ice'' Jacke. This
guy kicked in Green Bay. Ice is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everybody else, I was a little excited,'' Jacke said.
``Two weeks in a row we're going to kick game-winning field goals.
(The timeout) helped me calm down a little, get my spot prepared,
and I thought I kicked the ball as well as I have since I've been
here.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know exactly it was perfect, but he had that gut
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I hit it well. Now, whether it was going straight, I
had to look up and check,'' he said. ``I looked up, and it was
going straight. I usually don't hook the ball or fade a ball too
badly, so it was pretty much down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   And nobody in the stadium was any happier about it than the guy
on crutches with a brace on his surgically repaired left knee. That
would be Joe Nedney, who started the season as the club's kicker
and suffered a season-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, my situation is that I'm just trying to be the
biggest Cardinals fan anybody can be and really root my butt off
for those guys,'' Nedney said. ``It's out of my hands, and that's
all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is a very surreal feeling standing there watching Chris
Jacke hit two game-winning field goals in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, however, that without Nedney's similar
game-winning heroics in a 17-15 victory at Detroit and a 29-27
defeat of Washington at Sun Devil Stadium, Jacke's kicks wouldn't
mean a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just good to see this team with one game left to clinch a
wild card,'' Nedney said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
