<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ER PLAY CALLS DON'T GET PASSING GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The game was over. An NFL scout and a
television analyst sat side by side at the back of the press box,
shaking their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``Can you tell me what the San Francisco game plan was?
What were they trying to do out there?''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst: ``Looked like they were trying to run themselves into
third-down situations so Young could get sacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Scout: ``I'm befuddled.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst: ``Beats me.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of the day, when it was all over and the Patriots
had beaten San Francisco, was: What were the 49ers thinking about?
</P>
<P>
   Against a team that gives up more first downs to the pass than
just about any team in the league, the Niners ran 34 times and
threw the ball just 24 times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, San Francisco racked up 292 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   An average of 8 yards per pass attempt is considered
outstanding. The Niners were averaging 12 yards per pass, and still
didn't want to throw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we could run the ball,'' said 49ers coach Steve
Mariucci, whose play selection frustrated quarterback Steve Young.
``We had success with the run, but in the fourth quarter they
stopped us. But we had our chances to put the game away before that
and we didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into the fourth period, the Niners led, 21-14. To this
point, they had dominated the statistics, gaining 400 yards to 223
for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   However, that completely reversed in the final quarter, as the
Patriots outscored the 49ers, 10-0, and outgained them, 109-10.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. After gaining 400 net yards through three periods,
San Francisco died in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the last nine San Francisco offensive plays: run, no
gain; run, no gain; pass, interception; run, 2 yards; run, 3 yards;
pass attempt, sack minus-10 yards; run, 7 yards; run, 2 yards; pass
attempt, sack minus-10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And on the last play, Young hurt his knee, ending what had to be
one of the most frustrating games of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Young wanted to attack New England in the air. Time and again,
after his team ran for short yardage on first and second down, he
looked to the bench and motioned for his coaches to call a play
that would go up field.
</P>
<P>
   Young's body language told the story. Many times he stood with
hands on hips, shaking his head in disbelief after short runs, or
looking skyward for some divine guidance. None came.
</P>
<P>
   The favored Niners gave the Patriots a chance to win, and New
England took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we could run the ball against them,'' said backup
quarterback Ty Detmer, who threw a 27-yard touchdown pass just
before the half on a muffed field goal attempt, giving his team a
21-14 lead that looked like it might hold up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did run it against them, but it seemed that when we got to
the red zone we bogged down and couldn't get it in. That's not like
us. We usually get it in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Niners admitted they underestimated the ability of Scott
Zolak. ``We knew we were going to play a backup quarterback,'' said
linebacker Ken Norton. ``We thought they would try to run the ball
a lot to help him out, and then throw the ball short. But he
surprised us with that bomb (a 61-yard scoring throw to Shawn
Jefferson in the second period). After that we backed up a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a pretty good job on defense against them until the
fourth quarter. Then they made some plays on us and ran the ball to
the outside better than I thought they could.''
</P>
<P>
   All the credit belongs to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak played tough when it counted. He threw two interceptions,
but he did enough to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, with the game on the line, he was stout.
He completed 14 of 30 passes on the day, but in the fourth period
he was 5 of 7, throwing for first downs on a third-and-17 and a
fourth-and-2 with the rush right in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to blitz him in passing situations, but we didn't
get any pressure on him. Their offense did a good job of picking us
up,'' said Norton.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots offensive line did a terrific job. Zolak was sacked
just once, and that was more of a coverage sack than a breakdown in
front of him. And the Patriots were able to run the ball 31 times
for 132 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, San Francisco played a very dumb game. Four times the
49ers had to call timeouts to cover mistakes. (Three times they
didn't have enough men on the field; another time their tight end
didn't know the play.)
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, they threw just twice on 13 first-down
plays.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Young found himself in third-down passing
situations, with the Patriots blitzing him and not enough blockers
to account for the rushers. He was sacked five times and didn't
have a single yard rushing. Not once did he elude would-be rushers
as he has so well in the past, establishing himself as one of the
greatest running quarterbacks of all-time. The Patriots kept him in
the pocket and banged him around.
</P>
<P>
   Young was 13 for 15 passing in the first half, and yet his
coaches called for just eight passes in the second half, when his
team was shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play at home, we are a great football team,'' said
Mariucci. ``Away, we don't know how to win. And you can't be a
great team unless you can win on the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
