<HEADLINE>
MURELL GAINS 1,000 WITH UNLIKELY HELPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Adrian Murrell got his 1,000-yard rushing season
against the New Orleans Saints on Sunday. Now he figures he's going
to have to buy an unlikely source a thank-you dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell, who needed 48 yards against the Saints to crack the
1,000-yard barrier and become the first Cardinals running back to
do it since Garrison Hearst (1,070) in 1985, did it on a 21-yard
scoring run on which quarterback Jake Plummer threw the springing
block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buy dinner for my linemen when they do something right, so I
guess I'll have to buy him one, too,'' said Murrell, who gained 65
yards on 19 carries and has 1,017 for the season. ``He finally got
it right. He owed me one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week he had a chance to spring me and missed the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer threw a perfect crossbody block on cornerback Tyronne
Drakeford and wore a sheepish smile all the way back to the bench
as Arizona took a 13-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third consecutive 1,000-yard season for Murrell, who
came to the Cardinals along with a seventh-round draft pick in a
trade with the New York Jets for the Cardinals' third-round
selection. He had 1,249 yards in 1996 and 1,088 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He became the eighth active NFL running back to reach the mark
in three or more consecutive seasons, and joins Ottis Anderson, Jim
Otis, John David Crow, Hearst, Ronald Moore and Stump Mitchell as
the only Cardinals to reach 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   About the only sour moment Sunday came when he was hit just
after taking a handoff and fumbled on his own 17. The Giants
recovered, but the Cardinals defense rose to the occasion and
stopped New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The odds on Murrell reaching 1,000 yards didn't seem good. The
Cardinals averaged just 78 yards a game rushing last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line is doing a great job for me,'' Murrell said. ``We
took a lot of heat earlier about being more productive on the run.
But we just kept pounding it at them. It's been going smooth all
year. Some weeks it's going to go well, and some weeks it isn't.
That's the game. But as long as we win, it surpasses everything
else.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
