<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BEATING COLTS, SEAHAWK SHORTCOMINGS ALL TOO APPARENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you had earned a permutations minor while obtaining
a math degree in college, you might have looked forward to Sunday's
Kingdome game, what with the Seahawk possibilities for playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But since all the options ended by the game's third play, when
New England recorded a victory over San Francisco, you could have
had more fun looking for a downtown parking space.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' 27-23 win over the inept Indianapolis Colts (3-12)
was as desultory as it was irrelevant, falling just shy of
embarrassment. Colts quarterback Peyton Manning, with a
first-and-goal at the Seattle 7-yard line in the final minute, blew
all four chances at the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Nine weeks earlier in San Diego, Charger quarterback Ryan Leaf
failed at the threshold against the Seahawk defense in almost
identical last-minute circumstances, and the Seahawks prevailed,
27-20.
</P>
<P>
   So think of it this way: If it hadn't been for the rookieness of
QBs for two desperate franchises, the Seahawks are 6-9 this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   That's one thing to recall in the woulda-shoulda-coulda
lamentations that commence now that the Seahawks have been issued
formally their standard non-invitation to the NFL postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Seahawks were jobbed by a bad call in New York. Yeah,
they had bad luck in a Kansas City monsoon. And they should have
beaten the Oakland Raiders twice. But for every call or turn of
fortune that went against them, they also had their share of
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The point about the Manning-Leaf rookie vulnerability
underscores a larger theme: Among the many veteran quarterbacks
having stellar seasons, the Seahawks will have faced only John
Elway, Troy Aikman and Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the Seahawks had a schedule of baby's-bottom softness.
With a week left in the season, they have played only three teams
that are assured of winning records: Denver, Dallas and the New
York Jets _ the teams with the three good QBs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Seahawks are 8-7, and the odds favor a seasonal tally of
8-8 after a game Sunday against the AFC-best Broncos in the
Colorado refrigerator. That's the same record they had in 1997 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Siberia can't build this many snowmen.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of snow, what has a longer tradition: Christmas, or the
Seahawks missing the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Arizona Cardinals look to be the NFC's sixth and
final playoff team, the Seahawks' 10-year absence is the new NFL
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Wait 'til next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you count on other teams to lose, it's our fault,'' guard
Brian Habib said of the Seahawk playoff requirements. ``We never
should have been in that position. There were so many games we
should have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoulda. Woulda. Coulda.
</P>
<P>
   Never dida.
</P>
<P>
   At least not in the four years of coach Dennis Erickson. In a
sport jiggered to achieve parity, the Erickson Seahawks have been
the league's poster child.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Seahawk wheel-spinning means the end of the
Erickson regime, perhaps as soon as a week from Monday. The primary
reason will be opportunity squandered, especially relative to the
payroll (No. 4 in the NFL) and the success of other recently
middling teams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.2l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This season alone, Atlanta went to 13-2 from 7-9 a year ago;
Minnesota to 14-1 from 9-7; Buffalo to 9-6 from 6-10; the Jets to
11-4 from a non-playoff 9-7. Even the Cardinals, who looked awful
in a 33-14 loss here in Week 2, managed to create a turnaround
within the season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.2l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Not the Seahawks. They almost never were awful, but seldom were
they stellar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.2l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was another example. Ricky Watters rushed for a
personal-best and Seahawk season-high 178 yards, and the defense
held the Colts' star back, Marshall Faulk, to 19 yards. Normally,
that sort of disparity in the game's most fundamental element
should be decisive. Instead, the Seahawks had to break every
fingernail to hang on to victory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.2l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Reasons were numerous. They always have been. Since the team's
shortfall rests almost exclusively with the offense, here's four
large reasons:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.2l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Biggest bust, individual: Warren Moon. He had his moments. But
the holdout, limited mobility, injuries and persistent third-down
failures conspired to turn the talk about his age into shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest bust, group: Erickson and his offensive staff, who
switched from last year's wide-open air attack to an emphasis on
rushing without the personnel to pull it off so abruptly. Then they
switched back, which fails to inspire confidence or convert third
downs.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest continuing travail: The line. A 10th straight year of
starting lineup change helps extend the 23-year shutout from the
Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Worst fate, individual: Linebacker Chad Brown. ``I've always
been in the playoffs _ Pop Warner, high school, college, Pittsburgh
(for four years). Except for here.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the tradition, Chad. It soon may supplant rain,
coffee, slugs, the Space Needle and bad rock music atop the list of
Seattle icons.
</P>
<P>
   The season was hardly without achievement: The establishment of
Jon Kitna as a legitimate starting quarterback; the recovery of the
special teams; the creation of a defense that held up remarkably
under the weight of carrying the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But the virtues likely won't come to more than 8-8, which will
add up to an 86 for Erickson and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   A close, cruel call, but the right one.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
