<HEADLINE>
THEY LEFT HEART IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They asked themselves the same questions
everyone else was asking them.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   How could a team whose passing game was moving so well in the
first half get shut down in the second half, especially in the
fourth quarter?
</P>
<P>
   How could such an offensive breakdown _ and accompanying
defensive malaise _ happen against a team missing its best
defensive player, its starting quarterback, and its best receiver?
</P>
<P>
   None of the answers the 49ers came up with Sunday seemed to make
sense. Nor did San Francisco's stunning 24-21 loss to the Patriots
at Foxboro Stadium, which put New England into the AFC playoffs and
put the 49ers in jeopardy of having to play a wild-card playoff
game on the road.
</P>
<P>
   And there was even more ominous news in the 49ers locker room.
Quarterback Steve Young, who had toyed with the Patriots in the
first half _ completing 13 of 15 passes for 185 yards and two
touchdowns _ was limping around on a sore left knee, which will be
tested Monday to see if there is significant damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say a thing until I see what the tests
show,'' said Young, who was injured on the 49ers' last series when
defensive end Greg Spires pancaked him onto the Foxboro Stadium
turf. ``I have no idea on my knee. I'm going to wait until I have
an MRI done.''
</P>
<P>
   If Young has a serious injury, the 49ers situation may become as
dire as the Patriots' seemed to be when they came into the game
with Drew Bledsoe in street clothes on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers had come in acting like the 49ers of old, powered by
an awesome offense led by Young, wide receiver Jerry Rice, and
running back Garrison Hearst, who had amassed a career-high 198
yards in a romp over the Detroit Lions last Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco came to New England with some underlying
concerns. Although the 49ers had won 11 of their 14 games, they
were a shaky 3-4 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   They were especially shaky defensively. Throughout the season,
they had shown a few cracks: letting some opponents get out in
front early, letting others back into the game after they should
have been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Neither bodes well for the future.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half Sunday, however, the 49ers looked just fine.
Led by Young, they had a 21-14 lead at the half. And they had a
sense that they were controlling the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want us to be aggressive and dynamic,'' said Young, who was
neither in the second half, especially in the fourth quarter, when
he attempted just one pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been having a difficult time running the ball,''
said Young. ``Those running plays have been working for us all
season.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't work well in the second half, however, and as a
result the 49ers find themselves in dire need of a win in next
week's regular-season finale against the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   And they find themselves wondering just what kind of team they
are. ``We've got ourselves into a situation where we need to be
able to win on the road against the kind of teams we're going to
see in the playoffs,'' said 49ers head coach Steve Mariucci.
</P>
<P>
   Young was more definite about what San Francisco must do.
``We've got to finish drives off,'' he said. ``We need to be able
to put teams away when we get a lead. We should have done that
today.''
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't. The 49ers didn't win a game that may not have
been easy but certainly was winnable.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   About the condition of Young. And their role as a championship
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the San Francisco 49ers feel vulnerable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
