</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL APPRECIATES IMPORTANCE OF WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll and Steve Israel are two
Patriots who can fully understand how significant it is to beat the
San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking about the best receiver (Jerry Rice) to ever
play the game,'' said Israel. ``You're talking about the best
quarterback (Steve Young), whose efficiency is better than anyone's
in history. You're talking about the best receiving corps and I
haven't even gotten to Garrison Hearst yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' corner spent two years with the 49ers when Carroll
was the defensive coordinator. During Sunday's 24-21 win over the
49ers, the Patriots blitzed at all the right times and controlled
Young when they absolutely had to.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive end Greg Spires, who was filling in for Chris
Sullivan (knee), who was filling in for Willie McGinest (groin),
had a huge sack in the fourth quarter and came up big in his most
significant performance as a Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just some real gutsy play and he had to play a lot
because Chris was banged up,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's biggest play came on a third-and-5 from the 49ers' 29.
He blitzed from the left side and sacked Young for a 10-yard loss,
which forced the 49ers to punt from their own end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had missed an interception earlier and I said to myself to
keep going because there'll come a time in the game when I would be
called upon to make a big play. Thank God, that opportunity arose
again,'' Israel said.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots cornerback Ty Law, who intercepted a Young pass (Law's
ninth interception of the season) and returned it 30 yards in the
second quarter, said, ``This means a lot, but nobody expected us to
win. They have All-Pros and Hall of Famers on their team and we
have guys who are banged up and couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we held up together as a team. We didn't give up. We
played four quarters of football and even when they got up, we
figured if we could make a big play here and there we could get it
back. Willie got the pick and (Scott Zolak) led us back.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Clay, victimized on Rice's 75-yard pass play in the
second quarter, made a fourth-quarter interception that started New
England's game-tying drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big boost for us, I was glad to make the play,'' said
Clay. ``I think we won because we made less mistakes than we did
last week. You can't turn the ball over. We turned the ball over
twice and we limited it to that. The big plays they made hurt us,
but they had one or two. We limited that pretty well when it really
counted down the backstretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense also got after Young, sacking him five times. Chris
Slade, who had the type of game Slade fans have come to expect, had
one sack and nine tackles, with Israel, Spires, Chris Carter, and
Sullivan all getting in on the sack parade.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Milloy played a big part in stopping the run as he made
14 tackles to lead the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   While Hearst managed 107 yards on the ground, the Patriots held
him in check when they had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearst did OK, but we did a decent job holding him down,''
said Chad Eaton. ``We knew if we could keep Hearst from running
wild against us we had a chance to win the game. He had a good
game, but it wasn't like he had last week. I will say he was the
best running back we've faced all season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
