<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS LIMPS IN WITH GAME ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD AND BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Sore left big toe and all, Cardinals
veteran &UR; Aeneas Williams limped to his cornerback position in the
final two minutes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had been out of the game for most of the second half of
the 19-17 victory over New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was on the line,'' Williams said. ``You know what the
stakes were. Remember, I've been here eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't able to stop the New Orleans Saints from driving 75
yards in 14 plays to take a one-point lead with 1:21 left. But he
was there on the sideline leading the cheers as quarterback  &UR; Jake
Plummer drove the offense 73 yards in six plays, capped off by
 &UR; Chris Jacke's game-winning field goal with no time remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens, we always believe Jake can win,''
Williams said. ``We believe in Jake.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates in the defensive backfield were awed by Williams
putting himself back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy wants to win,'' defensive back  &UR; J.J. McCleskey said.
``He was in pain, but he knew we had to have the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't just go back out there,'' rookie cornerback &UR; Corey
Chavous said. ``He went out there with the belief that he would
make the play that would seal the game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Williams was out, he was replaced by  &UR; Tom Knight, who had
missed the past three games because of a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been frustrating from the standpoint of what I
envisioned my role,'' said Knight, who began the season as a
starter. ``I think I've developed an understanding of what it takes
to be successful. I'm still part of the team and want to
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost recovered a fumble on the Saints' last drive, but
offensive guard  &UR; Chris Naeole beat him to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I should have had it,'' Knight said. ``I jumped on it,
but two guys came in on me and got me off the ball.'' &QL; 
Goat to glory
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Frank Sanders was shaping up as the goat for the Cardinals
after a couple of first-half blunders.
</P>
<P>
   On the team's first possession, on third and 1 at the Saints'
28, Sanders was charged with a false start that moved the ball back
five yards. Following an incomplete pass on third down, Jacke
missed a 51-yard field goal try. The Cardinals had nothing to show
for an 11-play march that lasted 3:42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, on second and goal at the New Orleans 5,
Sanders caught a hitch pass from Plummer and seemingly had a clear
path to the end zone. Saints cornerback  &UR; Alex Molden knocked the
ball loose from behind, and Saints safety  &UR; Chad Cota recovered it
for a touchback in the end zone, killing another drive.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game on the line in the closing 1:16, Sanders
caught passes from Plummer that covered 25 and 28 yards, postioning
the Cardinals for a game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exciting turn of events,'' said Sanders, who caught
10 passes for 138 yards. ``I never let my faith waver. The game is
60 minutes long. You've got to keep your faith. With our two-minute
offense, there's never a dull moment. Jake made great reads on
those two passes at the end. That's just Jake being Jake.'' &QL; 
Out with the crowd &QL; 
The Cardinals asked for a big crowd, and the fans responded. More
than 5,000 bought tickets at the game, about 4,000 more than usual.
</P>
<P>
   But preparations at Sun Devil Stadium for the Fiesta Bowl mean a
whole lot of those fans never got to their seats until near the end
of the first quarter. The Fiesta Bowl has taken over the stadium
ticket offices, according to  &UR; Tom Stadler, Arizona State's stadium
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary ticket locations were set up near Wells Fargo Arena _
in trailers _ but there were long lines, and traffic jams formed
near the stadium as fans tried to drive up to the ticket locations.
The problem could be the same next week when San Diego visits, so
fans are encouraged to buy tickets before going to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walk-up fans didn't know where to go,'' Cardinals
spokesman &UR; 
 &UR; Paul Jensen said. ``The best thing fans can do next week is buy the
tickets ahead of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are available at the Cardinals training facility at
Hardy and Warner roads in Tempe, at Safeway stores with ETM
machines or by calling 1-888-ETM-TIXX. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
