<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAINTS-COLLAPSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4TH-DOWN FAILURE DOESN'T FAZE DITKA  
 BUT HE'S UPSET WITH DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Mike Ditka's answer was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters wanted to know what he was thinking when he decided to
go for it in a fourth-and-one situation at the Arizona 9-yard line
early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of your business,'' Ditka replied.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka's response had the same result as the critical fourth-down
play: It came up short.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of forging a tie with the chip shot field goal, the
Saints failed to gain the critical yard, and the Cardinals drove
down the field to set up a 46-yard Chris Jacke field goal for a
16-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the Saints later came back to take a 17-16 lead.
But had it been 20-16, Arizona would have needed to go 90 yards for
a touchdown in the final 1:21 instead of merely into field goal
range for Jacke's 36-yard game-winning kick as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   But Ditka was bothered more by his defense's execution on the
final drive, in which the Saints gave up two long pass plays to
receiver Frank Sanders, than he was the fourth-down failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ahead, 17-16,'' Ditka said, finally responding to
questions. ``They got some 90 yards to go. I made the call. Only
me. I made the call. You got a half-yard to go (on fourth down). If
you can't make it, you don't deserve to win. We talked about this
all year, fellas. I made the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have made any difference. We were not going to win
this game at the end. We went into a shell. We are not going to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid (Sanders) ran no route. Believe me, (he) came off and
ran 20 yards and turned around and then the ball was thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their best receiver, and we didn't have anybody
covering him.''
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans defensive coordinator Zaven Yaralian was at a loss
to explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason in my mind for us to let that happen,''
Yaralian said. ``We called the defense we've called all year. Maybe
we called the wrong defense, but we could have blown any
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it has been the Saints' defense which has carried a
struggling offense all season. This time, quarterback Kerry Collins
made the plays to get his team the lead, and the defense wilted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what happened or what went wrong, we were there
at the end,'' Collins said. ``And we made mistakes, we did some
good things, but it still doesn't belie the fact we didn't get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who converted a fourth-and-four play during the
go-ahead drive, defended the fourth-and-one call. ``We got a yard
(to go), and we've got to get those fourth downs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Collins was convinced the decision was moot after New
Orleans took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very confident in the defense,'' he said. ``They've been
playing well. I think they're a great defense. And they'll do it in
the future, I'm confident of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to score more points. I don't think there's any doubt
about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
