<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9828 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-VINATIER     12-21 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-VINATIERI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL ALIVE AND KICKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The tradition is the holder doesn't speak to
the kicker when the game is on the line, even more so when New
England's playoff chances were resting on Adam Vinatieri's toe. So
Tom Tupa and Vinatieri went about their business. Silently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, Adam and I were patting down the field,'' said Tupa,
when asked to provide details about what transpired during the 40
or so seconds of the timeout just before Vinatieri's 35-yard field
goal attempt with six seconds left on the clock and the Patriots
and 49ers tied, 21-21. ``We were trying to get a good spot on the
field so Adam could get some good footing. And I was looking for a
good spot to place the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   This is routine in December in New England. Usually, said
Vinatieri, ``the field is pretty chewed up when you get to December
and you need to pat down the field. But the weather hasn't been too
hard this year and the field wasn't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tupa, head down, looked for a good spot to place the ball,
then tamped it down with his spikes. So Vinatieri, head down,
looked for a good spot where he estimated he would plant his left
foot and tamped down the grass. All this was done in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' said Tupa, ``it was pretty calm out there. It was
just like another kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri already had missed a chip shot for him _ a 32-yarder
that hit the left upright and bounced away on the Patriots' first
drive _ but, Vinatieri said that miss was out of his mind when he
waited for the snap from Mike Bartrum and Tupa's hold in those
final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kicker has to have a short memory,'' said Vinatieri. ``No
matter what you did before, you have to put that out of your mind.
You can't let how you kicked the last one affect how you'll kick
the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, was anxiety rushing into his bones, not to mention his
mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you've got the adrenaline going and you've got some
butterflies going,'' said the Patriots kicker. But that was all,
because in his rookie year three years ago Vinatieri had kicked a
winning field goal in overtime against Jacksonville, and he had won
three other games since with field goals, ``so I felt confident
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it seemed Vinatieri might have to try a 44- or
45-yard attempt because the Patriots gained little on their first
two downs after a first-and-10 from the 49ers 31. ``But distance
isn't a factor,'' said Vinatieri. ``If I had to kick it 45 yards, I
still have to kick it straight and I still have to kick it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartrum snapped it straight and true back to Tupa (``The guys on
the line huddled up and said, `Just give Adam some time,''' said
Bartrum), Tupa placed the ball, and Vinatieri kicked. It is no
understatement that Vinatieri's kick did not split the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a yard or so inside (the right upright),'' said Tupa,
``but as soon as it took off you knew it was good. It didn't move
from its line or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri, too, said he felt confident as soon as he looked up
and spotted the ball's flight. When he first looked up, ``I knew it
was close, but I still knew it was good. I turned around and
started celebrating right away. That's a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The next-to-last play of the game truly made up for the last
play of the first half for the Patriots special teams, when a
botched field goal attempt by the 49ers resulted in the
slowest-of-seemingly-slow-motion 25-yard touchdown passes from
holder (and backup quarterback) Ty Detmer to Irv Smith, who had
been lined up just inside San Francisco's wide blocker.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer fumbled the snap and then, after players on both teams
froze for a second, he rolled to the left and stood there for
second after second as confusion reigned. But the Patriots remained
frozen for more than a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had blocked (a field goal attempt) earlier and that time we
had a middle block (play) on,'' said Marty Moore, the heart of the
Patriots special teams. ``And what happened was we had some guys
who thought that the other guy had some of their guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be as good a description as any of a field goal
attempt botched by both teams. What was most irksome, though, was
New England had faced the same play last week in St. Louis, when
the Rams' Rick Tuten fumbled a snap, ``but that time Tebucky Jones
got to (Tuten) before he could make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   This time?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything sort of went haywire,'' said Moore. ``Guys who had
their guys kind of just dropped them and I dropped back with their
tight end. But I thought the tight end was behind me. It just got
sort of messed up out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
