A9831 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR     12-21 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEK BY WEEK, THE LEGEND OF JAKE GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Where would they be without him?
</P>
<P>
   Adrift. With a head coach requesting his last meal and a stadium
blueprint lining the bird cage. With apathy prompting a call for
moving vans. With Mr. Bidwill checking out land in Houston and
trying on 10-gallon hats.
</P>
<P>
   So Andre Wadsworth is ``The Gift.'' What, then, is Jake Plummer?
</P>
<P>
   ``The miracle,'' Wadsworth said. ``How about that?''
</P>
<P>
   When the fireworks exploded, when the combination of relief and
disbelief washed over 51,000 people, they stood and cheered for an
eternity. Until Plummer raced off the field, his feet barely
touching the ground, tapping his heart before blowing kisses into
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   And as the roar continued, the signs were held like property of
zealots:
</P>
<P>
   ``PLUMMER 3:16.''
</P>
<P>
   ``ON THE EIGHTH DAY, GOD CREATED JAKE.''
</P>
<P>
   ``WE BELIEVE.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 24 years old with 24 career starts, and the numbers are
preposterous: Eight comeback victories. Six this season. And that
doesn't count two others that resulted in losses, including a
furious 28-point rally against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   You're ridiculous, I tell Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he says with a smile. ``This team's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, this is a group effort, a team that is getting better
by the week. But it all stems from Plummer. A kid who glows with
stardust, acts like the frat boy who just tied your shoelaces
together, performs with no fear. A kid blessed with the magic, the
ability to part the sea for an NFL doormat. And with one more
victory, he will have guided them across.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how the NBA is building things around Grant Hill?''
Redskins' safety Darrell Green said last month. ``The NFL, if this
can be an analogy, should do the same thing with Jake Plummer.
Build it around that kid. He's a nice kid, he's hungry, he's a
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations to the Cardinals. For all their lack of vision,
they were the ones who plucked him in the second round. The ones
who rewarded him with a multiyear extension on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' Saints coach Mike Ditka said. ``Their
quarterback made us look like fools all day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Plummer threw 44 passes, completing 32, wracking up
394 yards. With a few exceptions, every toss was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   It was an afternoon when the game slowed to a crawl in his
cranium, when he routinely checked off one receiver, two receivers,
before finding the proper target. An afternoon when he threw a
block that sprung a touchdown. When he walked into the huddle at
the 8-yard line with 81 seconds remaining _ this kid who once
emerged from the shower and danced naked in front of teammates just
for a chuckle _ and told 10 other guys to ``get the look.'' When he
had the game on a string, and once again, made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys have it, some guys don't,'' reserve quarterback Dave
Brown said. ``He's definitely got it. What impresses me most is
that he feels like he ``should'' do it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   A feeling that comes from . . .?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, and I don't want to know,'' Plummer said. ``But
I like to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd like something else. A full house for the season finale
against the Chargers. A game that could propel the Cardinals into
the playoffs for the first time since the continents split. And if
you can't pack the place for this guy, this team, this occasion,
you don't deserve an NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on you fans that didn't come today,'' Plummer said.
``You missed a great ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, in a hallway, Plummer hugged Fiesta Bowl
president Herman Frazier. The two go back a long way, but the irony
is this: If the Cardinals make the playoffs, the Fiesta Bowl will
be an afterthought in this city.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cardinals make the playoffs, they are poised to make
some noise. Turnovers and red-zone troubles aside, the Cardinals
played their best football game of the season on both sides of the
ball against the Saints. Beating the Cowboys in Dallas is not
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is with this guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legend grows every day, right?'' player personnel boss Bob
Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Without fail. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
