<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE USES `CUB' TO CLUB NEW ORLEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The Cardinals' defense closely resembles the
famed Revolutionary War painting of the crippled fife and drum
corps hobbling along in pain but with great pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is beat up and crippled, but I can't say enough
about the character of this team or the way Vince has built it,''
Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said after Sunday's
thrilling 19-17 win over New Orleans. ``It believes in him and
believes in us. It a pretty good deal we've got going here, guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our front four played outstanding. This team has a lot of
stuff going for it.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has a pretty good defensive strategist in Coach Vince
Tobin. With starting defensive tackles Mark Smith and Eric Swann
and middle linebacker Ron McKinnon limited because of sprained
knees, it was Tobin who came up with a variation of the Chicago
Bears defense and proposed it to McGinnis on Tuesday in hopes of
creating a run defense and a pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin named the defense the ``Cub,'' and it played a large role
in holding New Orleans to just 82 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   In general terms, it put end Andre Wadsworth at nose tackle,
linebackers Jamir Miller and Patrick Sapp out wide and safety Pat
Tillman at middle linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals run about five different variations from the
formation. It was the defense used when Sapp sacked Kerry Collins
and Miller recovered the ensuing fumble to stop the Saints' first
drive of the second half at Arizona's 23. The Cardinals marched to
a go-ahead touchdown on the next series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cub worked, but I don't want to go into too much detail
about it,'' Miller said, grinning widely as if he were keeping a
state secret. ``It confused them. They didn't know where we were
coming from, and that's always a good thing. They didn't know how
to block it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis said the Cub was employed six to eight times in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were having so much success in our regular defense, we
thought about not using it in the second half,'' he said. ``But it
created the big fumble, and it was successful several times in the
red zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tillman played well, and so did Jamir. It puts a lot of heat
on him because he's got to make all the adjustments. They didn't
know how to block it, which was the intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth wasn't into discussing the X's and O's, preferring to
talk about the inner strength of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always fight to the end,'' he said. ``You know what it
looked like today? We looked like a team that just didn't want it,
but one that had to have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like somebody who hasn't eaten in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth will get no argument from Pro Bowl cornerback Aeneas
Williams, who missed most of the second half because of a sprained
big toe before returning for the Saints' final series, in which
they scored to take a brief 17-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating having to watch,'' he said. ``But the guys
who were out there did a great job. Tommy Knight (playing with a
hamstring pull) did a great job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to experience this (playoff chase), because of
what we have going and the fashion in which we're doing it. We've
been planting the seeds for a long time, we've watered them, and
now it's close to harvest time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
