<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-CO     12-21 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Help, I'm being held prisoner by an ATM machine!
 &HT;    For release Dec. 23, 1998.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON - It was just past 11:30 p.m. and we were returning to
our hotel after enjoying a performance of Oscar Wilde's ``An Ideal
Husband.'' As we emerged from our tube station, I spotted an ATM
machine. I am drawn to ATM machines as a moth is drawn to light.
This time, however, something turned out the lights.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bleak moment when you realize that you are thousands of
miles and five time zones away from home, your funds nearly
depleted and the card you have carried with you to get more has
been eaten by an alien ATM machine.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps ``bleak'' isn't the proper word; ``panicky'' is more
likely.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30 p.m., in a darkened arcade in the Kensington section of
London, I panicked in the sense that I was down to the equivalent
of about $8.50 with no way to get more money. The language that
spewed from my mouth was crude and I apologize to any Britishers
who heard it within the five-miles range of my raucous voice.
</P>
<P>
   It took a calming wife to settle me down, although I
repetitiously continued to declare ``The $%&AMP;(% thing ate my card!''
</P>
<P>
   This was a lesson in both economics and travel. I long ago came
to the conclusion that the world is populated with more ATM
machines than it is trees. As a result of that incredulous notion,
I found it easier to travel with less funds, less credit cards, no
personal checks and no travelers checks.
</P>
<P>
   My belief in ATM machines was so great that I began preaching
about them. They're wonderful, I would tell friends and occasional
strangers. Each day, withdraw just the amount of money you need to
carry you through the day, get it in the funds of the country
you're in, have it drawn electronically from your checking account
in the U.S. at that moment's exchange rates and pay only a small
fee for the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   It made it so easy. On this trip, I left the U.S. with but
little more than $100 cash in my pocket _ and that ATM card.
</P>
<P>
   So, here I was standing in the shadows of a London arcade, down
to my last $8.50 and my financial lifeline sucked into this
unyielding machine. How I longed for those travelers checks, how I
wished I had brought more cash. How I swore!
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to reach a bank executive near the midnight hour is
like trying to make sense of what is going on in Washington, D.C.
these days, but my wife persevered (while I sulked.) Working her
way through the London Yellow Pages, she finally located an on-duty
somebody who, naturally, couldn't help us but told us who to call
in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the morning that we were told the card would not be
removed from the ATM machine until the next day but based on other
factors (my wife had a duplicate of the card but absolutely refused
to use it because she feared it, too, would be eaten) we were given
some money to tide us over.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, and two bank branch offices later, we had our card
returned to us with apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lesson was learned not to put all my eggs into one
ATM machine, I remained curious. ``Why,'' I asked a bank officer,
``was my card kept? I had sufficient funds, I put in the right ID
number . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   The bank officer referred to a computer printout. ``You took too
long to make your decision on how much money you wanted,'' he
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for that, you kept my card?'' I exclaimed. ``Why wasn't it
just sent back and me told to try again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he said, ``that's the way we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepted, however grudgingly. But the next time I leave the
country, I'll be backed by more than just an ATM card.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-HATE-CRIME22     12-21 1734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HATE-CRIME22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keying in to `high-tech hate' on the Internet
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A couple of months ago, Internet hate
groups pulled a high-tech, in-your-face trick on the mainstream
press that normally tries to ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   It got them immediate attention, but not the kind they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In early October, certain U.S. and foreign newspapers suddenly
began getting puzzled and angry reports from people searching for
their World Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of finding the Chicago Sun-Times, St. Louis
Post-Dispatch or Atlanta Constitution, people were landing on the
swastika-emblazoned site of Stormfront Inc., a Nazi-patterned white
power organization based in West Palm Beach. Stormfront is run by
Don Black, a former Ku Klux Klansman who was the first to set up a
white supremacist site on the Internet, according to groups that
monitor bigotry on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Someone _ Black says he didn't do it _ had registered variations
of 14 newspapers' names on the Internet, then programmed them to
divert searchers to the Stormfront site. For example, a searcher
looking for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution Web site who typed
atlantaconstitution.com would wind up instead at stormfront.org.
The Constitution's real Web address is ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver was a new twist on cyber-squatting, in which
opportunists register names similar to famous trademarks and try to
make businesses pay them to give up the names.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first known time that Web searchers had been hijacked
to a hate site, according to the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai
B'rith. The ADL, which monitors hate groups worldwide, estimates
several hundred now operate on the Internet. The Simon Wiesenthal
Center in Los Angeles, also a monitor, lists more than 800 sites
that it classifies as hate-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message was we're now in the generation of high-tech
hate,'' said William Rothchild, ADL regional director in West Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers got another message from the Stormfront incident.
Cyber-squatting has opened a chaotic new realm of legal conflict
over trademark protection, and the hate-group twist added a free
speech element that made it even more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is moving ahead faster than the law, and the law
needs to catch up,'' said Jon Vegosen, attorney for the Chicago
Sun-Times. ``Fortunately, there were (trademark) laws here to
protect people in this case, and we were able to take advantage of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago and St. Louis papers sued the groups in federal
court for trademark infringement in October and got restraining
orders. Within a month, the groups had given up the soundalike Web
domains to the newspapers, which registered them to their own
companies. The remaining sites either have been or are being
re-registered to the trademark owners, or have been shut down.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania attorney general also has sued Stormfront and
two white supremacy groups with cyber links to it. That suit, filed
in October in Pennsylvania state court, accuses ALPHA HQ and White
Pride World Wide of using their Web sites to make ``terroristic
threats'' against two state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Stormfront holds the distinction of being the first Internet
bigotry site, according to the ADL and other hate-watch
organizations. It showed up in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Black, 45, is a former Grand Wizard of the Alabama Ku Klux Klan.
In the 1980s, he was sentenced to three years in prison for leading
an unsuccessful attempt to overthrow the government on the
Caribbean island of Dominica.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Chloe _ formerly married to Louisiana
politician and former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke _ have lived
in West Palm Beach since 1987 and have a 9-year-old son. Black
manages a network of Web sites and computer servers from his home,
according to court records in the newspaper suits.
</P>
<P>
   Groups maintaining such sites range from old-line ones such as
Aryan Nations and Knights of the Ku Klux Klan to the newer
Skinheads of the Racial Holy War and record companies peddling
white-power albums with violent lyrics. Graphics are heavy on
swastikas, Celtic crosses, Gothic type and dark backgrounds with
flames, flags and thunderbolts. Articles quote ``scientific''
evidence that whites are genetically and culturally superior to
other races and allege persecution of white, Gentile,
English-speaking patriots by blacks, Hispanics, Asians, Jews, the
media and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Black said in an interview that he knew nothing about the plan
to divert newspaper searchers to Stormfront. He said it was
strictly the work of Adrian Edward Marlow of Suisun City, Calif.,
from whom Black rented space on a computer and knew only through
online communication.
</P>
<P>
   But newspapers sent lawyers after Black and Stormfront, as well
as Marlow and others. Court documents from the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch case disclosed a national network of connected Web
sites, post office addresses and computer-support functions. For
example, according to the documents, Black provides Internet access
and Web site links to:
</P>
<P>
   _Frank Weltner of St. Louis, who calls himself Von Goldstein
Mohammed and calls his Web site Jew Watch.
</P>
<P>
   _Adrian Marlow, who created and maintains a site called White
Pride World Wide and who provided computer space for part of
Black's Stormfront operations, as well as for Weltner's
jewwatch.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Tim DeLaire of St. Charles, Mo., listed as the contact for
Bluelantern Inc., the name used to register the White Pride World
Wide site.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to contact Weltner, Marlow and DeLaire were
unsuccessful. Marlow did not respond to telephone messages
requesting comment, and the number listed for DeLaire on his
Bluelantern site registration produces a recording saying the call
can't be completed.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge found that Weltner had reproduced a copyrighted
Post-Dispatch story and photograph about Jewish religious services
on his Web site without the paper's permission. He signed a consent
order forbidding further use of copyrighted material.
</P>
<P>
   Federal courts in Missouri and Illinois also issued injunctions
against Black, Weltner and the others, ordering them to stop using
any variations of the newspapers' trademarked names. They, too,
signed consent orders agreeing to the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents showed that Marlow had used the initials, MKM,
and post office box of his mother, Monika K. Marlow _ without her
knowledge _ to register the names. She was dismissed as a
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the newspapers, two variations of pharmaceutical
giant Abbott Laboratories' Web address also were registered to MKM.
A spokeswoman for Abbott said the company is ``working to
invalidate the current registrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Stabbe, an attorney for The Atlanta Constitution said
Marlow told him in a telephone conversation that he wanted money
for the atlantaconstitution.com address. Stabbe said Marlow told
him he had linked the address to Stormfront to create publicity,
attract more traffic and thus make the site appear to be worth
more.
</P>
<P>
   But Marlow gave up the name, under a cease-and-desist letter and
threat of a suit, without ever saying how much money he wanted,
Stabbe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got that far,'' Stabbe said.
</P>
<P>
   Tweaking the noses of the establishment press, and being hauled
into court for it, wasn't as impressive to Black as it was to the
newspapers and their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a ripple, but it wasn't that big a story,'' Black
said. ``The attorneys certainly put forth a great deal of effort.
Getting a court injunction is a big deal, considering it's such a
trivial issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania lawsuit is another matter. As in the St. Louis
and Chicago newspaper cases, the suit is directed at a cross-linked
network of organizations, Web sites and individuals _ including
Black and Stormfront; DeLaire and Bluelantern; and a Philadelphia
white supremacist group called ALPHA HQ and its founder, Ryan
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says the ALPHA HQ Web site posted pictures of two women
employed as fair housing and human relations workers by the state
and made ``terrorist threats'' against them. It called one a ``race
traitor'' and said traitors ``will be hung from the neck from the
nearest tree or lamp post.'' It also carried a photograph doctored
to look like the employee's office building was exploding.
</P>
<P>
   The state wants the court to ban publication of the photos and
images on the ALPHA HQ site and prohibit Black and the other
defendants from providing computer support for the site. Further,
it wants the court to force Network Solutions Inc., the worldwide
registry for Internet names, to banish ALPHA HQ from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Black says the suit is an attack on the groups' First Amendment
rights and the attorney general would be wise not to push it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a violation of the Ku Klux Klan Act,'' Black said. ``He
could be countersued based on that act.'' The Civil Rights Act of
1871, known as the KKK Act, was an attempt to curb Klan violence by
forbidding one person or group from usurping another's
constitutional rights, including by force of law.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions Inc., which has 3 million Internet ``domain''
names registered, says monitoring trademarks and content on Web
sites is not its job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is it's up to trademark owners to police their
own trademarks,'' said spokeswoman Sheryl Regan. ``We register Web
addresses . . . on a first-come, first-served basis, but we don't
concern ourselves with the content on sites using those
addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been 4,000 disputes since NSI began registering names
in 1993, Regan said. NSI has been targeted in court actions 44
times, including the Pennsylvania case, and has never been found at
fault, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Internet sites promoting hostility and even
violence against racial, religious, ethnic and other populations
keeps changing as groups adopt the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Black and his inspiration, David Duke, are enthusiastic leaders
of the Internet movement. They say it gives them access and
exposure to millions of potential recruits and followers they can't
reach through other media that shun them. A headline on Duke's Web
site sums up their expectations: The Coming White Revolution _ Born
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
