<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: At last! Boxing day off
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Thanks to a calendar quirk this year,
Americans will get a taste of Stephenstide. Maybe after we've tried
it, we won't want to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Because Christmas falls on a Friday, the feast of Stephen falls
on Saturday, a day off for most American workers. So, finally, the
civilized practice of recognizing the second day of Christmas will
extend to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the English-speaking world, however, a Dec. 26th
at home does not depend on happy coincidence of calendar and work
week. It is an every-year, bona fide, no-mail,
``closed''-sign-hanging-in-the-front-door, sit-around-the-house
holiday. It is the Feast of Stephen, the Second Day of Christmas,
Boxing Day.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it called Boxing Day? Because that's the day in family
holiday gatherings when the gloves finally come off. I thought
everyone knew that.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, other explanations. It is also said to be
the day when, Christmas having been safely taken care of, gifts
were boxed for service employees: postmen, doormen, coal
deliverers, the paper boy and the like.
</P>
<P>
   In our consumer-driven economy, however, the emphasis of the
Boxing Day has shifted almost entirely to boxes plopped on the
counters of returns departments. It is the day when bad guesses by
unskilled present-buyers are put right. Second Chance Day.
</P>
<P>
   We've come to believe that holiday second chances are restricted
to bringing back misguided purchases. Wrong. That's
one-day-of-Christmas thinking. On the second day of Christmas, one
has the opportunity for salesmanship. The time to convince
recipients that misguided present choices are actually
misunderstood present choices. Items the recipient always wanted
without knowing it. Objects that undoubtedly will grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   Such dialogue demands the leisure of a Boxing Day away from
work.
</P>
<P>
   The other second chances of Stephenstide have to do with being
able to do Christmas things you were too busy to do on or before
Christmas because of intense holiday preparations. With the day off
you can practice the fine art of holiday cooking by microwaving
pre-prepared cookie mix. You can force teen-agers to pretend to
like their families in photographs taken by the tree. (``Jonathan,
the spikes stay off until you see the flash go off.'') To sing
Christmas songs whose second verse you almost know.
</P>
<P>
   For this last activity, there is even a custom-made,
day-after-Christmas song, ``Good King Wenceslaus.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, I considered this song wonderfully exotic because
you cannot sing it with a Southern accent. All its syllables must
be pronounced. Its rhythm is fast, choppy and hard, like something
big falling down the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   It also demands that you pronounce ``cruel,'' ``crew AL.'' The
way a hammy villain would in a bad horror movie on television. Then
you must immediately match it with ``fuel'' pronounced as ``few
AL.''
</P>
<P>
   Way coo-AL.
</P>
<P>
   Within its Dr. Seuss rhyme scheme, the words paint a Christmas
tableau like a crowded and garish cover of a paperback book from
the wizards-and-lizards fantasy shelf: Glowing footprints in the
snow, fountains in the middle of a forest, a hiking king and his
long-suffering page. All topped with a socially responsible message
about the blessings of charity.
</P>
<P>
   A neat song for a holiday this country somehow thought it could
do without.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no more. Increasingly, the days before Christmas are a
shrieking tinseled blur. They involve mall hiking, involuntary arts
and crafts, home cleanup, dig out and decoration, as well as
amateur electrical work, familial negotiation and reckless baking.
A break is needed whether we call it Boxing Day, Holiday Overload
Day or Second-Chance Day.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing Day is just the kind of fadeout and reward we need. A
time when the kids have not yet lost interest in their toys and are
no longer hyper with expectation. When there's still enough
leftovers to avoid making meals. When the singing Christmas tree
ornament has been successfully disabled. When the batteries are
installed, assembly completed and computer reconfigured.
</P>
<P>
   When I was little, I used to look forward to Christmas. Now that
I'm older, I look forward to Boxing Day.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
