<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `It doesn't matter if it's one string of lights or 100, it's all
beautiful'
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He didn't intend to decorate for Christmas this
year, but Michael Neitman couldn't help himself. Some Christmas imp
_ maybe one of the 500 or so animated figures in his collection _
spurred him on, and, almost against his will, he started stringing
lights.
</P>
<P>
   His mother told him he was crazy. For Neitman, after all,
decorating isn't what it is for most families _ string up a few
lights and you're done. Back in the old days on Yale Avenue, it
took three weeks to put up the 120,000 lights and 100 or more
mechanical figures that transformed the stately old mansion into a
Christmas phantasmagoria. Neitman hired a Santa Claus who passed
out candy canes and small toys to the children. (As a special
nostalgic touch, many of the animated figures are from the old
Rike's windows.)
</P>
<P>
   Neitman wasn't a rich man, but for 15 years his Christmas
display outdazzled the showiest showplace in town. More than 35,000
people from all over the Miami Valley made the pilgrimage every
year. For many families, it was an annual tradition. ``Every year
we would go over there,'' says Charlene Martin, a retired Dayton
teacher. ``We were so touched by the fact he was doing this for the
people, something so extraordinary to look at, when he was not a
wealthy man.''
</P>
<P>
   The tradition ended in 1996, when the house at 16 Yale Ave. was
sold. Neitman, one of six renters, bought a small house at 218
Edgar Ave. in Walnut Hills.
</P>
<P>
   It ate at him that he couldn't put up his display, couldn't
greet the friends who had visited Yale Avenue year after year. The
regular visitors missed it, too. Every year since 1985, Christina
Anderson of Kettering and her mother, Martha Goldberg, had visited
the display after Thanksgiving dinner. ``My mother called Mike a
gentle giant, and he always had a special gift for her,'' she says.
``I just think that he has a magical gift. His display takes you
back to a time that was very loving and giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while driving up Wayne Avenue, Anderson looked to her
left and noticed a blaze of Christmas lights. She turned down Edgar
Avenue and ``there were beavers chopping wood, teddy bears and an
elf decorating a Christmas tree on the front porch,'' she says. The
animated windows, with the dancing gingerbread and bobbing Santas,
looked familiar too. She knocked on the door and, sure enough, it
was her old friend.
</P>
<P>
   They cried a little together when Anderson told Neitman her
mother was dying of lung cancer. A few nights later, Anderson
talked her mother into going over with her. Goldberg told her she
was daughter was too weak, ``but her frail little body was as a
child again, looking for things she enjoyed like the beavers
chopping the tree. And her buddy the gentle giant came out and as
always gave her a tin of chocolate candy and a warm hug, as if time
had stood still.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg died Monday night. The reunion ``meant a lot to me,''
Neitman says.
</P>
<P>
   So he's not sorry he put up his display this year, even if it
could only be a tenth of his collection of 300,000 lights and 500
mechanical figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as big as at Yale Avenue,'' Neitman concedes, ``but
it doesn't matter how big it is, as long as you're making smiles.
It doesn't matter if it's one string of lights or 100, it's all
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   He says it like he means it, and I think he does. But I can't
help noticing he's eyeballing his neighbor's yard. ``A two-yard
display would be nice,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
