<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season brings out deeds of generosity, genius
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Judge Bill Logue looked down and saw chocolate
still under his fingernails. This despite countless hand washings.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't going to jump him about it. You can't get on a guy's
case after he's filled 308 coffee cans with 3,000 or so pieces of
candy he's made by hand, and made sure that each can gets to
someone.
</P>
<P>
   Logue's candy _ chocolate-covered dollops commonly known as
Martha Washingtons _ is so good I'm surprised Waco didn't make it a
controlled substance by now. It causes work stoppages and
arm-wrestling matches. It is a disruptive force in our fair city.
</P>
<P>
   This uncommon labor of love entails 60 pounds of pecans, 160
pounds of sugar, 35 pounds of coconut. These figures come from his
wife Gloria, who's witnessed this ritual for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The McLennan County district judge is retiring next year, and
says this is his last batch. I doubt it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Logue isn't a man of his word. It's just that he
appears hopelessly addicted to giving.
</P>
<P>
   Cliches aside, this is a season that brings out remarkable
gifts, not just the kind you lay before a friend but also inspired
deeds.
</P>
<P>
   One can't help but be inspired, for instance, hearing the
combined Waco High orchestra, choir and show choir do ``Oh Holy
Night,'' crescendos that make neck hairs stand. They did that the
night of Dec. 12 in concert at Baylor's opulent Jones Hall. It's an
imposing venue to fill with sound. The high-schoolers were more
than equal to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds and silence
</P>
<P>
   Putting matters crass and commercial aside, we have a range of
celebration this time of year, from the jubilant to the somber,
from the decorated homes that stop traffic to the single string of
lights across a blue-collar frame, or one candle in a window.
</P>
<P>
   We have the moving choruses and the jaunty standbys. We also
have offerings in silence _ in meditation.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the colors, one of the more striking offerings is a
plain booklet that came my way written by the members of Lakeshore
Baptist Church. An annual booklet of Advent meditations,
``Extravagant Gift'' contains 34 offerings of prose and poetry from
members of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   In this day and time, getting people to contribute expressions
like these is remarkable _ valuable to those who read them and
valuable to those who write them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extravagant gifts''? The Lakeshore writers find themselves
showered. Each expression in this pamphlet is a heartfelt
celebration of blessings without pricetags.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday and Friday throughout McLennan County extravagance was
carried out in the most humble of offerings: a single storybook for
a single child, carried out over and over.
</P>
<P>
   The fruits of the Tribune-Herald/Central Texas Literacy
Coalition Storybook Christmas were shared, 14,805 books for little
ones in local grade schools and pre-schools.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't at any of the parties this year that distributed the
books, but I've been at several. And I've seen little ones hug
those books tightly and recoil momentarily from a grownup's reach.
Then they realize that rather than wanting to take the book away,
the grownup wants to share the book, read the book, to that child.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas, Hanukkah, holy observances near and far, find people
celebrating life and connectedness. When bombs fall and partisan
spears fly, it's easy to feel disgusted about our species.
</P>
<P>
   But among the rewards of this season is the abundant
demonstration that we are in fact an extraordinary species, with
extraordinary blessings and extraordinary opportunities to increase
our connectedness.
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course: Why does this need a season?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor at the Waco
Tribune-Journal. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
