<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time to take crash course in brakes
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How do you know when you need new brakes? What is that
squealing noise when stopping or the chirping noises while still on
the move? Why does the brake pedal vibrate when pushing on it to
stop?
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few of the questions that come up about brakes.
</P>
<P>
   I have a rule for teaching; I won't tell anyone how to fix
something before explaining how it works. So, sit back and let's
take a crash course on brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are several combinations of brake systems, they
all basically work the same. The parts of the system attached to
each wheel that actually stops the wheels are called either brake
rotors or brake drums.
</P>
<P>
   A brake drum looks like a heavy metal cake pan and is commonly
made of cast iron. Unless the car is very old, they are only used
on the rear wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Brake rotors, also called ``discs,'' are flat metal cast iron
disks and vary in thickness depending on the size of the vehicle.
They are used on the front wheels and are becoming more predominant
in rear brake use.
</P>
<P>
   Either the brake rotor or drum rotates with the wheel. The
stopping action of the wheel is achieved when the friction material
attached to a brake shoe (for drum brakes) or brake pad (disk
brakes) is forced against the spinning drum or disk. There are two
brake shoes or brake pads used at each wheel.
</P>
<P>
   All brake systems also must have a way to move the shoes or
rotors against the drum or disk. This is accomplished
hydraulically, with brake fluid, which is contained in a closed
system of cylinders, plungers, seals and tubing. Let's talk about
how all of this works, starting at the brake pedal and working
down.
</P>
<P>
   When you step on the pedal, it moves a rod that pushes a plunger
inside a cylinder, which in turn moves the brake fluid into a
network of tubes or brake lines. The principle is the same as the
hypodermic syringe a doctor or nurse uses to give you an injection.
</P>
<P>
   In need of assistance
</P>
<P>
   The pressurized fluid moves through the brake lines into another
cylinder mounted near the wheel, where the fluid pushes against
another plunger (piston).
</P>
<P>
   In a disc-brake system, the fluid pressure moves the piston
against the back of the brake pad, forcing it against the spinning
rotor. This action causes the wheel to stop.
</P>
<P>
   On drum brakes, the piston pushes against the brake shoe, which
is thrust against the inside of the rolling brake drum, stopping it
and the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Most brake systems use some form of power assist unit. The most
common type gets its help from the engine.
</P>
<P>
   However, power assist is not a frequent source of trouble.
Anti-lock brake systems also are separate so I'll save them for
later.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, I'll answer some specific questions about brakes. You
might want to keep this column so you can refer back to the terms
I've used today.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1. Write her in care of
Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta,
GA 30302. Or send comments online to
nora(at)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or 2wrenchs(at) bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
