<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Check the movie sites before you head out
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not clear when going to the movies became part of
the Christmas ritual, right up there with eggnog, mistletoe and
caroling.
</P>
<P>
   If movie reviews just don't do it for you or the malls are too
crowded, take a peek at this season's hottest offerings on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Major motion pictures seem to be the one group left that doesn't
understand packing as many applets, plug-ins and other bells and
whistles into one place does not necessarily a good Web site make.
While special effects may be a thrill in the theaters, they can be
a turnoff to movie lovers checking out movies on their home PCs.
Most of the new movie sites are inventive and informative, but be
prepared to download special tools or reboot your browser. And if
all else fails, you can always just see the movie in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's ever had even a brief encounter with America Online
will be intrigued by the title of the new Tom Hanks/Meg Ryan film
``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The title is a direct lift from the quasi-cheery message that
greets AOL users when they log on. The site at
http://www.youvegotmail.com offers pretty standard movie site fare
but includes some of the e-mail exchanges between the lead
characters, who go by the online screen names of Shopgirl and
NY152.
</P>
<P>
   The site also invites people who have met online to send in
their stories of real-life Net romance, which gives the movie's
plot a little more credibility as well as interesting reading. The
one trouble with the site is that it is an odd combination of a
marketing site and a creative site. It's a strange user experience,
but you'll learn something about the movie and about love online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt'' (http://www.prince-of-egypt.com), the
big, elaborate animated feature from DreamWorks, has an equally
big, elaborate animated Web site that really is something to see.
There's very little pointing and clicking; users can just sit and
watch the story unfold, almost like an actual movie trailer. The
site is available in several languages and offers a study guide,
special visual downloads (including a desktop music player), the
trailer for the film and a collection of images from the movie. The
brief synopsis of the film will also help parents and kids learn
more about the biblical characters before or after seeing the film.
This is a lovely site for a visually beautiful film.
</P>
<P>
   Trekkers, as they like to be called now, have probably already
bookmarked the site for the newest Star Trek feature, ``Star Trek
Insurrection.'' The builders of the Star Trek site clearly know
their audience, and the site is meant to replicate, if you will,
the computer images on the bridge of the Enterprise. This site
really is a trekker's paradise with creative tidbits such as the
``Briefing From the Federation Regarding the Prime Directive,''
desktop pictures, cast biographies (as if fans didn't already know
everything there is to know about Patrick Stewart and company),
audio interviews and more. This is a fans' site, clearly designed
for devotees of the ``Star Trek'' series and the inside references
to the series. The variety of interviews and pictures make this an
excellent promotional vehicle for the film as well as a nice
stand-alone site.
</P>
<P>
   For families that can't get enough and other grown-ups who
wonder what all the fuss is about, there is the Web site for the
Rugrats movie at http://www.rugratsmovie.com. It's easy to spend
hours on the Rugrats site, playing games, meeting the characters
(from baby Tommy's point of view), downloading screen savers and
just cooing over the characters. Since Rugrats is part of
Nickelodeon, the cable kids channel, the site is very careful to
avoid pitching products or trying to sell things to kids surfing
the site. Advertisements are clearly marked, and clicking on an ad
brings up a warning that users are about to view an ad. It's easy
to spend hours here bonding with the characters without a lot of
complicated Web gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW
</P>
<P>
   Royal Archive: Prince William: This comprehensive site is packed
with info on the young royal, from his height (an impressive 6 feet
1) to his dog (a creature named Widgeon), royal genealogy, the
royal estates, etc.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gilmer.net/royalty/william/
</P>
<P>
   Bed &AMP; Breakfast: Recipes and Cookbooks: This delectable site
features recipes from North American bed and breakfast inns, neatly
categorized by topic from muffins to Mountain Maple Poppyseed
Dressing.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bbonline.com/recipe/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
