<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX     12-21 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Only Senate can abort shameless coup by House
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Make no mistake: this is a partisan coup in constitutional form.
We have entered dangerous political territory, with potentially
grave consequences for our republic.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment of a president, to be legitimate, must be the
child of necessity. The impeachment of President Bill Clinton is
the bastard of a counterfeit necessity, born of an excuse trying to
pass as a reason.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted to impeach the president not because it had to
but because it could. The vote was more nearly an attempt to
overturn the last presidential election than it was the fulfillment
of a constitutional obligation. This over-reaching is itself closer
to the high crimes the constitution would disallow than are the
misdeeds alleged against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Now only the Senate can abort this coup, and while it is widely
assumed that will be the outcome _ one reason some moderate
Republicans, figuring they were working with a net, cravenly joined
the vote _ it seemed certain, too, just weeks ago that the House
would abandon impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that changed in the interim was a political
calculation. No new charges were brought; no new evidence surfaced.
The public did not take back its opposition to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, under intense pressure from the most extreme
Republicans _ and ramrodded by Majority Whip Tom DeLay, one of the
chamber's claw-and-fang partisans _ GOP moderates came more to fear
primary challenges from their radicalized party's right if they
didn't vote to impeach than to fear general-election punishment if
they did.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute alibiing for that shift was shameless.
</P>
<P>
   The president was held by some to fatal account for giving
slippery answers to 81 questions put to him by Judiciary Committee
Republicans. But the questions were a trap to set the president up
for eventual criminal conviction for perjury. He declined to hang
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Others complained the president was not repentant enough, but he
had repeatedly apologized. The president was being held to further
fatal account for failing to prove his sincerity to members in a
position simply to doubt his sincerity if it did not suit them to
be convinced of it.
</P>
<P>
   The very open question of whether the president committed
perjury, a narrowly-defined offense, is better settled in a
post-presidency trial, if it comes to that, than by this partisan
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Clinton is at the end what it seemed at the
start: that he lied all over the place in a desperate attempt not
to admit having had sex, sort of, with an intern. It was a shabby
performance _ hanky-panky and lying both _ but if personal
misconduct involving no misuse of presidential office is elevated
to a high crime, the precedent could reduce the presidency, and
with it national stability, to unsustainable frailty.
</P>
<P>
   In refusing to permit a vote on censure and instead impeaching
with an overwhelmingly party-line vote wholly based on a
prosecutor's slanted reading of uncrossexamined testimony, the
House has brought shame on itself and peril to the political
institutions of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
