A0109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING22-COX     12-21 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All I want for Christmas is Mustang hall
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When I made out my Christmas wish list this year,
there was one item not just for me, but for the Atlanta automotive
community at-large, especially those people who love Ford Mustangs.
I asked Santa to see what he could do about the location for the
Mustang museum.
</P>
<P>
   You are probably saying, ``What has Santa got to do with this?''
The location has been narrowed down to two finalists, Atlanta and
Orlando. It may take someone with the magic of Santa Claus to
offset the magic Orlando can bring to bear from the Disney
corporation, ABC television and even ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, on the other hand, has history in its favor. If it
weren't for a small group of Georgians who 22 years ago formed what
would grow to become the Mustang Club of America, the Mustang might
not even be in production today. Under the leadership of Dalton,
Ga., resident Bill Dillard, they launched what is today the world's
largest Mustang Club.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's first meeting was April 11, 1976, and by the
time the first Grand National show was held at Stone Mountain Park
that August, the membership had grown to 250 with more than 100
Mustangs and 1,200 enthusiasts in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   International status came quickly with over 600 names, including
many from foreign countries making up the roster at the second
Grand National event in 1977. As the club continued to grow, a
national headquarters was established in 1981 in Lithonia. Today
the Mustang Club of America has its headquarters in Stockbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are over 429 Mustang clubs worldwide and more
than 70,000 members who want to build a permanent facility as a
lasting tribute to their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, 25 metro areas were identified as potential sites.
Dillard said the mayor of Detroit even ``offered for free the land
that Tiger Stadium sits on. (But) there was no way we were going to
take responsibility for the destruction of another American icon,
even if the land was free!''
</P>
<P>
   Now the time is near to open the winning envelope. The ultimate
decision will be made by the Mustang Club of America's board of
directors next year.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 1, Ford Motor Co. donated $1.5 million toward the
museum's construction.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, while he is a fine fellow, I think Mickey Mouse has
enough coins and enough attractions. So, if you have ever owned a
Mustang, thought about owning a Mustang or even had a date in a
Mustang, let the club know how you feel. Its mailing address is
3588 Hwy. 138, Suite 365, Stockbridge, GA 30281 or e-mail at
mustang(at)mustang.org.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written exclusively for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
