<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rise of news sites on Web traced to Clinton scandal
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was the year the Internet joined CNN as one of
the prime places we turn for breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, his Gap-garbed intern and Kenneth Starr's
tell-all of their sloppy affair get most of the credit. The January
issue of Yahoo! Internet Life tells us why. The magazine's Top of
the Net for 1998 names Sept. 11, the day the Starr report was
released on the Internet, the year's top Net traffic day. The
report sent Internet traffic to an all-time high and, since it was
released in the morning, it likely dropped office productivity to
new lows. ``It was sleazy. It was sad. It was a political
earthquake,'' according to the article's read-in.
</P>
<P>
   The best-of list named the evolution of electronic commerce, Web
communities and portalmania the top Net trends. Portals are the new
name for search engines, which are trying to recast themselves as
more than just Internet on-ramps.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo DiCaprio and Pamela Anderson Lee were the names most
often typed into search engine windows. Leo edged Clinton in a
close race between male cyber-stalkees.
</P>
<P>
   There's less Intel Inside
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the company that makes the chips that power our PCs, is
losing market share.
</P>
<P>
   Intel processors, with their ubiquitous Intel Inside icon, went
from being in about 70 percent of all desktop PCs sold to somewhere
around 40 percent. Advanced Micro Devices has picked up the slack
and now leads the retail PC market for processor chips. Cyrix is
still a distance third.
</P>
<P>
   The chart, and a short explanation, are in the January 1999
issue of PC Computing.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also offers a seven-step cure to reduce the amount of
junk e-mail in your life. Death to Spam offers tips such as hiding
or ``spoofing'' your e-mail address should you post to a newsgroup.
Such postings usually list your e-mail address and leave you open
to software programs that search the Web for addresses. To
``spoof'' your address, just add an easily recognizable phrase to
your address, something that will fool a computer but not a person.
If your address is ed(at)aol.com, ``spoofing'' it would change it
to something like ed.ignorethispart(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   The article recommends simpler tricks. Like just ignoring it.
Like an annoying neighbor, responding to a junk e-mail usually
encourages more spam. Sending a return e-mail to the spam source
often just confirms yours is a valid address.
</P>
<P>
   Blabbing e-secrets
</P>
<P>
   They say telling a secret unburdens you. Depending on who is
involved, it also can louse up a friendship. An Internet site may
have split the difference, a chance to lay bare your conscience
anonymously, a scream in the a cyber-forest.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if the http://www
</P>
<P>
   .secretxchange.com postings are true? At the very least, they're
funny. This week's load-offs include ``Three Day Ordeal: I Glued
Myself to My Easy-Chair'' and ``I Threw Up on a Twenty Topping
Pizza and None of My Fraternity Brothers Even Noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret exchange idea started as a newsletter in 1994, which
led to a book, ``I Forgot to Wear Underwear on a Glass-Bottom
Boat,'' in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Business cards, updated
</P>
<P>
   They don't really fit into Rolodexes and are a hassle to
transcribe. But with CardScan, a software program from Corex
Technologies, you can scan your business cards and keep them on
your desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   The scanned cards create an interactive card file. If a business
card lists a Web address, CardScan lets you link directly to the
Internet site. Other features include direct modem access to any
fax numbers on the cards, the ability to merge the names with your
word processing program and the chance to add notes to the card
once its in your digital card file.
</P>
<P>
   CardScan's version 4 sells for $79. The software with a
dedicated card scanner sells for $299. The program is available in
office supply and computer stores and online at
http://www.cardscan.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
