<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apple giving it the old college try
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Apple's heyday, universities and colleges were a
bedrock of support. The company sold Macs to top universities at a
steep discount, and students became Apple Computer enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Many in academia remain Apple Computer fans, but support for the
company has seriously eroded over the past several years. Macs no
longer dominate college campuses. Some colleges, such as Yale, are
even trying to steer students away from Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Now Apple Computer is making a renewed push into higher
education. It has restored its advisory council of college
officials and announced a new program designed to encourage
students to develop software for Macs.
</P>
<P>
   And the company has created focus groups of students, deans and
professors. One of the things these focus groups have been looking
at is a new, low-cost portable computer Apple Computer hopes to
release sometime next year. This portable will be marketed
especially to the college market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to wade back into higher education,'' Interim
Chief Executive Steve Jobs told a technology conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Apple Computer reigned supreme on college campuses,
and Jobs was responsible for that. During his first tenure at Apple
Computer during the 1980s, he targeted both universities and their
students as an important market for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs created a unique partnership with higher education called
the Apple University Consortium. It consisted of representatives
from 24 elite campuses.
</P>
<P>
   These colleges agreed to buy thousands of Macs at prices up to
50 percent off retail. It was a winning combination that helped
establish the Mac in its early years.
</P>
<P>
   But then Apple Computer began to take colleges for granted, and
it lost much of its share in this market. Some are skeptical Apple
Computer can regain much of the lost ground. But the company is
determined to give it the old college try.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
