<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrating the season along with new cycles
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My son Kristofor and I have been together for
31
</P>
<P>
   Christmases now, and we've run the gift wish list gamut from
Pooh bears and model trains to computers and cars. Even though I'll
always miss the little guy in the footy pajamas who would scuffle
into my bedroom at daybreak to announce:
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun is up and Sandy Claus has been here,'' this Christmas
promises to be the best one ever.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor was only four months old the first time Santa came to
call. He didn't quite know what to make of the colored lights and a
tree growing in the living room, but his baby eyes danced with
excitement anyway. That was the year his grandmother gave him a
giant stuffed tiger. It was a love match at first sight and by
afternoon the pair were napping together under the Christmas tree -
the boy sprawled on top in guileless baby sleep, drooling in the
tiger's ear.
</P>
<P>
   By the time his second Christmas rolled around, Kristofor had
forgotten all about the first one so his father and I decided to
make it a big surprise. We waited until he was tucked in for the
night before putting up the tree and hauling presents down from the
attic. Somewhere around the house I have a faded Polaroid of a
curly-haired toddler on Christmas morning, all zipped up in a fuzzy
bunny sleeper and frozen in his tracks at the living room door as
he catches his first glimpse of the lighted tree.
</P>
<P>
   A second shot shows him just moments later reaching for a
particularly shiny
</P>
<P>
   ornament that has caught his fancy. The final shot is of a
puzzled little boy with his mouth in a wide-open ``O'' as he stares
at the pieces of the ornament scattered on the floor at the foot of
the tree.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, for his two-year-old Christmas, there was an easel
with a sketch pad and a king-size box of tempera paints. On the
first warm day I slipped one of his father's old T-shirts over his
sun suit and helped him set up a studio in the back yard. He said
he was going to paint the pine trees. I told him I thought that was
a dandy idea. A while later I came back to check on his progress.
There was no paint on the sketch pad but he had indeed painted the
pine trees - some yellow and a whole lot blue. It never occurred to
me to ask the obvious question in advance.
</P>
<P>
   This was also the year of the shiny red fire engine - the one
that boasted two removable ladders, and ran on a car battery with
enough juice to take him a few times around the neighborhood
fighting fires and rescuing treed cats before
</P>
<P>
   it needed recharging.
</P>
<P>
   When Kristofor was 3, he and his dad did a back-to-nature thing
and went out into the country to cut their own tree. I have a
picture of that too. He's the short one with the swagger and a
hatchet tucked into the hammer loop of his overalls. He says that
was a great year because in addition to helping his dad cut the big
tree, he was allowed to cut a sapling (which he now feels badly
about) for his very own to decorate any way he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   We've had some memorable Christmases along the way. One of our
favorites was
</P>
<P>
   spent in Cortina D'Ampezzo, a storybook village in the Italian
Alps. We remember window shopping and listening to the church bells
on Christmas Eve. No glitz just the snow and some friendly people
wishing us Merry Christmas in Italian. We answered in kind.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, it was easy to tell the age of the boy by
the presents under the tree. They ranged from Playskool filling
stations to archery equipment with straw targets that mildewed in
the southern humidity. Soon, chemistry sets and ant farms had given
way to requests for computers and car insurance.
</P>
<P>
   And almost before I knew it, Christmas became a brief vacation
to be spent at
</P>
<P>
   home. The holiday season signaled the arrival of duffels of
dirty laundry and a
</P>
<P>
   college boy who slept until noon and spent the rest of his time
emptying the
</P>
<P>
   refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Christmases through the years have been good for us, but this
one is going to
</P>
<P>
   be the best of them all. This year I'll be packing up the
presents and driving to Pennsylvania to spend the holidays with my
son, his fiancee, and the family
</P>
<P>
   we're going to be marrying into.
</P>
<P>
   And so the cycle begins again. New wish lists, new generations,
and eventually a new Pooh bear or two - and I intend to be the lady
carrying the tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Send mail to: 320
West
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
