<SLUG> BC-TECHMEDIA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anyone can exterminate pesky bugs
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   IN PRINT
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled that the box is sealed in shiny plastic wrap.
Many pieces of software, even from the biggest companies, are far
from finished when shipped to stores. Most include at least some
bug, which is computerese for a glitch or feature that doesn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, most common bugs are fixable. The January issue of PC
World features a story called ``Bug Busters: Top cures &AMP; fixes for
software snarls.'' You'll find a list of the 10 worst bugs, tricks
for working around glitches and Web sites where you can download
something called a patch, which is a mini-program that fixes buggy
software.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue of PC World, you'll also find a review of the
top 10 high-resolution digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   With the latest generation of digital cameras, the article says
image quality is advancing rapidly _ and so is the list of
features. Among the cameras examined, PC World recommends Toshiba's
PDR-M1 as the best deal. The magazine says this camera offers the
most at the best price ($499).
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Girls are increasingly becoming the target of CD-ROM makers. It
seems every month brings news of yet another title to be marketed
to girls. The latest is Activision's ``Teen Digital Diva.''
Designed for the teen market, this computer CD lets girls create
their own magazine. Players do virtual makeovers, try out clothes,
generate personal horoscopes and take personality quizzes. The CD
is based on Teen magazine and comes with tons of animations, music
clips and color schemes.
</P>
<P>
   If you're serious about your flight simulators, check out the
latest from Electronic Arts called ``WWII Fighters.'' It's a game
based on designs from Jane's, the world-famous military magazine of
the same name. This game lets you fly seven famous WWII fighters.
It also includes lots of information about each of the planes and
its role in history.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   No, the Geminids meteor shower, among the largest in recorded
history, did not knock out satellites or disrupt communications
back on Earth, as feared.
</P>
<P>
   It was still darn interesting, and now you can learn all about
it online. There's an entire Web site devoted to the phenomenon.
You'll find it at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.geminids.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
