<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holidays a good time to reflect on computers' magic
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Christmas has always been a confusing time for me. I
hate the months of department store carols that lead up to it, am
deeply traumatized by shopping of any kind, and have to fight a
neurotic desire to sing the only song to which I know all the
words: ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer.''
</P>
<P>
   But I can't deny the magic and wouldn't if I could. I have the
same love-hate relationship with the gadgets that surround me.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when I get pleading e-mails asking what
to give a geek for the holidays. Parents, overwhelmed by the
computer wizardry of their kids, feel helpless at a time like this.
And maybe because I have a beard and am getting past the middle of
middle age, some mistake me for Santa's high-tech adviser.
</P>
<P>
   I make a puzzling elf, they soon discover. I just finished
answering a long e-mail from a reader who explained that her child
already had a 400-megahertz computer, a paid-up membership to an
Internet service provider and access to the family's home theater.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how I answered:
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad you asked. I know a way to multiply the value of all
your gadgets and make the computer's power much more amazing. I
know you expect to spend money to do this, and that's good because
my suggestions will cost $23 and change.
</P>
<P>
   The real wonder of technology is understanding how magical it
is, and this is the right time of the year for magic. With that in
mind, I've prepared a Christmas gift list for you.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's work on increasing the power of that computer. For
$13 you can buy a book by Joel N. Shurkin for your child called
``Engines of the Mind: The Evolution of the Computer From
Mainframes to Microprocessors.'' This isn't a geeky book, and even
I know most of the words in it. The publisher is W.W. Norton and
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Once your child reads that book, he'll understand he owns a
computer more powerful than the ones that ran big businesses and
government agencies a decade ago. When he pops in his favorite
video game, he'll appreciate the magical nature of a machine that
creates entire worlds using the words, letters and symbols that
make up a computer program.
</P>
<P>
   It's better he hear it straight from a book that the
400-megahertz computer chip is mostly made of silicon, an element
common as sand. And if you told him the circuits on that chip, all
those tiny transistors, are merely photographic etchings, he might
not believe you.
</P>
<P>
   So for $10 or so, you've turned what was a good computer into a
magical machine. You can't match that for $1,000 down at the
computer store.
</P>
<P>
   If you still have $10 more to spare, we can change the Internet
into something magical, too. We can take those chat groups and Web
pages and wrap them in some paper. The paper I'm talking about
comes from another book called ``Where Wizards Stay Up Late: The
Origins of the Internet.'' It's by Katie Hafner and is published by
Touchstone Books.
</P>
<P>
   Your child will discover that many of the pioneers of the Net
weren't much older than he is. They couldn't point and click in
those days, because the mouse wasn't an option 25 years ago.
Instead, they wrote programs that let them link computers together
and _ like a bunch of harnessed mules _ learn to work together and
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time your child logs onto a chat group and says
nothing much is happening, he may remember there are still enormous
things to be done with a computer that have nothing at all to do
with telling the hangers-on at some chat channel that he's bored
beyond words.
</P>
<P>
   None of this stuff requires a battery and _ even when you factor
in the cost of wrapping paper _ you'll spend less than what a game
from the discount bin costs.
</P>
<P>
   Have a wonderful holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
