<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A22-COX     12-21 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter and I visited a new car dealership. She selected
a car and left her car as a trade-in. The papers were not signed
but we agreed on the transaction details. Later that week the
dealership called and said the deal was off. When my daughter
returned the new car, the dealer said her old car had already been
sold! She is still driving the new car. The dealership says maybe
they can make her a new deal on the car. Do we need an attorney?
_Ben Polambi
</P>
<P>
   A: No, you need the Motor Vehicle Board. Before I could finish
relating your story, Heidi Jackson, licensing director of the MVB,
said, ``And they already sold her car.'' This is de-horsing _ as in
``to take your horse (the old car) away.'' The consumer ends up
either paying more for the new car than originally agreed, settling
for a less expensive car, reaching less favorable terms or (imagine
this) with no car at all, leaving both new and used cars with the
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   De-horsing is illegal and expensive (fines up to $10,000 per day
per offense _ hello!). Do not sign anything until you have
contacted the MVB, the agency charged with overseeing car dealers.
After completing the paperwork an investigator will contact the
dealer. ``Sometimes it only takes a call from us,'' says Jackson,
and either the original deal or the old car appears. Magic.Q: I
have been searching diligently for gifts for my Jewish ``secret
pal'' for Hanukkah, but I only find Christmas things. Do you know a
store with inexpensive, appropriate gift items? I also would like
to find Jewish items _ a dreidel (a spinning top), a menorah, etc.
_ to help my students experience all types of holidays. _L.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Linens 'N Things, Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond and Cost Plus carry
Hanukkah decorative items _ serving pieces, menorahs, tableware.
Stein Mart also has some items.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can we get Flutie Flakes, Doug Flutie's fund-raising
cereal? The proceeds benefit autism research. _J.A.N.
</P>
<P>
   A: Flutie is the talented and attractive quarterback of the
Buffalo Bills. Winner of the Heisman in 1984, Flutie played in the
Canadian Football League for several years. To purchase Flutie
Flakes call (888) BUF-GEAR or go online at buffalobills.com. The
flakes, a product of sports marketing firm PLB Sports, are $10 a
box with shipping but worth every penny, since a portion of the
proceeds goes to the Doug Flutie Jr. Foundation for Autism. Doug
Jr. was diagnosed with the neurological and developmental disorder
three years ago. Need more? How about a Flutie Flakes T-shirt? Send
a check for $15.95 to PLB Sports, P.O. Box 99185, Pittsburgh, Pa.
15233.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My home economics group is having a social, and for one of
the questions in our questionnaire, I want to use the cost of ``The
12 Days of Christmas'' for 1998. If you know where to find this,
could you tell me? _Julia Krizak
</P>
<P>
   A: According to PNC Bank, this year's 12 days of indulgence will
run $58,405.09, about a 6 percent increase over last year's cost.
One of the big winners in 1998? Nine ladies dancing received a
20-percent wage increase over last year, putting the ladies'
salaries higher than men (traditionally) in the standard song.
Sorry, lords-a-leaping, drummers drumming and pipers piping. (It's
high time, some may say.) Unfortunately maids-a-milking are still
receiving minimum wage. In a few years, automation may do in the
maids altogether. For a complete accounting, visit
www.pncbank.com/12 days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a red wine stain on a light oak table. The stain has
been there since Thanksgiving of 1996 (why hurry?). Is there any
remedy other than sanding the surface and refinishing the table?
Please give me hope. _Sarah Phillips
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe someone will spill something else and cover it up this
year? Jim Neuberger, furniture magician, says what you do depends
on the finish. You can try a dab of a water/bleach solution (just a
teaspoon of bleach in a cup of water) or Murphy's Oil Soap. Chances
are the tabletop will need a professional. If the table gets a lot
of use, ask the refinisher for a polyurethane finish to prevent
future problems.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Colin Powell doll I mentioned recently includes a display
of the America-- Division patch, not ``America-- .'' Mea culpa. The
Americal Division is the only Army division created outside the
continental United States and south of the equator, according to
Cecil A. Green of the Public Affairs Office, III Corps and Fort
Hood. Originally formed in 1942 in New Caledonia, the name
``Americal'' derives from ``American Forces in New Caledonia.'' The
blue division patch has four stars, representing the Southern
Cross, the dominant constellation in the Southern Hemisphere. Thank
you to the soldiers who served in this division in World War II and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tips from ``The Old Farmer's Almanac Traditional Holiday
Recipes'' for those poinsettias decking your halls: Keep the soil
evenly moist and place the plant in a sunny location (65 to 72
degrees), away from drafts and frosty windows. If a poinsettia
drops a few leaves when you bring it into the house, check the
light level and the humidity. The air may be too dry.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
