<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOTIES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After 50 years, this popular game has legs (and eyes, ears and a
proboscis)
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's hard to believe, but we've had Cooties for
50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Not the kind you get from kissing girls. I'm talking about the
plastic ones that come disassembled in a cardboard box.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro, manufacturer of Cooties, is celebrating the golden
anniversary of the venerable children's game this year by doing a
complete makeover on the bugs that are central to the game.
</P>
<P>
   And while I'm not much of a traditionalist, I kind of wish they
had left well enough alone.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hasbro, a Minneapolis mailman carved the first
Cooties from wood in 1948. He was trying to design a fishing lure,
but Cooties attracted more kids than carp.
</P>
<P>
   The mailman carved by hand 40,000 wooden Cootie games for
children over the next year, and three years a toy company used
machinery to make 1.2 million of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro estimates about 50 million Cootie games have been
purchased in the 50-year history of the toy.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1998 Cootie is clearly different from its 1948 ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   The original Cootie had a plastic body with holes for six
plastic legs and a head. Each head had holes where two antennae,
two eyes and a proboscis could be inserted.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played by rolling a die and adding parts to your
Cootie according to what you rolled. Ones were bodies, sixes were
legs and so on. The first player with a complete Cootie won.
</P>
<P>
   Except for body color, each of the four Cooties that came with
the game were the same.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cooties are more varied. They can be built with roller
skates or gloved fingers; hair bows or antennae; kissing lips or
buck teeth.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the changes deprive the Cooties of some of their homely
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the fun of playing Cootie with my brothers and sister as
a child was making fun of the pathetic half-built Cooties in the
middle of the game.
</P>
<P>
   There were three-legged cripple Cooties, and cockeyed Cooties,
and stone-deaf Cooties and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cooties are trying so hard to be cute, it's no fun
trashing them.
</P>
<P>
   My 8-year-old daughter played with the 1998 Cooties several
times over a recent weekend before losing interest. That's more
attention than she gives stuffed animals, but much less attention
than she gives anything with a video screen.
</P>
<P>
   She proclaimed Cooties ``OK,'' but they were no match for
Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
