<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUILD-BETTER-MOSQUITO     12-21 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILD-BETTER-MOSQUITO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Scientists working to change genetic makeup of mosquito
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Scientists in Texas and elsewhere are working to
change the genetic makeup of a malaria-causing mosquito whose bite
kills nearly 3 million people a year worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to build a benign mosquito is considered a scientific
long shot, but the stakes are enormous. As many as 500 million
people a year in tropical Mexico, Central and South American,
Africa and Asia are infected by the Anopheles mosquitoes, according
to the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making progress quicker than we thought we could,'' said
Greg Lanzaro, a medical entomologist at the University of Texas'
Center for Tropical Diseases in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to recent genetic advances and a discovery by Lanzaro,
some mosquito project scientists say the effort might move out of
the laboratory and into the field by 2003, 15 years sooner than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a paradigm shift in approach, and experimental of course,
but so were insecticides at one time,'' said Anthony James, a
moleucular geneticist at the University of California at Irvine who
is working with Lanzaro and other project scientists. ``And we're
running out of insecticides because the mosquitoes are resistant to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say if altering mosquito genes to prevent the bugs
from spreading malaria worked in Africa, where Anopheles gambiae _
one of about 60 species of the mosquitoes _ carries the deadliest
form of the disease, the remedy could be swiftly shifted to the
Americas and to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Success not only would eliminate a scourge that's plagued
humanity for thousands of years, but could lead to similar
campaigns against other insects that spread killer diseases such as
yellow fever and dengue.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way to engineer insects might even provide clues for
ongoing efforts to use gene therapy to reverse inherited genetic
defects in people. The attempt to build a better mosquito is not
without critics. Andrew Spielman of the Harvard School of Public
Health argues that the effort cannot succeed because genetic
engineering of even thousands of Anopheles mosquitoes, which were
then turned loose to breed in the wild, could not be sustained
through many generations of their descendents.
</P>
<P>
   Nature provides no guarantee that specific genes in any species
will be transmitted from parent to offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a major challenge of making Anopheles mosquitoes benign
is not only to find genes to prevent them from transmitting the
parasite that causes malaria, but a mechanism to insure that the
anti-parasite genes can be spread widely among their offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But, this year, researchers in the 5-year-old Anopheles
improvement project have made significant advances toward both
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at New York and Duke universities and the National
Institutes of Health have identified two characteristics that
prevent some mosquitoes from transmitting the parasite. They're
looking for the genes responsible.
</P>
<P>
   James, and a colleague at the University of Notre Dame,
meanwhile, have identified genetic mechanisms called transposable
elements, in houseflies and Mediterranean fruit flies, that might
be used to force transmission of engineered genes from parent
mosquitoes to their offspring.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers demonstrated the usefulness of the transposable
elements, also called ``gene driver systems,'' by using them to
change the eye color in 10 generations of Aedes aegypti, a mosquito
that transmits yellow fever.
</P>
<P>
   Lanzaro also has removed a potential roadblock. Previous
research suggested that the three known subgroups of Anopheles
gambiae don't interbreed. Collecting some of them in Mali, in West
Africa, and analyzing their genetic make-up, Lanzaro recently
discovered that two of the three subgroups do mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a pattern that suggests there's lots of mating
going on,'' Lanzaro said.
</P>
<P>
   While some project scientists hunt for anti-parasite genes,
others are considering alternative approaches.
</P>
<P>
   James, for instance, favors transplanting a gene from a mouse's
immune system into Anopheles gambiae to make proteins to kill the
parasites. Others are trying to figure out why the mosquito's
immune system doesn't attack the parasite, and find ways to force
it to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best solution will be adopted, or maybe two or three of
them,'' James said. ``It's hard to say what the preferred way will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenging as it is, the researchers see the effort as easier
than trying to bring the political stability and sophisticated
health care required for a sustained malaria control effort to the
poor countries of the tropical world most afflicted by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is very efficiently keeping malaria down,'' Lanzaro
said. ``If local authorities uncover transmissions, they spray
quickly. But it's getting worse every year in Central and South
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get this to work in (tropical) Africa, we can pretty
much get it to work anywhere, because the problems there are
formidable. They're very poor, there's little health infrastructure
and there's political instability.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
