<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LBJ-LIBRARY22-COX     12-21 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LBJ-LIBRARY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inaugurating the gallery
 &HT;    By Janet Wilson
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lyndon Baines Johnson was sitting in the dining
room of the Driskill Hotel, anxiously awaiting a sophisticated dame
he had met at the Texas Railroad Commission the day before. Johnson
had asked her to join him for breakfast and now was worried she had
changed her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Alta ``Lady Bird'' Taylor was having second thoughts.
She had joined the strapping and intense admirer for drinks the
night before, but had a ``sort of queer moth-in-the-flame feeling
about this remarkable young man,'' she said in ``The President's
Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when she passed the hotel window and saw him sitting in
the dining room alone, Lady Bird decided to join Lyndon Johnson.
They shared a meal that August day in 1934 and then drove into the
country where the future president did everything he could,
including propose marriage, to impress this woman who had caught
his eye.
</P>
<P>
   A two-month, whirlwind courtship ensued, forever changing the
life of the shy young woman from East Texas whose ambition was to
be a teacher in some place exotic, like Alaska or Hawaii. Instead,
she traveled the world as a loving and supportive wife to the late
President Johnson, an author, a savvy businesswoman, a champion of
education and conservation and a mother, grandmother and
great-grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, a permanent exhibit opens at the LBJ Library and
Museum celebrating her life, from Lady Bird's graduation from the
University of Texas through 38 years as the wife of a consummate
politician to the legacy she created after her husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   While Lady Bird always has been included in the permanent
exhibits of the museum, the focus has been on her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've done a permanent exhibit on Mrs.
Johnson that was dedicated strictly to her,'' says curator Lisa
Royse.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady's Gallery is a loving memoir of a Southern lady
who left gentle fingerprints on America's landscape and who, as she
turns 86 tomorrow, continues to earn admiration for her dignity and
grace. It was carved out of space on the eighth floor of the
library next door to the replica of President Johnson's Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-square-foot hall, formerly offices for Lady Bird and
her staff, highlights programs she actively promoted while first
lady, such as Head Start, VISTA and the National Park Service, as
well as her life after the White House and today, as she champions
the importance of wildflowers through the Lady Bird Johnson
Wildflower Center.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery is being opened now because Lady Bird, whose vision
is severely limited because of macular degeneration, has decided to
curtail some of her public appearances and open her office to
museum visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area tells about the life and times of Lady Bird
Johnson,'' says her daughter, Luci Baines Johnson, walking through
the gallery and pointing to walls that hold photographs and quotes
from and about Lady Bird. ``You can't tell the story of Lyndon
Johnson without telling the story of his best friend and
helpmate.''
</P>
<P>
   The office Lady Bird used for 28 years is exactly as she left
it. The credenza is topped by photographs of family and friends,
and her desk, made of burnt orange lacquered wood and brass, offers
a sweeping view of downtown Austin, the Texas Capitol, and Darrell
K Royal-Texas Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The caboose platform Lady Bird used while campaigning for her
husband in the 1964 presidential election has been re-created, and
artifacts and memorabilia are displayed throughout. In another
area, visitors can hear Lady Bird reading previously unreleased
recordings from her book, ``A White House Diary.''
</P>
<P>
   Snippets of historic moments always attract visitors. But it's
the personal items in the exhibit _ notes she made critiquing her
husband's speeches, home movies she took of their early life
together and of daughters Luci and Lynda as children, and love
letters Lady Bird and Lyndon exchanged during their courtship _
that stir the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the letters, which Luci Johnson says show ``a wonderful
sense of youth and intimacy,'' are displayed, while others are
featured through dramatic readings performed in 1977 by Kirk
Douglas and the late Helen Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   These missives of love and devotion between Lyndon, who was in
Washington, D.C., as secretary to a congressman, and Lady Bird, who
was at her father's home in Karnack, overseeing a reconstruction
project, have an almost frantic quality, as if Lyndon feared if
they waited too long they might never be married.
</P>
<P>
   Darling, ...I haven't had a letter from you since Saturday _ it
was written Thursday . I'm not fussing, just checking up on Uncle
Sam's efficient postal service. ... Tell me you love me if you want
to and if you don't I'll believe you do anyway and keep on loving
you every minute ... Here is a big hug-kiss and the everlasting
love of Lyndon Baines.
</P>
<P>
   Austinite Nicole Nugent Covert, Lady Bird's
granddaughter,marvels that her grandparents knew one another less
than three months when they married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Nini (Lady Bird) about their courtship and
asked her how she knew so fast that it was right,'' says Covert.
``My grandfather asked her to marry him on the first date and that
was a little too fast for her. She says he was so persistent. She
says they just knew it was right, but for her piece of mind they
needed to wait a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Covert says this is the first time she has seen most of the
letters, written when her grandparents were younger than she is
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really beautiful, like poetry,'' says Covert. ``They
flow so well.
</P>
<P>
   President Johnson, who left Washington in 1969, died at the LBJ
Ranch near Stonewall on Jan. 22, 1973. Lady Bird said then that it
would be ``ungracious not to be terribly grateful for 38 wonderful
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Their love story, spawned over coffee in a hotel dining room 64
years ago and re-created in the First Lady's Gallery, continues
today, says Lyndon Nugent, Lady Bird's grandson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously she's gone on with her life, but she still misses
him,'' says Nugent, an attorney in San Antonio. ``It's been a long
time, but she still gets nostalgic and a little sad that on
Christmas morning when she wakes up he won't be there to sit down
with her, or when she goes to bed and he won't be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's never gotten over it, but she's gotten used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
