<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES2     12-21 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES22-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: A holiday gift from the bride
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My granddaughter, Mira, is 2 1/2. This was the first Chanukkah
of which she was fully aware. By about 10 o'clock, the holiday
candles long since guttered out, and drugged by gifts, attention
and fatigue, Mira retrieved a cotton baby blanket, draped it over
her head like a veil, declared herself to be a bride, and began to
dance around the room.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if you're not the child's grandparent, such a performance
is usually considered insufferable, but if you are the child's
grandparent, it's delightful and extremely appealing. We started
applauding and laughing, and Mira responded by dancing even more,
even more furiously.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a while, and the appeal of cuteness being quickly
finite, we began to lose focus. Mira, sensing that her bid for
stardom was slipping away, made a little leap, froze in place, then
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop! Please! The bride is very danceable . . . and singing!''
</P>
<P>
   No one knew what it meant, and we made the big mistake of
laughing. Once you laugh at a kid's gooniness, you've lost control.
Mira beamed. A new chapter had entered the family book of memories.
</P>
<P>
   May all your brides be danceable . . . and singing.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 0929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
