<P>
   SOCSEC-REVIEW (Undated) _ Imagine you could save the Social
Security system from bankruptcy by raising every American's
retirement check _ without increasing taxes. Such is the radical
cure proposed by Martin Feldstein, a chief economic adviser to
President Ronald Reagan and a professor of economics at Harvard
University, who made his case earlier this month at a conference
sponsored by the White House. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-REVIEW (Undated) _ Even analysts who urge the United States
to actively promote a coup d'etat against Saddam Hussein and
consider the sanctions a useful form of pressure on the regime say
that getting to the dictator will be extremely difficult physically
and politically. Some experts note that the Iraqi people still
accept and support Saddam, and that the bombings have little effect
on people accustomed to suffering. By Youssef Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARMS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Seven years after Saddam Hussein
promised to come clean about his weapons of mass destruction, and
days after yet another military confrontation with the West over
his continuing refusal to do so, the book on Iraqi arms is still
riddled with holes. Military experts say the unanswered questions
are serious and legion. Still unaccounted for are hundreds of
chemical arms, tons of nerve gas, more than 100 germ weapons and
parts for up to four nuclear warheads, which are said to lack only
the uranium to fuel them. By William J. Broad and Judith Miller.
WITH GRAPHIC on Iraqi arms positions.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-DESERTFOX (Undated) _ A look at the origins of the name
Operation Desert Fox. By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-LEADERS-REVIEW (Miami) _ All across Latin America,
presidents and party leaders are looking over their shoulders. With
his landslide victory in Venezuela's presidential election on Dec.
6, Hugo Chavez has revived an all-too-familiar specter that the
region's ruling elite thought they had safely interred: that of the
populist demagogue, the authoritarian man on horseback known as the
caudillo. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-CHRISTMAS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christmas has returned to
Cuba; Cubans are once again free to observe the holidays. By Mirta
Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
