<P>
   _ By PAM BELLUCK
</P>
<P>
   Questions About Truth Of Nobel Winner's Book
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the 1992 Nobel Peace Prize, Rigoberta Menchu of
Guatemala, has had her reputation tarnished a bit as a result of a
new book, written by an American anthropologist, that questions the
truthfulness of the autobiography that made her famous.
</P>
<P>
   David Stoll of Middlebury College spent nearly a decade
researching Ms. Menchu's account, and found that the Nobel laureate
fabricated the circumstances in which some relatives died, received
an education she claimed not to have and comes from a family that
owned land she claimed it never possessed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Menchu responded angrily to the accusations, saying, ``This
is my testimony and I will defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By LARRY ROHTER
</P>
<P>
   Koreans Clone Human Cell
</P>
<P>
   South Korean scientists said they had cloned a human cell from
an infertile woman, creating an embryo that theoretically could
have grown into an identical replica of the woman. But because of
the legal and ethical implications of their work, they said, they
stopped the experiment and did not try to create a human clone. The
research has already caused controversy. Korean groups are calling
for a ban on such experiments.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL WuDUNN
</P>
<P>
   In Puerto Rican Vote, None of the Above
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in six years, Puerto Ricans rebuffed their
Governor's efforts to win statehood. In a referendum, ``None of the
above'' was their top choice, a selection promoted as a protest by
those who want to maintain the current commonwealth relationship
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The other options were commonwealth, ``free association'' (a
form of independence that delegates certain powers by treaty to the
United States), statehood and independence. The winning option got
50.2 percent of the vote, compared with 46.5 percent for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Historically divided over whether to seek a closer association
with the United States through statehood or to remain distinctly
self-governing, the electorate this time was split among options
that confused some voters and angered many others. The small vote
for the option to maintain commonwealth status was evidence of
this, reflecting a boycott by the pro-commonwealth Popular
Democratic Party, which claimed the definition of that option was
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Charges in Disappearance Of New York Millionaire
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged the lead suspects in the disappearance of an
elderly Manhattan woman with murder, setting the stage for a trial
next year that would be one of the rare cases where a murder is
prosecuted without the victim's body being found.
</P>
<P>
   Sante Kimes, 64, and her son Kenneth, 24, carried out a
sophisticated scheme to defraud Irene Silverman of her ornate Upper
East Side Manhattan mansion, according to an 84-count indictment.
And they left a detailed paper trail, including notes about the
scheme and a forged deed transferring the mansion to a corporation
they control, according to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID ROHDE
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unraveling the Hiss Case
</P>
<P>
   Was Alger Hiss a spy, or was he steamrolled by McCarthyism? That
question has gnawed at the country for half a century, and despite
seemingly damning evidence from Soviet archives, there's no firm
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in yet another effort to nibble away at this mystery, a
group of scholars has asked a federal judge to unseal grand jury
records of the Hiss perjury case. Even as they did so, though, one
historian conceded that the puzzle would probably remain unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Happy Christmas, Merry New Year
</P>
<P>
   In China, a growing passion for things Western has in recent
years meant a special interest in Christmas, especially among
fashion-conscious young people.
</P>
<P>
   Friends exchange gifts, stores force sales clerks to wear Santa
suits _ young women are often persuaded to wear the miniskirt
version _ and there is a lively trade in Christmas cards.
</P>
<P>
   With such a large cultural divide between East and West, perhaps
it is inevitable that something gets lost in translation. A typical
card reads: ``Wish you all the luck in the Uorld!'' and the
accompanying message says: ``You're here, There's nothing I fear,
And I know that my heart will go on, We'll stay forever this way,
You are safe in my heart, And my heart mill go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   In another card, Santa is pictured on the Western side of the
Earth exchanging gazes with a Chinese god of fortune in the East,
with the message: ``As the world is round, the far end of East is
West and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   A card entitled ``Friendship,'' displays champagne and flowers,
with the message, translated from Chinese: ``Time is like flowing
water _ once passed it cannot be recovered. Friends are like old
wine; getting better with age.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing about Christmas or the New Year on this card,
but hey, it's the thought that counts.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH FAISON
</P>
<P>
   Lord Lloyd Webber for the Defense
</P>
<P>
   Does it often seem that Andrew Lloyd Webber is everywhere? Well,
it's more serious than you thought.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do his musicals _ so many of them! _ hang around
Broadway just about forever, but he could recently be found in a
New York courtroom giving a piano rendition of a snippet from
``Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   A little moonlighting, perhaps? A midday gig to soften jurors'
hearts? No, it turns out that nearly a decade ago _ a mere blip in
the typical run of a Lloyd Webber blockbuster _ a composer named
Ray Repp was listening to a ``Phantom'' CD and said: ``Holy Cow! He
stole my song.''
</P>
<P>
   Or so he asserted near the end of an eight-year legal battle to
prove that Lloyd Webber stole a passage from his 1978 song ``Till
You'' (sales: $75.87) and made it the main theme of ``Phantom''
(sales: $1 billion or so).
</P>
<P>
   So Lord Lloyd Webber took to the keyboard himself as he gave his
version of the birth of the song.
</P>
<P>
   On Repp's behalf, two music professors testified to the
compositions' similarities. But with composers great and small
routinely borrowing phrases, the whole notion of tracing musical
lineage is frightfully slippery _ DNA evidence is no help whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber, in fact, countersued in 1991, saying Repp had in
fact stolen one of HIS tunes. He lost, as did Repp this time. In
little more than an hour, the jury bestowed originality on Lloyd
Webber.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
