<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTA-IMPEACHED!-HUMO     12-21 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-IMPEACHED!-HUMOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA CLAUS IS IMPEACHED! 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a controversial and partisan vote, the
Republican-majority House of Representatives has voted to impeach
Santa Claus, aka ``Kris Kringle,'' aka ``St. Nick,'' aka ``Jolly
Old Nick.''
</P>
<P>
   The grounds? Perjury, obstruction of justice, eavesdropping,
mail fraud, operating an illegal monopoly ... and other ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time in modern history that a fabled holiday
character has been impeached. (Of course, The Grinch Who
 &UR; allegedly &LR;  Stole Christmas would have faced an impeachment hearing
and almost-certain conviction in 1957 had he not experienced a
change of heart and returned an estimated $1.2 million in gifts and
personal possessions to the constituents of Whoville.)
</P>
<P>
   Claus has perennially achieved astronomical approval ratings
with the public, but he has also been the subject of rumors and
innuendo about the way he conducts his seasonal gift-giving
business _ including almost-yearly allegations that his North Pole
headquarters are ``gingerbread sweatshops,'' as one workers' rights
group once put it.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years there also have been pointed questions and
numerous inquiries into the near-total monopoly on business enjoyed
by Claus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy makes Bill Gates look like a social worker,'' said
Rep. Henry Hyde (R.-Ill.), who led the charge to impeach Claus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees you when you're sleeping, he knows when you're
awake!'' cried Rep. Dan Burton (R.-Ind.), who called for the
ambassador to the North Pole to immediately return to the United
States as a safety measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like people seeing me when I'm sleeping, and I sure as
heck don't want 'em to know when I'm awake!'' Burton said. ``Big
Brother is alive and well, apparently.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day marked by stunning developments, prompting the
cable networks CNN, MSNBC and Fox News to cancel regularly
scheduled programming in favor of nonstop coverage. (The original
Big Three networks provided frequent updates, while Fox TV carried
on with its planned lineup, including a two-hour special, ``When
Animals Attack Criminals Who Are Caught on Tape in the Act of
Stealing From Strippers' Dressing Rooms.'')
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders filled the air with passionate rhetoric. In a
press conference after the vote was held, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott (R.-Miss.), who is pushing for a Jan. 6 trial date,
thundered: `WHAT did Claus know and WHEN did he know it!!!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a lawyer, but I have questions about this whole
chimney thing,'' said Rep. Mary Bono (R.-Calif.), who tried
unsuccessfully to get colleagues to join her in a rendition of
``Let it Snow'' before the articles of impeachment were voted upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I don't even have a chimney and I always find gifts
under the tree!'' Bono added. ``What's THAT about?''
</P>
<P>
   Equally stunning was the surprise resignation of Claus' head
elf, Jimmy ``The Fixer'' Spritely, who announced he would be
leaving his post in the wake of an Internet report alleging
numerous extra-elfin affairs over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot in good conscience ask for Mr. Claus to resign if I
do not lead by example,'' said Spritely. ``As much as it pains me
and my family to admit this, I did indeed stray from the path of
fidelity years ago, indulging in youthful indiscretions with, oh,
about 11 or 12 elfin interns.__ OW!!''
</P>
<P>
   (Spritely's ``Ow!'' remark was apparently in reaction to the
kick in the shins he received from his wife, Lonnie, who was
standing next to him during his announcement.)
</P>
<P>
   The Spritely story was published in the on-line version of
Barely Legal magazine and was then picked up by The Washington
Post. A spokesman for the newspaper said the fact that Barely Legal
had already gone with the story compelled it to do follow-up
reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was already out there for the whole world to see,'' The
Post's spokesman said. ``What are we supposed to do, ignore it?''
</P>
<P>
   Barely Legal's on-line site has a daily readership of
approximately 143, according to a Barely Legal spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mr. Claus, he issued a defiant statement vowing never to
resign and to continue his job: the business of ``manufacturing
toys for good girls and boys the world over.'' While Congress
debated his fate, Claus and Mrs. Claus followed a business-as-usual
routine. This included ``making a list and checking it twice,''
according to a North Pole spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   When Claus appeared briefly in public to feed his reindeer, he
ignored the shouted questions of reporters _ although some
observers claimed he bellowed a hearty ``Ho ho ho!'' in the
direction of Sam Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was an editorial comment,'' said the North Pole
spokesman, who refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
