<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-BAND-ALABAMA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA: STILL LOOKING FOR NEW ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Randy Owen, Teddy Gentry, Jeff Cook and
Mark Herndon of the country band Alabama. 
 By JANET E. WILLIAMS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Since their 1980 debut, Alabama has received virtually every
accolade the music business has to offer: gold albums, platinum
albums, multiplatinum albums, Grammy Awards, American Music Awards
and more.
 &HT;    They've also proven their durability. With 41 No. 1 records _
probably 42 by the time you read this _ to their credit, the four
members of Alabama continue to tour, playing to sold-out crowds
year after year.
 &HT;    In 1998, Randy Owen, Teddy Gentry, Jeff Cook and Mark Herndon
commemorated their success with ``For the Record,'' a 45-song
retrospective that featured all 41 chart-topping hits, plus three
new tunes. The first single from the two-CD set, ``How Do You Fall
In Love?,'' was an instant hit.
 &HT;    And, just as the Fort Payne, Ala.-reared foursome hit the
concert trail for the new album, they learned that they would be
honored with a star on the legendary Hollywood Walk of Fame.
 &HT;    All in all, they're entitled to rest on their laurels, but show
no inclination to do so. Even if they did, Cook claims, they
couldn't, because they need the money.
 &HT;    ``We're at the awkward time in our lives when we're too old to
work and too broke to quit,'' he says. ``We're driven to work.''
 &HT;    `` ... by our moms,'' adds Herndon, the group's jokester.
 &HT;    Actually, Owen says in all seriousness, the band is driven.
 &HT;    ``It's a motivation for excellence,'' he says. ``Excellence
meaning success, musical success. I realized after about three or
four years in the music business, having all these No. 1 records,
you're not ever going to be a rich person. You have four guys in a
band, you have many people that work for you, you have the
government who is more than willing to take ... ''
 &HT;    `` ... all of your money,'' Gentry finishes the sentence.
 &HT;    ``Or at least half of it,'' Cook says with a straight face.
 &HT;    ``I mean really, this is true,'' Owen insists, undistracted.
``We've made lots of gross money, as a band. Now, if you was one
guy or one girl, it'd be different.''
 &HT;    ``You'd wind up giving even more to the government,'' Herndon
adds, laughing.
 &HT;    ``We could retire and all of us go home and be comfortable the
rest of our lives,'' Gentry admits. ``But be rich?
 &HT;    ``I relate to Michael Jordan,'' he says. ``Does Michael want to
win any less than he did back six years ago? You can see it on his
face _ he wants to win even more, I think. When he comes down on
the floor, he doesn't make that shot because of his salary. If he
didn't make that shot, he would still draw the salary.
 &HT;    ``I think it's the pride _ it's the pride you have, we have of
putting out good product,'' the musician concludes. ``I think if we
didn't believe we had a good product, we wouldn't want to put it
out.''
 &HT;    In almost 20 years in the music business, the band says, nothing
much has gotten easier.
 &HT;    ``The deck's stacked against us now,'' Gentry says. ``Why I say
that is because when we broke in, we were the darlings of the
business. Like Minnie Pearl told Randy, `Right now you're the
little darlings, but as soon as everybody knows you, after you've
been successful for a number of years,' she said, `that's when the
industry is ready to write you off.'
 &HT;    ``I think we've lived through all that,'' he adds, ``and we're
still around because of one reason _ the fans and our own
determination to do what we're doing.''
 &HT;    ``I think the industry expects you to become more complacent,''
Gentry concludes. ``Or I guess, after all the success, they think
you should reach a point where you don't care, you don't have the
pride or the drive to do it at the level you've been doing it at.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, in an industry often rife with exploitation and
underhandedness, Alabama enjoys a healthy respect pretty much
across the board.
 &HT;    ``I think the industry knows that we haven't cut every song that
we've wrote over the years, that we've really looked to try to keep
our career up by cutting the best songs available to us,'' Gentry
says. ``We've made a lot of young songwriters' lives by going out
and cutting a song and it being on an album or being a single.
 &HT;    ``I think we have a reputation among the publishers in town that
we're all fair people,'' he adds, ``that if you write a hit song
and Alabama gets it in their hands, political reasons won't keep
them from cutting it if they believe it's a hit.''
 &HT;    Though many of their hits were written by others, ``How Do You
Fall In Love?'' is a collaboration between Gentry, Owen and road
manager Greg Fowler.
 &HT;    ``We were working on this song two or three different times on
the bus,'' Owen recalls, ``and then, I guess on the highway coming
back from Seattle, we kind of finalized it.''
 &HT;    ``I carried the melody around for several months and had no idea
what to put to it,'' Gentry says. ``Greg, me and Randy was supposed
to get together and write one day, and Greg said, `I just jotted
down some lines the other night.' He just wrote down some things he
was thinking about.
 &HT;    ``The title was one of the lines that was in the verse,'' he
continues. ``We took that line and it fit the hook, and from there
we got together and started working on it.
 &HT;    ``It seemed so simple when we finished it,'' Gentry adds. ``The
mark of a really great song, to me, is it felt like it didn't need
anything else, at 2 1/2, not quite three minutes long.''
 &HT;    Early ``test audiences'' confirmed that the song would work.
 &HT;    ``I went in and sang it for my kids,'' Owen says. ``They said,
`You are gonna cut that ballad, aren't you?' My son told me, `I'm
really excited about this.'''
 &HT;    Some country purists have complained that the arrangement is a
bit heavier on strings that the usual Alabama fare.
 &HT;    ``It's what the song calls for,'' Gentry says calmly. ``First
time I heard it, when they played it back to us in the studio, I
went, `Whoa! This is a little strong for Alabama.' In fact, I
wanted to come back in and remix it.
 &HT;    ``I called Randy on Saturday morning and we was talking, and he
said, `I've listened to it a few times, and I'm kind of starting to
like it.' So I backed off for a couple of days.
 &HT;    ``It sounds really new for Alabama, a little different place
than where we've been before,'' he admits. ``Which is what we've
got to keep doing. You've got to try to pave a new road.''
 &HT;    That was the idea of ``For the Record,'' Gentry says, a
greatest-hits album that was as much about the future as the past.
 &HT;    ``The whole thing starts out with these three new songs,''
Gentry says. ``To me, let's start with where Alabama's at now, and
then we'll reflect back on where we've been. You think back about
where you was at and what you was doing that year.''
 &HT;    Owen agrees.
 &HT;    ``I guess for me it's futuristic,'' he says, ``looking for the
future.''
 c.1998 Janet E. Williams  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Janet E. Williams is a Nashville, Tenn.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
