<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERT-RODRIGUEZ-DIRE     12-21 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERT-RODRIGUEZ-DIRECTS-THE-FACULTY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT RODRIGUEZ: A `FACULTY' FOR FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Robert Rodriguez directing Jon Stewart in
a scene from ``The Faculty.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Blame it on the aliens.
 &HT;    If it weren't for creatures from beyond, we might not have
Robert Rodriguez and such films as ``El Mariachi'' (1992),
``Desperado'' (1995) and ``From Dusk Till Dawn'' (1996).
 &HT;    Really.
 &HT;    ``The movies that were the most important to me, the ones that
were my favorites _ like `Blade Runner' (1982), `The Thing' (1982),
`Alien' (1979), `Escape from New York' (1981), `Road Warrior'
(1981), Sam Raimi and David Cronenberg movies _ all came out when I
was about 12 or 13,'' the director says with boyish energy during a
conversation at Beverly Hills' Four Season Hotel. ``That's when
everything opened up for me.
 &HT;    ``That's when I realized, `Well, I could maybe make movies, too.
I want to do that. I think I'm going to try.'''
 &HT;    And now, as of Christmas Day, Rodriguez is back where it all
began. That's when his latest film, ``The Faculty,'' is set to
debut.
 &HT;    The science-fiction movie, a sort of ``Body Snatchers Go to High
School,'' has everything that it takes to generate pre-release
buzz, including a script by red-hot ``Scream'' scribe Kevin
Williamson, a cast that's part gorgeous newcomers and part familiar
veterans, and of course Rodriguez's trademark restless camerawork,
nifty editing and booming soundscape.
 &HT;    Life at Herrington High resembles that of any high school. The
faculty (including Robert Patrick, Piper Laurie, Bebe Neuwirth and
Salma Hayek) may be a bit out of touch, and the students range from
jock (Shawn Hatosy) to geek (Elijah Wood) to brilliant drug dealer
(Josh Hartnett), and from bitchy cheerleader (Jordana Brewster) to
outsider (Clea Duvall) to eager-to-please new girl in town (Laura
Harris).
 &HT;    Everything turns upside down, however, when aliens take over the
faculty and it's up to the students to save themselves, their
school and _ oh yeah _ mankind from the hideous extraterrestrials.
 &HT;    ``I recreated my high school, right down to the mascot, the
colors, the way the teachers looked and dressed, and even some of
the lines they said,'' says Rodriguez, who was born and raised in
San Antonio, Texas. ``I was a combination of the characters played
by Elijah and Shawn.
 &HT;    ``I was Shawn because I was really big at that age,'' he
explains. ``My school was small, and they needed people to play on
the sports teams. My brother was good at sports, but I hated them
and never felt comfortable. I liked drawing and making videos.
 &HT;    ``In that sense I was like Elijah's character, the guy always
taking pictures,'' he says. ``The girls never even looked at me.
They'd say, `Oh, he's going to marry his camera someday.' I was
more the loner.''
 &HT;    The sets may have looked familiar to Rodriguez, but everything
else about ``The Faculty'' was alien territory. It was more or less
the first time he'd worked with a script which he hadn't at least
co-written. The budget was $20 million, modest by Hollywood
standards but vastly beyond any of his previous films. And never
before had he put so large a cast through its paces.
 &HT;    Still ...
 &HT;    ``This was probably the most fun I've had on a movie,'' he says.
``I had a lot of freedom and got to do the movie my way. We knew it
would be entertaining if we did it right. There was so much going
on on the set, so much variety.
 &HT;    ``For two weeks straight I worked just with the kids,'' the
director recalls, ``and they were all fresh, really there, and did
whatever I asked. They didn't know what it was supposed to be like
yet.
 &HT;    ``Then for the next two weeks I worked with all these
professionals, like Piper and Bebe and Robert, who gave the set a
different vibe,'' he says. ``I felt like I was making five
different movies, between the young actors, the veterans, the
special-effect sequences and all of that.''
 &HT;    Like many veterans of independent films, Rodriguez doesn't
aspire to helm mega-budget blockbusters. The $20 million
``Faculty'' was about his speed, he says.
 &HT;    ``I understand why movies can cost $80 million,'' he admits.
``It's not always a matter of effects or big stars, but it can be a
lack of planning or of getting too much of what you want rather
than just what you need.
 &HT;    ``It's better not to get everything you want,'' the director
adds. ``It makes you think, `How do I achieve this without turning
on the money hose?' You have to be creative.''
 &HT;    Rodriguez has been making movies since he got his first
home-movie camera in childhood. He studied film at the University
of Texas in Austin, and first displayed his creativity with ``El
Mariachi,'' an acclaimed action thriller about a musician mistaken
for a murderous outlaw.
 &HT;    It was a prototypical low-budget film: Rodriguez not only
directed but also served as writer, camera operator and editor, and
the final tab came to an astounding $7,000.
 &HT;    On the heels of its success came ``Roadracers'' (1994), a
cable-TV movie with Salma Hayek and David Arquette, and
``Desperado,'' a ``Mariachi'' sequel starring Hayek and Antonio
Banderas. Rodriguez followed those with ``The Misbehavers,'' a
segment of the misbegotten 1995 anthology ``Four Rooms,'' and
``From Dusk Till Dawn,'' the over-the-top vampire thriller with
George Clooney, Harvey Keitel and Quentin Tarantino.
 &HT;    ``It's funny, but as much as I've done since `El Mariachi,' I
almost want to try to go back to the simplicity of that film,''
Rodriguez says. ``I want to go back to the art of just creating
something with complete abandon, as I did on that movie.
 &HT;    ``I didn't think anybody would ever see `El Mariachi,''' he
adds. ``I made choices that were my own, and I didn't think about
an audience, critics or a studio looking over my shoulder.
 &HT;    ```Desperado' was for a studio. We did it in 35 millimeter and I
had a crew. And I've kept going from there. I hope I've grown and
that I keep growing.''
 &HT;    Rodriguez, who lives in Austin, Texas, with his wife/producer
Elizabeth Avellan and their two sons _ a third is due in January _
is currently writing a family feature that he plans to direct in
March. He's also executive-produced two completed films, ``The
Hangman's Daughter'' and ``Texas Blood Money,'' a prequel and a
sequel, respectively, to ``From Dusk Till Dawn.'' Both films were
made for direct-to-video release, and should be out in early 1999.
 &HT;    This sort of unpretentious, low-profile work feeds the
occasional criticisms of Rodriguez: He's an undeniable talent, some
say, who is frivoling it away on unworthy projects.
 &HT;    The director shrugs.
 &HT;    ``I enjoy making entertainment,'' he says. ``I enjoy making
entertainment totally as a learning device. I think I learn more by
making the kinds of movies I'm making than I would if I just went
and made a drama that represents the script.''
 &HT;    Rodriguez shakes his head, groping for words.
 &HT;    ``That kind of movie, it's all there on the page,'' he says.
``It might be a good movie, but you have nothing to do for the next
10 months. I don't think I'd learn from that.
 &HT;    ``If I get a piece of material that I want to see exist as a
movie, I might do it for the sake of the movie, not for the sake of
the craft,'' he adds. ``The craft itself is more fun, more creative
and more satisfying when it's some type of entertainment that needs
to be completely created.
 &HT;    ``I like to create a moment with shots and angles and edits and
sounds, rather than just shoot a moment on film. And I don't think
that will ever change.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
