<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICK-VAN-DYKE-IN-DIAGNOSIS-MURDER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAGNOSIS: DICK VAN DYKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Dick Van Dyke in a scene from ``Diagnosis
Murder.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1998 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For someone who grew up watching ``The Dick Van Dyke Show,'' the
most surreal thing about meeting Dick Van Dyke today is that he
still looks a lot like Rob Petrie.
</P>
<P>
   He's a tad heavier, his hair's snow white and there's an equally
white mustache now, but those blue eyes still sparkle, and when Van
Dyke laughs he still sounds like Rob chuckling at his dizzy wife
Laura or cracking up at a Buddy Sorell one-liner.
</P>
<P>
   And, since he who laughs last laughs best, these days Van Dyke
is laughing a lot. At 73, he's the star of one of television's most
popular hour-long dramas, ``Diagnosis Murder,'' which is a top-30
show for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   That he's playing Dr. Dick Sloan, who doubles as a suave senior
sleuth, is worth a laugh, Van Dyke adds. In real life, he says, he
has never been a fan of medical or mystery dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a business!'' he says, chuckling. ``I have no idea how I
ended up playing a doctor and a sleuth. We did a few
movies-of-the-week, it turned into a series and now it's been six
straight years of episodic television. The show's a hit, and it's
the one time in my entire career when I can't figure out exactly
why. I have no idea, but I'm having a terrific time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Diagnosis Murder'' is unabashedly wholesome, clean family fare
that manages to tell crime stories without any of the violence, sex
or nudity that abounds elsewhere in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stuff on TV, I just think, `My God, so much
trash,''' Van Dyke says, his laughter fading. ``What are the kids
taking out of this? And the producers and networks and movie
studios keep saying: `We are simply reflecting the culture.' Well,
they're not _ they're shaping the culture. They're getting to these
kids, because they have all the money to spend on advertising, and
they're shaping the way they think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a family show,'' he adds, ``and I know there are a lot
of young people watching us, along with the older viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyke is entitled to assess the state of the televised art.
After more than 40 years on the small screen, he's a genuine
television icon, but still the lanky, likeable Montana boy who grew
up idolizing silent comedians such as Stan Laurel, Oliver Hardy and
Buster Keaton.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Air Force during World War II, Van Dyke
first made a failed attempt to launch an ad agency, then decided to
go into show business. After winning his spurs in 1950s radio, he
graduated to the then-fledgling medium of television, hosting ``CBS
Cartoon Theatre'' and appearing as a regular on ABC's ``The Andy
Williams Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile he was also working in the theater. The 1960 Broadway
hit ``Bye-Bye Birdie'' won him a Tony Award, and in turn caught the
eye of writer/comedian Carl Reiner, who was putting together an
innovative sitcom based on his own career as a comedy writer and
New Rochelle suburbanite.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, as they say, is television history. Van Dyke became
Rob Petrie and the show became a hit, earning him three Emmy Awards
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV comedy is the toughest,'' he says in retrospect. ``It's the
most fun, but it's the toughest. Carl Reiner was really the one
responsible for it all. You have to have that one brilliant,
creative person in charge, and that was Carl.''
</P>
<P>
   His version of Rob was based primarily on his childhood hero,
Stan Laurel, Van Dyke says. During the show's run he had the chance
to meet Laurel, and told him so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I've stolen a lot from you over the years,''' Van
Dyke recalls, ``and he said, `I know!' But I think he was
flattered.''
</P>
<P>
   During ``The Dick Van Dyke Show's'' six-year run and immediately
after, its namesake acted in more than a dozen movies, but he never
quite became a film star. Forgettable comedies such as ``What A Way
To Go!'' (1964), ``The Art of Love'' (1965) and ``Fitzwilly''
(1967) were mixed with a few classics, such as ``Chitty Chitty Bang
Bang'' (1968) and, particularly, ``Mary Poppins'' (1964).
</P>
<P>
   ``What fun that was,'' he says, grinning at the memory. ``It was
all done on Walt Disney's sound stage, and there's not an outdoor
shot in it. In the scenes where I was dancing with the penguins,
the animators were right there, telling me how high and how far
away the birds were. It was meticulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walt was planning a sequel around the same time he died,'' Van
Dyke adds. ``And the whole project fell through.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyke was always a physical comedian who liked to toss his
body around with abandon. The pratfall he takes in the opening
credits of ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' was the least of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hurt at the time,'' he says. ``I took so many falls
in my life that my spine looked like the Colorado River. So I've
got some arthritis now. But I swim, I do weight exercises three
times a week and I do yoga stretching. I exercise by keeping moving
_ it's the best guard against arthritis.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there have been other struggles for Van Dyke over
his career. In 1972, he admitted publicly that he was an alcoholic.
Shortly after completing rehabilitation, he used the experience in
an award-winning television movie, ``The Morning After,'' in which
he played a middle-aged businessman whose life falls apart because
of the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, because of that film, I get more mail from people
who've been in rehab and saw it there,'' he says. ``They use it
because of its authenticity. I'm so proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Van Dyke is enjoying one of the best stretches of
his career. The ``Diagnosis'' set is only a few miles from his
Malibu home, where he lives with his longtime mate, Michelle
Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a five-minute commute for me, so it's ideal,'' he says.
``And, out of deference to my age, they limit the amount of hours I
have to work, which is lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   Another perk is getting to work with his son, Barry Van Dyke,
who has a regular role as Detective Steve Sloan on ``Diagnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good-looking guy, and he does a great job,'' Van Dyke
Sr. says proudly. ``He's actually very funny, and I wish they would
show that more, but there's not much opportunity for that.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, ``Diagnosis Murder'' will run, Van Dyke promises,
``as long as I'm still standing and can make it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   He still keeps in touch with his old ``Dick Van Dyke Show''
pals, including Mary Tyler Moore and especially Reiner, who lives
near him. But he admits to disappointment that ``Mary and Rhoda,''
the long-awaited, much-hyped CBS sitcom reuniting Moore and Valerie
Harper, has apparently fallen by the wayside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows she had a pilot with Valerie, and I guess it
just didn't go,'' he says, sighing. ``There again, it wasn't the
quality of the show, it was the fact that it skewed older. The
networks say advertisers won't buy commercials directed at an older
audience. I think they're wrong, because the yuppie generation is
turning 50 now, and they control all the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable we're still on the air,'' he concludes, ``but
there has to be room out there for a family show.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
