<TEXT>
<P>
   TOP 1997-98 FUND-RAISERS AMONG PRESIDENTIAL PROSPECTS
</P>
<P>
   Politicians who raised large sums for their re-election efforts
or personal political organizations in the past two years could
excel at raising the $15 million to $25 million needed in 1999 to
prepare for the short, costly presidential primary season in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, Texas ............................ $17
million
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Malcolm ``Steve'' Forbes, New Jersey .... $13.1
million
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer, Virginia ........... $7
million
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander, Tennessee .......... $6.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, Arizona ......... $6 million
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, Arizona ................................ $3.9
million
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, Ohio .....................................
$3.6 million
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, Missouri .............................. $3.2
million
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Pat Buchanan, Virginia ............... $2
million
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, Tennessee ....................... $1 million
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Jack Kemp, New York .................... $869,000
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith, New Hampshire ........................ $290,000
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, Missouri ....$6.1 million
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Tennessee ..................... $4.3
million
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, Massachusetts ........................ $3.6
million
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, Minnesota .........................
$645,000
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, New Jersey ................. $388,000
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Federal Election Commission, staffs of potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Note:These totals, collected for re-election efforts or personal
political organizations, show money-raising power but not
necessarily the amounts currently available for use in a federal
race. The money remaining from Bush's re-election campaign cannot
be transferred to a presidential race because it was not raised
under federal laws, which include contributions limits. Texas law
includes no limits on contributions.
</P>
