<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0263 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGHT-COLD-LIFEBEAT-N     12-21 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHT-COLD-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXERCISE WHEN YOU'RE SICK?
</HEADLINE>
  By KEN MCALPINE 
 c.1998 Ken McAlpine 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many studies have been undertaken to ferret out the machinations
of the common cold, but few were as bluntly simple as one conducted
at the Common Cold Clinic in Salisbury, England. Are colds caused
by cold temperature, mused researchers? No, they concluded, when
not a single subject got sick after researchers doused them with
water and had them stand outdoors naked.
</P>
<P>
   A nod to British practicality and stoicism, the study
illustrated two important points. First, it is better to be a
researcher than a subject. Second, contrary to folk wisdom, colds,
flus and their attendant miseries _ goopy heads, sniffly noses,
achy muscles and a basset-faced population that shares them all
with you _ are not caused by being cold. They are caused by viruses
and bacteria. Ruthlessly effective viruses and bacteria that, given
an iota of opening, will lay you low. According to the National
Center for Health Statistics, 90 out of 100 of us are leveled by a
cold each year.
</P>
<P>
   Why does this happen more often during winter? Because we're
jammed together indoors, infector and infectee, flip flopping
roles. But there's another critical piece of the equation. A strong
immune system can rebuff viruses and bacteria. If your immune
system is at its peak, it wins the day and you don't get sick. And
exercise, done wisely, seems to give the immune system a tremendous
boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moderate activity actually ends up improving
immunosurveillance, the ability of the immune system to to protect
you against viruses and bacteria,'' says David C. Nieman, professor
of health and exercise science at Appalachian State University in
Boone, N.C., and one of the leading researchers in the field of
exercise immunology. ``During these times of year where viruses and
bacteria are widespread, a moderate, daily exercise bout might be
as good a medicine as you can take.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies by Nieman and his fellow researchers have shown that
moderate walking, swimming, cycling and running can boost the
levels and effectiveness of some of the immune system's most
valuable defenders, in some cases dramatically. In a recent study,
a large group of women who walked briskly five days a week, 45
minutes a day, for 12 weeks lowered the number of days they
suffered from colds and flu by half. Perhaps those dampened British
subjects were jogging in place when the researchers weren't
looking.
</P>
<P>
   These same studies also highlight another important point. The
immune boost of exercise is only temporary, a matter of hours at
most. So it behooves you, as Nieman's ladies did, to exercise
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a really good housekeeper come in for 30
minutes each day,'' says Nieman. ``The killer cells tidy up the
body and everything stays much cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately when it comes to fighting off colds and flu,
exercise can also be a curse. Examining exercise and its effect on
immune function, Nieman has also noted several adverse thresholds,
points where exercise swings from benefit to detriment - in short,
weakening the immune system enough to turn you into one of the
mucus minions.
</P>
<P>
   Observing the training habits of over 2,000 marathoners, Nieman
noticed that runners who logged more than 60 miles a week doubled
their odds of getting sick. On a broader scope, in a variety of
sports Nieman found that athletes' immune systems began to show
marked negative effects when they pushed too hard for too long, as
a rule for more than 90 minutes at effort levels above 70 percent
of their maximum.
</P>
<P>
   These immune system suppressions were only temporary. But cold
and flu viruses need only the barest of windows. More often than
not, subjects who exercised hard and long got sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exercising for as long as an hour and twenty minutes at a
solid pace seems to be safe,'' says Nieman. ``But if you work the
body harder, you're taking a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished marathoner himself, Nieman is well aware that
many athletes view moderation in the same light that Beverly Hills
residents view a credit check. Which may be why he recently
conducted a series of studies with elite athletes, studies whose
definitive results shocked even Nieman.
</P>
<P>
   In the depths of cold and flu season, Nieman and his fellow
researchers exercised athletes hard, but had some of them drink a
6-percent carbohydrate sports drink while they did so _ roughly a
liter an hour of the stuff. Almost without exception, the athletes
who got the carbs remained healthy. Those who didn't get the
carbohydrate injection got yucky sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those `Eureka!' moments in research,'' says
Nieman happily. ``It was just unreal the difference. There is every
reason to believe that if athletes keep carbohydrate feeding during
prolonged and heavy exertion, there is less physiological stress to
their immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   In his studies, Nieman used Gatorade, but any sports drink
that's 6 to 8 percent carbohydrate will do _ so will a mix that's
half water and half 100 percent fruit juice (fruit juices alone are
about 12 percent carbohydrate, too concentrated for the body to get
what it needs quickly).
</P>
<P>
   What if it's already too late? What about exercising when you're
already sick? It's a winter dilemma we've all wrestled with. On the
one hand, the need to get the hell out of the house. One the other,
a head clotted with goo.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when exercise of any kind is out of the
question. How sick is too sick?
</P>
<P>
   Flu is too sick, says Nieman. Ditto for fever, extreme
tiredness, muscle aches and swollen lymph glands. These are
symptoms of serious illness, and they demand rest, not activity, if
your immune system is to stamp out the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will exercising with the flu prolong recovery, says
Nieman, it could be dangerous. In some instances the virus spreads
to the heart, where it can cause potentially fatal infection.
</P>
<P>
   For the flu Nieman prescribes unadulterated rest until the
symptoms are completely gone, then nothing but very easy effort for
at least two weeks. Push too hard too soon and you could relapse.
Viral warfare forgives few mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Good news, though, for those who can't stomach idleness. If you
have a cold, a minor headache, a mild sore throat, or all three,
measured activity may be the best remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The science here is sketchy as research institutions are
reluctant to give their scientists the go ahead to shoot viruses up
the noses of human subjects. But from the few studies that have
been done, it appears that the same light activity that boosts your
immune system when you are healthy may also shore up your defenses
when you're already sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still largely theory,'' says Nieman. ``But based on what
I've seen, during the height of a cold moderate activity like a
walk or an easy bike ride is more help than complete rest. But
nothing severe. The intensity should be way down. It's better to
keep it moderate and not push your luck.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ken McAlpine is a free-lance writer based in Ventura, Calif.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
