<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVARIAN-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVARIAN CANCER'S SUBTLE SIGNS
</HEADLINE>
  By SUSAN MCCLURE 
 c.1998 Susan McClure 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It could begin as an extra trip to the bathroom every night or a
touch of constipation that doesn't go away. Maybe the waist band of
your skirt is getting tight even though you haven't gained weight.
</P>
<P>
   These small symptoms, easily brushed aside as insignificant,
could influence the course of a woman's life. They may be the only
clues you are going to get about the condition of your ovaries.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden deep inside the pelvis where they can't be seen and
sometimes can't be felt, ovaries can develop malignant tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike cervical cancer which can be caught at a precancerous
stage with a pap test, for ovarian cancer there is no way to find
the precancerous condition. It just suddenly happens and there is
no way to screen for it,'' said Dr. Edgardo Yordan, gynocologic
oncologist at Lutheran General Hospital in Park Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Yordan, a top ovarian cancer clinician trained at the
prestigious Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York and
the University of Southern California, deals with up to 60 cases of
ovarian cancer every year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Cancer Institute, 1 in 70 women will
develop ovarian cancer, most cases occuring in women over age 50.
Risks are higher for women with close relatives who have had the
disease, who have no children, or have had breast cancer. Taking
oral contraceptives appears to reduce the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Ovarian cancer is highly treatable and can have a cure rate as
high as 90 to 95 percent, but must be caught at an early stage. If
it spreads undetected, it can metastasize to the abdominal cavity
or occasionally beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treatment of ovarian cancer is very frustrating,'' Yordan
said. ``The best chance is early diagnosis but most people are not
so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in advanced stages of the disease, the norm, the cancer
is treatable with expert surgery and chemotherapy. In fact, the
response rate is among the highest for solid tumors. Unfortunately,
recurrence is frequent and permanent remissions are relatively
few,'' Yordan said.
</P>
<P>
   This is why it's important to be alert to subtle changes, such
as the following, that might be caused by your ovaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expanding waist line
</P>
<P>
   _ Frequent urination
</P>
<P>
   _ Change in bowel habits
</P>
<P>
   _ Indigestion
</P>
<P>
   _ Loss of appetite
</P>
<P>
   _ Abdominal bloating
</P>
<P>
   _ Pelvic pressure
</P>
<P>
   _ Pain with intercourse
</P>
<P>
   _ Change in menstrual pattern
</P>
<P>
   _ Foul smell to menstrual flow
</P>
<P>
   _ Unusual cramping or pain before menstruation or at ovulation
</P>
<P>
   ``If you develop these symptoms, it's important to follow up,''
said Yordan.
</P>
<P>
   Gynecologists can check the size of the ovaries with a pelvic
exam. They may request a C-125 blood test, which measures a hormone
released by some ovarian cancers, but which can show false
positives or negatives. Ultrasound scans of the pelvis can provide
a picture of the ovaries and even give an idea of whether a cyst is
solid or fluid-filled.
</P>
<P>
   But for the actual diagnosis of cancerous or benign cyst,
surgeons must go in for a look. This sometimes can be done with
minimally-invasive laparoscopy using small scopes inserted through
tiny incisions in the abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Should cancer be found, major surgery including a total
hysterectomy is needed to remove any visible tumor and sample other
tissues to determine the extent of spread. Statistically, best
results at this stage come from having a gynocologic oncologist on
the surgery team rather than relying exclusively on a gynecologist
or general surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining cancer cells, lingering individuals too small to be
detected surgically or tumors that could not be completely removed,
are eradicated or minimized with chemotherapy. Cure rates have
risen dramatically with the advent of aggressive new chemotherapy
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '70s, ovarian cancer was battled with a single
agent such as cyclophosphamide. The response rate was modest and
the cure rate was zero for advance stage cancer,'' Yordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Now chemotherapeutic agents are teamed up to catch and kill the
maximum number of cancer cells. Currently, taxol with cisplatin has
proven to be the most effective in trials conducted by the
Gynecologic Oncology Group, a collaborative clinical research
group. Carboplatin with taxol is expected to prove equally
effective and safer than cisplatin in current trials.
</P>
<P>
   Chemotherapy also can be injected directly into the abdomen, a
protocol developed in part by Yordan.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful therapy, however, begins with early
diagnosis and prompt attention to subtle body signs, a
responsibility every woman can attend to.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: SUPPORT FOR WOMEN WITH OVARIAN CANCER
</P>
<P>
   When Gilda Radner, 1980s Saturday Night Live comedienne, died of
ovarian cancer at age 40 she left behind a legacy that benefits
cancer patients and survivors today. While dealing with advanced
stage cancer, she found comfort in interacting with people facing
similar struggles.
</P>
<P>
   After her death her husband, actor Gene Wilder, and her
psychotherapist, Joanna Bull, established Gilda's Club to help
support all people living with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Located in major cities across America, Gilda's Club offers free
wellness groups, support for children and teens, networking for
different kinds of cancer, lectures by specialists, enrichment
workshops and stress management, social activies.
</P>
<P>
   Women with ovarian cancer can find helpful hints from survivors
in the newsletter Conversations, P.O. Box 7948, Amarillo, TX
79114-7948  &QL; http://www.ovarian-news.com &QR; . More information is
available at the internet site maintained by The National Ovarian
Cancer Coalition at  &QL; http://www.Ovarian.Org &QR; .
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure is a free-lance writer based in Valparaiso,
Ind.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
