<SLUG> BC-SINGLE-MOM-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS AND THE SINGLE MOM
</HEADLINE>
  By MELINDA BLAU 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You hear about the ``plight'' of the single mother all the time.
She's alone. She's broke. She's exhausted. But chances are you know
at least one single mom who defies that stereotype. She's focused
and in charge; her kids are thriving and happy. So what's the real
story?
</P>
<P>
   There are some 10 million single mothers-divorced and widowed
women and, increasingly, women who choose solo motherhood-in the
United States today. In 1997, they represented 27 percent of all
families with children, compared with 11.5 percent in 1970. Beyond
their growth in numbers, these women are savvy, strong and worth
listening to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see many single mothers who are inspiring for their
resilience, strength, courage, sense of humor and dedication to
their children,'' observes Miriam Galper Cohen, a psychotherapist
based in Philadelphia and author of ``The Joint Custody Handbook.''
The challenges that single moms face _ more hectic schedules, less
money and fewer resources than mothers in two-parent homes have _
often spur them to come up with highly creative, kid-centered
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly difficulties,'' Cohen acknowledges. ``But
with supportive families and friends, these women provide their
children with homes filled with love-the key ingredient in raising
well-adjusted kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are four their most successful strategies:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BANISH MORNING MADNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Because they alone steer their families through the morning,
single moms tend to wake everyone up early. ``An hour before we
walk out the door, we're all sitting at the table,'' says Val
Jones, a fund-raiser in Media, Pa., and the mother of Spencer, 9,
and Lucy, 6. The key, she says, is an unvarying routine: getting
dressed, then brushing teeth, then making beds. That way, the kids
know exactly what's expected of them.
</P>
<P>
   Getting input from the children is also important because giving
them a say engages their support. Shoshana Alexander, author of
``In Praise of Single Parents,'' enlisted the help of her
9-year-old son, Elias, to plan their morning routine. Together they
made a checklist: wash face, brush teeth, comb hair, feed pets,
make lunch. If he finishes early, Elias is rewarded with extra time
with his friends before school. ``Me bonus for me is that I don't
have to goad him, and I get time to do something calming for
myself,'' comments Alexander, who meditates in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Leah Klungness, co-author of ``The Complete Single
Mother,'' divorced when her children, Andrew and Sarah, were 8 and
3. She notes the importance of anticipating children's needs. The
night before a school day, she would lay out clothes, get book bags
ready and pack lunches.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a last-minute rush _ and the nagging that goes with it
_ Pat Dell-Ross, a clinical social worker in Boston, sets a timer
to ring 10 minutes before 10-year-old Jesse's bus arrives.
``Otherwise, he dawdles until the bus is here and then relies on me
to grab everything he needs,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Similar strategies are crucial at night too, when tired single
moms are forced to be especially resourceful. After all, there is
no one else around to take the baby or help with homework. For her
part, Jones prohibits television at night. ``It just sucks up time,
and we don't have that much,'' she says. And dinner is always eaten
by candlelight. ``Even if we're having macaroni and cheese,'' she
says, ``it makes the meal more civilized. Sitting down to dinner,
reading stories and snuggling before bed are the best parts of the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STICK TO A SCHEDULE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A finely honed daily routine is the cornerstone of family life,
especially for single mothers. Jones breaks up her day into blocks
of time. She leaves work at 5 p.m. and picks up Lucy at daycare by
5:45 and Spencer from his dad's by 6. She's home by 6:15. Between
6:30 and 7, dinner goes on the table; at 7:30, she and the kids
play a game or do a puzzle; bath and bedtime come soon afterward.
``There's a lot of nudging along the way,'' Jones admits, ``but
it's important for children to have structure. Otherwise, I become
Sergeant Mom!''
</P>
<P>
   Routine not only helps you avoid becoming a cop but also teaches
your kids important lessons about responsibility and independence.
Many single moms, like Dell-Ross, rely on blackboards and timers,
which motivate kids in a nonthreatening way. ``Developmentally,
young children don't have a good notion of time,'' Dr. Klungness
explains. ``Timers and calendars teach them about time
management.'' Dell-Ross adds, ``Because the timer is an outside
arbiter, it's easier for Jesse to accept''
</P>
<P>
   Being organized is also critical, says Klungness. She suggests,
``Run your home like a business.'' Set times for meals, homework,
and chores. Keep a calendar, and use a different color pen for each
child's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Because the job of running a household falls squarely on their
shoulders, single mothers start doling out responsibility early.
Dell-Ross, for example, encourages Jesse to take part in dinner
preparation. Even as a preschooler, he could do simple tasks like
helping to make a salad and stirring cake batter. Now he also
pitches in with grocery shopping and recycling. Sharing tasks is
particularly important in single-parent families, says Stephanie
Coontz, author of ``The Way We Really Are: Coming to Terms With
America's Changing Families.'' ``Working side by side is great. It
makes the child feel like part of the family team,'' she reports.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T BE `BEST FRIENDS' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Mom is the only parent at home, she tends to have an
especially close relationship with her children. ``It's an
intimate, almost blurred generational bond,'' says Coontz. These
moms have to sidestep the trap of becoming ``best friends'' with
their kids. The key is to set limits, because that establishes your
role as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids feel secure when they know there are limits,'' Klungness
agrees. ``You can say yes more and no less if you anticipate
debates and give children a choice ahead of time.'' For instance,
when you need to go to the supermarket, let your child help you
make out the shopping list, but stay in charge by saying, ``We can
buy ice cream-what flavor do you want?'' Or, before a birthday
celebration, say: ``Which two friends do you want to invite?''
</P>
<P>
   With children over the age of 3, regular ``house meetings'' can
be very helpful in limit setting as well. ``The formal context
gives a child the safety to express whats bothering him, to say
what he thinks is or isn't fair,'' Alexander says. ``And a meeting
is an important external authority that takes pressure off Mom. It
says, `We both have to live by this.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARN TO HANDLE YOUR ANGER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Single moms know they can't afford to lose it _ there's no one
else around to step in. But if you've set clear limits and
established expectations of your child, even if he's a toddler,
``your anger is less likely to get out of control,'' maintains Jane
Mattes, author of ``Single Mothers by Choice'' and mother of a son,
Eric.
</P>
<P>
   Most single moms try to calm themselves before their anger
spirals out of control. If Jones has a rough day or feels that the
walls are closing in on her at home, she takes a walk outside or
goes into her bedroom to listen to music for a bit. Her children,
at 6 and 9, are old enough to play by themselves for a while.
</P>
<P>
   With children under the age of 2, try to change the scene. Put
your child in the stroller and go outside or walk around inside
your house, suggests Mattes. ``With older children, reassure them
by saying, 'I'm just grouchy. I'm not mad at you.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of overload, instead of feeling beaten down and
resentful, Alexander's best remedy is to play a game or sit down
and read with Elias. Or they turn on the radio and dance. ``It
always brings me back to the here and now,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Melinda Blau is author of ``Families Apart: Ten Keys to
Successful Co-parenting.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
