<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER-MURDERED (Mexico City) _ The remains of San Antonio
Express-News correspondent Philip True were cremated after a second
autopsy confirmed earlier forensic findings that he had been
brutally murdered. By SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-GIFTS (San Francisco) _ It's Christmas time, and the
usual high-tech toys beckon from the pages of glossy catalogs. But
another type of gift _ alternative gifts _ is catching the
imagination of comfortable families who feel they, personally, have
more than enough. By ANASTASIA HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   CHAIRS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Chairs have been around since the
Egyptian civilization. But according to books on traditional
decorating, the ottoman was an auxiliary seat in American
furnishings dating only to the early 1840s, prior to the Victorian
period, and so was the occasional chair. A simple parlor, dining
room or bedroom chair was customarily used for this as-needed type
of seating. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader cheers up garden columnist
with a letter detailing her purchase of milkweed plants and how
Monarch butterflies visit the plants. Q&AMP;A. By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ It always seems to happen. Savvy
consumers find a way to take advantage of the game, forcing
businesses to change the rules. The latest example is the credit
card industry, which is out to teach ``rate-surfers'' _ people who
sign up for a credit card at a low rate, then transfer the balance
to another card when that entry rate is about to expire. Issuers
are beginning to charge consumers a fee to transfer balances to
their new low-rate card. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   TRENDS-FORECASTER (Rhinebeck, N.Y.) _ There are no crystal balls
to be found at the Trends Research Institute, but don't be
surprised if Gerald Celente puts one on display. The
fortuneteller's accouterment would be right at home alongside globe
ornaments and yin-yang symbols hanging from wooden beams. By DOUG
BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS (San Francisco) _ George Bailey keeps staring at the
pink slip, then begins thinking about Mary and their four children.
Bailey Brothers Building &AMP; Loan had survived the run on the banks
and that foul-up with Potter, but not the hostile takeover. He
shakes his head and mutters to himself, ``I wish I'd never been
hired.'' By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KENNETH-STARR (San Antonio) _ Hours after the House of
Representatives voted to impeach President Clinton Saturday,
independent council Kenneth Starr called his mother in San Antonio.
The conversation never touched on Clinton, Monica Lewinsky or
impeachment. By BILL HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-TRAVEL (San Francisco) _ When a storm at Washington's
National Airport forced the plane back to the terminal, Molly
Brodie booked another flight to San Francisco and a hotel room for
the night even before stepping off the plane. With the prospect of
holiday crowds, travel experts are urging passengers to expect
delays and be ready with a ``Plan B.'' By JACOB H. FRIES.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SAVE (Undated) _ What better holiday travel gift than
finding out how to save money on your next vacation. Here are 50
suggestions for cutting costs. By HARRY SHATTUCK and SYD KEARNEY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ When last we checked in with Santa,
Rudolph and the gang, they were trying to come to grips with
holiday capacity controls for their frequent-flyer mileage. Now, a
new dilemma: ``What do you mean that new carry-on limits keep me
from taking the Furbys aboard the airplane?'' Santa asks the ticket
agent at the North Pole. By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-TOURISM (Roatan, Honduras) _ The winds of Hurricane Mitch
seem to have blown the tourists clean off this Caribbean island
near Honduras' northern coast. ``You go to restaurants, they're
dead. Cabin accommodations, dead. Everything is dead,'' says Foster
Diaz Bush, 42, owner of a restaurant and bar. Tourism officials say
the stampede from Honduras' tourist meccas is an overreaction. By
DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The continuing saga: So many
stories, so little time ...If you don't like the warm weather, then
check out Eagle Lake in Lassen County ... like minus-2 degrees last
week. With another cold snap, it's possible the entire lake could
freeze over by New Year's Day, 13 miles long, 4 miles wide, 100
miles of shoreline, 27,000 surface acres, creating the biggest
ice-skating rink in the West. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I went to a homeless shelter and
found sanity. The dining room and dormitory in the basement of St.
Boniface Catholic Church in the Tenderloin are a winter shelter for
about 40 men. The warm spaces of St. Boniface offered sanctuary
from the nation's nervous breakdown. There was no television set
showing bomb blasts in Baghdad and bombast in Washington. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ To grasp just how troubled are
our times, all that was needed was to listen to the debate over the
impeachment of President Clinton at the end of last week. As the
hours of debate droned on, speaker after speaker invoked the name
of God on behalf of their argument. By HARRY ROSENFELD
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ To help wind down this year and
prepare to welcome 1999, columnist Clay Robison offers some
seasonal greetings with relevant observations on everything from to
Lt. Gov. Rick Perry to schools. By CLAY ROBISON
</P>
