<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTA-HEALTH-REVIEW-N     12-21 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-HEALTH-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNUAL REVIEW OF SANTA'S HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Note sidebar below that could accompany a photo or
graphic.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY MERRITT McKINNEY  
 c.1998 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Santa Claus may be able to travel around the world in a single
night, but when it comes to his health, he's no Superman, according
to the latest medical research. That bowl full of jelly, a diet
rich in fatty cookies and a lack of regular exercise all put Santa
at risk for a number of health problems.
</P>
<P>
   But adopting a healthier lifestyle won't be as difficult for
Santa as it may sound, according to Dr. Joseph A. Lieberman, the
chairman of the department of family and community medicine at the
Christiana Care Health System in Wilmington, Del., and a clinical
professor of family medicine at Jefferson Medical College in
Philadelphia. And Santa's jolly nature already gives him a head
start on improving his health, he said. While Lieberman has never
examined Santa himself, he has taken a peek at the Jolly One's
medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Medical Tribune News Service's annual review of the
state of Santa's health.
</P>
<P>
   --Santa needs to trim a few pounds. This may seem obvious, but
the importance of weight loss continues to be a subject of debate
in the medical community.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, the editors of a prestigious medical journal,
The New England Journal of Medicine, published an editorial stating
that Americans are too obsessed with trying to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   But in the spring, the American Heart Association placed obesity
in the same risk-factor class as smoking, high cholesterol, high
blood pressure and a sedentary lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   And the National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute in Bethesda,
Md., announced new obesity guidelines, which declared that 55
percent of American adults need to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with these mixed messages, Santa should stay calm,
according to Lieberman. The Delaware expert recommended that St.
Nick ``use an exercise program and dietary discretion to keep his
weight under control,'' but that he should ``not be so obsessed
that it affects his jolly disposition.''
</P>
<P>
   --Year-round exercise can boost Santa's health. Besides helping
him trim down his bowl full of jelly, research published this year
has highlighted a number of exercise's health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   A Finnish study of about 8,000 sets of twins found that those
who walked or jogged for just 30 minutes six or more times a month
had a 43 percent lower risk of death than sedentary people.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise may also help ward off Alzheimer's disease, according
to a study conducted at Case Western Reserve University in
Cleveland. In a group of 370 people, those who did not have
Alzheimer's had engaged in significantly more exercise during their
lifetimes than people with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Santa may not have much room for error, since ``he's already
making his list and checking it twice,'' Lieberman commented. ``We
want to insure that he forestalls the development of Alzheimer's,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman recommended that Santa exercise for 20 minutes at
least three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   --Lay off the cookies. ``An occasional indulgence in cookies is
OK, but kiddies may also want to put out other things,'' Lieberman
advised.
</P>
<P>
   Veggies may be good substitutes, since they are rich in
nutrients and fiber. And a study from Italy found that some
vegetables, carrots in particular, may help prevent certain types
of cancer. Vegetables and fruits rich in potassium, such as
bananas, may also lower the risk of stroke, according to a Harvard
study of more than 44,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   --Have an occasional glass of wine. While earlier research has
shown that a daily drink or two -- especially red wine -- may help
protect the heart, the habit may also help preserve Santa's sight,
according to a study of more than 3,000 adults that found that
moderate wine drinkers were less likely to develop age-related
macular degeneration, the leading cause of blindness among the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman agreed, but he warned against drinking while behind
the reins. ``It would be wonderful to have wine, but not while he's
driving the sled,'' he advised.
</P>
<P>
   --That jolly disposition counts for something. University of
Kentucky researchers have discovered that optimism may improve more
than a person's mood: it may also boost the immune system. ``We
should learn a lesson from Santa that a pleasant disposition may
prolong life,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Santa's outlook may be getting rosier. In a nationwide poll of
2,727 people ages 25 to 74, older men and women were more likely
than younger folks to say that they had felt happy, cheerful or
satisfied in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: A HEAD-TO-TOE ASSESSMENT OF SANTA'S HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: This sidebar is designed to accompany a full-length
graphic of Santa. Each blurb should point to the particular area of
Santa's body.
</P>
<P>
   --Eyes. Elderly people are at risk for a number of eye diseases,
including cataracts and age-related macular degeneration. The San
Francisco-based American Academy of Ophthalmology recommends a
complete eye exam every one to two years for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   --Nose. That red honker may mean that Santa likes to unwind with
a drink every now and then. While a drink or two a day can be a
boost for the heart, Santa should not overdo it, since excessive
drinking may lead to liver problems.
</P>
<P>
   --Smile. Santa's cheery attitude may help keep his immune system
strong.
</P>
<P>
   --Pipe. Besides increasing the risk of heart disease and stroke,
smoking a pipe increases Santa's odds of developing mouth and
throat cancers.
</P>
<P>
   --Heart. Fatty cookies and lack of regular exercise makes life
tougher for Santa's ticker.
</P>
<P>
   --Belly. It may jiggle when he laughs, but that spare tire
increases Santa's chance of heart attack, stroke, diabetes and a
number of other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   --Knee. Unless he sheds a few pounds, Santa's extra weight may
lead to a painful joint disease known as osteoarthritis.
</P>
<P>
   --Hat/Hands/Feet. To protect himself against frostbite and
hypothermia, St. Nick must not forget to wear gloves, hat and
snow-proof boots.
</P>
<P>
   --Bones. To help keep Santa's bones strong, kids should leave
out glasses of milk -- skim, of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-$ADV26a-COX     12-21 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-$ADV26a-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIME RUNNING OUT TO EXTERMINATE Y2K BUG
 &HT;    With Y2K-DATA, Y2K-CONSUMERS, Y2K-CONSUMERS-DATA AND
Y2K-LAWSUITS. Repeating for all needing in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Saturday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Millennium Bug's sting only a year away,
businesses and governments haven't completed the expensive task of
fixing computer systems nationwide, and experts can't rule out
major disruptions from the software glitch.
</P>
<P>
   For years, programmers have been scrambling to fix trillions of
lines of code that assume every date begins with the digits ``19.''
Unless the errors are fixed before the year 2000, the so-called Y2K
bug threatens to send computer systems around the globe into a
state of paralyzing confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories abound. Some activists fear that elevators will
trap riders, electricity and water won't flow to homes, mass
transportation systems will be halted and airplane pilots will be
unable to communicate with air traffic controllers. Some people are
hoarding food, water and medicine out of fear that the basic
machinery of society will break down.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts say that such scenarios are wildly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say exactly what's going to happen,'' said Joel
Willemssen, director of Civil Agencies Information Systems for the
General Accounting Office. ``But there are likely to be some
disruptions in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Americans might see Y2K ripples much sooner than
midnight on Dec. 31, 1999. For example, because unemployment
insurance benefits are typically calculated a year in advance, the
Labor Department estimates that some state systems will fail when
new claims are filed Jan. 4. So some states may not be able to
process unemployment claims, or they may cut checks for the wrong
amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest misconception is that this will be a one-day
blip,'' said Lou Marcoccio, managing partner for the Gartner Group,
a U.S. information technology firm. ``We're going to be dealing
with this well into 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   In the race to fix the world's computer code, here's the
situation:
</P>
<P>
   _ GLOBAL OVERVIEW: The United States, Canada and much of Europe
are leading efforts worldwide to fix computer code, but the Gartner
Group still estimates that at least 15 percent of companies in
these developed nations will experience one ``mission critical''
failure _ severe enough to disrupt businesses or services. In
developing countries such as China and Pakistan, it's estimated a
dismal 66 percent of companies will experience such a computer
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. GOVERNMENT. In February, the White House appointed a
corporate turnaround artist, John Koskinen, to coordinate 24
federal agencies. As of Dec. 8, he reported, 61 percent of 7,000
federal mission-critical computer systems had been fixed and
tested. However, only 43 percent in major agencies such as the
Department of Defense, Department of Energy and Department of
Health and Human Services had been tested and replaced.
</P>
<P>
   _ CORPORATIONS. The nation's corporate giants are in good shape,
with industries such as banking, investments and pharmaceuticals
leading the pack. But such progress comes at a high cost. The
Federal Reserve estimates the 500 largest companies will spend
between $40 billion and $50 billion over four years to fix the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ SMALL BUSINESS. Thousands of smaller companies are causing
concern. International Data Corp., a Framingham, Mass. technology
firm, surveyed 400 companies for Y2K readiness in January. Of those
companies, one-third hadn't evaluated or started Y2K fixes. Of the
laggards, nearly all were smaller businesses with revenues of less
than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ STATE AND LOCAL GOVERNMENTS. They are in bad shape too. The 49
states, for example, use 421 separate computer systems to
administer federal money through Medicaid, welfare and food stamp
programs. Of those, only one-third now are fixed, according to GAO.
Worse, the National Association of Counties says half the counties
nationwide lack plans to tackle Y2K trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest impact is likely to be the cost to the economy.
Today, the Y2K computer problem is devouring 60 percent of the
world's information technology resources. And the price tag for
fixing Y2K glitches is expected to surpass $1.2 trillion worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Economists don't agree on the implications of the resource
drain, but at least one prominent economist, Edward Yardeni, chief
economist at Deutsche Banks Securities Inc. in New York, has put
chances of the Y2K bug causing a global recession at 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yardeni has examined the Securities and Exchange Commission
(SEC) disclosure statements of 400 publicly traded companies. He
says these corporate giants alone will spend $29 billion fixing Y2K
glitches. Bell South, for example, expects to spend between $250
million and $350 million, but has only expended $40 million as of
September 30.
</P>
<P>
   The financial industry says most banks are on track to have
systems tested and replaced by June. The U.S. stock exchanges have
conducted dress rehearsals to simulate year 2000 scenarios, and
reported no glitches in stock trading. Still, the Federal Reserve
is printing $50 billion in extra dollars to prepare against
shortages if people start withdrawing cash from their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another trouble spot is the global interconnections in today's
business markets. Dell Computer Corp., for example, relies on 70
key suppliers to manufacture parts for its computers. The chemical
giant du Pont has surveyed one-third of its suppliers to find 40
percent at high risk for Y2K failures, according to SEC documents.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell and du Pont may have solved their internal Y2K
problems, ``the failure of the supply chains could bring everything
to a halt,'' said Michael P. Harden, president and CEO of Century
Technology Service Inc. of McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The same supply-line dependencies threaten public services such
as natural-gas transmission lines, experts warn. This worries
officials who realize that local governments, which typically have
responsibility for emergency response teams, are laggards in the
Y2K repair race.
</P>
<P>
   Steven D. Davis, budget manager for Montgomery County, Md.,
estimates that 73 percent of local governments nationwide lack
emergency response plans for Y2K emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local governments have been slow to deal with this,'' Davis
said. ``First we thought this was a computer problem. Then we
though it was a community problem. Now we realize it's an emergency
response problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, President Clinton's Y2K czar, Koskinen, is urging
community leaders and business executives put their energy into
solving remaining problems, rather than fretting about unlikely
disaster scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to use common sense,'' said Koskinen. ``Just
because you are know a hurricane is coming, you don't go out and
stock up on five months of food.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
