<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-DATA-$ADV26a-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE RACE TO AVOID Y2K PROBLEMS
 &HT;    With Y2K. Repeating for all needing in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories for release Saturday, Dec. 26.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's where U.S. industries and agencies are in efforts to fix
computer glitches related to the millennium date change. Each
sector's position is based on the percentage of its companies
expected to experience a crippling ``mission-critical'' failure.
</P>
<P>
   HOME STRETCH (15 percent): Banking, computer manufacturing,
insurance, investment banking, pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   HITTING THEIR STRIDE (33 percent): Aerospace, biotechnology,
consulting, heavy equipment, medical equipment, publishing,
software, semiconductors, telecommunications, retail.
</P>
<P>
   HALFWAY MARK (50 percent): Chemical processing, transportation,
power, natural gas, water, oil, medical practices, ocean shipping,
television, law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   STARTING LINE (66 percent): Agriculture, food processing, city
and town services, farming, education, government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Gartner Group, a Connecticut-based information
technology consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
