<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-CONSUMERS-DATA-$A     12-21 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CONSUMERS-DATA-$ADV26a-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A CONSUMER'S CHECKLIST FOR Y2K PREPAREDNESS
 &HT;    With Y2K-CONSUMERS. Repeating for all needing in (w) Washington
and (f) financial categories for release Saturday, Dec, 26.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some issues that consumers should be aware of in
connection with the Year 2000 (Y2K) computer problem:
</P>
<P>
   AIR TRAVEL: Consider staying home for the millennium weekend.
Airplanes are expected to be safe, but airports will be crowded.
Globally, airplane reservations already are up 300 percent for that
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL SERVICES: Discuss hospital services with your doctor.
Health care facilities are lagging behind other industries in Y2K
preparedness. Consider scheduling elective surgery before the end
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL ADVICE: Make certain you have contracts, including real
estate, wills and investments, reviewed to make sure you are
protected in case a Y2K issue affects the transaction. Many law
firms have Y2K experts on staff.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICINE: Take stock of medical supplies, especially if you need
routine medicine such as insulin or others produced by a limited
number of suppliers. Doctors are urging patients not to hoard
supplies, though.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL COMPUTERS: Contact the manufacturer of your PC or
Macintosh. Most PC should be Y2K compliant, unless they are very
old. Recent versions of popular software should be fine too.
</P>
<P>
   PORTFOLIOS: Review investments and retirement accounts to make
certain you aren't heavily invested in companies or countries
expected to be hit hard by Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL BUSINESSES: Assess business-related systems. The Small
Business Administration will guarantee loans to fix Y2K programs
for companies employing fewer than 500 people or generating less
than $5 million annually. For information, call 800-827-5722.
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTEER SERVICES: Volunteer to help sick or elderly persons
with medical or financial transactions. Experts warn that some
individuals may use Y2K as a scare tactic to swindle others out of
money or property.
</P>
<P>
   For an overview of Year 2000 consumer issues, a free brochure,
``Y2000 and You,'' is available from the Consumer Information
Center of the U.S. General Services Administration. Call
1-888-878-3256 or clicking on the center's World Wide Web page
(http://www.peublo.gsa.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Gartner Group, a Connecticut-based information
technology consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
