<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0403 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-21 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN POLITICS IS THE REAL CRIMINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ To grasp just how troubled are our times, all
that was needed was to listen to the debate over the impeachment of
President Clinton. As the hours of debate droned on, speaker after
speaker invoked the name of God on behalf of his or her argument.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians taking the name of the Lord in vain on behalf of
nothing more noble than their political self-interest is nothing
new. In this regard, the marathon of speeches in the House of
Representatives was special only because of the repetitiveness with
which the divine was enlisted in dogmatic political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   As the Republicans bulldozed toward their party-line vote, they
were disdainful of arguments that impeachment would gridlock the
work of the Senate and the Supreme Court during the trial of
Clinton. But once their doubting moderates fell into line, and it
became clear that their effort was sure to succeed, they attempted
to turn the argument they had earlier rejected to their own
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they solemnly intoned, it was up to Clinton to spare the
country the continuing spectacle and disruption of a Senate trial.
And he could do so simply by resigning his office. So once again,
as so often in the past, the affairs of men, begun as tragedy,
resolve themselves as farce. The Republican appeals for Clinton to
make the nation whole by resigning, recalls the son who, having
murdered his mother and father, asks mercy of the court because he
is an orphan.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Republicans resorting to dubious legal tactics of an
independent counsel especially chosen for the task of getting the
president, if not one way then another, that brought us to this
state of affairs. They created the crisis, and they have never
relented in their goal, which some of them have harbored and even
publicly declaimed before Clinton's affair with a White House
intern became known. To prove out that assertion, merely ask
yourselves what would have the Republicans said and done if the
president in question had been a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' attempt to stampede Clinton into collaborating
in his removal from office, exploiting the last-minute resignation
of their designated speaker because of sexual misconduct, is in
keeping with their purpose from the beginning. For the sake of the
nation, and not for his own sake or public ambition, it is
imperative that Clinton demonstrate that he will not give way, that
his backbone will not bend, that on this crucial decision he will
not retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan political adventure that has brought the nation to
this historical juncture must not be crowned with success. To
Clinton, resignation might appear more tempting than a prolonged
trial in the Senate on the embarrassing charges that already are
all too well known in their lurid detail to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   But this is an issue far surpassing the personal situation of
Clinton, whose reckless and compulsive conduct in having and then
covering up a consensual sexual affair invested the political
campaign against him with the trappings of plausibility. He must
stay the course, not for his own and his family's comfort, but for
the welfare of the nation. Were the Republicans to win now, the
signposts have long been clear. Republicans would be encouraged to
try again. Democrats, looking toward the Clinton precedent, would
be tempted to seize the first opportunity to revenge themselves on
a future Republican president.
</P>
<P>
   The abuses of congressional prerogatives would enshrine a new
anti-democratic politics, in which the will of the electorate as
voiced in presidential elections could be thwarted by a determined
and partisan Congress. These are grievous times, because a
one-sided political effort is on the verge of removing a president
from office for the commission of offenses in his private conduct
which do not merit the constitutional sanction of removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate is widely expected not to convict Clinton if it
comes to trial, no one can be sure of how developments will unfold.
The most respectable argument made by Republicans on behalf of
impeachment was that a president is not above the law. It should be
beyond dispute that Clinton should face the same sort of penalties
that an ordinary citizens would. But as the Constitution does not
provide for punishing a sitting president for low crimes, his day
in court has to be postponed until he leaves office. Therefore, the
president is not above the law. Neither should he below the law,
sustaining legal disabilities that ordinary citizens would not.
</P>
<P>
   In this consideration, the endless repetition of perjury
allegations against him remain only allegations. They have not been
proved and many legal experts have testified that the particulars
of perjury with which Clinton is accused and of which he stands
impeached, would not stand up in court. Proving obstruction of
justice would also be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   If sanity prevails, and the welfare of the nation is honored,
then we should be able to discover the merit of these allegations
sometime after Jan. 20, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
