<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SHELTER FROM BOMBS AND BOMBAST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I went to a homeless shelter and found sanity.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room and dormitory in the basement of St. Boniface
Catholic Church in San Francisco are a winter shelter for about 40
men. Last week they talked and laughed quietly while eating dinner
brought from St. Anthony's Dining Room next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the churches I know, this is the only one that opens up
for people to go to keep out of the rain,'' said Jaime Patino, who
helps out at the shelter. ``It's truly a sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm spaces of St. Boniface also offered sanctuary from the
nation's nervous breakdown. There was no television set showing
bomb blasts in Baghdad and bombast in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   St. Boniface is a growing parish, but the magnificent
111-year-old building must be retrofitted or be torn down. The
Franciscan friars need to raise $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   The many Vietnamese parishioners fast on Fridays and donate
their grocery money to the cause. As the Rev. Louis Vitale says,
``They don't have a lot of body weight to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot for a poor parish to raise, the equivalent of 11
cruise missiles or a quarter of the report by special prosecutor
Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Giving is an antidote to both of those.
</P>
<P>
   I went home and found sanity.
</P>
<P>
   We sat in front of the fire with hot cider and avoided the
images of blustering politicians and Baghdad through green lenses.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, though, we got up early to watch the
impeachment. It was a historic event, we told ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   My wife couldn't take listening to men in suits, known liars and
adulterers, using words like ``perjury'' and ``reprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember junior high and only the weenies ran for student
council?'' she said. ``Well, the weenies are running the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   She quit watching. I took a break to get some tea, and when I
came back Saddam Hussein was on the screen. He fit right in with
the congressmen.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's version of Henry Kissinger, Tariq Aziz, said: ``They
attacked radio and television stations. They are not weapons of
mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, they are. In this country at least. In the toxic
electronic cloud, there have been only a few breaths of fresh air,
like the caller to a San Francisco talk show who said she was going
to lead a ``Million Mistress March'' on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   I went Christmas shopping and found sanity. Yes, even Christmas
shopping is a relief.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby of San Francisco Centre I found a group of students
from the Barnard White Middle School in Union City. These polite,
happy kids had been shopping, and were looking forward to pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Their principal, Judy Silver, told me that many of these kids
were poor and had never been to San Francisco. They earned this
trip on the first day of their Christmas vacation by maintaining a
high grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have low expectations for teen-agers, they'll meet
them,'' Silver said. ``But if we have high expectations, they'll
meet those.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that should go for politicians, too. I asked Silver how
the kids were taking the weirdness in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I think it's weird? It's very weird for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver invited me to join them for pizza. It seemed a good way
to get away from CNN, but I had to say no. I just didn't have an
appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one antidote to impeachment and bombing madness. When you
get off a bus, or thank a salesclerk, smile and say, ``Merry
Christmas,'' ``Happy Holidays'' or the holiday greeting of your
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure not to use the phrases ``rule of law,'' ``history will
not be kind'' or ``Operation Desert Fox.'' Some bozo in the
Pentagon never heard of Nazi Gen. Erwin Rommel.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to call the attacks on Iraq ``Operation Desert
Weasel.''
</P>
<P>
   And please, no more generals using the word ``degradation'' when
speaking of blowing up things in Iraq. It's an apt word, but ask
not which nation is most degraded this Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
