<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNETH-STARR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER IMPEACHMENT VOTE, STARR MAKES WEEKLY CALL TO HIS MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Hours after the House of Representatives voted to
impeach President Clinton, independent council Kenneth Starr called
his mother. Yet the conversation never touched on the president,
Monica Lewinsky or impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't talk about business,'' Vannie Mae Starr, 91, said
Sunday at her home in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Starr _ who with Clinton will share the cover of Time
magazine this week as the Men of the Year _ focused on personal
matters in his weekly telephone call to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was tired and he was going to bed early,'' Vannie
Starr said of her son, who phoned home on Saturday after a divided
House voted to impeach Clinton based on charges made by the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a day like no other in U.S. history _ Clinton became
the first elected president to be impeached _ but Starr's mother
said their conversation wasn't any different than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a 1964 graduate of Sam Houston High School in San
Antonio, grew up in the same tiny, white house on the city's East
Side where his mother still lives.
</P>
<P>
   Vannie Starr said she was proud of her son's accomplishments as
a lawyer and judge. She said she followed the House impeachment
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My television's been acting up and I got most of it on
radio,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Often when reporters call, Vannie Starr refers them to former
Sam Houston teacher Roberta Mahan, 81.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know his mother until (about two years ago) when she
called me and asked what to do about all the reporters that were
calling,'' Mahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Mahan has been interviewed often about Starr's
student days.
</P>
<P>
   Mahan tells them Starr was a hard-working, academically talented
student who was well liked by classmates. Starr was in Mahan's
English and journalism classes in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In May, when he was in San Antonio to speak at a Law Day
luncheon, Starr arranged for his mother and Mahan to be in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Mahan recalled Starr rallying classmates to subscribe to the
school newspaper, The Raven. He wrote a number of stories and
editorials on a variety of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   In a teaching career that spanned a half century, Mahan said,
she had many talented students. Only one has been named a Time
``Man of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to death,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
