<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-GIFTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING GIFTS THAT HELP OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's Christmas time, but gift-giving can mean
more than gems or high-tech gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative gift giving _ in which a donation is made to charity
in someone's honor _ is catching the imagination of comfortable
families who feel they, personally, have more than enough. Churches
and schools have opened ``alternative gift markets'' in recent
years. You can buy your gift of charity through a catalog, a
toll-free phone line, or from a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the perfect way to honor a member of your family or
friend and still contribute to a greater cause,'' said Helen
Jacobsen, who last year bought gifts of rain forest trees, shelter
for street children in Brazil and donations to Habitat for Humanity
for her sons, daughter and daughter-in-law, then wrapped the
information in boxes and bows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sat around the Christmas tree and cried because they were
so moved and so appreciative,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Menlo Park Presbyterian links up with larger organizations
such as the Southern California-based Alternative Gifts
International, which raises more than $1 million annually for
programs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The organization offers a 30-page catalog called ``My Shopping
List for the World'' that fits almost any pocketbook. Through it,
people can buy medicine for China ($40), supplies for eye surgery
($30), a milk cow for a village in Somalia ($330), or, for those on
a budget, $10 for a share of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animal banks in Laos with chickens and pigs and other kinds of
animals are always popular with the kids,'' said Jez McIntosh, the
church's assistant director of children's ministries. This year,
the congregation's fifth- and sixth-graders researched the various
projects and made posters to hang in the parish hall during the
``alternative gift fair'' held last month.
</P>
<P>
   In four hours, the gift fair raised $20,000, twice the amount
raised at last year's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting more popular every year,'' McIntosh said. ``The
most common comment I've heard is that everybody has enough of
everything, especially in our community. It's nice to not have to
go out and shop and still be able to give something that will be
worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Though alternative gift fairs have grown in popularity mostly
over the past four or five years, the Alternative Gift
International catalog has been around since 1980 and has seen an
increase in donations every year, said Harriet Pritchard, the
organization's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans lead very privileged lives and a lot of people
really want to make a difference or do something significant,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another similar group is the Heifer Project, founded in 1954,
which raises about $1 million a year to promote self-sufficiency by
providing farm animals to poverty-stricken families around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Tom Peterson said interest has grown steadily. This
year, the project has a Web site (www.heifer.org) to help the
cyber-savvy get more connected. On it, you can buy a trio of
rabbits ($60), a crate of honeybees ($30), a flock of chicks ($20),
or a water buffalo ($250). For $5,000 you can buy The Ark, with all
of the above plus many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people always look for a way to connect with what they
see as the deeper meaning of the holidays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of such alternative gifts is similar to that of a
two-for-one bargain, according to authors Jo Robinson and Jean
Coppock Staeheli in their 1982 book, ``Unplug the Christmas
Machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you purchase your gifts from church bazaars, Third World
craft organizations, indigenous craftsmen, or nonprofit agencies,
you are giving a double gift _ one to the person who unwraps it on
Christmas morning and the other to the charitable organization
itself,'' the authors write.
</P>
<P>
   There is one caveat in charitable giving: Organizations that
monitor charities recommend doing your homework before giving to a
cause. Charities that are hesitant to provide financial information
_ such as how much of their income goes to administrative expenses
_ should be avoided. Also, it is helpful to find out where the
charity is based and talk to representatives about their mission
before giving money.
</P>
<P>
   One organization that monitors charities is the National
Charities Information Bureau, 212-929-6300, or www.give.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
