<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID TRAGEDY, SCOTTISH TAKE THE HIGH ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE, Scotland _ Ten years ago (Dec. 21, 1988) the sky
rained metal and bodies, and this small town will never be the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Because 259 people fell to earth here when Pan Am Flight 103 was
blown out of the sky, this town will be forever linked with one of
the worst aviation disasters and one of the most ruthless acts of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   What is most striking when one comes here is how small and
nondescript it is. There are just a little more than 3,000 people
living in and around the town, which looks like so many others
around the England-Scotland border.
</P>
<P>
   What is also striking is how friendly people are. It is not
surprising that many of the Americans who lost loved ones on Flight
103 have become friends with the people of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath of the disaster, some American
families had asked the US State Department to return the clothing
of the dead. The bureaucrats said no. The people of Lockerbie paid
no heed to the bureaucrats. Without being asked, they retrieved the
clothing, washed it, pressed it, and sent it back so that grieving
Americans would have something to hold.
</P>
<P>
   The victims on Flight 103 included people from 21 countries, as
well as 11 people on the ground in Lockerbie killed by the falling
debris. The people of Lockerbie guard their memories fiercely and
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter took out a notebook in a pub during a recent
visit, an older gentleman leaned over and gently said in a soft
birr, ``Be a good lad, and put that away.'' To show his
appreciation, the man bought the reporter a pint of ale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is another community in Scotland that is in mourning. If
it is possible, what happened to the tiny island community of Iona
last week was even more devastating than what happened to
Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   There are only 86 people still living on Iona, which is a sacred
place to the Scots, the birthplace of Christianity in Scotland.
Last week, four men, ages 19 to 24, drowned when the small boat
they had used to travel to a Christmas party on the mainland
capsized on the way back. A fifth man swam 45 minutes to safety,
then ran more than a mile in his bare feet to raise the alarm.
</P>
<P>
   The young men who died were single, but they were expected to
father the next generation of islanders. They were the only men on
the island between the ages of 19 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Grant, whose 33-year-old son Gordon was the only one to
survive the disaster, said many islanders now believe the
community's demise is inevitable. ``These boys were the future for
this island and we have now lost that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the Lockerbie disaster, Scotland has had one of the most
emotional 10 years of its history. In 1996, 16 children and their
teacher were fatally shot by a madman who burst into a school in
Dunblane. Sandwiched between Lockerbie and Iona, Dunblane cuts much
deeper into Scotland's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   And yet despite all of this tragedy, or maybe because of it,
Scotland's 5 million people have never seemed stronger. Its people
overwhelmingly approved a referendum last year that will give them
their own parliament. Rather than dampen the desire for outright
independence, British Prime Minister Tony Blair's decision to give
the Scottish a greater degree of autonomy has breathed more life
into the secessionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's opening of a national museum was greeted with
enormous pride. The BBC, however, recently turned down a request by
Scotland to have its own national newscast at 6 p.m. The Scottish
think the 6 o'clock news from London is too English-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Helena Kennedy, the Scottish lawyer who just became the first
woman to head Britain's biggest arts and cultural organization,
said it is a good time to be Scottish.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedies be damned. As Kennedy put it, ``The Scottish are on a
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Cullen is the Globe's London bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
