u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISLAMIC-SCHOOLS-ART-B     12-21 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAMIC-SCHOOLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIM SCHOOLS: A FEELING OF BELONGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHBOROUGH, Mass. _ In most ways, it is a typical fifth grade
classroom, decorated with posters of constellations, the solar
system and the presidents of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But taped to another wall are items that distinguish this school
from almost all others in the state: posters of Muslim prayers and
verses from the Koran, Islam's sacred book.
</P>
<P>
   Housed inside a nondescript brown brick office building here,
the Al-Hamra Academy was founded four years ago as the first
Islamic elmentary school in Massachusetts. The 64 students at the
school pray twice a day to Allah, sing Islamic hymns and learn
Arabic so they can read holy texts.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the children were concentrating on Ramadan, the
holiest month of the Islamic calendar, which began Sunday and
celebrates the divine revelation of the opening chapters of the
Koran to the prophet Mohammad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this school because we can be Muslim without having to
feel like we're like out-of-place or something,'' said Asma
Lazzouni, 11, a sixth grader at Al-Hamra Academy. ``We are learning
how to grow up to be good Muslims and that's very important to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the school was founded by Muslim families from the
Worcester area because they worried about their children's ability
to carry on the Muslim faith. Growing up Muslim in America, many
Islamic faithful say, is not always easy.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of Muslims in Massachusetts and across the country
grows, families trying to pass on their religious heritage to their
children must contend with the forces of assimiliation and a
society with a high degree of ignorance and even suspicion about
Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to fit into mainstream culture because mainstream
culture, for the most part, is still not knowledgeable about
Islam,'' said Imam Talal Eid, the spiritual leader of the Islamic
centers in Sharon and Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   Asma, who lives in Northborough, still has painful memories of
being ridiculed by her first grade public school classmates when
she told them she was Muslim. ``I'd tell them about the Koran and
they'd say that it was a fake book and that Islam wasn't a real
religion,'' recalls Asma, whose parents helped start Al-Hamra
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's challenging because, obviously, we don't live in a Muslim
culture,'' said Idrisa Pandit, who lives in Maynard and whose
5-year-old daughter is in kindergarten at a public elementary
school. ``If you lived in a Muslim culture, no matter how observant
or oriented you were toward Islam, there is still an ethos that is
pervasive, especially in the month of Ramadan. In America, we have
to create that environment.''
</P>
<P>
   One pragmatic response has been the creation of Islamic schools.
There are two in Massachusetts, which is home to between 40,000 to
50,000 Muslims, according to practicing Muslims. Besides Al-Hamra
Academy, the Islamic Center in Sharon started a K-8 school three
years ago. Both are approved by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Islam is not just going to the mosque on Friday for prayers,''
said Sadia Kahn, headmaster of Al-Hamra Academy. ``It's a way of
life. It's how you eat, it's how you work, it's how you dress. It's
everything. We felt we needed a place where the children would be
immersed in Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   The desire to instill religious values in a younger generation
of Muslims is underscored by the demand both Islamic elementary
schools have experienced.
</P>
<P>
   After starting with 100 students, the school in Sharon now has
130 pupils and the only reason the number is not higher is because
of limited space, Eid said.
</P>
<P>
   The Al-Hamra Academy plans to move to a new and bigger building
next year, adding an eighth grade and doubling its enrollment to
120. ``This school is a good way to make sure that we don't forget
the things that make us Muslims,'' said Amina Lazzouni, 7, Asma's
younger sister, who is in fourth grade at Al-Hamra Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching kids values that they don't feel or see in other kids
is very difficult,'' said Nadjette Lazzouni, Asma and Amina's
mother, who teaches at the school. It is hard, she added, to tell
Muslim children they can't do something they see their friends and
classmates doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine telling a child that they can't go trick-or-treating
or can't visit with Santa Claus,'' Lazzouni said. ``We adults know
that Muslims don't celebrate Halloween or Christmas, but children
don't. You don't like doing that to your child.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Muslim families, even those who send their children to
Islamic schools, say they do not want to isolate their children
from American society.
</P>
<P>
   But they do want to teach them that a culture whose youth are
entertained by television, movies and music seemingly saturated
with sex, violence and drugs, stands in stark opposition to Islam's
conservative mores.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason why Marwan Dajani, who owns two furniture
stores and lives in Mattapan, sends his two children to St. Mary of
Hills Elementary School in Milton. While Islam and Roman
Catholicism are certainly different, both share a strong moral
base. ``We try our best to create a healthy environment for them,''
Dajani said.
</P>
<P>
   The main challenge, many Muslims say, is to prepare their
children to flourish, academically, economically and socially, as
Americans, while still retaining a strong Islamic identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we decided to do was not to set our culture as
being against American culture,'' said Abdelsalam Hedaya, a
cofounder of InfoLibria, a computer firm in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   So Hedaya and his wife put up a Christmas tree and, at
Halloween, allow their three children to go trick-or-treating. ``We
don't decorate with religious symbols, but we still celebrate the
seasons,'' he said. ``At the same time we are very consistent about
celebrating Ramadan. We hang up lights around the house.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hedaya's children attend a rigorous weekend Arabic school in
Quincy sponsored by the Saudi Arabian embassy in Washington and
taught by Boston area Saudi scholars and graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed that if the kids felt that there was any
particular contradiction between the cultures that they might have
to choose one or the other and we don't think they need to,''
Hedaya said.
</P>
<P>
   While Islam may not yet be deeply woven into American society,
many Muslim families say they have been heartened by the tolerance
and respect shown their children by neighbors, classmates and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Because fasting from dawn to sunset is a central feature of
Ramadan, many schools give Muslim students greater leeway, allowing
them skip gym or allotting more time for assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Nadjette Lazzouni has no qualms about where her three children
will go to high school once they graduate from Al-Hamra Academy.
``I feel they are well-equipped to defend what they believe in,''
no matter where they are, she said. ``They are proud to talk about
their religion. That means the whole world to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
