<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS RUNNING OUT OF KEY CLOT-BUSTING DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hospitals around the nation are rationing their dwindling
supplies of a widely used clot-busting drug after federal officials
suspended shipments because of concerns about the risks of
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, called urokinase or Abbokinase, is a mainstay for
treating blood clots in the legs that can threaten the loss of a
limb, for dissolving dangerous lung clots, and for clearing the
tubes used by patients with kidney failure and cancer for dialysis
and chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really need this drug,'' said Dr. Anne Roberts of the
University of California at San Diego. ``There really aren't good
alternatives for many patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Boston hospitals say they have only a few days' supply of
urokinase, with no information from the drug's manufacturer, Abbott
Laboratories, about when it will resume shipments.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman Saturday said, ``We expect to have this
situation resolved shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an impending crisis,'' said Kenneth Lawrence, the
pharmacy manager at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center. ``This is
something that's starting to occur more frequently, drug shortages
that sometimes even the companies can't always explain.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with doctors Thursday, officials from the
US Food and Drug Administration were unwilling to estimate how long
the drug will be off the market, according to Tricia McClenny of
the Society for Cardiovascular and Interventional Radiology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supplies are dwindling,'' McClenny said. ``Our members say
they have almost no supplies or only enough for one or two cases.''
</P>
<P>
   McClenny said physician members of her organization say that
some patients could die or lose a limb for lack of urokinase.
Although the FDA notes that there are alternative clot-busting
drugs, physicians have far more experience using urokinase for some
common situations, and doctors say it is much less likely to cause
dangerous bleeding or allergic reactions than similar drugs.
</P>
<P>
   At New England Medical Center lat week, a man with a clot in a
leg artery was sent to surgery rather than given urokinase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we would try to use urokinase, but in this instance
the guy had to have an arterial bypass operation because we
couldn't afford to use up our available urokinase,'' said Dr. Neil
Halin of the medical center, who said the hospital has about a 1
1/2-day supply.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA ordered Abbott to suspend distribution of urokinase in
late November after inspections of the Chicago-based firm's
manufacturing plants turned up multiple problems, according to an
inspection report obtained from the federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Urokinase, a drug introduced about two decades ago, is derived
from a natural clot-dissolving substance produced by the kidneys.
Its manufacture begins with human kidney cells derived from infants
who died shortly after birth.
</P>
<P>
   Although no lots of urokinase were found to be contaminated with
bacteria or viruses, the FDA report indicates that two lots of the
neonatal kidney cells were contaminated with the hepatitis B virus
or mycoplasma, a microorganism that is intermediate between
bacteria and viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal inspectors also faulted Abbott for failing to test 10
lots of urokinase for hepatitis C virus in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of hepatitis C is one of the driving forces behind
the FDA's action, according to urokinase authorities. ``There were
a number of concerns'' about Abbott's manufacturing process with
urokinase, said an agency spokeswoman, Lenore Gelb, ``but the
number one was the viral inactivation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur Sasahara of Brigham and Women's Hospital, a former
Abbott researcher and one of the first doctors to use urokinase in
the 1970s, said that he knows of no instance in which the drug has
been contaminated by disease-causing organisms, due to a 10-hour
heat treatment. But he said the possibility of hepatitis C
contamination, which could lead to fatal liver disease, ``is what
the FDA is worried about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
