<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOOD WILL TOWARD MEN'? NOT THIS HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ The fifth-graders in the Washington public
schools brought home a work sheet the other afternoon. The answers
were: majority vote in the House, two-thirds vote in the Senate,
Andrew Johnson. You can guess what the questions were.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country schoolchildren are also having their holiday
concerts. You can hear the strains of ``Peace on earth, good will
toward men,'' even as the latest update on our bombing of Iraq
echoes in the background.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no peace. Precious little good will, either. This
is the most unsettling holiday season in years _ since, maybe,
1972, when on Christmas Day American airmen bombed the outskirts of
Hanoi, or maybe even 1941, when Americans were first coming to
grips with the notion that they were at war on two fronts, our
liberty and lifestyle in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season we're at war with ourselves. No party
dispute about that; no gender gap, either. It's as plain as day.
And we just happen also to be at war with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   So what are we to do to reclaim the holidays from politics?
Perhaps the answer is to turn away, just for this period, from
public conflict and take solace in private comforts: the strains of
familiar anthems and hymns, the reassuring presence of family, the
warm waves of enduring memories. There is a civic cost to such a
withdrawal, of course, for Thomas Jefferson reminded us that the
price of liberty is eternal vigilance. But the Founders will
forgive us, this once, if we don't let Monica S. Lewinsky and
Kenneth W. Starr nor Trent Lott and Bob Livingston intrude on our
thoughts until, say, the day after New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Odd that things have turned out this way, at the end of a year
that began with so much promise: A roaring economy. American
soldiers and sailors and fliers far from harm's way. The budget
deficit gone. Voter rebellion vanished. Crime down. Optimism up.
The pollsters even showed that more and more Americans believed
that the nation was heading in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   These were the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Were. Now we're racked with worry (over Iraq), rent with
bitterness (over impeachment), unsure of our way (about many
things.). The experts say that politics doesn't matter the way it
used to, that people aren't interested in Washington the way they
used to be, that foreign-policy challenges don't chill us the way
they used to. All three have been proven wrong in the last week. We
care a surprising amount.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we don't impeach a president every day. The last time
we did it was 1868, when we were hardly one country, though no
longer two. We were fresh out of the Civil War and the wounds, real
and psychological, were fresh. Only three years earlier, in one of
the most stirring speeches ever, Abraham Lincoln marked his second
Inaugural by pledging ``to finish the work we are in, to bind up
the nation's wounds.'' That passage, memorized by generations of
Americans, concluded with a pledge ``to do all which may achieve
and cherish a just and lasting peace among ourselves and with all
nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a modern president, charged with the ancient but common
flaws of lust and lies, faces impeachment. No one doubts that he
behaved deplorably. But, in truth, there has been bad behavior all
around; the revelations on Thursday about the infidelities of House
Speaker Livingston _ a man eager for an impeachment vote _ reminded
us of that.
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't excuse any of it, of course, but only makes the
whole atmosphere worse. Partisan anger and frustration helped fuel
the drive for impeachment; even more partisan anger and frustration
grew out of that drive. And in any case, the anger and frustration
have contaminated the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, this is the season of suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   And so as war and impeachment crowd in on the celebrations _
Christmas week, Hanukkah, Ramadan, Kwanza are all affected, a
multidemoninational downer _ we're left with the thoughts of
Lincoln, and with the yearning for a just and lasting peace among
ourselves and with all nations.
</P>
<P>
   We are, moreover, left the way we started: searching for peace
within ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Happy holidays. Happy hunting.
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
