<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETERMINING SHARES' BASE COST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I need help. I bought 100 shares of stock at $22 each. The
shares split two for one, so I then had 200 shares. I then bought
another 100 shares at $38 each. The stock again split two for one,
leaving me then with 600 shares. When selling, either 100, 200,
400, or 600 shares, what is my cost base?
</P>
<P>
   J.R., Allentown, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your total investment in the 600-share position was $6,000 _
plus the amount of the brokerage fees you paid for the two
purchases. Just as an example, let's assume the brokerage fee was
$30 each time. Thus, your base cost would be $6,060.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to sell your entire position, you would determine
your capital gain or loss by subtracting that $6,060 from the net
proceeds of the sale (again reflecting brokerage fees). If the
result is a negative number, you would have a capital loss. If it's
positive, it's a gain.
</P>
<P>
   But if you sell only part of your holdings, it can get a little
more complicated. You have two choices of how you handle the sale.
You can calculate your average cost per share, which would be
$10.10, and simply multiply the number of shares sold times $10.10
to get your base cost. Again, you would subtract that base cost
from your net proceeds to establish the capital gain or loss.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax rules also allow another method of calculating the
base cost, which is to specify the particular shares sold. Thus, if
you decided to sell 100 shares and if you wanted to minimize your
gain, you could specify that you are selling some of the shares you
purchased at $38. Adjusted for the second split, the cost base for
those shares would be $19 each, or $1,900 for 100 shares. You could
follow the same procedure if you wanted to sell 200 shares and
achieve the highest base cost _ reporting a base of $3,800 for
those 200 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose you want to go the other way _ reporting the lowest
possible base cost.
</P>
<P>
   (Perhaps you have a capital loss on some other transaction, and
want to build an offsetting capital gain.) You can then specify
that you are selling some of the shares acquired in your first
purchase. The initial 100 shares have now become 400 shares, and
their cost basis is $5.50 each. You may then sell as many of these
400 shares as you like, multiplying the number of shares sold by
$5.50 to get the cost base.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's one important technicality. The IRS dictates that
unless you specify otherwise, you must use the first method _
calculating your average cost per share for the entire position.
</P>
<P>
   To claim that you have sold specific shares you must specify in
writing to your broker that the shares you are selling were the
shares purchased at a particular date _ and/or the shares resulting
from the splitting of shares purchased on that date. Once you have
written out those instructions, maintain a copy for your tax
records.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 39 and my husband is 43. We have been putting $10,000 a
year into a 401(k) plan and $8,000 a year into a SEP-IRA, with the
two accounts now worth $140,000. All of the investments are in
stock funds. We plan to save at this rate until we retire in 15
years, but we will stop contributing to our retirement savings
plans for a six-year period beginning in six years, to pay for our
two daughters' college education. Like many investors, we are
concerned with the recent declines in our investments. Our goal is
to have $1 million saved in 15 years. Do you have any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   L.S., Portland, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, according to my calculations, you should come mighty
close.
</P>
<P>
   Following the plan you outlined above and presuming average
annual portfolio gains of 10 percent, your contributions of $1,500
a month for the next six years would take the pool to $393,269.
</P>
<P>
   During the next six years, with no additional contributions, it
would reach $697,700. And then, resuming the $1,500 monthly
contributions for the final three years, it would reach $989,620.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I run a long calculation such as that one, the answer
tends to make me nervous. It sounds so definite _ I could even have
made it $989,620.27.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, at bottom it's only a projection, and you should
probably view it as an approximation _ probably within 10 percent
plus or minus. So if you want to tilt the odds in your favor, you
could adjust the contribution levels each year.
</P>
<P>
   What I usually suggest is that you calculate how much that
$18,000 annual savings represents as a percentage of your income.
Then, presuming you achieve raises each year, maintain the savings
level as a percentage, thus raising the dollar level of your
savings program.
</P>
<P>
   The current market makes me nervous, too, but with 15 years to
go until your projected retirement date, you have plenty of time to
stay the course and ride out the market bumps.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio, which is too extensive to list here, is fairly
well diversified. The only addition I would make is to add a health
care fund to the SEP-IRA, making sure that the amount represented
there never exceeds 10 percent to 15 percent of the total
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a single divorced woman, 40 years old and without any
type of savings set up for myself. I make $27,000 a year, and I
plan to work until age 70, God willing. What can I do at this late
date to make some kind of retirement for myself? My work doesn't
offer any kind of benefits that way. I do not own anything and have
been barely scraping by most of the time, but things have settled
down. I do not understand all the different options that are out
there today, but I am willing to learn. I think I need to start an
IRA to save something for myself, but what exactly is an IRA? Where
would be the best place for me to start?
</P>
<P>
   M.J., Fullerton, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're right that the starting point to build retirement
savings is an IRA. Those letters stand for Individual Retirement
Account. These are special savings vehicles that have been set up
by the government, providing tax incentives to people to save for
their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, you are allowed to put up to $2,000 a year into an
IRA _ providing you earn at least as much as your contribution
amounts to. When you put money into an IRA, you are allowed to
deduct the amount of your contribution from your taxable income,
thus reducing your current tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the government allows your money to build in an IRA on
a tax-deferred basis until it is withdrawn in retirement. Then,
when it is finally withdrawn, it's payback time for Uncle Sam _ the
withdrawals are treated as earned income, and are taxable at that
point.
</P>
<P>
   But most people who are retired find themselves in a lower tax
bracket than when they were working, so the ultimate tax bill is
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are a few rules involving withdrawals. If you
withdraw money from an IRA before age 59 1/2, you will face a 10
percent penalty for premature withdrawal (unless you fit into a
fairly narrowly defined list of exceptions), and also have to pay
taxes on the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   After age 59 1/2 you may make any withdrawals you like, but the
amounts withdrawn will be treated as taxable income. And finally,
after age 70 1/2 you must begin a sequence of annual withdrawals
from your IRA.
</P>
<P>
   For a person who is as many years away from retirement as you
are, a prodigious amount of money can be accumulated in an IRA
account.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you could make the maximum $2,000 annual
contribution and achieved average annual gains of 10 percent from
the investments you chose for the IRA, the account would grow to
$344,064 over 30 years. Even if you could manage only half that
amount _ $1,000 a year or $83.33 a month _ you could accumulate
$172,032, following the same assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing with a program of this sort is to adopt a
savings discipline and stick to it. Better, for example, to go over
your budget and decide you can only manage $83.33 a month than to
stretch for $166.66 _ and then find that you're skipping payments
on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up an IRA is easy. You can go to a bank and face no
risks at all, but the kind of accumulations I outlined above
require moving into the riskier world of stock investments.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to write or call one of the major mutual
fund companies such as Fidelity or Vanguard (both of which have 800
numbers) and ask both for literature describing IRAs in general and
material describing their funds that track the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   However you proceed, you will probably have to begin with a
bank, because you'll have to reach the minimum investment level,
usually in the $500 to $1,000 range for IRA accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no difficulty in transferring an IRA from a bank to
a mutual fund company _ you simply tell the mutual fund company
what you want to do, fill out some forms, and they'll take it from
there.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
