<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERBER BABY JOINS THE ELF'S CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - We had the 35mm camera. We had the camcorder. There
would be another camera waiting for us there, of course, and a
computer diskette with photographic capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Edmund Hillary didn't lug along this much equipment to
document his big adventure.
</P>
<P>
   But all he did was climb Mount Everest. We were taking our
daughter to a mall to visit Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   She's only 6 months old and wouldn't know Saint Nick from
``Saint Elsewhere.'' But this is a storied American tradition, and
we intended to take part.
</P>
<P>
   If she smiled on Santa's lap, friends and relatives would have
great Christmas cards. If she shrieked in terror, we would have
something with which to embarrass her in front of future
boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   So we dressed her in a Christmas-themed outfit, combed what few
wisps of hair she has (she currently sports a modified Charlie
Brown look) and made our way to the mall. It was decked out in an
orgy of ornaments, lights and whatnot, and in its middle stood
Santa's cottage, with the Jolly Old Elf himself holding court in a
kind of wicker love seat.
</P>
<P>
   And the line was short.
</P>
<P>
   There didn't seem to be an entrance, however, so we stepped over
a string of garland and waited. I looked around for a moment, when
what to my wondering eyes should appear but a teenage girl, the one
working the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closed,'' she told us. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Unseasonable mood
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What??? How could this be?
</P>
<P>
   We have to cut it off somewhere, she explained. That's why you
couldn't find the entrance. It's closed.
</P>
<P>
   Ugh. This put me in the Christmas spirit about like a nail gun
to the head would have (though it affected my daughter not at all).
But we licked our wounds and came back another night.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the line was much longer, naturally, with about 15
families in front of us. It was going to take a while.
</P>
<P>
   The people behind us were veterans. They had packed their
daughter, Susan, a sandwich (excited in line, she cried on Santa's
lap). The family in front of us had four children, ranging in age
from 7 years to 18 months, which meant their level of excitement
ranged from mild to off the meter.
</P>
<P>
   Kids fueled the whole experience. Every time anyone in front
moved an inch, the whole line behind squeezed forward, hoping this
might knock a few seconds off the wait. But no one complained _
this Santa had a reputation as a pro with patience who read every
list and listened to every wish (he proved his mettle by not
erupting when a fat kid jumped up and down on his thigh). That's
great when you're on his lap, less so when you're waiting in line.
</P>
<P>
   After almost an hour, there were only a couple of families in
front of us. One, however, had an entire brood of kids. Who were
they, the Waltons? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Picture-perfect
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they moved on. Merry Christmas, John Boy. Now we had to
decide which photo package to buy. We thought for a minute before
opting for the inevitable Ton 'o Photos. A sucker for this kind of
thing, I also bought the computer diskette.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw you coming,'' the father in front of me said,
laughing. His family had been doing this for years; he bought a
single 5-by-7 photo for the family album. With experience comes
wisdom, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was our turn. Not old enough to fear strangers (a
problem for some kids), my daughter was perfectly happy on Santa's
lap. She smiled and giggled and looked like the Gerber baby on
holiday tour. Good plan, buying all those extra shots.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's hard to get into the holiday spirit when you're
still running the air-conditioner in your car. Balmy days and
``Sleigh Ride'' aren't always a good mix. But as we left the mall,
I realized I hadn't felt this Christmasy in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature didn't matter. Neither did the decorations.
Santa, jolly as he was, didn't either.
</P>
<P>
   But that funny little smile on my daughter's face did.
</P>
<P>
   I can hardly wait till next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
