<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE'S VOICE   WAS IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We interrupt this constitutional crisis to bring you a slice of
reality: The Great Train Store in Natick, Mass. is running low on
Lionel starter sets; Borders is doing a brisk enough business to
keep Tom Wolfe in white suits into the next century; Furbies are
out of stock everywhere, but there are still Cool Blue Barbies to
be had at Kay Bee Toy Stores.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States Congress breathlessly counts down the
days of the Clinton presidency, we are ticking off the shopping
days until Christmas. We are not apathetic; we are irrelevent. We
recognize that Congress is again off on a toot of its own. Who can
blame people for going to the mall given our lack of impact on the
vote Saturday in ``the people's House?''
</P>
<P>
   In telegrams and opinion polls, Americans for weeks have
appealed to our elected representatives to find a middle course, to
punish the president for his reckless misdeeds without subjecting
us to an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing my constituents or anyone else could say to
me at this point,'' Congressman Bill McCollum, a Republican
Judiciary Committee member from Florida said as House debate on
impeachment resumed Saturday. ``We are not listening to the public
at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   If not at this moment, then when, Mr. McCollum?
</P>
<P>
   McCollum and his majority party in the House insisted that one
man's record of deceit and manipulation has put the presidency
itself in peril. What is the risk, then, to representative
democracy when the well-modulated voice of the American people is
silenced by the vengeful cries of our elected representatives? What
is the danger of a political process engineered for retribution
rather than resolution?
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the surface comity _ the gentle lady from Impeachment
Now yielding without objection to the gentleman from Censure
Alternative _ the refusal to consider any but the ultimate sanction
against President Clinton was the culmination of a bitter
partisanship that has undermined progress on substantive issues
from health care to Social Security. The rancor did not begin with
William Jefferson Clinton, though certainly the personal enmity his
behavior engenders has exacerbated it.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been moving for a quarter century toward partisan
paralysis and away from what the historian Arthur Schlesinger Jr.
once called ``the search for remedy.'' The idealism that once made
so many Americans view politics as an instrument of social progress
has been reduced to the sexual voyeurism that Saturday forced
Congressman Bob Livingston of Louisiana to surrender his seat and
his pending speakership of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no stability in the House since 1987 when Thomas
P. O'Neill Jr. returned home to Massachusetts after 10 years as
speaker. Livingston is only the latest victim of what O'Neill's
successor, Jim Wright of Texas, called the ``mindless cannibalism''
of a once deliberative body, now riven by vicious
self-righteousness. Republican Newt Gingrich of Georgia
self-immolated only a month ago, singed by the flames of his own
incindiary rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   For all the meanness and mistrust, for all the smallness and
suspicion, there were moments of quiet grace and stirring eloquence
on the floor of the House within the last 48 hours. Not every
Republican was participating in what Patrick Kennedy of Rhode
Island characterized as ``a political lynching.'' One could hardly
doubt the sincerity of J. C. Watts Jr. of Oklahoma, who could not
reconcile the president's lies with the ideals he is trying to
teach his children. Not every Democrat was simply doing his party's
bidding. One could hardly doubt the dismay of Charles Schumer of
New York, who could not reconcile the use of impeachment to punish
a sexual indiscretion, no matter how cunningly covered up.
</P>
<P>
   If we only had any sense that those of differing but good will
were actually listening to one another Saturday. Maybe then, we
retain some hope that, at some juncture, the people's House will
respond to us once more.
</P>
<P>
   It took a political Independent, Bernard Sanders of Vermont, to
speak for the hopeless among us who finally gave up and went
shopping. ``I have never fully appreciated before just how out of
touch this institution is with the American people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
