A0497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-21 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE CONGRESSMEN IN SEARCH OF AN IMPEACHMENT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in microcosm, you can see what went wrong in the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Charles Bass and John Sununu of New Hampshire and
Democrat Jim McGovern of Massachusetts were not players in the
impeachment farce and are doubtless happy that was so. But they
were voters nonetheless, just as powerful in the end as Bob Barr,
Lindsey Graham, and Bill Delahunt.
</P>
<P>
   And as such, they were stuck with what proved an impossible task
_ explaining a decision that could not be justified with reference
to a body of ``facts,'' a common concept of what constitute
impeachable offenses, or even a clear definition of the offenses
with which President Clinton is charged.
</P>
<P>
   All three were bipartisanly partisan. McGovern voted ``no'' all
the way; Bass and Sununus voted ``yes'' on all the close votes,
though Bass did join 80 other Republicans in rejecting the fourth
article of impeachment alleging perjury in last month's game of 81
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, they reflected what all voting commentators on this
mess were forced to reflect: a mass of grand jury material that was
never investigated, its internal contradictions never resolved, its
witnesses never tested by the probing heat of cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Under such impossible conditions, the best roles Bass, Sununu,
and McGovern could play were as sightless people touching different
parts of an elephant and identifying their tiny corner of reality
with certainty.
</P>
<P>
   On the guilty side, Bass and Sununu deplored perjury without
identifying a single perjurious statement, exactly as in the
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On the House floor late Friday, Jim McGovern argued for a
summary judgment based on prosecutorial abuse, as did most of the
Democrats on the Judiciary Committee. He made no case against the
case itself, inferential and incomplete as it is.
</P>
<P>
   This unhappy situation is the result of what both the
Republicans and the Democrats did during an inquiry that was really
not an inquiry at all.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the fortunately expiring Independent Counsel Act, all
the Republicans did was receive Ken Starr's argumentative referral,
release it along with his grand jury material, and then reproduce
it with different words. No testing of the evidence or of the
witnesses ever occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The burden of proof should never be on a defendant, presidents
included, but the fact remains that the Democrats also chose to
pick at the evidence rather than put on their own inquiry. And
worse, the full committee never did what its Watergate counterpart
did with such care _ reach a consensus on what constitutes
impeachable conduct and on the standards for a yes vote on an
article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The result, almost by bipartisan conspiracy, was a bunch of
people (initially 37, eventually 435) picking and choosing their
favorite and least favorite pieces of raw material or dismissing
the entire case.
</P>
<P>
   Bass got but 60 seconds on the floor late Friday to claim that
Clinton ``knowingly'' lied under oath, following the Judiciary
Committee's tack of labeling unidentified testimony. Similarly, he
followed Republican form in asserting that Clinton ``attempted to
corruptly influence'' others' testimony, ignoring the assertions of
Monica Lewinsky and Betty Currie that he did not.
</P>
<P>
   In his material announcing his decision last week, Bass at least
departed from many of his GOP colleagues in not claiming he was
simply voting to ``send'' the case to the Senate, saying his vote
to impeach means he believes the president should not hold his
office any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Sununu, who announced his intention a bit earlier, to no one's
surprise, followed a similar path in his own statement. Where he
differed primarily was in flatly stating many of the ``facts''
actually in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sununu said Clinton conspired to ``obstruct justice
by encouraging witnesses to hide evidence'' _ despite the fact that
no grand jury witness testified to that effect. And he bought into
another element of that alleged offense by ignoring the testimony
of Betty Currie that the president did not try ``to intimidate her
into providing false testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   And both, to their shame, attempted to draw inferences from
their claim _ which is false _ that the president offered no
contradiction of the ``facts'' in Starr's referral.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, McGovern attacked partisanship, the subject matter
of the case, and the denial of a censure alternative. In effect, he
demanded summary judgment rather than acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the three congressmen were footnotes to the main
story. But they were also metaphors, with full voting rights, for
an inquiry that accomplished nothing beyond the amplification of
deep divisions.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't their fault. The case they had to consider could never
have been anything more than the vehicle for a shouting match. But
they voted, and that act will eventually be judged.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
