<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      12-21 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CLINTON'S FATE, A CONGRESSIONAL ASCENDANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton began his march to the White House in the fall
of 1991, only two years had passed since the fall of the Berlin
Wall marked the end of the Communist empire and the transformation
of the American presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The president has always reigned supreme in wartime, as the
national leader and emblem of American values, and the Cold War
period had been no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, was vying to become the first postwar
president in almost five decades. Politically dextrous and
emotionally responsive, Clinton seemed as well suited to an era
dominated by domestic issues, and thus by shared power and
persuasion, as he was ill-suited to wartime.
</P>
<P>
   His liabilities _ avoidance of military service, marital
infidelity _ might have ruled him out during a time when the
president unblinkingly answered to ``Leader of the Free World.''
But that title, and the grandiose expectations that went with it,
died with the Communist empire.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was elected to a weaker office, amid lower expectations.
And last week, as the House denied him even the usual deference
accorded a commander in chief when soldiers are in the field, both
the president and his office seemed to grow even weaker by the
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Clinton stands impeached, some historians are wondering
about the extent to which the tides of history, and not simply the
accidental confluence of a sexual harassment suit, a lie about sex,
and an aggressive independent counsel, are drawing the presidency
inexorably into the arms of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an argument of luxury,'' said Michael Corgan,
presidential historian at Boston University, as he watched last
Friday's impeachment debate. ``We wouldn't be doing this if the US
were really imperiled. It's now safe for Congress to take power
back and make the president less of a leader. He can't use that
excuse anymore _ that he can't be disturbed because there are vital
issues at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Columbia University historian Eric Foner, ``National
crises tend to aggrandize the power of the president. In more
normal times, the balance tends to shift away from the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, of course, is not alone in having assumed the
presidency during a period of congressional ascendency. Similar
fates befell other postwar presidents _ including, most
dramatically, the man to whom he is now twinned in history, Andrew
Johnson, the only previous president to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson survived a trial in the Senate by one vote, but the
impeachment presaged a long era of weakened chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   While Foner noted that the Johnson crisis was spurred by sharp
policy differences over vital national issues _ differences all but
absent in the current clash _ others saw the 1868 impeachment as a
reaction to the unprecedented powers assumed by Abraham Lincoln
during the Civil War, a kind of pendulum swing back in the favor of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the House and the Senate had stayed home for much of
the Civil War, allowing Lincoln to rule largely unfettered as
commander in chief of America's armed forces, the major power
ascribed to the president under the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln's political acumen, combined with the prestige earned by
steering the Union to victory, seemed to promise an orderly
reconstruction. But Lincoln was assassinated just as the war was
ending, and Johnson, a Southerner who had remained loyal to the
Union, uneasily assumed his mantle.
</P>
<P>
   When the Republicans in Congress clashed with Johnson over the
standards for readmitting Southern states, the House and Senate
moved quickly to restrict the president's powers.
</P>
<P>
   They approved the ``Tenure of Office Act'' to prevent Johnson
from replacing any of Lincoln's Cabinet officers, thereby assuring
that the hawkish Edwin Stanton would remain as secretary of war.
When Johnson defied the act by firing Stanton, the House impeached
him by an overwhelming majority.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson remained in office for another year, his standoff with
Congress paralyzing the country.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency, many believe, didn't regain its luster for more
than 30 years, until Theodore Roosevelt ascended ``the bully
pulpit'' and, in the name of the people, declared war on the
economic excesses of the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   The office assumed even greater power under Roosevelt's rival,
Woodrow Wilson. World War I made the United States a world power,
and Wilson became the preeminent figure of the postwar world.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress, following a familiar postwar scenario, rejected
Wilson's grand vision for a League of Nations in an epic grudge
match that rendered the president politically weakened even as he
was physically disabled by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Warren G. Harding, Wilson's successor, promised a ``return to
normalcy'' that would last a dozen years, before the successive
crises of the Depression and World War II would restore the
dominance of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not in a war, it's hard to see what the power of
the presidency is,'' Foner said, citing the relatively powerless
presidencies of the late 19th century and the 1920s. ``The power of
the presidency is the ability to put yourself forward as spokesman
of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Harry Truman clashed with the ``do nothing''
80th Congress in a standoff somewhat reminiscent of Johnson's and
Wilson's struggles. But Truman's invoking of the Communist threat
broke the logjam, prompting Congress's approval of aid to Greece
and Turkey, and the ``Truman Doctrine'' ushered in the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Truman and his four immediate successors bestrode the world
stage: Lyndon Johnson's escalation of the Vietnam War, based only
on a loosely worded Senate resolution, was a high-water mark of
presidential authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Watergate scandal, immediately following the Vietnam War,
and Richard Nixon's resignation, changed the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the aftermath of the president more or less running
the Vietnam War out of his back pocket,'' said Corgan. ``I see
Watergate, and Nixon's resignation, as part of the same'' pattern
toward postwar congressional leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Clinton struggles to remain in office, a desire for more
congressional control is ``not the only argument out there, but
it's part of it,'' Corgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Hillary Clinton have long maintained that they are
transitional figures representing a younger generation, with a
world view informed by the clashes of the '60s: the antiwar
movement, the civil rights movement, and feminism.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's overtly political style _ the narrow
tailoring of issues to build coalitions, the cat-and-mouse
gamesmanship with Congress _ also marks a transition from the more
lordly approaches of Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   No longer the guardian of American freedom against a foreign
enemy, the president must, by necessity, lead by persuasion. The
history of the Clinton administration _ from the epic defeat over
health care, to the tussle over the Contract With America, to the
government shutdown of 1995 _ reflects the seesawing of power
between the president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion surveys suggest Clinton commands the support of the
people in the impeachment crisis, but with the next election two
years away, it's hard to tell how much the polls will hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   As Foner, Corgan, and others point out, the sheer ``normalcy''
of the times, with no imminent threat abroad and no economic crisis
at home, leaves Clinton vulnerable. After all, how profoundly
disruptive can it be to replace one moderate Democrat with another?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
