<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-TRAVEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARATION CAN EASE THE STRESS OF HOLIDAY TRAVEL DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in national news, ``a,'' and travel, ``t,''
categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When a lightning storm at the Ronald
Reagan-Washington National Airport outside Washington forced the
plane back to the terminal, many passengers got confused, some got
upset, others got ready to run for the gate agent. Molly Brodie got
out her Rolodex and cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Before Brodie even stepped off the plane, she had booked another
flight to San Francisco and a hotel room for the night.
</P>
<P>
   With the prospect of holiday crowds, travel specialists are
urging passengers to expect delays and be ready with a ``Plan B.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the survival of the fittest,'' said Lauri Berger,
editor of Consumer Reports' Travel Letter, who recommends that
holiday travelers use ``guerrilla tactics,'' or face sleeping in an
airport. ``You learn to play the game, and it's the road warriors
that talk their way in and out of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The busiest travel days this holiday season are likely to be
Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday as travelers try to reach the homes
of friends and relatives by Christmas Eve, airport officials said.
Terminals also are expected to be packed on Jan. 2, as passengers
return home after New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to crowded parking lots and congested traffic
outside the terminals, travelers can expect beefed-up security
because of the recent airborne attacks on Iraq by American and
British forces. Weather also could lead to delays.
</P>
<P>
   Brodie, who flies more than 100,000 miles a year as a senior
researcher for the Kaiser Family Foundation, said just having the
phone number for an airline or travel agent can reduce many delays
caused by crowds and poor weather. The payoff for her: While most
of the other 200 passengers on her storm-delayed flight were
waiting in line for help, she strolled off to dinner and a soft
bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't dare wait for someone to take care of you,'' she said.
``Expect beyond-belief delays and create options for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodie said holidays fliers should allow more time between
connecting flights to steer through crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said passengers should demand a seat assignment when
making reservations to avoid the dreaded middle or nonreclining
seat. As a ``road warrior'' herself, Berger said she tries to board
the plane first, regardless of where she is supposed to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They generally don't check your boarding pass, and that way
you can get some place to put your carry-ons,'' she said. ``And the
worst thing that can happen is they'll send you to the end of the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   During holidays, airlines strictly limit passengers to two
carry-on bags. To avoid bulk, airport officials suggest that
passengers pack gifts in their checked luggage and wrap them once
they arrive at their destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wilson, a spokesman for the San Francisco International
Airport, said X-ray machines at security checkpoints have trouble
detecting through foil wrap and tin containers. If X-ray monitors
can't see what is inside a package, passengers may be asked by a
security guard to unwrap it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent military action against Iraq, Wilson said
passengers would hardly notice stepped-up security, which includes
more bomb-sniffing dogs and tow trucks to remove unattended
vehicles. He said passengers would still be asked to present photo
identification and answer security questions, precautions put in
place after the Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kabo, a consultant specializing in corporate travel,
said his best advice was to fly early in the day and enter through
the arrivals area.
</P>
<P>
   If crowds become too much, Kabo said, he likes to escape in a
book. Others, he said, take free shuttles to nearby hotels to avoid
airport noise and bustle.
</P>
<P>
   When all else fails, Brodie said, it helps to recognize that
other people are going through the same frustrations and that
airline workers probably aren't responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``And once you've done all that you can to fix any problems,
then the only thing you can do is remove yourself mentally away
from the chaos,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
