<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-21 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WILL LOSE IN SENATE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if he survives? That's the question Democratic senators ask
themselves as they contemplate President Clinton's impeachment by
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome in the House is no longer in doubt. A president who
has been impeached is governing us.
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings then move to the US Senate for trial. There will
be no deal on censure there, just as there was no deal on censure
in the House. Republican constituencies simply will not allow it.
Indeed, on this point of procedure, the voice of Republican
constituents has already prevailed. Thursday, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott said the Senate would not deviate from the
straight and narrow path prescribed by the Constitution. There will
be no easy way out.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of Republican senators will vote for
conviction, so the president's fate now rests in the hands of 45
Democrats. They must decide whether to condone or condemn his
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Morally, they know that if they vote against conviction, they
will have ceded the high ground to their Republican colleagues.
They will not be the ones upholding the Constitution. They will not
be the ones insisting that no man is above the law. Their
Republican colleagues will state that case and it will ring true,
as it always has.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Democratic senators who vote to condone will establish
what may in time become known as The Clinton Exemption. The Clinton
Exemption will aver that a president may lie under oath in a sexual
harassment suit, may lie under oath to the presiding federal judge
in that suit, may lie to his Cabinet and counselors, may lie to the
country he governs, may lie under oath to duly appointed officers
of the Department of Justice in a federal criminal investigation,
may lie to the House Judiciary Committee presiding over hearings on
his impeachment, and, should he so choose, may engage any number of
people in our employ to lie on his behalf, so long as he lacks the
courage to face embarrassment. It is a precedent that will be
etched in the acid of dishonor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, senators who vote to condone Clinton's conduct will
be voting to overlook serious and substantial charges of witness
tampering and obstruction of justice, both of which are ongoing
subjects of federal criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tall order for men like Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, a devout Roman Catholic and a dedicated public servant.
That is a tall order for Senator Robert Kerrey of Nebraska, whose
character is attested to by a Congressional Medal of Honor. That is
a tall order for Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, whom history will
regard as perhaps the greatest senator of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Those that vote to condone will do their best to put things in
the best possible light. They will argue that Clinton's offenses do
not rise to the level of impeachment. They will minimize and
rationalize and justify Clintons conduct; splitting every legal
hair as they go. They will decry Republican tactics and the
zealotry of its right wing. They will recite the chapter and verse
of public opinions polls objecting to the president's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And as they do so they will dishonor the very liberal values
that have guided their party across a century of political life.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, if enough Democrats vote to condone, then they will
have Clinton hanging around their necks for the next two years. The
president himself will lack the moral authority to do anything, and
the corruption of political life will continue apace. Everything
will be transactional. Ethics will be a joke. Spin will reign
triumphant. And come the year 2000, they can all campaign together
under a banner that states: One Man is Above the Law.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, they will be left with their consciences and the
judgment of history. They work in office buildings named after men
like Everett Dirksen and Phil Hart, giants of political courage and
fortitude. In the halls and in committee hearing rooms, they sit
under portraits of men who changed the course of history. Almost to
a person, the 45 Democratic senators don't admire Bill Clinton.
They admire his political skills and facility, but with regard to
his character they can barely conceal their contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Why any Democratic senator would lift a finger to help him is a
mystery. It is said in Washington that the votes to convict Clinton
cannot be found in the Senate chamber. Do not believe it. Not one
Democratic senator believes the four articles of impeachment are
insubstantial. And most of them believe that every word of the
articles is true.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
