<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-21 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN AGENDA LEGIBLE TO ALL BUT MOST DON'T WANT TO READ IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Republicans' rush to get President Clinton impeached
before the new Congress is sworn in next month strongly suggests
that their true intentions had nothing to do with their
constitutional responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they had everything to do with a right-wing agenda to
finally accomplish what they have been trying to do for the past
six years: humiliate, embarrass, and, if possible, destroy Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   GOP partisans would not allow even US air attacks against Iraq,
or the latest Republican scandal _ House Speaker-elect (and now
resigned) Bob Livingston's admission last week of marital
infidelities _ to slow the impeachment stampede.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to judgment is fueled, in part, by the Republicans'
knowledge that some of the current members voting for impeachment
won't be back next month, having lost their seats in last month's
elections. It's hard to say how the new members might vote.
</P>
<P>
   After all, some of those new members might wonder, as does most
of the nation's electorate, what Clinton's affair with former White
House intern Monica S. Lewinsky has to do with a constitutional
danger to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Livingston forced to acknowledge his own adulterous
affairs, the Republicans' moral standing has grown even more shaky.
His GOP supporters claim that at least Livingston didn't lie under
oath _ as they say Clinton did. But that begs the question of
whether lying about sex under oath is truly an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress believes it is, then it might also consider whether
a congressman who takes the oath of office, but fails to uphold the
trust of his electorate by committing adultery, is equally
culpable.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, with all due respect to the moral integrity embodied in
Congress, Livingston, and even Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, could also be accused of breaking a public trust _ a lying
under oath, of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Although the legality of such a charge might be open to
challenge, it does help to underscore the hypocrisy of the GOP
right-wing in its pursuit of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Once Clinton acknowledged his affair with Lewinsky, the entire
issue should have ended with a reprimand or censure from Congress.
However, such an appropriate punishment was never the intent of a
right-wing Republican-dominated Congress frustrated over its
inability to nail Clinton after failing to defeat him in the last
two elections. The GOP has had Clinton in its sights because he
trumped their issues, and seized control of much of the Republican
agenda, including overhauling welfare.
</P>
<P>
   After the GOP could not get him on Whitewater, Travelgate,
Filegate, or charges of illegal campaign fund-raising, it saw an
opening _ with independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's questionable
charges _ to zero in on the president. Both Clinton's critics and
supporters know that he, as President Andrew Johnson 130 years ago,
will be remembered for the impeachment effort against him _ even if
the Senate acquits.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win the support of wavering Republicans and the
public, the GOP argued that a House vote for articles of
impeachment was little more than a procedural vote, and that the
Senate will likely not convict Clinton anyway. That strategy
persuaded some members to swing over to the pro-impeachment side.
But for Republicans to treat a such a serious charge so frivously
betrays their true motives; they are using, not following, the
Constitution to pursue their own political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate hearings could paralyze Congress, if not the nation,
for several months. If the Congress of 1998 did almost no
legislating, the Congress of 1999 might end up doing even less.
</P>
<P>
   There are, at the moment, not enough votes in the Senate to
convict Clinton by the required two-thirds majority. But by having
the hearings proceed anyway, Republicans give themselves another
opportunity to vilify the president. They reason that if they can
get him to resign, they will have accomplished a second goal:
making Clinton the second president in history to resign from
office.
</P>
<P>
   When Hyde suggests that Clinton resign to save the country from
this difficult Senate trial, he is not saying it as a humanitarian,
but as a partisan who wants to even a so-called political score.
</P>
<P>
   However, when President Nixon was forced by his own party to
resign, the charges against him were so legitimately serious that
his closest supporters were convinced that he would have been, and
perhaps should have been, convicted in the Senate of far more
serious charges than perjury.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans hope that a Senate trial will be a lengthy
setack for the Democratic Party's agenda, it may instead result in
a serious setback for the nation and its people. A trial could
degenerate into a political civil war between the parties that
would ultimately destroy an already eroding link between government
and its people.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republican right wing will be blamed for creating a
very costly post-impeachment disaster, it will be the people who
will have to pay the price. And, for millions of Americans who see
through the Republicans' agenda, that price is already too high.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
