<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!  1/2 ``Prince of Egypt'' DreamWorks' splashy animated biblical
epic tells the story of Moses and the Exodus from Egypt more
fleetly than Cecil B. De Mille did in 1956 with Charlton Heston.
The drawing is spectacular, the acknowledgment that Moses' people
were Jews more overt. But in the end, this noble effort is more
imposing than stirring, and leaves one wondering why DreamWorks
didn't insist on creating a new animation style that moves farther
away from Disney's. (PG)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``La Separation'' Christian Vincent impressively details
the disintegration of a Parisian couple's relationship into a
minefield. Daniel Auteuil and Isabelle Huppert supply beautifully
gauged and nuanced performances, acting mostly with their eyes as
they slide into ever more corrosive territory. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``You've Got Mail'' Tom Hanks, Meg Ryan, and
writer-director Nora Ephron know just how to mix the comedy and
sentiment. This warm, clever confection plays more like their
``Sleepless in Seattle'' than like the update it is of ``The Shop
Around the Corner'' to the age of e-mail. Ryan and Hanks woo on the
Internet, unaware that he's behind the voracious chain out to
devour her book shop. A bit prefab, but the faults are overridden
by the charm and appeal of the leads. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   (FR)  &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Ten Benny'' Eric Bross's assured debut film
convinces us that there are streets in suburban New Jersey as mean
as any in Manhattan's Little Italy in this story of three buddies
who grow up, then grow apart. Adrien Brody's jumpy, appealing
performance, as a kid with a gambler father and a self-detructive
streak, got him a lead role in ``The Thin Red Line.'' (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
