<HEADER>
A0518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-JERKS-BOS &LR;      12-21 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-JERKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANK YOU FOR BEING THE CLOD OF OUR FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
hol-i-day (hol'i-da') n. A designated day during which one is
obliged to spend time with relatives one normally avoids.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is one definition of ``holiday.'' And it happens to be the
one that's in the lexicon of Mark Rosen, author of ``Thank You For
Being Such a Pain: Spiritual Guidance for Dealing with Difficult
People.''
</P>
<P>
   The book could hardly be more opportune, this being the time of
year when families reconvene, stress levels rise, and someone can
usually be relied on to offend someone else: The obnoxious uncle
who brags about how much money he makes, right after you've told
him you just got laid off. The cousin who gets into an argument
with his father, then walks out in a huff. The aunt who loudly
informs her niece that she's wearing too much makeup.
</P>
<P>
   In the presence of such difficult people, the average person
would probably be tempted to cringe, or slip away, or swear, or
yell and make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you dealt with these situations in a more charitable
way, a spiritual way? What if you viewed that oafish person not as
an antagonist but, as Rosen suggests, a teacher who is part of a
larger cosmic scheme, challenging us and giving us ``a divine kick
in the spiritual butt?'' A person, in short, whose characteristics
``exactly correspond to the places within us that need learning and
healing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the perspective that Rosen invites his readers to
consider in his recently published book, which grew out of the
workshops he teaches to businesses and adult education classes.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult people are lurking everywhere, all the time, notes
Rosen, an industrial relations specialist who teaches management
courses at Bentley College and at Brandeis University's Hornstein
Program in Jewish Communal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult people are the customers who demand a refund when they
can't produce a bill. They are the managed-care representatives who
won't listen to logic. They're the coworkers who gossip, the bosses
who yell, the guy in the next car who honks because you stopped to
let a pedestrian cross. ``There's no escaping them,'' Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   But he contends that our encounters with difficult people are
not just chance occurrences but rather events orchestrated by ``an
intelligence totally beyond our comprehension'' to enhance our
personal and spiritual growth. An experience with a deceitful
person, for example, teaches us the merits of being cautious. An
encounter with someone cruel reminds us to treat others with
kindness. A selfish person shows us the value of generosity.
</P>
<P>
   For Rosen, a Newton, Mass. resident who is an observant Jew,
that elusive ``intelligence'' is God, but he acknowledges that one
needn't believe in a higher power, or even possess a spiritual
mind-set, to benefit from his guide, published by Harmony Books.
``I'm not on a campaign to get anyone to believe,'' he said in an
interview. I'm looking to help people make practical changes in
their behavior, so they don't hurt anyone, or hurt themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Difficult people are in our lives for a reason,'' Rosen
writes, and that reason isn't always the one we ascribe to them
(such as ``They're out to get us,'' or ``They're insensitive
fools''). ``Sometimes,'' writes Rosen, difficult people ``help us
learn about ourselves, work on difficult issues, and confront
painful truths.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this doesn't make the other guy's boorish behavior
any more palatable, so in his book _ which draws on Eastern,
Christian, and Jewish doctrines _ Rosen recommends a multifaceted
strategy to keep from being driven buggy by annoying people. He
urges readers, for example, to remember that there are lots of
explanations for why someone might be difficult _ they are ill,
perhaps, or preoccupied with a personal problem. He recommends
giving the difficult person the benefit of the doubt, a notion, he
points out, that derives from the Torah. (``You shall judge your
fellow man with righteousness,'' Leviticus 19:15.)
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean resigning yourself to the behavior, but it
does keep you from acting rashly by drawing premature conclusions,
Rosen said. ``It means that in your personal life, you practice the
same principle that applies in a court of law: Difficult people are
innocent until proven guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastering your own anger in aggravating situations is another of
Rosen's suggestions _ an idea inspired by the Dalai Lama, who
maintains that anger cannot be overcome by anger. If tempers flare
on both sides, ``no one gets anywhere,'' said Rosen. Best to
practice a more constructive ``intrapersonal'' method of blowing
off steam, like going for a walk, or getting in the car, driving to
the far corner of a parking lot, and screaming at the top of one's
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   If all this talk about God and the Dalai Lama and the Torah
seems an unlikely vocabulary for an industrial relations
specialist, Rosen, 45, agrees. He describes himself as a
``professor by day, and seeker by night'' _ a spiritual seeker,
that is. Even as he worked toward his doctorate in industrial
relations from the University of Wisconsin, he was reading sacred
texts in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, I probably should have gone to divinity
school,'' Rosen said. Instead, he nudged his career toward the
``people side of the business world,'' teaching human resource
management as well as workshops on dealing with difficult people in
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   But he said his students started telling him that the workshops
applied to more than just the workplace. ``They said this can apply
to my brother-in-law too.'' So he stretched the workshop to include
interpersonal conflicts and was approached independently by both a
literary agent and a publisher to write a book on the subject.
``Thank you For Being Such a Pain'' is now being translated into
Chinese and Japanese and is recommended by five national book
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen came by his interest in difficult people naturally. For
one thing, he says, he is the son of one. His father, a ``lovable''
man to whom he now feels very close, was a Polish Holocaust
survivor who ``carried around an enormous amount of emotional pain
which he never expressed,'' and inadvertently redirected it to his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen himself admits to having done ``some bonehead things''
when he was younger, particularly to his two younger siblings. ``I
wasn't the best older brother,'' he admits in the book. ``I would
be less than honest if I didn't also admit to being difficult
myself. Certainly not to everyone, and hopefully not all that
often, but enough so that I've managed to annoy some and hurt a
few.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Rosen's tips for dealing with difficult people on the
holidays:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ If someone offends you at a holiday gathering, deal with the
situation as soon as possible in a direct and respectful way, so it
doesn't fester. ``Take Aunt Sadie aside and say, `That was an
unkind thing you just said,''' Rosen suggests. You'll get it off
your chest and save yourself a lot of anguish. But, he warns, don't
count on being able to change Aunt Sadie's personality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monitor your own alcohol consumption level, and that of
others. The potential for causing problems is multiplied by
alcohol, and ``people who are normally mildly annoying can be
outrageously stupid when intoxicated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Try gentle humor, especially when the conflict is over
something trivial, but avoid sarcasm, name-calling, and other
negative forms of humor.
</P>
<P>
   _ If all else fails, grin and bear it. You only see that uncle
once a year, ``and anyone can make nice for one evening.'' See the
situation as an exercise in self-restraint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
