<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BO     12-21 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAEKUP MEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's the biggest joke between roommates Lynn Quealy and
Nicole Dever. When Quealy wants to know the latest hot makeup
trends, she doesn't flip through Cosmopolitan or Elle. Her best
source is, of all things, a man _ Edward Fee, a Chanel makeup
artist at Filene's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really excited to get a makeover by a man. I've always
had it done by a woman in the past,'' says Quealy, 23, who visits
Fee regularly. ``It's exciting to get a man's perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, thought Dever, 23. Lipstick and mascara tips from a guy?
``I don't even go to a male hairdresser,'' she says. Then Dever had
a makeover too. ``He has ways of putting on eyeshadow that I would
never have thought of,'' she says now. ``And if he thinks it looks
good, then other men might too.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about role reversal. Today, more than ever before, there
are male makeup artists everywhere giving hands-on advice to women
about their looks. It's an interesting development for an industry
created, in many ways, by female entrepreneurs like Helena
Rubinstein, Estee Lauder, Mary Kay Ash, and Florence Nightengale
Graham (founder of Elizabeth Arden).
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that selling makeup was one of the few
good jobs available to women. ``The industry was in many ways built
by women because they were discriminated against in most other
industries,'' says Kathy Peiss, a University of Massachusetts at
Amherst history professor and author of the book ``Hope in a Jar:
The Making of America's Beauty Culture.''
</P>
<P>
   So why are men getting into the act? ``It's big business,'' says
Dave Dodge, manager of the cosmetics department at Neiman Marcus in
Boston, which employs seven male makeup artists (out of 60). ``More
and more, we live in an environment focused on youthful looks. We
(makeup artists) play a huge role.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have always been men in the industry. David
Hall McConnell founded Avon Cosmetics in 1886. Max Factor founded
his firm in 1909. And Charles Revson created Revlon in 1932. But
clearly, these were businessmen who worked mostly behind the
scenes, not on sales floors with actual women customers. Indeed,
says Peiss, ``Women really made cosmetics acceptable and popular
among women. They had some understanding of how to turn products
that were seen as disreputable into something that women should use
on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, it's much more common for stores to employ male
artists locally or host the visits of national makeup artists, who
travel around the country meeting with customers. Says Dodge, ``We
can book a man (for shopper makeovers). He's usually good-looking,
tall, and aggressive . . . and in society, there is a line of
flirtation.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Just ask Sarah Cardozo Duncan. After chatting for 20
minutes recently with Keith Cavaleri, a Bobbi Brown makeup artist
at Neiman Marcus, she decided to return later for a whole new look.
Why? Not only does Cavaleri know his colors, says Duncan, but ``he
has fabulous eyebrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might argue that men have an advantage over women behind
the counter because frequently the women artists are just too
heavily made-up for the real world. Says Dever, ``Sometimes I see a
lady at the counter and I say, `Eew, she's going to make me look
like her.' I'd much rather go to a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Julio Sandino, a New York-based artist who was in Boston
recently making over women at Saks Fifth Avenue, says ``Women like
having their makeup done by a man because men see them in a
different way.'' Sandino works for Francois Nars, another male
makeup artist who launched his own cosmetics line in 1994 and who's
known for doing the makeup for Madonna's album covers and videos.
Says Sandino, ``(Women) want a man's opinion of what they'd like to
see in a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, being in the business, a lot of men wear makeup too.
Cavaleri wears concealer and bronzing powder (which gives a
suntanned look), he says, because that helps to sell it. Also, he
says, ``It gives me a finished look. It makes me feel better about
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Men say they're choosing the field because they love fashion and
they enjoy helping people. ``We're a self-esteem counter,'' says
Johnnie Evers, who sells cosmetics for 29 lines at Neiman Marcus.
``We make people feel good about themselves. We're not judgmental .
. . . At the end of the day, I can go home and feel good because I
made someone else feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Evers started 12 years ago, selling Estee Lauder at Jordan
Marsh, after earning a college degree in marketing and interior
design. As a child, he says, he learned about makeup application
and skin care from his aunt, who owned a cosmetics studio.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Fee started in makeup to supplement his income as a
struggling actor. After several years of work, he says, ``I thought
this wasn't too bad a career.'' Working for Revlon's Borghese
division as a national makeup artist, Fee flew all over the country
meeting with customers. ``It's the only time I've been in Phoenix,
Seattle, and San Francisco. It was a wonderful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Fee has settled in Hingham with his wife and daughter. He
travels from upstate New York to Connecticut to Massachusetts doing
faces for Chanel. ``My reason for being here is my obsession with
fashion. I love to see people put together well, with matching
shoes and pocketbooks, hair and nails, gloves, whatever . . . I
think of it as art.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about societal reaction to his career choice? ``There's
an eyebrow that goes up,'' Fee says. ``I'm not ashamed. I love what
I do. I know a lot of men who go to 9-to-5 jobs and sit behind
desks and are miserable . . . I think sometimes the assumption is
that if a man knows how to do this he must be gay . . . Male,
female, gay, straight, (your success) always comes down to your
taste and how you connect with people.''
</P>
<P>
   And Fee says he connects very well. He says, ``I hear
everything. I hear about affairs. Oh my God, it's like being a
psychiatrist in a way. You're really in their space. Everyone has
something that you can enhance. Maybe that endears you a little
bit. It's a very personal thing when you're talking about a
person's colors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PENN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-21 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PENN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... for me.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't a peace that came easily. Penn and Wright met in 1987,
got together in 1990, had two children, broke up. In 1993, Penn's
house in Malibu (where he grew up) was destroyed by a fire. In
1994, while he was living in a trailer, listening to rock 'n' roll
and playing with guns, he asked her to marry him. In 1996, she said
yes, if he'd lose the trailer. He did, they did, and to this day he
says his toughness is overplayed, hers underplayed, citing the time
last year when she simply refused to allow a carjacker to drive off
with their two children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he performed the role of Eddie in a stage production of
``Hurlyburly'' in Westwood, got to know playwright David Rabe. ``I
realized it was the text that got me,'' he says. ``After I got to
know David Rabe and listened to him talk about the way he was
displeased with the New York production, it made the play sound
more interesting and rich, not as cerebral. Then, once having done
the play and worked so hard on it, it was hard to let it go to
somebody else as a movie. You know, good writers tend to be
provocative writers. I think there's not very good optimistic
writing out there. Most of the so-called optimists are really
cynics in hiding. They write love stories, but only about the first
five days of a relationship. Nobody can believe that people can
have an enduring love, so they don't write about that. I think
they're alienated, so they write about the alienated. I don't think
it works the other way. I don't think it's a pursuit of the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, good writing protects you from having to do anything
more than is real and honest in the piece you do. The guy I play
wants to be loved. He wants to feel like he's human by virtue of
having somebody love him. I felt like David Rabe more or less
created like a slide and the actor had to be willing to go down it.
So I'm probably forcing myself to analyze things that I didn't
necessarily ever analyze in the process of picking the text up
again and leaving myself open and remembering what I was going
after in the play and letting that process continue. The best thing
to do is to not analyze it too much and go by your gut.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn makes no secret of the fact that he felt burned by the
scant impact of the two films he directed. ``As a director, you're
so happy you made the film that I was completely unaware for two
years of anything to do with what the response was. It seemed to
come out and go away pretty quickly. I thought that `The Crossing
Guard' was treated just terribly and it was the best performance
that Jack Nicholson had given in several years. It's hard to be
objective about it. I feel that if a film is just a little
different, and not just my films, we ought to embrace those things.
It's a matter of valuing some attempt that isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it strange talking about myself. I always feel much
more revealed by other people. You know, when I sit and watch
somebody really articulate those things I'm stumbling toward.
That's when you're most understood _ when you understand them in
somebody else. Suddenly somebody will say something, have certain
ideas. Somebody says something, and you say, `That's right! That's
who I am!' Or, `That's who I want to be!' If anything, I think it's
about avoiding things that suck your blood. There's a level of
bloodletting that is probably not wrong, but when people don't
embrace the effort you make, that kind of takes the steam out of
you. I've found that I would prefer to direct if I was gonna let
blood. I'd rather do it in a way that seems worth the effort. I'd
be less whiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn's dissatisfaction with acting has been well documented,
starting when he announced in 1991 that he was giving it up
altogether. Soon afterward, he returned to it. Far from being
ridiculed, his heartfelt attitude has made him the new De Niro
among the generation following his. So highly is Penn respected for
his seriousness of purpose and his sense of vocation that Mike
Medavoy, who produced ``The Thin Red Line,'' told Premiere
magazine: ``Sean Penn was really a very important part of getting
the actors interested in the movie. He had apparently run into
Terry (director Malick) and said, in effect, `Anytime you're ready
to make a movie, just call me and I'll do it for a dollar.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The result was that Penn spent last summer in Australia, which
doubled for Guadalcanal. But then Penn says that for him many
acting assignments are Guadalcanal. ``I'm very clear what a
terrific and lucky profession this is, especially to be able to do
it on a certain level and be paid and all that stuff. I didn't lose
interest in it. I lost enjoyment of it. The process is very taxing
to me. It's like stopping the arc of your life to hold it in a
certain position. It's almost like when a parent holds a kid's
development back. You're doing that to yourself as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I heard recently that the biggest fear that many
actors have is being found out to be a fraud. The characters in
`Hurlyburly' are in a similar dynamic, afraid of being found out _
or of not being alive in the first place. Do I have this fraud
feeling? No. As an actor, I've always banked on the fact that most
of my peers were so bad. Not so much that I was particularly good.
No, I've never felt like a fraud. I always felt I had something to
contribute. I never was very hyperbolic about myself, but I always
was real clear about the playing field I was on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
