<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A WONDERFUL LIFE ... IN THE ERA OF DOWNSIZING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ George Bailey keeps staring at the pink slip,
then begins thinking about Mary and their four children. Bailey
Brothers Building &AMP; Loan had survived the run on the banks and that
foul-up with Potter, but not the hostile takeover by Oui, Cheatham
and Howe. He shakes his head and mutters to himself, ``I wish I'd
never been hired.''
</P>
<P>
   When he looks up, he sees his guardian angel, Clarence. ``Long
time, no see,'' George says. ``Don't worry. I'm not going to kill
myself this time. I'm just depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we don't handle suicides anymore,'' Clarence tells him.
``Now we're involved exclusively with layoffs. Our shareholders
wanted us to be in a growth industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel so stupid,'' George says. ``I should have taken
that job with Ebenezer Scrooge. He never laid anybody off just
before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling stupid is the worst thing you can do. You're a fine
man and a great worker _ Lord knows you're dedicated. Besides,
remember what Uncle Billy told you when Potter tried to close you
down: `I can get another job. I'm only 55.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but Uncle Billy never heard of the Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about all you've got going for you, George. You're great
with numbers, you know how to help people. You even ran paper
drives during the war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But _''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, you're deaf in one ear. You could go into
telemarketing.''
</P>
<P>
   George remains unconvinced. So Clarence shows him how different
life in Bedford Falls would have been if George Bailey didn't work
there.
</P>
<P>
   Without having his brother around to help, Harry Bailey couldn't
afford to go to college, and he missed out on his chance of being a
war hero. Potter took over the Building &AMP; Loan, and Harry was stuck
in the town's other dying industry: He wrote for the local
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   George sees how Bedford Falls has turned into Pottersville,
filled with struggling renters instead of struggling homeowners.
``Each man's life touches so many other lives,'' Clarence says.
``You see, George, you really had a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmacist, Mr. Gower, wound up going to prison, of course,
because he accidentally sent that poison to the child with
diphtheria. ``George Bailey wasn't around to help him,'' Clarence
says. ``He ended up having to hire that Kevorkian kid.''
</P>
<P>
   George puts his head in his hands for what seems like an hour,
then looks up at Clarence. ``You win,'' George says. ``Say, you
don't happen to have a winning lottery ticket in your pocket, do
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, all right. I want to work again. I want to work
again. Satisfied?''
</P>
<P>
   Clarence fades away like a hologram. Guardian angels have better
special effects than they did in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   George walks home through the snow, not having a clue about what
he'll tell Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary did it, George,'' Uncle Billy tells him as he walks in
the door. ``She told everybody what happened, and they all want to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary greets her husband with a kiss. As they huddle with their
children near the Christmas tree, people from Bedford Falls start
dropping by, some bringing money and food to help the Baileys get
by. Mr. Gower offers to let George take over the pharmacy, and Sam
sends a fax from London promising George a job in his high-tech
restaurant: Fish 'n' Microchips.
</P>
<P>
   But war hero Harry has the best offer of all. Using his
connections, he lined up a chance for George to finally take his
family around the world, inspecting purchases at all the military
bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the best job you ever had, George. You know the
federal government's not going to go out of business anytime
soon,'' Harry tells him, ``unless those rumors about cloning Ken
Starr are true.''
</P>
<P>
   As the group begins singing Christmas carols, George notices a
copy of ``What Color Is Your Parachute?'' among the presents. The
book includes a note from Clarence: ``Remember no man is a failure
who has friends.''
</P>
<P>
   As George sets the book aside, one of the bells on the Christmas
tree begins to jingle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Daddy,'' his daughter tells him. ``Teacher says every
time a bell rings, somebody gets laid off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right. That's right,'' George says, then looks to the
heavens and smiles. ``Attaboy, Clarence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
