<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PALTROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNETH PALTROW IS FREE TO PLAY SHAKESPEARE'S MUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like the fiercely independent young woman she
portrays in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Gwyneth Paltrow has always
chafed against the peculiar prison of public perception.
</P>
<P>
   Barely out of high school, she quickly found work as an actress,
but her ability was overshadowed by her bloodlines. The daughter of
acclaimed actress Blythe Danner and producer-director Bruce
Paltrow, she was considered another example of how having the right
name can open all the right doors. By the time she began to win
more substantial roles in ``Seven'' and ``The Pallbearer,'' she was
mainly known as the girlfriend of actor Brad Pitt. Suddenly, the
world was far more interested in her romances than in her roles,
and every mention of her name was rife with speculation on her life
with the Sexiest Man Alive.
</P>
<P>
   When her relationship with Pitt went up in flames, more people
were concerned with what went wrong than the fact that Paltrow was
developing into a smart, young actress in such films as ``Emma''
and ``Sliding Doors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you take your work very seriously, and you want
the focus to be on your work,'' said Paltrow recently. ``I think
it's taken me a lot longer than it would have taken anybody else to
achieve respect, because first there was my mother, and people
thought I was getting roles because of my parents. Then they said,
`Oh, she gets parts because of her boyfriend.' You start to think,
`Well, there must be a reason this is happening this way, and I'll
just ride through it, and keep doing my work.' At the end of the
day, hopefully that will speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be about to happen with ``Shakespeare in Love,'' which
opens Christmas Day, and also stars Joseph Fiennes, Geoffrey Rush,
Judi Dench, Colin Firth, and Tom Wilkinson. In this fanciful story
written by Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard, and set in the 1590s,
Paltrow plays Lady Viola, who is reluctantly set to marry the
stuffy Earl of Lord Wessex (Firth). She wants to be an actor, but
given the mores of the day, women are barred from the stage. She
disguises herself as a man and auditions for the still-developing
work by a young playwright, Will Shakespeare (Fiennes).
</P>
<P>
   Poor Will is having a vexing time with his new play, one he
calls ``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter.'' But everything
begins to change when Will meets Viola, and the two fall in love.
She becomes his muse, inspiring Shakespeare to write his great love
story, ``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't the traditional objectified muse; she brought out
the best in him, and was his partner. Who she was and what she
represented to him brought out a whole creativity,'' said Paltrow,
during a day's worth of interviews in a midtown hotel, not far from
her New York apartment (and before she was nominated for a Golden
Globe for her performance). ``It was a really interesting character
for me because she was so strong, and so proactive in dressing as a
boy to audition, and all of that. Even though the story is about
him, she's an important element in the story. It's not your basic
love-interest part.''
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow, 25, has certainly played her share of love-interest
parts, and judging by her looks alone, it's fairly easy to
understand why. Paltrow is pretty, even more so in person than on
the magazine covers she so often adorns. Her looks are so
Hollywood-friendly they border on cliche; even in jeans, with her
straw-blond hair in a ponytail, she manages to be both unassuming
and elegant.
</P>
<P>
   But Paltrow also possesses a crackling vitality and
determination, qualities which convinced ``Shakespeare in Love''
director John Madden that Paltrow was his Viola. He auditioned
about 40 to 50 actresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met her for another movie about five or six years ago, and
she was just a complete knockout,'' he said. ``When this project
came around, she was just the natural choice for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The only person who needed convincing, it seems, was Paltrow.
When the script first arrived in her agent's office, Paltrow wanted
nothing to do with it _ or, at that time, any other film. She had
been working steadily, was ``really burned out,'' and didn't want
to commit immediately to another film. After a few months, a
producer at Miramax, the studio behind the film, persuaded her to
read the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `You're crazy. You gotta do this,' '' Paltrow
recalled. ``So I read it, and I thought it was incredibly
well-written, and I'd never read anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the part was unlike anything Paltrow had read, she was
certainly familiar with the character's British accent. Two of her
recent roles _ ``Emma'' and ``Sliding Doors'' _ also required the
Los Angeles-born actress to affect the Queen's English. To master
Shakespeare's rhythmic iambic pentameter, she and her fellow actors
were coached by a member of the Royal Shakespeare Company. And
while Paltrow lacks formal Shakespearean training, it seemed to
come easily since she was raised with the words of the Bard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it comes from my mother who was always rehearsing
Shakespeare or a classical piece, and just being exposed to it
opens up a part of your brain that wouldn't necessarily be opened
up if you weren't constantly exposed to it,'' she said. ``She was
always taking me to Shakespeare in the Park or an experimental
theater production of `Hamlet' in some East Village church.''
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow's ear for Shakespeare, as well as her flawless British
accent, impressed costar Fiennes, who was born in England and spent
several seasons with the RSC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her ability to hit the accent is extraordinary,'' Fiennes
said. ``I haven't done much film, so it was remarkable to watch
someone just nail it, someone who understands the discipline of
Shakespeare, and has the poise and brilliance to get it right, and
doesn't need 15 takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, films like ``Shakespeare in Love,'' don't always have
the luxury of budget-busting, repeated takes. It is an independent
film, unlike Paltrow's other entry this year, ``A Perfect Murder.''
That was the big-budget summer thriller that aped Alfred Hitchcock,
and costarred Michael Douglas. Throughout her career, Paltrow has
moved between mainstream movies like ``Seven,'' with Pitt and
Morgan Freeman, and independent fare such as ``Sliding Doors'' and
``Emma.'' Working on big-budget movies is more like a job, albeit a
``great job,'' Paltrow said, whereas smaller films allow her to
flex her artistic muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing a movie like `A Perfect Murder' was strange because it's
not really the kind of movie I do, but I wanted to experience the
slick, big-budget Hollywood machine kind of movie,'' she said. ``I
felt like a blue-collar worker _ I got up in the morning, had my
coffee, went to work, did my job, and came home. It's fun, but it's
not difficult, and it's not really engaging work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you do a movie like `Shakespeare in Love,' you feel
like an artist,'' Paltrow said. ``It doesn't go as smoothly, it's
all quirky and backwards, but it's artful. You feel like you're
learning and discovering things, and you feel like you know why you
do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   For as long as Paltrow can remember, she wanted to be an
actress. What she never wanted to be, or expected to be, was a
gossip magnet. Yet for most of her career, which began in 1991 with
a small role in ``Shout,'' with John Travolta, the tabloids have
had their way with her. When she was with Pitt, their pretty blond
heads seemed permanently affixed to every gossip rag and TV show
dedicated to celebrity dish. Paltrow, who was then barely 21,
talked about her relationship with Pitt, only to soon realize such
honesty was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my last relationship, I was young, and didn't realize that
every time I divulged something, as innocuous as it was to me, I
was opening more doors for people,'' she said. ``Then I was like,
`Why are people so interested in this?' The little things give
people a personal hold or some kind of personal association where
they think they know you.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was going through it, I didn't think about it. I just
tried to live my life. But it was hard. At the time, I think it was
my own hubris or ego that made me think, `Oh, it doesn't matter,'
and I didn't realize the world perceived me as something other than
a working actress. Obviously, I see that now much more clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow is much more guarded about her current relationship with
Ben Affleck, who has a small role in ``Shakespeare in Love.''
During interviews she never mentioned his name, and bristled at a
reporter who implied she might have used her clout to get him in
the film.
</P>
<P>
   This is a different Paltrow, one rubbed raw by years of
intrusions into her personal life. She is no longer the smiling
ingenue who once talked in depth on ``Oprah'' about her life with
Pitt. Paltrow now believes she owes the public a good performance,
and nothing more. She will no more discuss her private life than
read the rumors that have her waltzing down the aisle with a
different man every other week. One tabloid even had her having an
affair with Matt Damon _ Affleck's best friend, and her costar in
the upcoming thriller ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Paltrow, the actress-turned-tabloid-fodder who has
reclaimed herself as an actress, feels that whatever the gossip
mill churns out is ``none of my business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't engage in it, I don't read it, I don't listen to it,''
she said. ``Whatever anybody says about me when they don't know me,
it's not my business what they say. It's my business what my family
says, my friends say. The people that I love and who love me,
that's what I care about.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while it was difficult because you enter into this world
where all of a sudden people are writing all these things and
speculating, and you're sort of feeling, `Who am I, and how did all
of this happen?' Paltrow added. ``It's difficult and wearing, but
you have to do your best and not take it personally. You have to
say, `It's not about me, these people don't know me, they don't
have my best interest at heart.' I'm not going to empower them by
allowing them to hurt my feelings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
