<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PENN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAN PENN AT PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For Sean Penn, every role is a blast furnace. He never skated
through a film in his life. For that matter, he never skated
through life. At 38, married to Robin Wright and a doting father of
two children, Penn has mellowed. A bit. But for Penn, the easy way,
the artistic or personal shortcut, does not exist, because, simply,
the guy cares. Holed up for a few hours in a Boston hotel room, to
which he rushed after a day of shooting Woody Allen's new film, a
flu-ridden Penn says, between sips of tea, that his succession of
angst-filled roles has never been a conscious career choice.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing Penn never could be is indifferent. This intensity
has kept him at the forefront of post-Brando, post-De Niro actors.
But he also says his choices say more about him than any words put
between quotation marks. He wouldn't want to accuse himself of
purity, he said a few years ago on the eve of the opening of his
second directorial effort, ``The Crossing Guard.'' But consider
that film and his directorial debut, ``The Indian Runner.'' Both
are rough, honest, grueling films (Penn wrote both) about men
grappling with what they must do to live with honor.
</P>
<P>
   In film after film, Penn has plumbed the pain of bad guys. Think
of his convicted rapist on death row in ``Dead Man Walking,'' his
army sergeant turned loose cannon in Vietnam in ``Casualties of
War,'' his coked-up lawyer in ``Carlito's Way,'' his criminal son
of a criminal father in ``At Close Range,'' his Irish-American
tough guy in ``State of Grace,'' his drug dealer turned traitor in
``The Falcon and the Snowman.'' Now add to that gallery his World
War II grunt under fire in Guadalcanal in Terrence Malick's
imminent ``The Thin Red Line.'' Not to mention _ in ``Hurlyburly,''
opening Friday _ his confused Hollywood casting agent, Eddie,
roller-coastering his way through a storm of sexual and other
confusion alongside buddies played by Kevin Spacey and Chazz
Palminteri.
</P>
<P>
   It's his kind of film, Penn says, because it takes pains to
shine a light on unruly stuff that usually is ignored by what
passes for adult entertainment. ``I like the idea that a movie is
going to last longer than when you walk out of the theater and will
impact an audience,'' Penn says. ``I'm much more interested in a
tiny bit of enduring emotional truth than a lot of
wham-bam-thank-you-ma'am stuff.'' After Eddie and his friends put
themselves and the women around them through several kinds of hell,
Penn says, there's only the tiniest window of hope remaining at the
end. But, Penn being Penn, he won't offer the easy consolation of
glib optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if his eyes open clear enough to see what's in
front of him. I don't know if he's that close to a relationship
with a woman because I don't think he's that close to a
relationship with himself. There's very little self-respect in the
lives that he and these people lead. Without that, I don't know if
the word `relationship' is even appropriate. There's a great, great
violence to any circumstance when someone allows himself to be
convinced that he can't change. To one who has lost his self-belief
and awareness, who has lost his belief in his ability to grow and
change, the cumulative effect of thinking and feeling like you're
stuck somewhere is feeling like you're dead. That's where the
creepiness starts to happen to these characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn has changed. He prizes his family, prizes time. All he
wants to do now, he says, is write and direct the films he wants to
make. After he wraps the Woody Allen project, he may concentrate on
another prison movie. At 38, it would be pathetic if he were the
same person he was at 28, he says. This is his veiled way of saying
that he has outgrown the bad-boy coverage that fell on him like
acid rain in the wake of a few punches thrown while drunk, a
drunk-driving charge, and a few dust-ups with paparazzi during his
tempestuous first marriage, to Madonna. ``People misperceive me to
a degree that I'll never be able to fix, never be able to
control,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, some of the things I was despised for I take complete
credit for. There were times I did things in an effort to be
helpful to someone else and got caught in the middle of that
situation and took heat. There were other times when, though
arrogance, you take pride in getting away with things like abusing
alcohol. At a certain point you realize it's not giving you much
back, then it gets tiring. Then suddenly it comes back one more
night and it makes you feel alive one more time. It's really about
where your energy is coming from. If the energy comes from anger or
from mental health, it's all going to feed the same beast. I had
allowed myself to sometimes be fierce in my arrogance, probably
still do sometimes. But a lot of the things I got in trouble for,
all it took was one pretty princess getting killed in a tunnel and
everybody's feeling about it was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``But am I worried that civility in my life is going to diminish
things? I'm not worried about that. My wife is in this film
(playing a role of a woman who is even more of a loose cannon than
the men). It was nice to have her there, to do the scenes together
and, you know, to go home. I have a sense of home now. My son likes
everything outdoors. He's an outdoors guy. My daughter is more of
an indoors person. So what do you do? I dunno. I read to her. I
take them both to the beach, the museum, camping out. They like to
just play a lot. Most of the time, I sit around and I cuddle them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being married, having kids, I think you have a lot more
accountability. It affects the way you look at life, your
resonsibilities, even the way you look at material. I've tried to
pick up the pieces of a movement toward total antisocial
surrendering of belief in the human race to believing in it,
despite itself. Then there are all these practical things, like
where are you at what time of year and how often do you get on an
airplane? My wife and I have to be very cooperative with each other
about when one's going to work. I mean, so much of being a parent
is just about being there. I think from the outside, it's always
going to appear a bit of a mess, but it's feeling more and more
peaceful a mess for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
