<HEADLINE>
TONI TENNILLE PLAYS VICTOR AS VICTORIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the chic black pants and jacket she wears for an
interview at the Ritz, the long-legged 5-foot-11 Toni Tennille is
dazzling, definitely more ``Victoria'' than ``Victor.'' And, that,
it turns out, is just the way she plays their roles.
</P>
<P>
   Tennille is best known for a 1975 pop hit written by Neil Sadaka
and recorded by her and husband Daryl Dragon. He's the son of a
coloratura concert soprano and Carmen Dragon, an Academy
Award-winning composer/conductor. The Captain &AMP; Tennille was how
the act was billed, and the song was ``Love Will Keep Us
Together.'' It and other hits propelled them from being the house
band at the Smoke House in Encino, Calif., to nine slots in
Billboard's Top 40 between and 1975 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Now 55 (``I don't say it, but I find it keeps popping up in
articles so I might as well''), Tennille is touring in the role
that Julie Andrews originated in ``Victor/Victoria,'' the movie and
subsequent stage musical set in a bohemian Left Bank nightclub in
Paris in the 1930s. The latest production of the play will be at
the Colonial Theatre Dec. 29 through Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Julie Andrews, Tennille succeeds Liza Minnelli and
Raquel Welch in the role of Victoria, a glamorous but unemployed
and indigent actress who finds herself constrained to bend her
gender for some cafe society hi-jinks.
</P>
<P>
   Tennille won the coveted role after apparently losing it.
Spurred by Cheri Ingram, her manager, who supplied her with a
bootlegged tape of a performance of the show for a Japanese TV
special, Tennille made her own tape of seven scenes and five songs,
edited it down to 11 minutes and sent it to Blake Edwards and
producer Tony Adams. Edwards, who is married to Andrews, is the
filmmaker who directed the movie version (it preceded the musical,
which opened on Broadway in 1995, by 13 years). Two days after the
tape was mailed, the signing of Raquel Welch for the role was
announced. ``I thought that was the end of it,'' says Tennille. The
next thing she knew, she was being asked if she might be interested
in doing the national tour.
</P>
<P>
   Tennille, like her husband, has show-business genes. Her father
sang with Bob Crosby (Bing's brother) and the big band Bobcats. Her
mother played classical piano and sang classical and jazz music.
She and Dragon have won gold, silver, and platinum albums and
singles and starred on their own network TV series and specials.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon, who was a keyboardist for the Beach Boys (who gave him
his stage name), hired her as a keyboardist for a Beach Boys tour,
making her, she says, the only female who qualified as a ``Beach
Boy.'' She had to be escorted onstage for performances because
security guards always tried to stop her, thinking she was a
groupie. She sang backup vocals in a tenor range, which turned out
to be good training for her approach to the Victoria role. She also
sang as a backup tenor on an untitled album that became Pink
Floyd's ``The Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite swimming through the show business milieu, Tennille and
her husband have remained married since 1975. Asked how they've
done it, she says ``first, you have to choose the right person.''
Then, she says, ``you have to survive the first year,'' which is
``the hardest. He comes from a large family that never talked.
They'd close doors. After we got married, if we disagreed, he'd go
in and shut the door. I'm one of three sisters. They're
overwhelming, like me. When he'd shut the door, I'd say `Let's
talk.' We refined the ability to talk things out at the time.''
They have no children. ``If we did, I'd want to be with them all
the time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Tennille says her strategy in playing Victoria involves several
approaches. Key is what she refers to as the drag queen's motto:
``Why do when you can overdo?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, Victoria hasn't spent her life learning how to be
gay,'' she says. She plays the role as if it was similar to ``the
idea of putting your wife in a tux so she can go out and be a guy.
She's very uncomfortable, especially in her first appearance as a
guy; then she becomes more comfortable with it. Always, though,
underneath it all, she's Victoria. She behaves like a woman. It's
only when she's in public that she behaves masculine, manly. It's
what they call a `pants role.' I played the pants role of Prince
Orlofsky in Nevada Opera's production of `Die Fledermaus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tennille, born in Euphala, Ala., says she plays Victoria
``Southern'' and that ``it's the most fun when Victor is not
performed as a woman but as a drag queen. ``There's a big
difference. When he does `Le Jazz Hot' he's over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that she's a contralto. ``Blake didn't want me copying
Julie. He told Raquel and Liza the same thing. I'm singing in the
contralto or male tenor range. I sing in a male tenor voice. But
don't let the voice fool you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
