<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY SWEAR THAT IT'S NOT ABOUT SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not about sex.
</P>
<P>
   We know it's not about sex because they keep telling us: It's
not about sex! It's about lying under oath. Sex has nothing to do
with it.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not about sex. Even though sex keeps coming up. Because
they keep bringing it up. Mostly to say: It's not about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see if we have this straight.
</P>
<P>
   It's all right to cheat on your spouse as long as you don't lie
about it under oath. You can lie to her, or to him, as the case may
be, but you can't lie under oath. And, as we've seen in the case of
Speaker-elect Robert Livingston, if you publicly admit having
multiple extra-marital affairs and tell the entire nation that
you're very, very sorry, you may get a standing ovation from your
colleagues. Hurrah! Thank you for sharing! Group hug!
</P>
<P>
   But if you cheat on your wife and lie about it under oath in
court, as opposed to lying about it under oath to your wife
(``Honey, I swear to God I never laid a finger on her!'') you may
find yourself impeached, disgraced, forced to forfeit the chance
that your likeness will ever appear on Mount Rushmore. Plus you may
bring down the government. Because lying under oath is serious
business, far more serious than sex.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not about sex. How many times do we have to hear it
before it sinks in? And yet somehow sex keeps coming up. How can
this be? If it's not about sex?
</P>
<P>
   It's about lying under oath. You can lie like a dog when you're
not under oath. Say, like Representative Henry Hyde, you indulged
in a youthful indescretion. You were in your 40s when you began it,
so it was really more of a midlife crisis. But you were just a kid,
or you felt like a kid anyway, and it was a meaningless affair of
no more than five or six years. Now you're sorry. And you're
forgiven because you told the truth, you owned up to it 20-odd
years after the fact, when you were forced to. You may have sinned,
but you never lied under oath, except that oath you took to love
and honor and cherish and keep thee only under her, and who takes
that seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Everybody lies about sex. ``Without lying there'd be no sex,''
Jerry Seinfeld said of the Clinton mess.
</P>
<P>
   You'll notice he didn't say ``Without lying under oath there'd
be no sex.'' Because it's not about sex. It's about lying under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   Even Republicans lie about sex, as we have seen, and may
continue to see, if Larry Flynt, this decade's answer to Woodward
and Bernstein, presses on with his campaign to expose congressional
philanderers. Flynt is a man for these times, truly.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about sex. But who'll be outed next? Who's the leading
candidate in the office pool? How long before the congressional
ranks are decimated? This is more fun than Jerry Springer, watching
our duly elected representatives wallow in the muck. It's a little
like Jerry Springer, actually. Except that it's not about sex. Even
though it seems to be about sex.
</P>
<P>
   How low can we go? When we hear Representative Richard Gephardt
deplore the politics of smear do we think, ``How refreshingly
high-minded,'' or, ``What's he trying to cover up?''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters. Because it's not about sex. It's about
lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine named Bill Clinton and Ken Starr as its Men of the
Year. Forget it. Flynt and Linda Tripp are the Co-persons of The
Year. Because they know what it's about. They don't mince words and
dance around the subject. It's about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Except that it's not.
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
