<HEADLINE>
TUTORIAL FOR TEENS ON CONSUMER RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the face of the barrage of ads and marketing pitches aimed at
teenagers, Peggy Meagher of the Massachusetts attorney general's
office is on a campaign to keep young people from getting taken in
today's slick consumer world.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, she spoke to an economics class at Matignon High
School in Cambridge and threw them a pop quiz. It's a good thing
this wasn't a high-stakes statewide test, since the average student
got six out of 10 questions correct. But then, Meagher said typical
adults don't score much better than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The quiz covered a range of subjects, from landlord-tenant
obligations and gift certificates to credit reports and debt
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Several students said the quiz revealed new and practical
information they plan to use in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have imagined that a landlord owed me interest
on my security deposit,'' said Lisa Caponigro, 17, referring to a
landlord-tenant question.
</P>
<P>
   Meagher, who heads the attorney general's consumer complaints
section, has visited a half-dozen high schools in the past year to
do some early-intervention consumer education. She said many young
adults approach her office with complaints about credit cards,
student loans, credit reports, health club memberships, and
vacation trips.
</P>
<P>
   Alerting young people to marketing scams and informing them of
their consumer rights, she said, helps them avoid problems.
</P>
<P>
   When asked for three consumer topics that parents and educators
should be sure to review with teenagers, Meagher said, ``Credit
cards, credit cards, credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, banks these days have become quite aggressive at
peddling plastic, particularly on college campuses. Many banks give
away mugs, T-shirts, and chocolates to students to get them to
apply.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Massachusetts Public Interest Research
Group found that students who get credit cards from on-campus
marketers are more likely to carry large balances and get more
cards than those who get them through other means, such as their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   In her talk, Meagher also emphasized that students should take
credit reports and student loans seriously. She stressed that the
obligation to repay a student loan cannot be escaped for any
reason, not even bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Meagher said teens often don't have enough life experience to
detect shady operators. She has heard tales of college students
scammed by the promise of a cheap Florida spring break trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be shocked that there are disreputable travel
agents out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Carr, head of Matignon's business department, said he
plans to ask consumer advocates to speak to classes every year to
strip away any naivete the youngsters might have. ``I don't want
them to get burned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gift certificate charges?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Al Calk picked up a $30 gift certificate recently at the Emerald
Square Mall in North Attleborough, Mass. and ended up paying $31.20
once a 4 percent service charge was added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never seen that before,'' Calk said. ``I thought it was
ridiculous. Basically, you're paying money to get money.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Fickeisen, general manager of the mall, said that without
the fee, the mall would have to discontinue the gift certificate
program.
</P>
<P>
   Fickeisen said mall gift certificates are issued as a courtesy
to customers and mall stores. He said the mall incurs a number of
costs, including paying a bank to handle the finances, credit card
fees, personnel, marketing, and packaging for the certificates.
</P>
<P>
   He said the certificates are like money orders, which can be
used in any store or even deposited in a bank. He said customers
concerned about the fee are told that they can obtain a gift
certificate from a specific store in the mall with no service
charge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southwest: No shuttle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines recently announced plans to launch service in
and out of MacArthur Airport in Islip, N.Y., which is on Long
Island about 40 miles from La Guardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   We think Southwest is one of the most consumer-friendly
airlines. The Dallas-based carrier transformed T. F. Green Airport
in Warwick, R.I., and Manchester Airport in Manchester, N.H., into
hubs for many Massachusetts residents. In the process, Southwest
drove down fares substantially at the two airports and in some
cases at Logan Airport in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Early news reports about Islip, particularly in The Wall Street
Journal, made it sound as if Southwest was about to use the Long
Island airport as a staging area to take on the shuttle carriers
that buzz between Boston, New York, and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not happening. Out of Islip, Southwest is flying
nonstop to Baltimore/Washington, Chicago, Nashville, and Tampa.
Warwick and Manchester are not in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   To get into New York City from Islip requires a short cab ride
to the nearest Long Island Rail Road stop and a 1 1/2-hour train
ride from there to Penn Station.
</P>
<P>
   A Southwest spokeswoman acknowledges the early reports were
misleading. She said Southwest for now will be servicing the travel
needs of Long Island's 3 million residents. ``MacArthur Airport is
the convenient airport for Long Islanders,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
