<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:40 p.m., the industrial average was up
159 points, and the Nasdaq index up 51 points. Elsewhere, prices
declined 0.3 percent in Tokyo and 1.7 percent in Hong Kong. They
rose 3.4 percent in Frankfurt, 2.6 percent in London, 2.9 percent
in Brazil and 1.3 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market,
the long bond was off 1 1/32 point, with the yield at 5.07 percent.
By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MYLAN-SUIT (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission and
several states sue Mylan Laboratories, alleging that the company
entered into illegal agreements with its suppliers to eliminate
competition in the market for two widely used generic drugs. The
government is seeking millions of dollars in consumer refunds. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-OUTLOOK (Washington) _ The unsettled global economy prompts
the International Monetary Fund to issue a rare update today of its
semiannual World Economic Outlook, a report that normally appears
only in the fall and the spring. Also today, the fund will issue
its first-ever update of its annual report on international capital
markets. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ An update on the economic
situation in Brazil. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
