<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS _ HOUSTON _ All eight babies born to a Houston couple
were in critical condition Monday, and doctors were giving them an
85 percent chance of survival. The mother underwent surgery Monday
to stop bleeding that was a side effect of drugs given to forestall
labor. She was expected to bbe released from the hospital by
Christmas. Meanwhile, the hospital, St. Luke's Episcopal, has been
deluged with reporters and phone calls. It's updating a web site to
provide updates. But little was known about the Chuwur family,
which requested that he hospital not give out any personal
information. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRESIDENT _ In public _ in the kinds of things political
advisers politically advise _ and in private _ in the kinds of
things your mother tells you to do _ uncandidate George W. Bush is
doing the kinds of things a presidential candidate does. Texans saw
it recently when he named longtime and trusted family friend Chase
Untermeyer as chairman of the State Board of Education and when
State Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer moved over to the
governor's staff. And one man in Davenport, Iowa saw it recently
when the governor of Texas thought it was important to offer
long-distance congratulations on the birth of a child. Bush insists
he is still undecided on whether to run, but the Iowa dad said Bush
sounds like a candidate. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FAULDER-DEATH-ROW _ U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks convened a
hearing Monday in the case of Texas death row inmate Joseph Stanley
Faulder who has challenged his conviction on several grounds,
including whether Texas' secret clemency system is unfair and
whether authorities violated an international treaty by not
allowing him help from his home country. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SHARP _ Interview with outgoing state Comptroller John Sharp. He
is expected to address his political future, including a run for
governor in four years. (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   COLD _ Winter arrives, as so does the first spell of really,
really cold weather. Low temperatures will dip into single digits
today (Tuesday) in the Dayton, Ohio area and highs may not get
above freezing the rest of the week. (Smith, Dayton Daily News). 8.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL _ Good news for holiday travelers: Gas prices are down,
despite U.S. military strikes against Iraq and tensions between the
United States and other Middle Eastern countries, officials said.
Travel experts anticipate that a record 45.2 million people will
travel 100 miles or more from home during the Christmas-New Year's
holidays, a 2 percent increase of last year's 42.3 million.
(Franklin, Dayton Daily News). 8
</P>
<P>
   SIXFLAGS _ A state court jury in metro Atlanta will today
consider punitive damages against Time Warner and other former
owners of Six Flags Theme Parks chain, accused of mismanaging Six
Flags Over Georgia, also located in metro Atlanta. (Weiss, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HATE-CRIME _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A couple of months
ago, Internet hate groups pulled a high-tech, in-your-face trick on
the mainstream press that normally tries to ignore them. It got
them immediate attention, but not the kind they wanted. (McLachlin,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
