<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1429EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-21 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONCILIATION? WHO GETS NICE FIRST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the past President Clinton and House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt have not always been singing from the same
political page, but in the House impeachment struggle the
Democratic leader emerged as the president's most eloquent
congressional defender.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's worst hour was Gephardt's finest.
</P>
<P>
   As did first lady Hillary Clinton and many other Democrats,
Gephardt appealed for reconciliation across partisan barriers and
an end to ``the politics of slash and burn.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said it better than anyone else, with passion, force and
spontaneity rarely seen on the House floor. The fact that the
Republicans did not listen did not take away from the historic
importance and potential impact of what the Missouri Democrat said.
If a narrowly divided Congress cannot recapture a sense of civility
and accommodation, it cannot adequately function at all.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, whom Gephardt may soon run against for
the 2000 Democratic presidential nomination, pointedly commended
Gephardt later at the White House. Gore called Gephardt's emotional
remarks ``the finest speech'' he had heard in Congress since they
both arrived in the House two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt tore up his prepared speech after Speaker-elect Bob
Livingston's stunning resignation in order to reach rhetorically
across the aisle and ask Livingston to reconsider his decision. He
called Livingston a ``good and honorable man,'' the kind of
cross-party praise for a political foe seldom heard in the House
these days.
</P>
<P>
   When Gephardt finished, he was rewarded with an unusual,
prolonged standing ovation from Democratic members. At that moment,
Gephardt proved he has the stuff to be speaker if the Democrats
recapture the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican members, unmoved and sullen, sat on their hands
in a sad demonstration of their unwillingness to give a partisan
inch even when a suffering colleague is praised.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's gesture was an empty one that came too late, as he
knew it would. But it was a symbolic way to begin retreating from
what he calls the partisan ``abyss'' created by the intolerance and
vicious self-righteousness that dominates the House and threatens
to consume our political system and our country.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston himself had contributed to Washington's downward
partisan spiral by refusing to allow the House to consider a
bipartisan censure resolution as an alternative to impeachment. It
confirmed the Republican House majority's real goal, which was not
to punish the president but to drive him from office. (The GOP
congressional leaders invented some legalistic poppycock, but their
refusal of a censure vote had more to do with the fact that it
might get GOP votes and pass than any credible constitutional
basis.)
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt could have crowed about the political demise of the
second GOP speaker in two months, ironically brought down just like
Clinton by illicit sex. It means the Democrats can't be tabbed the
sole party of immorality after all.
</P>
<P>
   When Livingston confessed to having had affairs, Republicans
tried unsuccessfully to pull the old double standard. They said it
didn't compare with Clinton's behavior because Livingston had never
been asked about sex and therefore never lied except during his
marriage vow. They said Livingston's acts were private, whereas
Clinton's involved public lying under oath. The difference came
down to which man had been asked about sex and which one hadn't. It
didn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gephardt could have warned ominously that the
Republicans would pay a price at the ballot box for unilaterally
doing in Clinton, extending the cycle of political retaliation into
eternity. The recent game of mutual revenge now stands at one GOP
and one Democratic president, one Democratic and one GOP speaker,
one GOP speaker-elect, several Cabinet officers and Cabinet
nominees of both parties and a GOP Supreme Court nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Schumer, the New York Democratic senator-elect,
observed sadly that ``what began 25 years ago with Watergate ...
has grown beyond our control so that now we are routinely using
criminal accusations and scandal to win the political battles and
ideological differences we cannot settle at the ballot box. It has
been used with reckless abandon by both parties. ... My fear is
that when a Republican wins the White House, Democrats will demand
payback.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt instinctively chose the high road, expressing
sympathy and understanding for Livingston and pleading for new
tolerance on both sides. ``No one,'' he said, ``can pass the
puritanical test of purity that some are demanding our elected
leaders take. ... The founding fathers created a system of
government of men, not of angels.''
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the polls, the country agrees with Gephardt that the
personal rancor and perpetual distrust in Washington have gone too
far. Clinton's job approval ratings have soared to remarkable highs
in the low 70s. A series of national polls all say roughly the same
thing: A two-thirds majority of those surveyed don't want him to be
forced out of office or to resign.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, slightly fewer than one third of the voters
surveyed have a favorable view of the Republican party. Two thirds
disapprove of the House decision to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no easy way to get from today's mean-spirited
climate to Gephardt's ``new politics of respect and fairness and
decency.'' One side has to start, and the other side to respond.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to the majority party members to begin that process.
They control the votes and the institutional congressional
structure. By ignoring the Gephardt opening, House Republicans have
shown they are in no mood to do so, even though it is in their
long-term interest.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment focus moves now to the Senate for trial, where
it is hoped members may have the class and common sense lacking in
the House. But will the House learn anything from a gentler, kinder
Senate? Not likely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
