<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0618 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRENDS-FORECASTER-HNS     12-21 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-FORECASTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR FUTURIST IMMERSES HIMSELF IN HIS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RHINEBECK, N.Y. _ There are no crystal balls to be found at the
Trends Research Institute, but don't be surprised if Gerald Celente
puts one on display.
</P>
<P>
   The fortuneteller's accouterment would be but another whimsical
decoration at Celente's office, a knickknack that would be right at
home alongside globe ornaments and yin-yang symbols hanging from
wooden beams. Or next to the two white coffee mugs signed by Oprah,
souvenirs from his appearances on the television talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Celente, founder and director of the institute, is paid to
predict the future, or at least make forecasts about what is likely
to happen in the months and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Trends 2000: How to Prepare and Profit from the
Changes of the 21st Century'' (Warner Books, 1997) has an
impressive following.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Fortune 500 companies, from Coca-Cola to Lockheed
Martin to Lehman Brothers, subscribe to Celente's pricey ($185 a
year) eight-page quarterly newsletter The Trends Journal, the
copyrighted ``voice of the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these businesses so respect Celente's vision that they
hire him as a guest speaker, for which he charges a $25,000 fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take on things is different than everybody else's,''
explained Celente, a wiry 52-year-old dressed casually in black
wale corduroys and a charcoal pullover sweater, reading glasses
hanging on a cord around his neck. ``I decode the system. I know
how it works, how it fulfills itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have up to 20 people contributing to the newsletter but I'm
the final arbiter of whether or not something's a trend. I eat,
sleep and drink this stuff. Sure, intuition plays a role, but you
only get that from experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Celente's resume lists more than 20 on-target forecasts. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Casual dress trends ('86).
</P>
<P>
   _ The rise of deep discount and warehouse shopping ('88).
</P>
<P>
   _ Alternative/complementary medicine/new age trends ('88).
</P>
<P>
   _ Downsizing and outsourcing ('90).
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 television and radio interviews scheduled for
January, the futurist is sure to be a widely quoted authority
during the final 12 months before 2000 and the new millennium. But
he has been forecasting the future for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   A Bronx native, Celente was a lobbyist and government affairs
director for a Chicago-based trade association when then-President
Jimmy Carter announced in 1978 that the Shah of Iran was firmly in
control of his nation, a notion that contradicted everything
Celente knew about the oil-rich country.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I started to think about the implications of this, the
probability of a successful revolution and the price of oil and
gold going up,'' Celente said. ``And I started playing the
commodities market.''
</P>
<P>
   His hunch mushroomed into a small fortune for Celente, and a new
career was born. Celente quit his job and moved here to a ranch
house with dark wooden beams and smooth oak floors tucked into the
gently rolling landscape east of the Hudson River. He wanted
tranquility and easy access to Manhattan, and this met the
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign on the mailbox or on the 40 acres enveloping
the house that tells visitors they have come to the Trends Research
Institute, despite its think-tank name. Celente no longer lives
here; after an unpleasant divorce several years ago that ended his
23-year marriage, a subject Celente prefers not to discuss, he
moved up the road to the hamlet of Tivoli. He makes the 8-mile
drive to the office daily.
</P>
<P>
   The institute has a small staff. Two assistants and two
librarians file and cross-reference every article Celente finds
interesting or noteworthy from the Internet as well as that day's
USA Today, New York Times and Wall Street Journal, publications he
reads devoutly. He also subscribes to less-well-known periodicals
(Covert Action Quarterly, Human Events, Skeptical Enquirer, etc.)
that offer particular points of view with which he likes to be
familiar. Celente has more than 300 files updated daily, covering
subjects from the Asian financial crisis to astrology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in the implications of current events,'' he
explained. ``We compile and analyze.''
</P>
<P>
   He also listens to his gut. If something strikes the right chord
with Celente, like the irreverent Comedy Central TV program ``South
Park'' did a year ago, he touts it as an ``on-trend'' in the
newsletter. Four months later, ``South Park'' was a Newsweek cover
story.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to tabulate Celente's batting average. He
estimates he's made ``several hundred'' predictions during the past
20 years, many of them broad enough that they're hard to disprove.
For example, he predicts in his book ``Trends 2000'' such obvious
developments as ``financial planning experts will find a booming
business helping boomers prepare for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   He claims he has accurately predicted numerous political and
economic events, from the October '87 stock market crash (forecast
in January of that year) to the emergence of a new political party
in the '90s (forecast in '88), as well as numerous cultural trends
such as the rise in popularity of gourmet coffees and
microbreweries.
</P>
<P>
   The only ``miss'' he acknowledges is the 1992 presidential
election. He picked George Bush to beat Bill Clinton, apparently
ignoring his own sage prediction regarding the rise of Ross Perot's
Reform Party. Said Celente: ``I had no way of knowing Perot would
drop out, then re-enter the race and make a fool of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celente has admirers at USA Today, which publishes his annual
top 10 trend forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bob Dubill, executive editor at USA Today: ``My
recollection is that his batting average is quite high. As far as
misses, pollsters have missed too. In fact, they seem to miss more
often than they hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerry's a tracker in the finest sense of the word. He devours
news. He's the kind of person who if he was interested in reporting
would come up with terrific stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Celente outlined his four-step formula for tracking a trend,
which starts with his reading news stories. He tracks clusters of
stories, looks for a trend, then analyzes the trend and makes a
forecast. The final step is designing strategies for making the
most of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   It is in this way that Celente runs counter to so-called new age
expectations. He is an unabashed capitalist, eager to cash in on
developments much as he did when he foresaw the overthrow of the
shah.
</P>
<P>
   He said he preferred to invest in companies and sectors that he
believes are going to experience long-term growth as well as
short-term hits. The merger of Chrysler Corp. and Germany's
Daimler-Benz auto maker inspired Celente to invest heavily in that
newly created company.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, he is looking for a new business in which to put his
money. He is dumbfounded that as we begin 1999 there are no
health-food fast-food eateries offering a free-range
organic-chicken sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell is the big mystery?'' Celente mused. ``People
will pay two or three dollars more for quality. That's one thing
that's been demonstrated time and again during the last decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Celente recalls his appearance before the National Coffee
Association in 1990. At the organization's annual convention in
Miami he predicted that gourmet coffee would be the next wave. At
that time there were just 13 Starbucks Coffee Co. outlets, all
located in the Seattle area. Today, Starbucks has more than 1,700
stores in North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people there thought I was a nut,'' Celente
remembered, his eyes twinkling. ``I overheard people at lunch later
that day asking each other who I was, and then one couple came up
to me to shake my hand. They had decided to start a gourmet coffee
shop in Chicago, and they hoped I was right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
