Harding at the Medical Tribune News Service at 212-686-8584 x35.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like sales information for your newspaper or Web site,
call The New York Times Syndicate at 212-499-3331.
</P>
<P>
   -- Researchers have mapped the location of a gene responsible
for sudden heart failure in young people. (HEART-GENE-MED)
</P>
<P>
   -- A new technique may eventually allow doctors to detect
cervical cancer earlier than is currently possible, according to a
new study. (CANCER-SCREENING-MED)
</P>
<P>
   -- Intense strength training might offer another option to
back-pain patients looking to dodge spinal surgery, according to a
new report. (BACK-STRENGTH-MED)
</P>
<P>
   --Young brass-instrument musicians who feel weakness in their
facial muscles may owe it to more than overexertion. In those who
have a heart defect called a patent foramen ovale, the pressure of
