<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-21 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRINCH TAKES FLIGHT, AS DO BUTTERFLIES &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   I've always been a sucker for Christmas. I've loved buying
gifts, squeezing the biggest tree possible into a corner of our
family room, getting teary-eyed when carols are played.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the decorations went up in the stores before the
Halloween costumes were packed away. What about Thanksgiving? Are
we going to just nudge it right off the calendar? I found myself
growing grumpy. I like a buildup to the big day.
</P>
<P>
   I'm on vacation while you're reading this. Visiting the family.
But before I left the office, a letter from a gardener arrived _ a
gift that took the commercialism right out of Christmas. Perhaps it
will boost your spirits, too:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Kathy: Four years ago I purchased two milkweed plants that
I planted in my garden. The two plants have now multiplied into
five plants. The Monarch butterflies visit the plants and lay their
eggs. Each season as the caterpillars emerge, I bring three or four
inside and place them in a large plastic jar with holes in the lid.
I place a few sticks in the jar and feed the caterpillars fresh
milkweed leaves each day and clean their poop out several times a
day.
</P>
<P>
   I watch them eat and grow. Eat and grow. I watch them spin their
silk pads and hook their little bodies to them and hang in the
letter ``J.'' I watch them split their skins and each shape into a
beautiful green-and-gold-speckled chrysalis. I check on them until
the chrysalides turn dark, and I watch as beautiful butterflies
emerge. I watch the butterflies stretch and dry themselves. I then
place the jar in a quiet place and wait until the next morning to
release the butterflies back into my garden.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I watch this cycle of life occur, I feel like a child
at a birthday party. I share this experience with those I know who
love nature and might wish to share it with their children and
loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I would share this with you. Perhaps your readers
might enjoy this gift of nature in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Have a wonderful holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   A: Thank you. You chased the Grinch away.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you provide me with a list of native flowers or
perennial flowers or shrubs that I might plant to attract
hummingbirds, birds and butterflies? If you could give me the color
and approximate height of these, I could arrange them in a
stair-step fashion.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are many nectar-bearing flowers that will feed
butterflies and hummingbirds. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ageratum (blue, 18 inches; perennial native)
</P>
<P>
   _ Asters (lavender, blue, 12-18 inches; perennial, some native)
</P>
<P>
   _ Black-eyed Susans (yellow-gold, 2-3 feet; perennial)
</P>
<P>
   _ Butterfly bush (Buddleia, white, purple, red, pink; to 6 feet;
perennial shrub)
</P>
<P>
   _ Butterfly weed or milkweed (Ascle- pias, orange-yellow or
red-yellow; 3 feet or more; perennial shrub)
</P>
<P>
   _ Lantana (yellow, white, lavender, orange; 1-3 feet; perennial,
some native)
</P>
<P>
   _ Pentas (red, pink, blue; 2-4 feet; tender perennial)
</P>
<P>
   _ Summer phlox (magenta, rose, pink, white; 3-4 feet; perennial)
</P>
<P>
   _ Purple coneflowers (pinkish-purple; 2-3 feet; native
perennial)
</P>
<P>
   _ Salvias (various blues, purples, red, pink, white; to 4 feet;
perennial, some native)
</P>
<P>
   _ Verbena (`Apple Blossom,' `Blue Princess' and `Purple
Homestead' some of the best perennials; 1-foot range)
</P>
<P>
   _ Shrubs and trees that draw birds include:
</P>
<P>
   _ American beautyberry (fall-winter purple berries; to 6 feet)
</P>
<P>
   _ Parsley hawthorn (white flowers, red fall fruit; to 24 feet,
native)
</P>
<P>
   _ Junipers (berries, shelter; varying heights)
</P>
<P>
   _ Southern wax myrtle (berries, shelter; to 15 feet; smaller
forms available)
</P>
<P>
   _ Yaupon holly (red berries on female plants; 15 feet, native)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
