<HEADLINE>
`RATE-SURFER' ALERT: ROUGH SEAS AHEAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It always seems to happen. Savvy consumers find a way to take
advantage of the game, forcing businesses to change the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of that is in the credit card business.
</P>
<P>
   Smart consumers found a way to keep their credit card interest
rates way down: Sign up for a credit card with a low promotional
rate. When that short-lived teaser rate is about to expire, these
``rate-surfers'' transfer the balance to another bargain card.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rate-surfing has been raised to an art form among some
people,'' said Jim Shanahan, a credit card consultant at Business
Dynamics Consulting in Wilmington, Del., consultants to the
financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the credit card industry is out to teach rate-surfers a
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Issuers are beginning to charge consumers a fee to transfer
balances to their new low-rate card.
</P>
<P>
   First USA, one of the largest credit card issuers and one of the
most aggressive marketers, has started charging a fee of 2 to 3
percent on balances transferred to some of its cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like paying points on a loan,'' said George McCane, First
USA spokesman. ``It's the cost of accessing credit.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the charges relate to ``handling costs and certain risk
factors,'' on which he declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers say lenders figure if you have to endure
the pain of paying balance-transfer fees, you'll think twice before
ditching your new credit card, when the teaser rate runs out, for
one that charges an even lower interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly can have that effect,'' McCane said. ``We view
our balance-transfer fees as part of a strategy to engender
loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit card issuers are moving toward these fees because they're
losing money when people jump from card to card, industry analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 million card holders transfer card balances several
times each year, and it costs card issuers about $100 in marketing
and mailing to attract each new card customer, ndustry experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of banks have lost money on this stuff,'' Shanahan said.
``You can't make money on 4.9 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Providian Financial in San Francisco will offer to beat your
original issuer's rate for a certain period, say, three months, but
then will raise the rates to between 12.99 and 21.99 percent,
depending on what rate a card holder is getting from his or her
current card issuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are typically in the market for consumers who are actively
using credit,'' said Laurie Cole, Providian spokeswoman. ``We are
hoping to get people who are interested in a long-term
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies your power as a consumer _ especially if you carry
a balance _ to get around these moves by issuers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a consumer who generally carries a balance on your
credit card, then you are a prime target for the credit card
industry and you're in a prime negotiating position as well,'' said
Gerri Detweiler, co-author of ``The Ultimate Credit Handbook.''
``It's very hard for issuers to find consumers who carry balances
and who are willing to transfer those balances to a new card.''
</P>
<P>
   If a card issuer wants to charge you a balance-transfer fee,
insist that the fee be waived. These aggressive promotions exist
because there are so many other companies out there hungry for
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very likely that if you qualify for that card, then
you'll qualify for another one,'' Detweiler said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if your credit record is good, contact your bank about its
credit card program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these banks, if they can't compete with these issuers
in terms of marketing dollars, can give a decent rate to
creditworthy people,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   There's another way you can get around the balance-transfer
fees.
</P>
<P>
   When you get your next card statement, pay off the balance by
using one of those ``convenience checks'' issued by the card with
the lower rate, said David Gagie, marketing director at Auriemma
Consulting Group in Westbury, N.Y., consultants to the credit card
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who ends up paying that (balance-transfer fee) is not
really being smart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One crucial piece of advice about balance transfers: Always
transfer the balance with a firm plan to pay off the debt. A
balance transfer isn't a license to keep charging up your debt. The
whole purpose of transferring a balance is to keep interest from
piling on so high that you don't make headway in paying off the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
