<HEADLINE>
GREETINGS, OBSERVATIONS AT DOORSTEP OF 1999 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To help wind down this year and prepare to
welcome 1999, here are some seasonal greetings with, I hope,
relevant observations attached:
</P>
<P>
   H _ Healthy. It would be great if the economy, our governmental
leaders and all of us taxpayers remain healthy in 1999. If we
remain as robust as our political skepticism, most of us will be in
great shape.
</P>
<P>
   A _ Absence. No disrespect intended, but state government will
survive the absence of Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, Attorney General Dan
Morales, Comptroller John Sharp and Land Commissioner Garry Mauro.
Although sometimes controversial, the four veteran Democrats made
strong contributions to Texas, some of which will be felt for years
to come. People of all political persuasions can be grateful for
their service. But life goes on, and so will Texas. Sharp and
possibly Morales may even get another shot at public office
someday.
</P>
<P>
   P _ President. Will Gov. George W. Bush run for president? If
you are tired of such speculation, better hide in a cave because it
will get worse until the governor finally clears the air within the
next few months. Although there doesn't seem to be much suspense
over the likelihood of his running, we won't know the answer to an
even more important question for a while longer yet. Will he win a
race that will be tougher than most of us can even imagine?
</P>
<P>
   P _ Perry. Lt. Gov.-elect Rick Perry is no Bob Bullock. But as
the Senate's next presiding officer, he will find himself the focus
of a lot more media attention than he was used to as agriculture
commissioner. Perry's new job will be a tough test of his
leadership capabilities, and, whether he likes it or not, many
people will evaluate him by Bullock's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Y _ Year (old). The departing 1998 was a landmark year for Texas
Republicans, who captured all the statewide offices for the first
time since Reconstruction. They deserved their celebration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H _ Hispanics. Although still voting heavily Democratic, this
fast-growing group of Texans is hardly monolithic, as the recent
election strongly demonstrated. Gov. Bush made large inroads into
the Hispanic vote, and former Secretary of State Tony Garza became
the third Hispanic elected to statewide office in Texas _ the first
as a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   O _ Oversight. Besides the $17.3 billion in tobacco payments
that are supposed to flow to Texas over the next 25 years, the
biggest legacy of the anti-tobacco lawsuit may be more oversight by
the governor and/or legislative leaders over the attorney general's
office. Some lawmakers will sponsor bills to curtail the attorney
general's independence in signing contingency contracts with
outside lawyers, which sparked huge fees _ and major controversy _
in the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   L _ Luck. All of Texas' officeholders will welcome a large dose
of this commodity in the new year. Perhaps the largest share,
however, should be reserved for state Sen. Bill Ratliff and state
Rep. Rob Junell, who have taken on the worthy _ but extremely
difficult _ task of writing a new state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   I _ Integrity. Government decision-makers should never leave
home without it. Unfortunately, 1998 showed us once again that many
officials _ even some high-ranking ones _ may not even be sure what
the word means.
</P>
<P>
   D _ Deregulation. The deregulation of electric utilities may be
the single biggest issue before the Legislature next year. Efforts
to forge a compromise will continue. It is a complex issue with
potentially enormous stakes for utilities, their consumers _ and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   A _ Appearances. These often are as important as reality in
government and politics. But Rick Perry _ or people close to him _
recently showed more zeal for raising political money than concern
for ethical sensitivities. Setting $50,000 quotas for some
lobbyists who supported Perry's Democratic opponent, John Sharp,
was out of line. The quotas may not have been Perry's idea, but he
is ultimately responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Y _ Year (new). The time for celebrating is almost over. The
Republican victors who were beside themselves with glee on election
night now face the serious task of governing. Everyone will have a
stake in their success or failure.
</P>
<P>
   S _ Schools. They will be a high priority for the governor and
the Legislature in the new year. One of the big fights again will
be over a proposal _ strongly supported by Bush and Perry _ to
allow students from low-performing public schools to use vouchers
paid by state tax dollars to attend private schools. But, once
again, the real test will be in the Democrat-dominated House, which
has defeated similar proposals in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
