<HEADLINE>
HURRICAN WIPES TOURISTS FROM ISLAND, BUT TOMORROW IS ANOTHER DAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Moved in ``i'' and ``t'' categories) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROATAN, Honduras _ The sea still shimmers electric turquoise,
and the reef fish dazzle with the colors of the rainbow, but the
winds of Hurricane Mitch seem to have blown the tourists clean from
this Caribbean island just off Honduras' northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to restaurants, they're dead. Cabin accommodations,
dead. Everything is dead,'' says Foster Diaz Bush, 42, owner of one
of the most popular restaurants and bars in the West End, a
tranquil jumble of small hotels, eateries and shops facing one of
Roatan Island's better reefs. ``Things were just starting to get
going when the hurricane hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Set like jewels in the second longest barrier reef in the world,
Roatan and the other Bay Islands of Honduras have long been a
favorite destination for scuba divers and adventurers. In recent
years, a real estate boom fueled by time-share condominiums and
vacation homes for well-heeled Americans had begun to transform the
islands.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the horror tales of Mitch's wrath in Honduras _ more
than 5,600 people dead, tens of thousands of others still missing
or homeless, billions of dollars in damage and the spectre of
epidemic _ the tourism business on Roatan and the country's other
Caribbean islands has, perhaps understandably, plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel and restaurant operators on Roatan, by far Honduras' most
popular Caribbean destination, report that business is off more
than 80 percent and that cancellations of reservations for
Christmas and well into the New Year are piling up.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials, hotel operators and visitors to the country
say the stampede from Honduras' tourist meccas is an overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the country was affected in one way or another, but it
wasn't destroyed,'' Kenia Lima de Zapata, the marketing director at
the Honduras Tourism Ministry, says of Mitch. ``Sure, there is a
lot of damage. Anyone with eyes in their head can see it. But it's
not like everybody is dead, like everything looks dirty, like
everything is smelly.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mitch battered wide swaths of Honduras, including several
villages on Roatan and almost all of neighboring Guanaja Island,
most of the diving resorts, Maya ruins and beaches that have
attracted tourists in the past were largely unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   The major exception is Guanaja, a small island just 20 miles
east of Roatan, which suffered heavy damage when Mitch stalled over
it for three days. Most of the island's small resort hotels were
either damaged or destroyed, and much of its jungle and pine
forests was leveled.
</P>
<P>
   The storm hit hardest in areas where few tourists ever ventured.
The high death toll in Tegucigalpa, Honduras' high-country capital,
took place mostly in poor shanty towns and residential
neighborhoods far from the tourist trail. The situation was the
same in rural central and southern Honduras, where many of the
remaining deaths occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest, Honduras has got some serious problems,''
says Julio Galindo, the owner of Anthony's Key, Roatan's oldest
resort, and still one of its largest, which suffered damage during
Mitch. ``But we don't have the problems here. Right now we need to
show people we are still here. We weren't wiped out.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 15 of the resort's cabins were destroyed when a surging
sea swept over the small island offshore. ``The wind didn't do
much,'' Galindo says as he walks through his resort, supervising
the repairs. ``It was the water.''
</P>
<P>
   But Galindo, who was insured for the damage his resort suffered,
has taken the storm as an opportunity to make long-needed
improvements. The destroyed cabins are being replaced, others are
being renovated. New power and water lines are being laid
throughout the resort.
</P>
<P>
   Galindo plans to reopen Feb. 1, and while as a business owner he
mourns the loss of the Christmas tourist rush, he believes the
long-term benefits will outweigh the short-term losses. He's
offering steep discounts, including 2-for-1 packages, to lure
customers back.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are ready to go,'' Galindo says of his resort's
employees. ``We're getting back to normal. We were lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the reef may have suffered damage _ some divers on
Roatan earlier this month said there were fewer fish in the reefs
than in past years, and marine biologists say a severe storm could
cause some coral heads to be broken off or otherwise damaged _ the
hurricane may have some good effects.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually warm temperatures in the sea surrounding the Bay
Islands may have contributed to the recent ``bleaching'' of coral
in the reef, which is part of the second largest such system in the
world, after Australia's Great Barrier Reef.
</P>
<P>
   Bleaching occurs when corals stressed by temperatures either
higher or lower than normal expel the algae that gives a reef its
brilliant hues. The coral turns white and dull, explains Thomas
Iliffe, a marine biologist at Texas A&AMP;M University in Galveston who
has done research on Guanaja and Roatan.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mitch, water temperatures around Roatan have dropped by 4
degrees, raising hopes that the reef will recover in the cooler
water, says Galindo, who runs a marine science institute at
Anthony's Key and whose wife, Cheryl, heads a group focused on the
reef's ecology.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras's income from tourism, at about $145 million this year,
pales in comparison to that of nearby Costa Rica, which boomed as
an eco-tourism and beach destination throughout the 1990s. Costa
Rica now earns about $900 million a year from tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But a new room tax by Honduras on hotels had created a $1
million pool of money that the Tourism Ministry was starting to use
to market the country in magazines targeted at scuba divers,
adventurers and travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials had just begun to promote Honduras
aggressively as the next big destination in eco-tourism and
Caribbean holidays, says Kenia Lima de Zapata, the marketing
director with the Honduras Tourism Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its beaches and coral reefs, Lima says, Honduras
boasts the Maya ruins at Copan, on the border with Guatemala, as
well as nine ethnic groups and more than than 100 protected natural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   San Pedro Sula, the country's industrial city that serves as the
gateway to both the Caribbean islands and Copan, suffered heavy
flooding during Mitch, but the waters have mostly receded and the
ruins were not damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Landslides on some roads leading to Copan, about 2 1/2 hours'
drive west of San Pedro Sula, forced travelers to take short
detours, Lima de Zapata says, but the ruins themselves were not
damaged by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to attract tourists now, Lima de Zapata and other
promoters clash with media reports quoting government and aid
officials claiming widespread death, destruction and disease across
the country in the wake of Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Apocalyptic reports of Mitch's legacy, which have sometimes
seemed wildly inflated, have attracted hundreds of millions of
dollars in international aid to Honduras and the rest of Central
America. They have also helped to drive away tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect people who have heard about cholera, who have
heard about malaria, to want to go on vacation here,'' says
Galindo, the resort owner.
</P>
<P>
   With most sources of Honduras' foreign income badly damaged by
Mitch, Lima de Zapata says, tourism holds out the best hope for the
country to keep earning dollars while industries such as bananas,
coffee and shrimp-farming recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourism is going to have to play a major role in the growth of
our economy,'' Lima de Zapata says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we were harmed. Yes, we need the aid,'' she says. ``But
we don't believe we should stand begging for the rest of our lives,
so we're trying to look at things positively.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
