<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0755 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MAIL-TEX     12-21 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO SENDER: YOU'VE SEEN THIS MOVIE ALREADY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As ``You've Got Mail'' unfolds, and the arrogant prince of the
city Joe Fox (Tom Hanks) gets his comeuppance _ from, of all
people, the wincingly decent Kathleen Kelly (Meg Ryan) _ you wonder
if writer-director Nora Ephron is apologizing for the brittle, cool
cruelty that she exhibited as a magazine essayist.
</P>
<P>
   As an Esquire magazine columnist 20 years ago, Ephron's laissez
faire hostility set a standard that other writers are still trying
to match _ each piece seemed chilled to exactly 34 degrees. (I
liked her stuff, but I never wanted to meet anyone like her.)
</P>
<P>
   The bright colors and small-town friendliness that she evokes in
``You've Got Mail,'' a remake of the sublime ``The Shop Around the
Corner,'' are literally the polar opposite of her print stuff. This
is a picture-postcard Manhattan with a big lipstick kiss on its
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Touchingly, Ephron is out to show a generosity of spirit as a
filmmaker that couldn't possibly have interested her as a writer.
She'd probably have made fun of Kathleen, the owner of the
children's bookstore The Shop Around the Corner, who's so
button-eyed cute that she does everything but show up to work
wearing a Pokemon knapsack.
</P>
<P>
   A touchstone on the Upper West Side _ her mom started the shop _
Kathleen's store is threatened by the imminent appearance of Fox
Books, a books superstore that seeks to be all things to all
people. Or rather, sell all things to people.
</P>
<P>
   Joe is the only relatively sane member of the Fox family. His
dad (Dabney Coleman) and grandfather (John Randolph) have married
women younger than Joe and had kids with them. Which means that Joe
ends up baby-sitting his grade-school-age aunt and her brother, a
touch of low-key eccentricity that gives this movie a little
freshness. Otherwise, ``You've Got Mail'' makes you feel like
you're in a pet shop; it's the only other place you're likely to
hear grown people purr ``Awww''' so often.
</P>
<P>
   Ephron does better with the media types. Greg Kinnear is
Kathleen's boyfriend, a professional Luddite and New York Observer
columnist who's more in love with his own writing than he could be
with any human being. Otherwise, she falls back on the device
that's made her, as David Letterman would say, such a big deal in
show business.
</P>
<P>
   This is another romantic comedy in which the leads spend a great
deal of time communicating while not in the same room, so they end
up talking to their friends about each other a lot, just like in
``When Harry Met Sally,'' which Ephron wrote, and ``Sleepless in
Seattle,'' which she co-wrote and directed. (In ``Mail,'' those
friends include the able actors Steve Zahn, Jean Stapleton, and
stand-up comic Dave Chappelle.)
</P>
<P>
   Here, Joe and Kathleen fall in love over the Internet and via
America Online, a product placement that will do more for AOL's
stock price than will its merger with Netscape. It makes ``Mail''
feel like a first of a sort, some kinda crypto-sequel/remake
companion piece to ``Sleepless.'' You've already seen it before you
walk into the theater; it's the equivalent of swallowing pre-chewed
Milk Duds _ mushy and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and Ryan join for their third team-up, the first being the
wildly uneven _ and mostly bad _ ``Joe Versus the Volcano.'' Ryan's
work in ``Volcano'' _ she played three roles _ was two parts a
marvel of comic intensity. She played a pale, cowed office worker
and an eccentric, exasperated heiress who rattles off every single
thought that comes to mind, and made them both distinct people.
</P>
<P>
   It was an undertaking that deserved credit for its ambition, not
to mention that she chose to display her timing and determination
in a movie that was barely worth sitting through. (She was even
better as the spurned monomaniac in the inferior ``Addicted to
Love,'' and shows backbone and style in a minor part in the
upcoming ``Hurlyburly.'')
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mail,'' Ryan is only determinedly cute. She plays a '90s
mainstream comedy cliche that strips her of all complication.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks, playing one of those true '90s movies freaks of nature _
an essentially good-guy mega-capitalist _ comes through with
pinpoint shadings. He gives Joe a bone-deep self-possession that
can register a little faster than the eye can see; his
one-upmanship slips right past his oblivious book editor girlfriend
_ Parker Posey, who always seems to have drunk one mochaccino too
many.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks has expressed some anxiety about being compared with Jimmy
Stewart, an anxiety he's apparently confronting by taking on a role
in which Stewart gave one of his best, most natural performances.
Hanks deepens his relaxed, all-American slyness here. He goes
drier, and his minimalism results in the best scene _ perhaps the
only good one _ in ``Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kathleen almost causes a riot by getting into the Cash
Only line of Zabar's with no cash, Joe sails in and rescues her
with his princely charm. Hanks, with the tiniest, swiftest
inflections, uses a winning aplomb that's so totally New York, you
almost forgive the rest of the picture, especially the last
half-hour, which is like being trapped in the Express Line behind
someone who's paying in rolls of pennies. (The aftermath, when
Kathleen tries to imitate his I Can't Believe It's Not Butter
polish, is funny, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Hanks shows he's ready for much more complex parts than he's so
far taken. He and Ryan show a spark here that makes you want to see
them in a much better, and riskier, film. With a scene like this,
Ephron even shows she's capable of directing it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``You've Got Mail''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Nora Ephron &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Tom Hanks, Meg Ryan
</P>
<P>
   Length: 116 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1601EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
