u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     12-21 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Monday, Dec. 21, 1998    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following
stories for Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston
Chronicle sports stories, please call the Houston Chronicle Sports
Department, 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: IMPEACH-SENATE; US-IRAQ; CLINTON-DAY; OCTUPLETS-FOLO;
OCTUPLETS-DANGER; DEATHROW-CANADIAN; FBN-BRONCOS; and FBN-COWBOYS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) _ A look at the maneuverings and
negotiations in preparation for the Senate trial of President
Clinton. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LAMEDUCK (Washington) _ Several senators warn President
Clinton against challenging last weekend's impeachment vote by
arguing that a lame-duck Congress has no legal right to impeach
him. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   US-IRAQ (Washington) _ The Pentagon updates its damage
assessment after 70 hours of aerial bombardments of Iraq, saying 85
percent of the targets were hit and 74 percent damaged sufficiently
to meet U.S. objectives. The Iraqis, however, claim differently. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (Washington) _ President Clinton attends a ceremony
for the victims of Pan Am Flight 103, vowing to continue to
pressure Libya to turn over the men suspected in the 1988 bombing
over Scotland. Also, Clinton makes an appearance at a soup kitchen.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS-FOLO (Houston) _ The world's first surviving octuplets
remain in critical condition at St. Luke's Hospital here. Two are
on ventilators while the others are breathing on their own. The
chief of the neonatal unit says the infants are not out of the
woods yet. By T.J. MILLING.
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS-DANGER (Houston) _ Medical specialists say multiple
births can be a dangerous side effect of using fertility drugs. By
T.J. MILLING
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW-CANADIAN (Austin, Texas) _ A federal judge hears
arguments on whether Canadian Joseph Stanley Faulder's due process
rights were violated when he was convicted of a 1970s murder of an
elderly East Texas woman. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In the past President Clinton and
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt have not always been singing
from the same political page, but in the House impeachment struggle
the Democratic leader emerged as the president's most eloquent
defender. Clinton's worst hour was Gephardt's finest. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS (Miami) _ For only the second time in their
illustrious careers, John Elway and Dan Marino will square off as
the Denver Broncos meet the Miami Dolphins in a nationally
televised football game. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Irving, Texas) _ For the first time in nearly a
month, the Dallas Cowboys showed signs that they could move the
ball on the ground. But their passing game remains stuck in neutral
heading into the final game of the regular season Sunday against
Washington. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
