<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN SANTA HAS HIS LIMITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By Harry Shattuck 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When last we checked in with Santa, Rudolph and the gang, they
were struggling to come to grips with holiday capacity controls on
their frequent-flyer mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new dilemma:
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean that I can't take the children's Christmas
presents aboard the airplane?'' Santa is asking the agent at the
North Pole Airport ticket counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, but we've got stricter carry-on restrictions this year,
Santa,'' the agent responds. ``Two bags maximum. One on crowded
flights. And that includes computers, cameras and briefcases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't have any of that stuff. All I've got is Furbys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping bags count against the limit, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So how many Furbys can I carry aboard?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a few hundred. They're even hard for me to find. Mrs.
Claus and I shopped all year to get just enough for the really good
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have to fit together within a 9-by-14-inch sizing bin
at the gate; otherwise, the flight attendant won't let the Furbys
board. Flights are really packed these days, Santa. We're jamming
in those seat rows. And finding room for all the carry-on bags is
delaying everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa scratches his beard in bewilderment. ``But airplanes are
empty on Christmas Eve. We're just about the only folks flying. And
we've got important deliveries all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth, Santa, it's not just crowding and delays
we're worried about. Thousands of passengers get hurt each year
when bags fall from the overhead bins and plunk them on the
noggin'. We can't afford the doctor bills and lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Furbys are innocent and soft and cuddly. Even a baby would
love for one to fall in her lap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Be honest now, Santa. I'll bet you've got some video games and
CDs and dolls in your gift satchels, too. If those fell on your
head, they'd sting. And, Santa, what are we going to do about that
big garment bag you're carrying? It will never fit in the sizing
bin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do without the garment bag. That's where I stash my
spare suits in case I get all sooty climbing down chimneys. Ever
looked at my Santa suit? It's bulky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a suggestion, Santa; you may want to redesign your suit
to fit into a tote bag. The luggage makers have all but ceased
production on carry-on garment bags because they don't meet our new
rules. We're going to see lots of adjustments in luggage-making
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Rudolph has watched the exchange in pained silence.
He feels partly responsible; ever since he and the other reindeer
retired from sleigh duty, Santa has had nothing but hassles while
making deliveries by less reliable air transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a bright red light of inspiration illuminates on Rudolph's'
nose. ``We'll check with other airlines, Santa,'' he consoles.
``Someone will make room for the Furbys. We can't let the kids
down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' the agent says, ``We're all in this carry-on
crackdown together. American, Southwest, Delta, United, US Airways,
TWA, Northwest. Sizes and rules vary, but not by much. Only
Continental is taking a different approach; they're building larger
overhead storage bins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it; we'll fly Continental!'' Santa and Rudolph say in
unison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't do, Santa,'' Agent Scrooge shakes his head. ``You've not
only got nonrefundable tickets, you've bought them over the
Internet through our e-mail program. You've got to use them tonight
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa bows his head in resignation. ``OK, we have no choice.
We'll ship the Furbys in the luggage compartment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, Santa, we may have a problem there, too. We've got these
questions we're required to ask you; understand, it's nothing
personal, but there are some crazy people out there. Did you do all
the packing yourself? Has anyone else had access to your luggage?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no. And yes. The elves always help me pack. I've got
elves everywhere. Moms. Dads. Uncles. Aunts. Grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'll have to inspect all your luggage. And we'll have to
unwrap the presents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there nothing I can do?'' Santa makes one last plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one exception to the carry-on rule, Santa. We permit
additional articles if they are for medical necessity: canes,
crutches, walkers, breathing devices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Furbys are a medical necessity,'' Santa argues. ``A lot of
really nice kids are going to be sick if they don't find them under
the tree tomorrow morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell you what, Santa _ it is Christmas. I've got kids, too.
We'll give the Furbys a medical exemption. They can board.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the agent checks his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, Santa, don't tell anyone. And don't you and Rudolph and
the Furbys expect a meal. We can't afford to serve steak on these
flights anymore. All you'll get are milk and cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time tonight, Santa smiles. Rudolph's nose glows.
Milk and cookies! ``Maybe there is hope for these airlines after
all,'' Santa says.
</P>
<P>
   Happy holidays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
