<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-LIST-HNS &LR;      12-21 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-LIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 WAYS TO SAVE ON YOUR NEXT VACATION  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Order free brochures from tourism offices; they often include
money-saving coupons and advice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Consult online sites for special promotions and as a research
tool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Take advantage of advance-purchase discounts.
</P>
<P>
   4. Avoid peak-season travel.
</P>
<P>
   5. Join frequent-flyer and frequent-guest programs and study
diverse ways to accumulate miles and points toward free or
discounted trips.
</P>
<P>
   6. Utilize a travel agent's ability to comparison shop on your
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   7. Study and evaluate advertised specials.
</P>
<P>
   8. Prior to a trip, read a newspaper or magazine whose ads cover
your destination; you may find bargains.
</P>
<P>
   9. Be alert for periodic air-fare sales.
</P>
<P>
   10. Maintain flexibility in scheduling flights.
</P>
<P>
   11. Consider consolidators for international flights.
</P>
<P>
   12. Inquire about discounts for seniors and military personnel
or for unusual circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   13. Join a student or teacher travel program.
</P>
<P>
   14. Get free travelers checks, maps, trip-planning services and
hotel discounts through membership in AAA or other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   15. Secure free point-to-point maps from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   16. Purchase all-inclusive group package tours.
</P>
<P>
   17. Become a tour-group leader.
</P>
<P>
   18. Consider volunteering or teaching as you travel.
</P>
<P>
   19. Visit a tourist office as soon as you arrive at a
destination and inquire about discounts for attractions, events,
lodging, dining and tours.
</P>
<P>
   20. Inquire about hotel packages that include special perks.
</P>
<P>
   21. Stay at hotels and motels that offer free breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   22. Reserve rooms at hotels during low-occupancy periods.
</P>
<P>
   23. Negotiate for a better rate at a hotel's front desk.
</P>
<P>
   24. Look for promotional specials at hotels in Europe and other
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   25. Join a program that offers half-price rates at hotels.
</P>
<P>
   26. Participate in a home exchange when planning a lengthy
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   27. Rent a villa when traveling as a family or group.
</P>
<P>
   28. Consider condominiums at popular and pricey resorts.
</P>
<P>
   29. Use alternative lodgings such as hostels and college
dormitories
</P>
<P>
   30. Join a discount dining program.
</P>
<P>
   31. Ask about fixed-price meals at restaurants, especially in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   32. Pack a picnic lunch; it's fun and inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   33. Purchase multi-use passes for extensive rail, bus and air
travel.
</P>
<P>
   34. Purchase multi-day passes for subways and city buses.
</P>
<P>
   35. Look for passes that provide admission to multiple
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   36. Consider hop-on, hop-off tours in large cities.
</P>
<P>
   37. Rent automobiles at off-airport locations.
</P>
<P>
   38. Avoid daily car rental rates; ask about discounts on weekly
rates.
</P>
<P>
   39. Don't let car rental attendants talk you into unnecessary
insurance charges.
</P>
<P>
   40. Avoid brochures prices when buying a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   41. Take advantage of repeater discounts offered by cruise
lines.
</P>
<P>
   42. Book a repositioning cruise.
</P>
<P>
   43. Choose a cruise itinerary that has lots of competition.
</P>
<P>
   44. Ask about last-minute cruise specials.
</P>
<P>
   45. Avoid expensive shore excursions by joining others to
negotiate with an English-speaking guide.
</P>
<P>
   46. Apply for passports and necessary visas early to avoid
expedited payments.
</P>
<P>
   47. Pack enough film and all necessities to avoid high tariffs
at your destination.
</P>
<P>
   48. Make certain to get VAT (Value Added Tax) refunds when
traveling abroad.
</P>
<P>
   49. Get sage advice from consumer-oriented books and
periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   50. Know your rights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1626EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0828 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-4TAKES-HN     12-21 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-4TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 HELPFUL HINTS MAKE SAVING VACATION DOLLARS EASIER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
and SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are suggestions on ways to stretch a budget for your next
vacation:
</P>
<P>
   _ 1. Free brochures. Tourism offices in all 50 states, most
foreign countries and major cities worldwide publish brochures
crammed with information that can help you save money during a
visit. This literature usually costs nothing and can be requested
in advance of a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Some brochures include coupons that provide discounts or free
admissions; San Antonio's seasonal S.A.V.E. program, for instance,
offers significant savings at hotels, restaurants and varied
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Most tourism bureaus have toll-free numbers; access
www.mbnet.mb.ca/lucas/travel/tourism-offices.html on the Internet
for a list of government tourism offices, convention and visitors
bureaus and other agencies. Access www.wwb.com to learn how to
request more than 10,000 brochures at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2. Online promotions. Travelers of all ages are learning to
use the Internet for two main reasons: (1) the vast information
available online and (2) bargains available from no other source.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites sponsored by several airlines inform about e-mail
services that tout exclusive weekend getaway packages with
discounted air and lodging; Houston-based Continental
(www.flycontinental.com) designates last-minute cut-rate trips
every weekend from Bush Intercontinental Airport; last weekend you
could have traveled round-trip from Houston to San Diego for $169,
Kansas City for $139 or New Orleans for $79. Southwest also offers
periodic Internet specials; access www.iflyswa.com.
</P>
<P>
   For the most comprehensive listings of discounted airline fares,
access these sites: www.bestfares.com and www.webflyer.com.
</P>
<P>
   Several online booking services offer packages or links to
airline, hotel and destination specials; some will send e-mail
alerts about bargains on specific routes. Among the largest sites:
www.travelocity.com; www.expedia.com; www.thetrip.com;
www.travelweb.com; www.itn.com; www.biztravel.com; and
www.previewtravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   You can even name your price for a specified airline trip or
hotel stay via www.priceline.com. But study the guidelines
carefully and make certain you don't submit a bid for a higher
amount than you would pay via more traditional means.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of other travel-related Web sites _
sponsored by tourism bureaus, hotels, museums, theme parks, you
name it _ and you never know when you may come upon a bargain; we
were planning a stop at a New Braunfels cafe recently and
discovered an Internet-only coupon valid for 50 percent off an
entree.
</P>
<P>
   _ 3. Book early. It's not a cardinal rule anymore, but planning
and purchasing in advance remains the safest way to get low prices
on airlines, cruises and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Because of better inventory control, airlines now occasionally
release unsold seats at low prices as the departure date nears. But
that's the exception; as frequent travelers know, most flights now
depart at or near capacity _ and those who pay the least usually
satisfy 14-day or seven-day advance-purchase requirements (earlier
for international travel). Airlines also offer periodic sales that
require almost immediate purchases even if travel is permitted
weeks or months into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines, too, offer significant discounts for
``early-bird'' bookings _ up to six months in advance. And if you
covet that $49 supersaver weekend rate at a chain hotel, don't dare
wait until the day before departure.
</P>
<P>
   _ 4. Off-season travel. Whatever your destination, recognize _
and if you're on a tight budget, avoid _ its busiest season.
Airline tickets, car rentals, train tickets and lodging likely will
be priced accordingly. Europe is a bargain in winter; the best
Caribbean deals occur in summer. Expect to pay double the regular
rates in New Orleans during Mardi Gras, but visit in August and
you'll find significant discounts. Low or shoulder season at some
destinations may not provide the ideal weather conditions, but
you'll avoid the crowds and pay substantially less.
</P>
<P>
   5 . Frequent-traveler programs. Many people consider these a
waste of time if they don't travel often. But more frequent-flyer
miles are earned on the ground than in the air. With careful
planning and the right credit card, you can accumulate miles while
buying groceries, dining out, making telephone calls, even paying
the home mortgage. And those miles can lead to a free trip. An
excellent source to learn ways to earn more miles is
www.webflyer.com. Randy Petersen, who operates this site, also
publishes ``The Official Frequent Flyer Guidebook''; its sixth
edition is due in January and costs $14.99. Call 800-209-2870 for
information.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every airline and hotel chain offers a credit card whose
benefits include mileage-earning opportunities. Even better are the
American Express Membership Rewards (call 800-297-3276) and Diners
Club Rewards (800-234-6377) programs, because they allow you to
accumulate points and transfer them to any number of
frequent-traveler programs.
</P>
<P>
   Look for partnerships among airlines and hotels. Say you're a
Continental OnePass member, but the Houston-based airline doesn't
fly to your destination; you can earn OnePass miles on more than a
dozen other carriers. Continental frequent flyers also earn credit
by utilizing any of 15 hotel chains and six rental-car firms.
</P>
<P>
   Don't automatically toss all those frequent-traveler
newsletters. True, much of what's written is propaganda, but
members-only discounts are often included.
</P>
<P>
   _ 6. Utilize a travel agent. The Internet is a wonderful tool
for information. But a local travel agent is still the
bargain-hunter's best friend in coordinating a vacation to fit
individual objectives and budgets. Keep in mind that a good travel
agent has access to the Internet, too, and knows how to use it for
your benefit. Unlike many Web sites, whose main purpose is to
promote and sell a specific service, the travel agent's main
responsibility is you. The value of comparison-shopping on your
behalf can't be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   Most travel agents now charge a small fee for their services.
But compare to the time and money you'd spend putting a trip
together. Just make certain the travel agent understands what you
want from a vacation and how much you can spend. If one agent
doesn't appreciate your budgetary requirements, find another who
does.
</P>
<P>
   _ 7. Advertised specials. Vegas for less! Maximum cruise value!
Guaranteed lowest price! Newspaper travel sections and magazines
are filled with advertisements touting the newest ``bargain of a
lifetime.'' It's always important to read the fine print and to
learn some background about the company making an offer, but a
savvy and cautious traveler can find a real deal. By evaluating a
variety of promotions and comparing prices, you can get a good idea
of which destinations or cruises are offering the best values. Ask
firm questions to find out exactly what you are getting for your
investment. And remember: If it sounds too good to be true, it
usually is.
</P>
<P>
   _ 8. Out-of-town publications. Target your reading just as
hotels, car-rental agencies and popular attractions target their
advertisements. Example: If you are planning a trip to New York,
consider buying a newspaper published in Boston or Washington, D.C.
Why? Because the best advertised discounts often are aimed at
travelers in neighboring cities.
</P>
<P>
   It's often worthwhile, too, to buy a newspaper published at your
destination and check it for planning and money-saving ideas. Some
bookstores, newsstands and public libraries in the Houston area
carry newspapers from other large cities.
</P>
<P>
   _ 9. Air-fare sales. Several times each year _ usually before
slow travel periods _ airlines advertise fare sales that cover
multiple destinations. And it's all but guaranteed that if one
airline reveals a sale, rival carriers will match the prices on
competing routes. Read details carefully when these announcements
appear: Often you are given only a short time _ maybe 10 days _ to
purchase tickets, but those tickets may be valid for months;
especially inviting are late-winter ``sales'' to Europe that allow
travel into early spring, when the weather may be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ 10. Maintain flexibility. This is important in any aspect of
planning a trip, but especially in securing the lowest air fares.
The traveler who calls an airline reservations number and asks,
``What's the best price on Flight 299 from Houston to Chicago at
noon?'' will get only a fraction of the information necessary to
find the best deal. The same airline may offer a lower fare on
Flight 399 at 3 p.m. or Flight 499 at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing is no longer standard; airlines are constantly studying
the probable load factors of each departure and adjusting fares
several times daily in an effort to fill the maximum number of
seats. Be persistent in asking about all flights on your preferred
travel date; better yet, ask a travel agent to use a ``bargain
finder'' tool that surveys flights to your destination by each
carrier. If you don't like the answer, check again the next day;
you'll probably find a different set of fares.
</P>
<P>
   Be flexible, too, in your choice of airports. If the fare from
Houston to Washington, D.C., is too steep for your budget, ask
about connections to Baltimore. Consider Oakland instead of San
Francisco, Fort Lauderdale instead of Miami. Or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   _ 11. Consolidators and couriers. These companies are
essentially wholesalers that distribute discounted tickets airlines
can't sell for full value. They are best used for international
flights. Make certain any consolidator you use is reputable and pay
via credit card; most travel agents will book your trip through a
consolidator but only if you ask. A good source for information is
``Consolidators: Air Travel's Bargain Basement'' (The Intrepid
Traveler, $7.95) by Kelly Monaghan.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers call to inquire about courier travel (flying at
little or no cost while accompanying a package or document). The
era of free courier tickets is all but over, and few if any
departures are from Houston. Travelers desiring information can
check out ``The Courier Air Travel Handbook'' (Perpetual Press,
$9.95) by Mark I. Field. Other sources: Worldwide Courier
Association (800-780-4359; www.wallstech.com); International
Association of Air Travel Couriers (561-582-8320; www.courier.org)
and Air Courier Association (800-282-1202; www.courier.to)
</P>
<P>
   _ 12.  &UR; Seniors discounts. &LR;  Most airlines offer travelers 62 and
older a 10 percent discount on any published fare. Houston-based
Continental, Delta, United and American also sponsor clubs through
which seniors pay an established fee, then get higher discounts
and/or the opportunity to purchase sharply reduced tickets for
travel within specific zones.
</P>
<P>
   Major carriers also sell coupon books that can provide discounts
for senior citizens, depending on the route traveled; books of four
one-way coupons cost from $540 to $600. Some airlines allow seniors
to take along a companion of any age. Continental sells four-coupon
books for $579, eight-coupon books for $1,079. These cover the
lower 48 states, Canada, Mexico and the Caribbean; trips to Hawaii
and Alaska require two coupons each direction. Make certain before
using a coupon that a lower published fare isn't available.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP)
qualify for discounts at many hotels and attractions. Despite the
name, retirement isn't a criteria: Chances are you will (or did)
receive overtures from AARP around age 50; or call 800-424-3410.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the destination, seniors should ask about discounts;
restaurants, museums, parks and other attractions frequently offer
bargain prices. A good source is ``The Mature Traveler's Book of
Deals'' (GEM Publishing, $7.95; write to P.O. Box 50400, Reno, Nev.
89513-0400.
</P>
<P>
   Others who fit specific categories can reap benefits, too. Most
airlines offer discounts to active military personnel, especially
valuable for short-notice leave. Bereavement fares are available to
individuals making unexpected trips because of a death in the
family (but airlines can be strict in requiring documentation).
Consult individual carriers about their programs and rules.
</P>
<P>
   _ 13. Student and teacher travel. Several airlines offer fare
discounts and/or fixed-price coupons available to full-time
students. Ages vary. Youth passes purchased prior to a trip can
provide significant discounts on European train travel; call
800-438-7245. For a small fee, the nonprofit International Student
Travel Confederation offers student and teacher identity cards
valid for discounts worldwide; its Web site (www.istc.org) includes
destination-by-destination details and addresses of offices. The
nonprofit Council on Standards for International Educational Travel
(www. csiet.org) can provide information on 64 youth travel and
exchange organizations. Numerous other organizations specialize in
student and/or teacher travel, including teacher education programs
abroad; check with campus advisers or browse the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ 14. Auto clubs. Sometimes it's worth spending money to save in
the long run. Depending on the scope of an individual's travel,
membership in AAA or another auto club can prove beneficial even if
your car never breaks down on the road. AAA members pay no extra
charge for travelers checks (including those issued in some foreign
currencies); get free maps, tour brochures (identifying lodgings
and attractions) and trip planning advice; and receive discounts at
many hotels (though you need to ask when making reservations).
</P>
<P>
   _ 15. Free point-to-point maps. Save money on gasoline _ and
avoid headaches _ by knowing the quickest way to reach your driving
destination. Several online services specialize in mapping almost
any route you choose within the United States _ even if the trip is
from your home in Sugar Land to see Grandma in The Woodlands. Among
the best: www.maps.com and www.mapquest.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ 16. Group tours. These aren't suited to every traveler, but
package tours offer the security of knowing that all (or most)
major costs of your vacation are included in one basic price.
Independent travelers can be amazed how quickly ``incidental''
charges _ meals, tips, entrance fees, subway tickets, etc. _ mount
into hundreds of dollars and destroy a budget. Even with group
tours, find out in advance what the package includes. A $700 tour
without lunches and dinners hardly represents a savings over an
$800 tour that includes all meals. Also take time to check on the
reputation of the tour firm; most (but not all) tour operators
belong to either the National Tour Association (800-682-8886) or
U.S. Tour Operators Association (212-599-6599).
</P>
<P>
   _ 17. Tour group leaders. If you can assemble a group of 12 or
more (sometimes less) fellow travelers, you may qualify for a free
trip. A travel agent may help with arrangements once you guarantee
a certain number of participants. Or contact tour companies. One
caution: The role of group leader doesn't come without
responsibilities; don't get involved unless you enjoy working with
others and have the knack (and patience) to deal with problems that
arise.
</P>
<P>
   _ 18. Volunteering and teaching. Several organizations sponsor
programs through which individuals get to see the world at little
or no cost in exchange for volunteering their services part-time.
Among the best are Global Volunteers (800-487-1074) and Habitat for
Humanity (800-422-4828); a good source for learning about these and
other programs is ``You Can Travel Free'' (Pelican, $15.95) by
Robert Wm. Kirk. That book also takes a comprehensive look at
teaching abroad. Also recommended is ``Volunteer Vacations''
(Chicago Review Press; $13.95) by Bill McMilian.
</P>
<P>
   _ 19. ``Tourism offices.'' Upon arrival at a destination, the
first stop for a traveler on a budget should be a local tourist
office. Representatives there know about any low-cost hotel
availability and about discounts on tours and attractions. Most
?Vmstribute free brochures.
</P>
<P>
   _ 20. Hotel packages. Modern-day hotels and resorts offer more
than a room; they tout fitness centers, golf courses (or course
privileges), tennis courts, spas, children's centers, activities
programs and other perks. If you aren't careful, you'll pay more
for the
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
