<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli Parliament rejected
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's peace policies today, then gave
initial approval to a law calling early elections. The election law
must be approved twice more, but Netanyahu has said he will not try
to block its passage. The early parliamentary elections will mean
another delay in the Mideast peace process. (Summary from wires.)
By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENT (Beijing) _ China demonstrated its firm resolve
to stamp out any organized political opposition today, sentencing
two of the country's most prominent democracy campaigners to long
prison terms. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLOON (Undated) _ Faced with a choice between a crash
landing in the Himalayas of Nepal or the possibility of being
forced down by China's armed forces, three balloonists seeking to
circle the world non-stop pressed on toward Chinese air space
Monday, hoping for a last-minute change of heart by the Beijing
government. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall on impeachment developments: Vice
President Gore calls for censure. Some Clinton advisors want a
trial instead. McConnell says there has to be a trial. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON (Washington) _ Rep. Robert L. Livingston saw
the Washington Post ad asking woman who have had affairs with
politicians to tell their stories, but even though he has had a
number of affairs while gaining power in Congress he said he
shrugged it off. ``I didn't consider the power of a million
dollars,'' said Livingston, chairman of the appropriations
committee and the man slated to be speaker. Other comments from the
interview on the rise and fall of a politician in an age of
fast-moving Washington scandals. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
