<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ A ravenous investor appetite for Internet
stocks brushed aside concerns about Washington politics Monday and
drove the market sharply higher, vaulting the Nasdaq index to
another record. The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 154.29, or
1.7 percent, to 9,058.92 in late trading, still 3.5 percent below
its Nov. 23 record. The Nasdaq Composite Index rose 48.62, or 2.3
percent, to 2,134.76. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MYLAN-SUIT (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission charged
today that Mylan Laboratories, the nation's second biggest maker of
generic drugs, had violated antitrust laws, and the government said
it would seek $120 million in refunds for consumers of two widely
used anti-anxiety medications. Attorneys General from 10 states,
including New York, Connecticut, Florida, Illinois and
Pennsylvania, are filing a similar lawsuit. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BANANA-TRADE (Washington) _ With an impeachment trial looming
and the conflict with Iraq temporarily subsiding, the Clinton
Administration chose today to fire its first salvo in the banana
war. After months of threats, the U.S. announced that in
retaliation for Europe's refusal to open up its market to bananas
shipped by two American firms _ Dole Food Company and Chiquita
Brands, controlled by Carl Lindner, a major contributor to both
political parties _ it would impose 100 percent tariffs on a range
of European-made products. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
