<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0837 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-4THTAKE-H     12-21 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-4THTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(Undated): rental dollar.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ 38. Avoid daily rental rates. A customer is quoted a $50 daily
car rental rate and a $200 weekly rate. He only needs the
automobile five days, not seven. Which does he choose? It's a
no-brainer. But you don't always know all the options unless you
ask. Rental car firms have myriad rates; inquire about discounts
for AAA, AARP and frequent-flyer program members and active
military personnel. Ask about special promotions. Persistence can
lead to a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ 39. Beware extra charges. Car rental clerks can dazzle you _
even scare you _ with suggestions about various insurance coverages
and fuel options. ``You pay only $10 extra for full security,'' the
employee will say, not bothering to add that the $10 is per day,
not for the full rental. It's essential to have sufficient
insurance, but your policy at home or work _ or the credit card you
use for payment _ may cover you fully. Know what you need, and
don't spend a penny more. And listen carefully when those fuel
plans are explained; you don't want to pay in advance for a full
tank if you plan to drive only 75 miles.
</P>
<P>
   _ 40. Avoid cruise brochure prices. These are akin to sticker
prices placed on new automobiles. Or to hotel rack rates. Nobody
should pay them. Any travel agent can offer a much better deal. Or
check newspaper advertisements in this and other travel sections
for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   _ 41. Repeater discounts. Cruise lines keep a careful record of
past passengers, and most invite you to join a repeaters club at no
charge; some enroll you automatically. As a repeater, you get
mailings about discounted sailings; some lines offer an automatic
savings.
</P>
<P>
   _ 42. Repositioning cruises. Many ships spend part of the year
in one part of the world (Europe perhaps) and another elsewhere
(the Caribbean). Voyages that connect these home areas usually have
a minimum number of port calls and quite a few sea days; these
repositioning cruises appeal greatly to veteran seafarers but not
to the mainstream, thus are usually offered for bargain prices.
This is a chance to sail on a top-quality ship at a price way below
normal. A travel agent can provide details.
</P>
<P>
   _ 43. Competitive itineraries. Fifteen years ago, cruises to
Alaska were priced beyond the means of most travelers; now, many
sailings cost little more than a Caribbean cruise. Why? Because
instead of three or four ships sailing in Alaskan waters, more than
30 call the area home in summer. Each tries to lure passengers by
offering the lowest price. Many veteran cruisers look for
one-of-a-kind itineraries, but they'll likely pay more. The best
bargains occur when ships vie for your business.
</P>
<P>
   _ 44. Last-minute specials. Yes, we advocate booking early, and
cruise lines offer advance-purchase savings on almost every
itinerary. But when specific sailings don't sell out as the
departure date nears, the line would rather sell a cabin at a
heavily discounted price _ even lower than the ``early bird rate''
_ than leave it empty. This benefits a flexible traveler who can
leave home in a hurry. Most travel agents know or can find out
about these bargains. Some companies specialize in last-minute
cruises. Among them: Houston-based Vacations to Go; call
713-974-2121.
</P>
<P>
   _ 45. Shore excursions. Prior to a cruise or as soon as you
board, a cruise line will give you a handsome brochure detailing
dozens of shore excursions. Most are efficiently operated and
convenient. Also expensive. These are best suited to single
travelers and couples; three or more passengers should consider
combining assets to hire an English-speaking guide to customize
sightseeing. Taxis and tour guides meet ships at almost every port
and are accustomed to negotiating prices _ per vehicle, not per
person. And you have more of a say in where you go and when you
stop.
</P>
<P>
   _ 46. Get documents early. The National Passport Agency can send
you a passport on short notice, but only for an extra fee. Be aware
when yours expires, and renew early. Don't tarry with visas and
other documents either, or you'll likely pay more for expedited
service.
</P>
<P>
   _ 47. Pack necessities. Making a packing checklist may seem
fundamental, but it's amazing how many frequent travelers forget
film, sunscreen or medications. At a resort destination or in a
foreign country, you'll pay a hefty price for items you buy at
Kmart or Target in your hometown.
</P>
<P>
   _ 48. Get VAT Refunds. Travelers to Europe, Canada and many
other international destinations pay a Value Added Tax on certain
purchases, sometimes including lodging and car rentals. This VAT
can represent up to 25 percent of your bill, but it's refundable _
but only if you take the time to complete the required paperwork.
In most instances, it's worth the effort; ask in stores or at your
hotel for the proper forms.
</P>
<P>
   _ 49. Consumer publications. We've cited several sources for
cost-saving information in this report. Bookstores and libraries
stock other helpful publications. These are books and periodicals
we find especially valuable:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Insider Travel Secrets You're Not Supposed to Know'' (Best
Fares, $19.95) by Tom Parsons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Fares Discount Travel Magazine. Published monthly; call
800-880-1234 for subscription information.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Consumer Reports Best Travel Deals'' (Consumer Union, $8.99)
by Ed Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumer Reports Travel Letter. Published monthly; call
800-234-1970.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arthur Frommer's Budget Travel Magazine. Published quarterly;
call 800-829-9121.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Travel Smarts: Getting the Most Out of Your Travel Dollar''
(Globe Pequot, $12.95) by Herbert Teison and Nancy Dunnan. (Ask for
the second edition.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Travel Smart newsletter. Published monthly; call 914-693-8300
for subscription information.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Best Bargain Family Vacations in the U.S.A.'' (St.
Martin's Griffin, $12.95) by Laura Sutherland and Valerie Wolf
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``America's Best Meal Deals'' 1998-99 (Zagat Survey, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ 50. Know your rights. When you are bumped from a flight or
your tour goes awry or your guaranteed hotel reservation isn't
honored, it helps to understand what obligation _ if any _ the
travel-service provider holds. Don't expect windfalls when things
go wrong, but don't be deprived of what you are due. One advantage
of using a travel agent is that the agency can advise about your
rights and support you in any disputes with companies it uses. The
American Society of Travel Agents can advise about any member; call
703-739-8739. The Aviation Consumer Protection Division of the
Department of Transportation publishes several informative
brochures; call 202-366-2220. The Better Business Bureau in any
city where a company is located can tell you if that firm is in
good standing; call the Houston BBB at 713-868-9500.
</P>
<P>
   Also, keep in mind that laws and protocol in foreign countries
aren't always what we're accustomed to in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
