<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
SHAKESPEARE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ The witty, fast-paced
``Shakespeare in Love,'' nominated for six Golden Globes last week,
portrays the young Shakespeare as a largely unknown playwright
without inspiration or material who falls for a woman who draws him
into a dramatic _ and very funny _ tale of star-crossed love. By
Fred Shuster. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1632EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0846 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-3RDTAKE-H     12-21 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAVE-3RDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(UNDATED): greens fees. _ 21. Free breakfasts. Budget motels and all-suite properties have
lured so many travelers by including free breakfasts with their
standard rate that many traditional full-service hotels now offer
this incentive; sometimes you have to ask. Breakfasts at some
European hotels (usually included in the rate) are so filling that
it's easy to skip lunch _ yet another savings.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ 22. Know occupancy trends. You can save on lodging just by
understanding the establishment's priority. Hotels geared toward
business travelers offer discounts on weekends. At resorts and
bed-and-breakfasts, which cater more to vacationers, the best rates
are Sundays through Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   _ 23. Negotiate at hotels. When you call a hotel reservations
number and ask for a room rate, the employee almost always will
quote the highest published rate. Don't accept it; inquire about
discounts. Rarely are specials volunteered. Some cost-conscious
travelers forego reservations, arrive in early evening and bargain
with desk clerks; desk personnel often are given considerable
leeway in ``adjusting'' set rates, especially if it appears rooms
may go empty that night.
</P>
<P>
   _ 24. Promotional specials. Hotels in Europe and at other
international destinations occasionally try to lure Americans with
special promotions, especially during low-tourism seasons. Example:
For the fourth consecutive year, Thistle Hotels in Great Britain is
offering a ``pound for dollars'' promotion through April 11;
whatever the standard rate in British pounds, you pay that figure
in U.S. dollars, in effect a 40 percent savings. Because of the
Asian financial crisis, hotels in that part of the world are
offering huge discounts. A travel agent can inform about these and
other bargains.
</P>
<P>
   _ 25. Half-price programs. For a set fee averaging about $50,
clubs or directories promote ``half-price'' rates (or thereabouts)
at thousands of lodgings, including high-quality chain hotels. (One
caution: Half-price is usually off the highest published rate; if
that rate is $150 and an advertised special is $69 ... well, you
figure the math.) That said, these programs can lead to significant
savings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the largest companies: Entertainment Publications
(800-445-4137), Encore (800-444-9800), Privilege Card International
(800-236-9732), International Travel Card (800-987-6216), America
at 50 Percent Discount (800-248-2783) and Quest (800-638-9819).
</P>
<P>
   Also offering discounts in large cities is Hotel Reservations
Network, a no-fee consolidator; call 800-964-6835 or access
www.hoteldiscount.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ 26. Home exchanges. Many travelers can't imagine leaving their
home in the care of strangers, but for extended trips home
exchanges can result in substantial savings. And since you'll be
living in the home vacated by those temporarily inhabiting your
property, ample incentive exists for everyone to exercise care.
Some travelers work out exchanges on their own, through
advertisements or direct communications; most pay an annual fee
($40 to $80) to receive a directory of prospective home-swappers.
Among companies recommended by Houston Chronicle Budget Travel
columnist Arthur Frommer: Homelink (800-638-3841; www.swapnow.com);
Intervac U.S. (800-756-4663); Teacher Swap (516-244-2845); Trading
Homes International (800-877-8723; www.trading-homes.com); and
International Home Exchange Network (www.ihen.com). One book to
consider is ``Home Exchange Vacationing'' (Rutledge Hill, $14.95)
by Bill and Mary Barbour.
</P>
<P>
   _ 27. Villa rentals. Planning a reunion with former college
buddies in Puerto Vallarta, Mexico? A three-generation family
gathering in Italy? Why pay $150 per night for several rooms when
you can rent an entire house _ often with housekeepers and a chef _
for considerably less. Villas are available primarily in popular
tourist destinations other than large cities; ask tourism bureaus
for listings and photographs. A travel agent can provide guidance,
too.
</P>
<P>
   _ 28. Condominiums. So you relish the prospect of a one-week
vacation on the beach in Maui? The full-service resort charges $200
per night; the condominium next door charges $700 per week and
includes a kitchen. ``But I don't want to cook on vacation,'' you
say. Don't. Just pay the cheaper rate at the condo and dine at the
hotel. Two- and three-bedroom condominiums are especially practical
for families on a budget. The highest savings are at resort areas
where hotels charge a high tariff. Consult a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   _ 29. Hostels and dormitories. Hostels were originally designed
for youths who embrace low-cost dormitory-style living quarters and
shared bathrooms as a means to save on lodging. Now travelers of
all ages are welcomed and hostels are located worldwide; good
sources for finding them are Hostelling International (call
202-783-6161; access www.hiayh.org on the Internet); the Internet
Guide to Hostelling (www.hostels.com); and ``Hostels USA: The Only
Comprehensive, Unofficial, Opinionated Guide'' (Globe Pequot,
$14.95) by Evan Halper and Paul Karr.
</P>
<P>
   _ 30. Discount dining programs. Numerous programs feature
directories of restaurants where savings are available. Most
frequent-flyer programs now feature dining programs. The Houston
Chronicle Gusto Card, free to all subscribers, focuses primarily on
the Houston area but also provides discounts at some restaurants
elsewhere in Texas. Large programs operated nationwide include
Entertainment Publications (800-445-4137), Transmedia
(800-422-5090), Dinner On Us (800-346-3241) and Dining la Card
(800-253-5379).
</P>
<P>
   _ 31. Fixed-price meals. These are especially practical at
European restaurants. They are usually posted in windows or
attached to standard menus and offer three or four courses at
substantial savings.
</P>
<P>
   _ 32. Picnic lunches. These appeal not only to cost-conscious
travelers but to romantics everywhere. Visit a grocery, bakery
and/or (especially in Europe) a meat market, then find an idyllic
setting. Some hotels will prepare picnic baskets, but you run the
risk of spending more on them than you would at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   _ 33. Rail, air and bus passes. European travelers reap
considerable savings by purchasing passes from Rail Europe prior to
a trip. Dozens of options are available covering specified days and
countries; some can be combined with car rentals. Complete vacation
packages also are available. Call 800-438-7245; access
www.raileurope.com on the Internet. The Europe Flight Pass provides
$90 one-way fares for intra-European flights operated by 13
airlines to 62 cities in 20 countries; call 888-387-2479 or access
www.europeflightpass.com. Amtrak offers special zone fares and
vacation packages; call 800-523-8720 or 800-321-8684 or access
www.amtrak.com. Greyhound offers several variations of its
Ameripass for multiple use on buses and sells other discount
packages; call 800-231-2222 or access www.greyhound.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ 34. Public transportation. When vacationing in large cities,
ask about multiuse or multiday passes before buying single-ride
subway or bus tickets. If you plan extensive intra-city travel,
these passes can save money; evaluate options and read the fine
print. Ask if passes are valid for all forms of public
transportation; in London, for instance, the same pass covers buses
and underground trains. Even without passes, public transportation
is usually a cheaper alternative than taxis or car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   _ 35. Multiple-attraction passes. Usually available through
tourist offices, these passes are ideal for travelers who plan
extensive sightseeing. A museum pass in Paris is valid at more than
70 museums and monuments. City cards sold in Copenhagen and
Stockholm include free admission to many attractions and use of
public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   _ 36. Hop-on, hop-off tours. Popular in London, Paris and other
world capitals, these tours allow you to pay one price, then board
and re-board buses or trolleys at designated stops (usually near
major landmarks) as often as you wish during a day. Plan your
itinerary carefully, and you get maximum value for your investment.
</P>
<P>
   _ 37. Off-airport car rentals. Yes, those rental counters
adjacent to baggage claim carousels are convenient, but companies
pay top dollar to rent the space, and guess where that expense is
passed along? To the consumer. Smaller companies situated down the
road usually can offer lower rates. And free shuttles make access
easy. One caution: Make sure exactly what you are getting for your
rental dollar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
