<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-MURDERED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AUTOPSY SHOWS REPORTER WAS STRANGLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A second autopsy on the body of an American
journalist confirmed earlier forensic findings that the reporter
had strangled, a spokesman for President Ernesto Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Philip True, the Mexico City correspondent for the
San Antonio Express-News, was found last week in a mountainous area
of western Mexico three weeks after he had set out on a solo hike
to report on a regional Indian tribe.
</P>
<P>
   True's remains were cremated Sunday in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the attorney general's office and a forensic
pathologist contracted by the FBI traveled early Sunday to the
remote Sierra Madre Occidental where True's body was found on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the order of the federal government, a second autopsy was
conducted Saturday, just hours before a memorial service in the
garden of his Mexico City home where he lived with his wife Marta.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo said the complete autopsy
report would not be available for several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took tissue samples to conduct ... studies. These take
several days to do cultures,'' Madrazo said. ``And we'll be able to
study these together with criminal analysis from the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The body was returned to the family Saturday night and taken to
a funeral home where it was cremated.
</P>
<P>
   The first autopsy, conducted in the state of Jalisco on Thursday
by Dr. Mario Rivas Souza, found True had been strangled with either
a cord or neckerchief. Rivas concluded that True's death was a
homicide.
</P>
<P>
   True's body was found in a shallow grave in a ravine deep in the
Chapalagana Canyon on the border of the states of Jalisco and
Nayarit.
</P>
<P>
   An experienced solo hiker, True, 50, set out on Nov. 28 for a
100-mile trek through a remote region of the Sierra Madre where as
many as 20,000 Huichol Indians live in scattered villages and
ranches.
</P>
<P>
   His intention was study and photograph the Huichol culture for
the the Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   When he didn't return on Dec. 10, family, friends and colleagues
began a frantic search. Three days later, Mexican soldiers joined
the search.
</P>
<P>
   His body was found by a Huichol Indian who had been hunting in
the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   But when the hunter returned with soldiers in helicopters,
True's body had been buried.
</P>
<P>
   Services for True were held Saturday in the back-yard garden of
his home. The ceremony was attended by more than 60 people,
including foreign correspondents and government officials who knew
True, the Express-News correspondent in Mexico City for more than
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the Jack Kerouac of the Mexico City press corps,'' said
Tim Padgett of Time magazine, referring to True's penchant for
roaming the back-country roads of Mexico in pursuit of
unconventional stories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0888 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DEEPSEA-AQUARIUM-     12-21 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DEEPSEA-AQUARIUM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DEPTHS OF OSBCURITY, AQUARIUM'S NEW STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ Miles beneath the turbulent waters of
California's Monterey Bay, research biologists, equipped with a
giant robot submersible, advanced sensory equipment and stomachs
almost of steel, are collecting some of the rarest sea creatures
known to man.
</P>
<P>
   If the biologists of the Monterey Bay Aquarium manage to keep
these bizarre animals alive after bringing them back from the
abyss, as they say they can, the researchers plan a public exhibit
of more than 40 species early next year _ the largest such display
of living deep-sea life ever.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these unusual creatures have never been seen in an
aquarium. Indeed, just a decade ago they had hardly been seen by
anyone, because they inhabit the walls and floors of dark,
underwater canyons more than 3,000 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   While remotely operated robots have been used to retrieve
deep-sea animals for several years now, few species brought back
from the ocean floor survived for long outside their natural
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   But after more than a decade of research, trial and error, and
advances in husbandry and life-support systems, the biologists of
the Monterey Bay Aquarium say they are confident that they can
maintain a variety of deep-sea life long enough for public exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strange creatures the scientists plan to display in
the aquarium's new deep sea exhibit, scheduled to open in March,
are mushroom corals, predatory tunicates, sea whips, spider crabs,
filetail cat sharks, ratfish, feather stars, and ellpouts. Many
biologists have never seen many of these species alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have seen television shows and discovery shows
about sea life but those programs deal mainly with what's in the
first 150 feet of ocean,'' said Gil Van Dykhuizen, a research
biologist for the Monterey Bay Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have captured creatures from thousands of feet deep _
creatures so unusual looking that they appear alien,'' Van
Dykhuizen said, ``and we have learned to keep them alive. Most
people will never see anything like this in their lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the picturesque Monterey Bay is an underwater canyon
more than two miles deep with steep rocky precipices. The
underwater canyon, which rivals Arizona's famous tourist
attraction, is rich in strange and elusive marine life.
</P>
<P>
   The deep-sea exhibit, which will contain 7,000 square feet of
displays, will focus on three of the habitats found in the Monterey
Bay's canyon: the midwater, vertical canyon wall, and sea-floor
habitats. The aquarium has spent more than $5 million over the last
decade to assemble the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   But gathering and sustaining these delicate, deep-sea species is
no easy task and continues to pose considerable technological and
logistical challenges. The success of the Monterey Bay Aquarium's
deep sea exhibit will depend on many factors beyond the biologists'
control. There is plenty of room for things to go wrong, and they
often do.
</P>
<P>
   The currents and weather conditions of the Monterey Bay are
unpredictable and sometimes violent, making it difficult for the
scientists to go collecting. The highly sophisticated machinery
used to gather these creatures from the deep sometimes
malfunctions, causing delays. And sometimes by accident, the
biologists fatally wound the animals while removing them from
hard-to-reach places in the underwater canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many deep-sea creatures perish outside the extreme
conditions of the deep where there is tremendous water pressure,
icy temperatures, limited food, low oxygen, and no sunlight.
Changes in pressure, oxygen content and water temperature causes
the immediate demise of some species.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are attempting has never been done before, so I guess
you can say we are in uncharted waters,'' said Edward Seidel, an
aquarium research biologist. ``But we've learned so much in recent
years that we believe that we can pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was graphically illustrated last month when aquarium
biologists went searching for predatory tunicates _ a star of the
planned exhibit. Extremely rough seas forced them to abandon the
expedition after three stomach-churning hours.
</P>
<P>
   That day the aquarium research boat Point Lobos left dock at
Moss Landing at 4:30 a.m., headed for a location off the bay where
the corals and tunicates are known to thrive. But the winds were so
high and the water so choppy that the research crew dared not place
the submersible robot in the water for fear of losing it. At least
one experienced biologist on board was seasick.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are days when the sea just doesn't want to cooperate,
and all you can do is try again tomorrow,'' said Susan Lisin, an
aquarium research biologist.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, the biologists were up bright and early,
departing dock at 5:30 a.m. with their fingers crossed. But this
time they headed for an unexplored area closer to shore, where the
crew lowered the robot, a giant remote-controlled submersible, into
relatively calm waters. The robot, which was adapted from an
oil-industry model used on offshore platforms and pipelines, is
equipped with sonars, video cameras, flood lights, sensors,
sampling tools, and collecting devices.
</P>
<P>
   On color television screens in the control room aboard the Point
Lobos, the scientists monitored the descent of the robot to the
bottom of the canyon. At first, only a constant rain of dead
plankton and animal wastes, known as ``marine snow,'' is visible on
the screens.
</P>
<P>
   But after diving for 30 minutes, the submersible reached the
ocean floor, a vast expanse of muddy ridges and cliffs, garnished
with colorful sea animals and plants and illuminated by the craft's
lights, which project out 10 to 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The search was under way. In the control room, the submersible
robot is operated by four research staff members, sitting at
workstations with television screens. A main pilot navigates the
submersible, while a second pilot maneuvers the robot's arms to
collect specimens.
</P>
<P>
   One biologist operates the cameras and identifies specimens, and
another biologist oversees a video program that records the entire
underwater excursion, noting the depth and location where sea
animals are encountered.
</P>
<P>
   While the mood in the dimly lighted control room is jovial _ the
blues guitar of Stevie Ray Vaughn flows from speakers overhead, and
there is constant joking _ the work is serious _ and after the
first hour or so often tedious.
</P>
<P>
   The submersible covers an area about the size of a football
field, meticulously searching for the predatory tunicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh where, oh where has my tunicate gone?'' the crew sang in
unison. After nearly an hour of searching, there were no tunicates
in sight. But there were several mushroom soft coral, deep-sea
cucumbers, and sea stars, which were collected and will displayed
in the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful mushroom corals also are expected to be big hits
of the exhibit. Related to anemones and jellyfish, mushroom corals
dwell at the ocean bottom where they extend feathery polyps to
feed, trapping small animals and particles from currents. When the
polyps are retracted, the polyp looks like the dimpled head of a
pink mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering these tender creatures is difficult because they are
often located on steep canyon walls that are hard to reach and
because even the slightest abrasions can kill them. Maneuvering the
robot arms can be especially tricky because the pilot has only a
two-dimensional view but is operating in a three-dimensional
environment.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two hours of combing the ocean bottom, the
researchers hit pay dirt. Perched on a canyon wall and resembling a
rubbery blob was a predatory tunicate. Tunicates are commonly known
as sea squirts because they pump water through their bodies to
filter out food particles.
</P>
<P>
   Deep-sea predatory tunicates are of particular interest because
they capture prey by closing their oral hood, trapping tiny animals
inside like a Venus fly trap.
</P>
<P>
   To gather the predatory tunicate, the pilot uses the robot's
clamshell arm, breaking the substrate with the animal attached, off
the canyon wall. The biologists have found that tunicates that are
torn from their substrate or that have their outer layer torn or
scraped, have little chance for survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't hurt a bit,'' said Stuart Stratton, the robot
pilot, as he grabbed the tunicate from the canyon wall.
</P>
<P>
   The tunicates and other deep-sea animals are stored in an
insulated drawer in the underside of the robot submersible. Such
isolation is necessary to protect the sea creatures, which are
collected in very cold water, from being contaminated by surface
water, which may be up to 10 degrees Centigrade warmer, the
biologists said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the biologists had collected four
predatory tunicates, five mushroom corals, three deep-sea
cucumbers, one pom pom anemone, and one basket star. But collecting
these animals was only half the battle. The creatures must be
sustained in a hostile environment above water.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the biologists could keep the predatory tunicates
alive in aquarium tanks for no more than six to eight months. But
after providing the tunicates with a low-oxygen environment similar
to that in which they normally live, the biologists can now keep
these animals alive for more than two years in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   At depths of 1,650 feet to 2,800 feet, oxygen concentrations in
the Monterey Bay are as low as one-hundredth the amount found in
the surface waters. There is so little oxygen that most surface
fishes would suffocate.
</P>
<P>
   But animals like the predatory tunicate survive in these low
oxygen zones by maintaining a low metabolic rate and extracting
oxygen efficiently. The biologists have designed special
low-temperature, low-oxygen tanks to house the tunicates.
</P>
<P>
   The biologists said they have collected about 70 percent of the
animals needed for the exhibit and that they plan to make at least
five more trips to the deep sea before the opening in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
