<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0903 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-980&AMP;     12-21 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: WHEN HOLIDAY TREASURES POSE DANGERS TO HOUSE
PETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cappy is a lovable but naughty 32-pound cocker spaniel with an
insatiable appetite. So it should not have surprised his owners
when, two days before Christmas, he raided the wrapped gifts under
the tree and ate an entire 12-ounce box of chocolate-covered coffee
beans.
</P>
<P>
   His owners returned from a holiday party to find him racing
about the house, his heart pounding rapidly. An emergency visit to
an all-night veterinary clinic revealed that in his haste to devour
the treats before he was discovered, he had swallowed the beans
whole, avoiding more serious consequences like seizures from the
stimulants in the dark chocolate and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Cappy was lucky. Many a pet dog and cat has suffered far more
disastrous health problems from holiday-related hazards, and more
than a few have died, casting an unshakable pall over the whole
season for those who loved them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Saidla, director of continuing education at Cornell
University's College of Veterinary Medicine, said he spent his
saddest Christmas trying in vain to save a young dog hit by a car
when it dashed across the street after children who were going to
inspect a neighbor's new bike. The dog had been a gift to the
children after their father was killed in a plane crash on
Christmas Day two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians who have treated countless holiday casualties
caution pet owners to pay as much attention to their animals'
safety as they would to a child's. In many ways, a pet dog or cat
is like a perpetual toddler _ insatiably curious, unlikely to heed
the word ``no'' and willing to put anything and everything into its
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Given the tumult that generally characterizes the holidays,
Saidla said: ``Christmas is a terrible time to get a new pet.
There's too much going on, too many distractions and not enough
time to pay close attention to a new animal in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Hazards
</P>
<P>
   Even for a pet that is a well-established member of the
household, there are many new dangers in the house at holiday time
that can attract an animal and cause serious, costly illness. Dr.
Ann Hohenhaus, who heads the department of medicine at the Animal
Medical Center in New York, listed three major categories of
holiday hazards for pets: foods, plants, and seasonal decorations
and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   FOODS ``There's tempting food everywhere at Christmas,'' Dr.
Hohenhaus said, ``and dogs will check out anything they can get to:
turkey bones, the string used in cooking a turkey or rolled roast,
the onions and greasy juice in the pan, corn cobs and even peach
pits.''
</P>
<P>
   The bones can cause an upset stomach, constipation and painful
defecation. The cobs, pits and string can get stuck in the small
intestine, causing severe vomiting and requiring emergency surgery
to remove them. Too many onions can result in ruptured red blood
cells. And too much fat can cause pancreatitis, an inflammation of
the pancreas that can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Family members and guests should be discouraged from giving pets
scraps from the table, especially foods that contain a lot of fat.
And foods, whether served or wrapped as gifts, should never be left
unattended where a dog can get at them.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol can also be a problem for the family dog that finishes
the beer and egg nog left around by holiday guests. ``Pets get
drunk and have hangovers, just like we do,'' Dr. Hohenhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   SEASONAL ITEMS Almost every kind of trinket, even the cords from
strings of lights, can put a pet at risk. ``Cats and dogs,'' Dr.
Hohenhaus said, ``especially young ones, will bite into dangling
electrical cords because they think they're interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting shock from the low-power Christmas lights is
unlikely to severely harm or kill a pet but can inflict a nasty
burn on the lips and tongue, and in some cases it can cause fluid
to collect in the animal's lungs, which can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Stringy tinsel or ``icicles'' which, when eaten, can lodge in
the animal's gut, is a common problem. It can cut through the
intestine and require major surgery to remove it. Tinsel that
resembles bottle brushes is much safer. Cats also like to chew on
ribbon used to wrap packages, so it is best to pick up ribbon as
soon as packages are opened.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Schaer, a professor at the University of Florida
College of Veterinary Medicine, said an animal that suddenly loses
its appetite and vomits repeatedly should be seen by a veterinarian
as soon as possible. A delay in diagnosis and treatment of an
intestinal obstruction can result in a ruptured bowel, which can be
fatal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saidla said that cats and dogs have knocked over fully decorated
Christmas trees and eaten the balls and tinsel right off them. He
recommends that trees be placed in a wide enough base that is
tightly screwed to the trunk. For further security, screw an eye
hook in the ceiling and attach the tree to it with a strong cord or
wire.
</P>
<P>
   Any gift or toy with little parts that a pet can swallow can
also cause an intestinal blockage. Dr. Hohenhaus said she once had
to remove a whole set of ``Toy Story'' figurines from the intestine
of a Labrador. Pennies (zinc, not copper) and Monopoly pieces made
of zinc, when swallowed by a pet, can cause severe anemia and
necessitate a transfusion and surgery to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   Decorative candles should not be placed on low surfaces where a
cat might jump up and get its tail singed or knock over the candle
and start a fire.
</P>
<P>
   PLANTS Poinsettias _ at least, the kind sold at holiday times _
are not nearly as toxic as many people think (their sap can
irritate the stomach and eyes), but the berries of Jerusalem cherry
can cause severe gastrointestinal symptoms like abdominal pain,
vomiting and diarrhea. Other popular Christmas foliage, including
holly leaves and berries, mistletoe berries, boxwood and Japanese
yew, are also toxic to animals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other Common Risks
</P>
<P>
   Holidays notwithstanding, winter presents its own set of
problems for pets. Schaer urges that, outside the house, pets
should always be kept on a leash and away from roads to avoid
encounters with drunken drivers. Also, it is hard to see pets on
roadways during the many hours of dim light and darkness in winter.
In very cold weather, outdoor pets need a shelter, extra food and a
source of liquid water.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet-tasting antifreeze left in the yard or garage can be
deadly to pets, said Dr. Larry Thompson, toxicologist at the
Cornell veterinary college. Though it is more expensive than the
more commonly used highly toxic antifreeze made from ethylene
glycol, antifreeze containing propylene glycol is much safer for
dogs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the mouse problem. When rodents seek indoor warmth
and comfort in winter, homeowners are likely to put out
rodenticides, which can kill pets. These toxins are best placed out
of a pet's reach and used in limited amounts. It takes only a
teaspoonful to kill a mouse, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   If you suspect your pet has been poisoned or harmed by holiday
trimmings, call your vet without delay. There is also a pet hot
line run by the National Animal Poison Control Center at the
University of Illinois College of Veterinary Medicine. Calls to
(900) 680-0000 cost $20 for the first five minutes. Calls to (800)
548-2423 can be charged to a credit card at $30 per case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BIRDS-MONOGAMY-2T     12-21 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BIRDS-MONOGAMY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUCKOLDS CARD FOR CHICKS THAT AREN'T THEIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ga., Nev., Ill.)   (af)  
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cuckoldry is the fate of males the animal kingdom over. In study
after study of species after species, the idea that females are
naturally devoted to their one and only mates, even as the males
wander, has fallen to growing evidence that many of the world's
supposedly monogamous females are guilty of their share of
indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in spite of these findings, many biologists, especially male
biologists, held out hope that some males might be immune to this
kind of treatment by their mates _ particularly the exemplary,
hard-working fathers, as in the bird species known as the wattled
jacana (pronounced JAC-uh-nuh).
</P>
<P>
   But research reported Tuesday in the Proceedings of the Royal
Society shatters that dream. Although the diminutive male jacanas
do everything to care for the eggs and young of their raucous,
beefy females, these males are cuckolded. Under some circumstances,
the researchers found, males had a 74 percent chance of spending
three months raising another male's chick, a mistake in the
evolutionary race to perpetuate one's own genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about as bad as it can be for these guys,'' said Dr.
Peter Wrege, of Cornell University, who wrote the paper with fellow
behavioral ecologists Dr. Stephen Emlen, Jacob Gould Schurman
Professor at Cornell, and Dr. Mike Webster of the State University
of New York at Buffalo. ``A male stuck with doing all the parental
care should have a very high certainty of paternity, but in fact,
that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patricia Adair Gowaty, behavioral ecologist at the
University of Georgia at Athens, who described herself as having
made a cottage industry of writing about mating behavior from the
female perspective, called the jacanas ``absolutely fascinating,''
</P>
<P>
   ``The females are really in the catbird seat,'' Dr. Gowaty said.
``They seem to be getting whatever they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who were also affiliated with the Smithsonian
Tropical Research Institute when they did the work, studied the
jacanas on the Chagres River in Panama. These strikingly patterned
birds peck out a living in the plants that grow in and near the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Known as one of the most extreme examples of sex-role reversal,
the large, bullying jacana females spend their days jousting with
one another at the borders of their territories while harems of
meek males cower on their nests of eggs or chaperon chicks from
feeding site to feeding site.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say they expected to see little or no cuckoldry
because research suggests that males would evolve to work this hard
raising young only if they were certain they were raising their own
offspring. But DNA tests showed that jacana males often raise
another male's chicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a breakthrough,'' said Dr. Lewis W. Oring, a behavioral
ecologist at the University of Nevada at Reno. ``This kind of
demonstration requires years of very careful work, marking all the
individuals, getting tissue samples and doing the DNA analyses.''
</P>
<P>
   In other species, males appear to keep track of such things as
the amount of time the female is out of sight or strange males
lurking around the territory to assess the likelihood that the
female is mating with another male. And when males sense trouble,
they sometimes do not work quite so hard to feed the young, letting
their cheating female pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   Females, meanwhile, appear to go to great lengths to keep any
transgressions secret, sneaking copulations when their mate is not
around and even soliciting copulations from other males in their
mate's presence only to make a grand show of rejecting them.
</P>
<P>
   But, researchers say, for jacana males it should be easy to
surmise whether they are cuckolds. Researchers found that the males
that receive their clutch of four eggs from a female while other
males in the harem are also unfettered by caring for chicks and are
ready to mate, a potentially easy thing to assess, are at great
risk of being cuckolded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   A male was even more likely to be a cuckold if his female mated
with another male around the time that her main mate's eggs were
developing or she was laying them, a frequent, easily observed
occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a paradox,'' said Wrege. With little on the river to
block a male's view of the territories, and with matings being
exuberant events, with females and males calling out and bright
yellow wing tips flapping, Wrege said, ``He should be able to
assess the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But female jacanas appear immune to retribution. Despite all the
evidence jacana males have, they do not do what researchers predict
_ break eggs, abandon clutches, fly off to find a new mate. They do
not mutiny, researchers say, because they cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Even if one or more eggs in his nest may be another male's, if a
jacana destroys his nest or young, he loses any chance of raising
his own offspring. ``It's a Catch-22,'' said Dr. Stephen
Pruett-Jones, behavioral ecologist at the University of Chicago,
who described the new work as ``a great study.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the male apparently cannot distinguish his chicks from
another male's, ``He can't do anything except care for all the
young'' if he wants to raise any offspring, Dr. Pruett-Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important, the likelihood of finding a faithful mate is
slim. As Oring said: ``What does he gain by deserting her? He's
just going to get the same situation later. He's a slave, a sex
slave.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, while every male researcher interviewed focused on
the costs of being a cuckolded harem-mate, Dr. Gowaty suggested
that jacana males could be receiving many evolutionary benefits _
that harems might actually be good for males.
</P>
<P>
   In other mating systems, she explained, many and sometimes most
males never get the chance to mate. Among jacanas, hard-working
males are fought over in vicious battles between females and many
males get the chance to sire young.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefits for males might be that they get some
reproductive success in comparison to a situation where they might
not get any,'' Dr. Gowaty said.
</P>
<P>
   But whether good or bad for males, the current state of affairs
seems to be nothing less than invigorating for females. Presented
with the opportunity to step out, female jacanas have really run
with it, chalking up the most copulations per hour of any of the
world's 9,000 species of birds, often going from one mating to
another in a matter of minutes in noisy succession, researchers
say.
</P>
<P>
   What females receive from these matings, other than what their
triumphant squawking might suggest is the obvious, remains a
mystery. Emlen and colleagues are looking into several
possibilities, including the hypothesis that females may be trying
to mate often with the most genetically desirable males, forcing
males of lower genetic quality to raise eggs sired by the best of
the harem.
</P>
<P>
   For many male researchers (themselves all mammals, a group in
which males typically take little care of their young), the plight
of the jacana male seems at once implausible and pathetic, leading
to the question: how did they get into such a mess?
</P>
<P>
   Emlen and his colleagues suggest that jacana males most likely
evolved to be the sole caretakers of eggs and chicks under
conditions in which they had a high certainty that they were the
father of all the chicks in their nest. But once the males had
become the sole caretakers, they were trapped. They had lost the
leverage of withholding parental care because the females would
provide none, no matter what the males did.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some researchers have begun gathering data that
suggest that, rather than being a sex-role reversal, the
stay-at-the-nest male jacana represents the ancestral state of bird
families, before evolution changed things.
</P>
<P>
   If so, then perhaps those devoted-father jacanas are not the
grievous evolutionary anomaly they are depicted to be but something
much closer to nature's ancient, original state of things _ at
least for birds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
