<HEADLINE>
TIME TO SCRAP TIES THAT BIND
</HEADLINE>
 TIE-CHRISTMAS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dutch men have found reason to rejoice this season: The demise
of the necktie may be nigh. In a fit of new-found fashion freedom,
Prince Claus of the Netherlands recently ripped the cravat from his
throat during an African fashion show in Amsterdam, calling the tie
``a snake around my neck.''
</P>
<P>
   On television that evening, a news anchorman and sportscaster
followed suit, and the country has coined the phenomenon
``Claustrophilia'' to honor the brave prince.
</P>
<P>
   Will the tie fade from fashion? Probably knot. But in the spirit
of Claustrophilia, here are 10 pretty good reasons not to buy the
man in your life a tie for Christmas:
</P>
<P>
   1. Can you say ``booooring''?
</P>
<P>
   2. When was the last time you saw him wearing the other tie you
bought him?
</P>
<P>
   3. Why buy now when there's a patent pending on the tie-free
necktie? Simply clip on the knot and go!
</P>
<P>
   4. If ``Claustrophilia'' goes trans-Atlantic, ties might soon be
as passe as that Tickle Me Elmo you bought last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   5. Was Mark McGwire wearing one when he hit his 70th home run?
</P>
<P>
   6. As far as gifts go, Pokemons are so much more interesting. On
second thought ...
</P>
<P>
   7. How would you like it if the man in your life gave you
pantyhose?
</P>
<P>
   8. Way too easy to pick an ugly one.
</P>
<P>
   9. Increases possibility of choking on turkey bone during Xmas
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   10. Monica gave one to Bill.
</P>
<P>
   _ .MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
