<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0990 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PRINCEOFEGYPT-TE     12-21 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PRINCEOFEGYPT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRINCE' MAKES MIRACLES ROYALLY ENTERTAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using animation to tell the story of Moses renouncing worldly
goods and taking his place with his people, the Hebrews _ as in
``Prince of Egypt'' _ is potentially a good and a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   What's troublesome is that, in animation, the miraculous happens
as a matter of course. That is, unless you think animals walking on
their hind legs, speaking with a Brooklyn accent and wearing gloves
is normal.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the parting of the Red Sea sounds like the kind of
spectacle that screams for animation, the cartoon context robs a
miracle of some of its power. (And, yes, there is the fact that the
Red Sea parting from ``The Ten Commandments'' is a special effect
against which others are still judged.)
</P>
<P>
   But a brilliantly conceived sequence from ``Prince'' _ the
slaughter of Hebrew baby boys, illustrated with hieroglyphs _ shows
how animation can triumph over apparent limitations.
</P>
<P>
   It was less than a month ago that ``A Bug's Life'' raised the
stakes for an animated feature film. ``Prince'' seeks to elevate
that standard even higher by offering the first epic animated story
for an adult audience in more than 60 years. (One of the first was
the long-forgotten, lushly rendered 1939 adaptation of Jonathan
Swift's ``Gulliver's Travels.'')
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious ``Prince'' features two songs in the opening five
minutes _ as the infant Moses is launched to safety by his mother
and adopted by the Egyptian royal family _ to reassure audiences
and not immediately subvert the genre. None of the animals bursts
into song, and Moses' staff doesn't whisper comic-relief asides
into his ear. ``Prince'' is played as straight as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for a version of Moses more faithful to the King
James Version of the Bible _ parts of which are so beautiful they
can make you weep _ may be a bit put off to find a teen-age Moses
who seems more like a suburban kid, sporting a goatee like the guy
at Starbucks who doesn't even pretend to be interested when he's
taking your order. ``High-spirited'' and ``irrepressible,''
adjectives not found in the Old Testament, would best describe this
energetic kid, voiced by Val Kilmer. To make Moses more obviously
sympathetic, he's a plainspoken American with convivial
inflections. He's lovable.
</P>
<P>
   His family _ brother Rameses (Ralph Fiennes), father Pharaoh
(Patrick Stewart) and mother Queen (Helen Mirren) _ are all voiced
by Brits. So even their corniest sentiments are trilled loftily,
spoken with a hint of condescension.
</P>
<P>
   What you may find yourself craving in a story like this, which
doesn't fall short in the big moments, is the idiosyncrasy of an
actor's eyes. It's the one thing that can have as much impact in
drama as the delivery of a line. It's also one of the things that
animators haven't quite mastered. But we do get an unusual
assemblage of actors with distinctive voices. They include Michelle
Pfeiffer as the spunky woman Moses marries, Sandra Bullock as his
sister Miriam, as well as the warm-honey growl of Danny Glover and
the hiccuping, stop-and-stutter Jeff Goldblum.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks honcho and ``Prince'' executive producer Jeffrey
Katzenberg has married ambition to a crowd-pleaser mentality. He
reached out to so many religious leaders and advisers while making
``Prince'' that the movie often seems like it's running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Which, again, is good and bad _ ``Prince'' lacks the show-biz
peculiarity that infests movies such as ``Commandments.'' (Billy
Crystal's impersonation of Yul Brynner's misplaced zest is one of
the best pieces of film criticism I've ever heard.) It moves
quickly, too, as if afraid to bore the audience. It doesn't want to
offend anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Right down to the songs, which are filled with the bland uplift
of an Amy Grant collection. (She's on one of the three soundtrack
CDs, along with DC Talk, and a Whitney Houston and Mariah Carey
duet in which they wrestle ``If You Believe'' to a standstill. The
collection of performers crooning ``Prince'' songs is, at least, an
answer to a VH1 prayer.)
</P>
<P>
   As an animation feature, ``Prince'' is handsomely rendered and
is realized with a performer's need to entertain, the kind of thing
some might say contradicts the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   On its own terms, it's an achievement _ the deft sand and sky
tones have majesty. With the big moments _ the plagues that sweep
through Egypt _ the animators run with the opportunity to strut
their stuff and display a graphic vitality not normally seen in
cartoons. Delineating the power of the Old Testament must've been a
dream come true for them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Prince of Egypt''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Brenda Chapman, Steve Hickner, Simon Wells
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Val Kilmer, Ralph Fiennes
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ for Old Testament depictions, such as the death of
children, that may be upsetting for younger kids
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
