</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, December 22, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ With a $70 million national TV advertising campaign under
way to raise its profile among corporations and consumers, Dell
Computer Corp. is involved in a rare public dispute with the ad
agency who worked on the campaign initially. J. Walter Thompson
claims in a lawsuit that Dell owes it more than $6 million for its
aborted role, while a counter suit by Dell accuses the agency of
breach of contract, misusing Dell money, slander and other
shortcomings. It's unusual for an agency to sue a former client.
Dell hired BBD&AMP;O late last summer to complete the campagn.
(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ABP-CHARGE _ American Business Products said it hired SunTrust
Equitable Securities as an adviser for the sale of the company's
book manufacturing unit, which will account for a charge in the
fourth quarter. The move looks to be the first major step in a new
strategic plan for the Atlanta-based company. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SYNOVUS-FORTUNE _ Synovus Financial Corp. (NYSE: SNV) has been
named No. 1 in FORTUNE's second annual listing of the 100 Best
Companies to Work for in America. The list appears in the January
11, 1999 issue of FORTUNE. This is the second year that Synovus has
been included on the list, having been named the 11th Best Company
to Work for in America in January 1998. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-F22 _ ATLANTA _ Air Force approves a $761 million
initial contract for Lockheed Martin's F-22 fighter, a milestone
for the Marietta plant. The contract covers two production test
planes and down payments on six more. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LEVITZ _ ATLANTA _ Levitz Furniture will close more than a third
of its stores and cut 25 percent of its workers in an effort to
return to profitability. The nation's No. 3 furniture retailer has
been operating under Chapter 11 since September 1997. Closing 27
stores in eight states in the South and Midwest while leaving open
63 stores on the east and west coasts and Minneapolis. (Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CERULEAN _ A judge in Augusta rules in favor of the plaintiffs
in a class action lawsuit relating to the for-profit conversion of
Cerulean Cos.' Blue Cross Blue Shield of Georgia. The ruling will
require Cerulean to issue five shares to all eligible Georgia Blue
subscribers at the time of the for-profit conversion. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEVITZ-CUTBACKS _ Levitz Furniture Corp. plans to close more
than a third of its stores and cut 25 percent of its workers in an
effort to return the company to profitability, the company
announced Monday. The nation's No. 3 furniture retailer has been
operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since September
1997.
</P>
<P>
   (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SOCOMPANY _ Southern Co. will take a one-time charge to net
income in its 1998 fiscal year to reflect a decline in the value of
some of its South American investments. The company's Chile
subsiduary has been suffering from the Asian crisis because demand
from that region for copper mines, powered by Southern Co., is off.
(Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ This Christmas, it's clearer than ever that
Americans are the big winners in the global economy. But in the
rest of the world, the combination plunging energy revenue,
deflating commodity prices and brutal wage competition are driving
millions into dire conditions. The fantastic disparity between our
fortunes and theirs is disturbing. How long can the United States
continue to be the peaceful, prosperous island surrounded by so
much poverty and turmoil? (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(k, f) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta has the weight of history
behind its drive to land the Mustang museum there. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ How do you know when you need new
brakes? What is that squealing noise when stopping or the chirping
noises while still on the move? Why does the brake pedal vibrate
when pushing on it to stop? Sit back and let's take a crash course
on brakes. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ It's not clear when going to the movies
became part of the Christmas ritual, right up there with eggnog,
mistletoe and caroling. If movie reviews just don't do it for you
or the malls are too crowded, take a peek at this season's hottest
offerings on the Web. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ If holiday shopping has cut into your
budget for computer games, you needn't fear withdrawal. Many games
are available free for the downloading on the Internet. Some of
these games fall into the shareware category: You download them
free and then are expected to pay if you like and continue to use
the game. Many of the shareware games are full-blown versions,
while others have only a few episodes. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ ATLANTA _ This is the time of year when I get
pleading e-mails asking what to give a geek for the holidays.
Parents, overwhelmed by the computer wizardry of their kids, feel
helpless at a time like this. What I recommend are a couple of
books that'll cost you about $23 dollars, but are worth hundreds.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHMEDIA _ ATLANTA _ Don't be fooled that the box is sealed in
shiny plastic wrap. Many pieces of software, even from the biggest
companies, are far from finished when shipped to stores. Most
include at least some bug. Luckily, most common bugs are fixable.
The January issue of PC World has a story that can tell you all
about remedies. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ Apple Computer is giving it the old
college try _regaining its hold on higher education, that is.
(Haddad , Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ ATLANTA _ Under the heading of ``What Will They
Think of Next,'' we have for our examination and amusement today
the Cruise Cat from Cirque, a touchpad device aimed at the Internet
addict. The Cruise Cat is a modified touchpad-pointing device, a
thin little pad that connects to a serial port and does not cancel
out or confuse your mouse. It simply competes with it for your
attention. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ This was the year the Internet joined
CNN as one of the prime places we turn for breaking news. President
Clinton, his Gap-garbed intern and Kenneth Starr's tell-all of
their sloppy affair get most of the credit. The January issue of
Yahoo! Internet Life tells us why. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
