<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1060 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      12-21 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION RUNS THROUGH IT  
 DEATH FROM ABOVE  
 FIGHTING FOR A BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A river is like a highway, flowing through the landscape.
Unfortunately, according to a new study, it is also like a car,
polluting the air as it rolls along.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from the United States Geological Survey, in a study
of the South Platte River in Nebraska and Colorado, determined that
the river gives off large amounts of nitrous oxide, a gas that acts
as a catalyst in the destruction of ozone in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Like many rivers, the South Platte is rich in nitrates and
ammonium, from agricultural runoff and the discharges from sewage
treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   Microbes turn these nitrogen sources into nitrous oxide. The
researchers, whose work was published in the Internet edition of
Environmental Science and Technology, found that the river in many
places was supersaturated in nitrous oxide, with the result that
much of it entered the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists estimated that the amount of the gas emitted
along a 450-mile stretch of the river each year was equivalent to
that produced by all the worst sewage treatment plants in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   And although they said more studies were needed, they added that
if the South Platte is typical, as seems likely, rivers are a major
source of man-made nitrous oxide pollution. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs became extinct, so the common theory holds, when a
large asteroid or comet struck the Earth near the Yucatan 65
million years ago, drastically altering weather patterns worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Now, scientists led by a geologist from Brown University have
discovered evidence in South America of a lesser, and far more
recent, impact that they suspect caused local extinctions.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied glass fragments in sedimentary deposits
on coastal cliffs in southeastern Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The fragments, known as escorias, were first described in 1865,
but their origin had never been satisfactorily explained.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the journal Science, the scientists theorize that the
escorias were formed by the impact of an asteroid or comet, the
intense heat of the event fusing the sediment into glass. By dating
the fragments, which are found over a distance of 20 miles, the
researchers determined that the impact occurred 3.3 million years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just above the level of the glass is another level of sediment
that is notable for the absence of about three dozen species of
animals that are present in older deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists theorize that the impact caused enough of a
climate change in the region to wipe out those animals. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life is a rat race _ even for bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Consider feeding, for example, or more specifically, how
bacteria in seawater get nutrients. One might think that the ocean
is a homogeneous soup, with nutrients equally available to all. In
this view, bacteria would not have to compete for food.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by scientists in Denmark and Australia shows that
this is not the case. Food often becomes available at a distinct
source, as when a protozoan excretes organic matter. The nutrients
then quickly spread out into a tiny, spherical ``patch.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in the journal Science, found that
this sets off a microscopic feeding frenzy, with bacteria
clustering around the patch for a few minutes and then dispersing.
</P>
<P>
   So feeding, rather than being a passive activity, becomes a
competitive one. And the study showed that, for patches over a
certain size, bacteria that can move toward nutrients or other
chemicals (known as chemotactic bacteria) have a distinct advantage
over those that cannot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0271 </DOCNO>
