<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PLUTO-BOS &LR;      12-21 1682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLUTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANETARY DEMOTION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``. . .now telescopes and satellites
</P>
<P>
   and computer calculations
</P>
<P>
   say that Pluto may not be a planet at all
</P>
<P>
   creating great consternation.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   _ Christine Lavin, ``Planet X'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, a group of astronomers will turn their attention from
weighty issues such as the fate of the universe and the search for
new worlds to a question most people thought had been answered a
long time ago:
</P>
<P>
   What the heck is Pluto?
</P>
<P>
   Those who ring their buzzers and answer simply ``the ninth
planet'' are in agreement with history, tradition, and most
astronomy textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   But, it turns out, there is a heated debate going on among
astronomers right now as to whether, in addition to its traditional
status as a major planet, Pluto should be given a kind of ``dual
citizenship'' as an asteroid, or minor planet _ the diminutive
members of the sun's family.
</P>
<P>
   The issue will come to a head with the conclusion of a formal
vote by a division of the International Astronomical Union.
</P>
<P>
   Two coincidental facts have given rise to this brewing tempest
in terminology. First, just as the numbers on the calendar are
rapidly approaching the magical and much-anticipated rollover to
triple zeros, a sequential numbering system for the known asteroids
is about to reach the momentous number 10,000. The count, updated
monthly, stands at 9,826 and is growing by more than 100 a month,
and some astronomers would like to save that special number for a
truly special case _ Pluto. Second, a new family of objects in the
solar system has been discovered over the last six years _ a family
to which Pluto bears a striking resemblance.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of saving number 10,000 for Pluto, while still
retaining its major-planet name, originated with Brian Marsden, a
Cambridge, Mass. astronomer who heads the International
Astronomical Union's Central Bureau for Astronomical Telegrams,
where astronomical discoveries are first reported, and its Minor
Planet Center, which maintains a rapidly-growing catalog of such
objects.
</P>
<P>
   When the first member of the new family _ known as the Kuiper
Belt _ was discovered in 1992, Marsden promptly asked the
provocative question of whether Pluto should, instead, be thought
of as the first of this class, rather than just the last of the
nine major planets. Soon, he began to think about the
rapidly-approaching number 10,000, and the idea clicked. Why not
Pluto?
</P>
<P>
   This apparently arcane discussion among astronomers about how to
organize their catalogs _ who knew asteroids even had numbers? _
seems to have touched a nerve in some quarters. A newspaper article
on the subject two years ago even inspired singer/songwriter
Christine Lavin to compose a lengthy and detailed ballad on the
subject. (Among other things, the song claims the distinction of
being the first to include an internet address, complete with
``http colon slash slash,'' in its lyrics.) She performed it at
Harvard's Sanders Theater earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL; 
``. . .others say that Pluto is an asteroid
</P>
<P>
   in the sun's gravitational pull
</P>
<P>
   but if you ask Clyde Tombaugh
</P>
<P>
   he'll tell you `That's all bull'.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among those who've gotten riled up by all this talk of celestial
demotion is astronomer David Levy, discoverer of 31 comets and
author of several astronomy books including a biography of Clyde
Tombaugh, who discovered Pluto in 1930 and died last year at the
age of 90.
</P>
<P>
   Levy feels strongly that defending Pluto's planethood is a
matter of protecting Tombaugh's honor and his legacy. He also
admits to being somewhat bewildered by the whole debate. ``I think
that doing such a thing would be a dreadful disservice to
history,'' Levy said last week. ``Pluto, by any definition I know,
is a major planet. . . Why is our time being wasted on a question
like this?''
</P>
<P>
   Marsden, meanwhile, is feeling a bit stung by all the rancor his
simple suggestion seems to have stirred up, and is getting
increasingly defensive about it. It started out as just a way to
find special significance for a special number, and to recognize a
new class of objects that, in terms of the evolution and behavior
of the solar system, do have a lot in common. Marsden also points
out that the Kuiper Belt _ a family of large icy objects extending
out beyond the orbit of Neptune _ may include other
still-undiscovered objects that could be as big as Pluto itself, or
even bigger. What will we call them?
</P>
<P>
   (No problem, says Levy; call them planets, too.)
</P>
<P>
   This has been a tough year for Marsden. He was criticized by
some astronomers for his announcement last March that an asteroid
called XF 11 might, just possibly, strike Earth in 2028. Within 24
hours other astronomers found earlier pictures of it that proved
there would be no collision, and some commentators _ and colleagues
_ were harsh about his ``premature'' announcement. Marsden
maintains that, until those earlier observations came to light, a
collision early next century was possible, and that without the
announcement those earlier pictures might not have been found.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, he is not eager to start another fight.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion of ``dual citizenship'' for Pluto makes sense, he
maintains. For one thing, observers searching for distant
solar-system objects sometimes get confused by Pluto. Minor planets
are catalogued in a way that allows observers to determine quickly
whether what they're seeing matches a known object or might be a
something not seen before.
</P>
<P>
   The nine major planets, however, are not in that catalog, so
astronomers sometimes report sightings of Pluto to the Bureau,
thinking they have found something new. Including Pluto in the
catalog would help to avoid confusion, he says.
</P>
<P>
   To confuse things further, now there are two proposals under
consideration. Richard Binzel, an astronomer at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, has proposed starting a numbering scheme
just for the Kuiper Belt objects, of which 85 (counting Pluto) have
now been found. He is not opposed to starting the list with Pluto
as K-1. The rest could be numbered K-2 and so on in their order of
discovery. The suggestion seems to be gathering steam.
</P>
<P>
   Binzel is not intending this as a demotion, either. ``When we
study the planets, we study their surfaces, their atmospheres,
their satellites,'' he said in an interview last week. ``Pluto has
all these attributes. It has been known as the ninth planet for
nearly three generations, so Pluto's planetary status is well
established. It's certainly not a minor planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why give it a separate designation? ``I think we need a new
numbering system for the Kuiper Belt,'' Binzel said, because ``I
think they are so different from the minor planets that they should
be in their own catalog. They are different in origin, different in
makeup, they may be different in evolutionary history. Creating a
new catalog emphasizes our understanding of the structure of the
solar system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``. . .and now 20 astronomy textbooks
</P>
<P>
   refer to Pluto as less than a planet
</P>
<P>
   I guess if Pluto showed up at a planet convention
</P>
<P>
   the bouncer at the door might have to ban it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many astronomers have made such distinctions in their
college classes for years, and some astronomy textbooks now refer
to Pluto as less than a major planet. Even some elementary and
high-school texts now raise the question.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 1990 text called Understanding the Universe says
this: ``Astronomers question whether it deserves the title
`planet'. . . Pluto should perhaps be called a `minor planet' or
`planetesimal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   William Hartmann, an astronomer at the University of Arizona and
author of a college-level astronomy text, said, ``It's entirely a
semantic issue at this point. But I believe words are important,
because they shade our understanding of the arrangement of the
universe. If Pluto were discovered today, we would surely have just
given it a number like one of the Kuiper Belt objects.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says Binzel. ``I would point out that Pluto is 10
times the size of any other Kuiper Belt object. If Pluto were
discovered today, there would be a roar over whether to call it a
planet. It's not cut and dried.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one likely outcome of the debate is that in the process
of deciding what to do about Pluto and the Kuiper Belt, astronomers
may for the first time establish a formal definition of just what a
planet is. The leading candidate was somewhat arbitrarily
constructed, to ensure that we still end up with the traditional
nine:
</P>
<P>
   A planet is any object orbiting the sun whose diameter is
greater than 1,000 kilometers. Pluto, at 1,440 kilometers, is
comfortably in. Ceres, the largest asteroid at 600 kilometers, is
out. The status quo prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after months of discussion, three options are being voted
on by a dozen members of the International Astronomical Union's
division on Planetary System Sciences. The votes, being tabulated
by e-mail and due in before Christmas, will determine whether to
leave things as they are, give Pluto the number 10,000, or start a
new list.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A'hearn, an astronomer at the University of Maryland and
president of that division, says he is aiming at a consensus,
rather than deciding by a simple majority, so it's possible that
there will be further discussion and some modification of one of
these options. But one way or another, Pluto's fate is likely to be
sealed within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At which point Lavin, who confesses she got a D in the only
astronomy course she ever took, might have to add new lines to her
song.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Ph.D.'s all disagree
</P>
<P>
   we don't know yet who's wrong or who's right
</P>
<P>
   but wherever you are, whatever you are,
</P>
<P>
   Pluto, we know you're out there tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
