<HEADLINE>
MANAGING ASTHMA WITH AID OF COMPUTER  
 CHOOSING NONHAZARDOUS TOYS  
 SLEEPING LATE IS NO DISADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute has created a new
Web site to help physicians, researchers and asthma patients. The
Asthma Management Model System was started this month and is
designed to keep researchers, health-care professionals and the
public abreast of developments in asthma management.
</P>
<P>
   The system _ at www.nhlbi.nih.gov _ consists of Web-site links
for research, education and communications.
</P>
<P>
   The research link brings users to an interactive search engine
that ties them to scientific databases like Medline and Crisp. The
education link provides access to an electronic library,
patient-education programs and medical-education programs for
physicians. The communications link connects to the Web master,
provides access to asthma chat rooms and online forums, and invites
users to register for updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AMMS provides quick access to information to keep
clinicians on the cutting edge of asthma management,'' said Dr.
Claude Lenfant, the institute director.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimate that 15
million Americans have asthma, and 5 million to 6 million of those
are children. The National Institutes of Health reported that
asthma was the third-leading cause of hospitalization of children
under 15 and that asthma-related deaths among children 5 to 14 more
than doubled from 1979 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Nonhazardous Toys
</P>
<P>
   Last-minute holiday shoppers, take note: Many toys are not safe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the last year for which statistics are available,
Americans bought 2.6 billion toys and games. And according to
National Safe Kids, an organization for the prevention of childhood
injury, about 121,000 children ages 14 and under were treated in
emergency rooms for toy-related injuries. Nearly 60 percent were 4
or younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leading cause of toy-related deaths is choking,'' said
Mary Beth Ogle, coordinator of Tulsa Area Safe Kids at St. Francis
Hospital in Tulsa, Okla. ``Food items, small parts of toys, wheels
and buttons on clothes are all potential choking hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   Children under 3 are at the greatest risk of choking, because
they tend to put objects in their mouths. And boys of all ages
account for nearly two-thirds of toy-related injuries, including
strangulation, burns, poisoning, drowning and falls from riding
toys such as tricycles.
</P>
<P>
   National Safe Kids recommends these guidelines for selecting
age-appropriate toys:
</P>
<P>
   INFANTS Babies do not move much in their first months. But once
they learn to reach, roll over and sit up, they are at an increased
risk for choking. Recommended toys include activity quilts, stuffed
animals without button noses and eyes, bath toys, soft dolls, cloth
books and squeaky toys.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 1 TO 3 Toddlers are curious and intrepid, and they like to
climb, jump, throw and play rough-and-tumble games. Good toys
include books, blocks, fit-together toys, balls, pounding toys and
shape toys.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3 TO 5 Preschool children tend to think with their feet and
spend hours running around. Recommended indoor toys include
nontoxic art supplies, books, videos, musical instruments and large
blocks. Good outdoor toys are baseball tees, tricycles, slides and
swings.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 5 TO 9 These children are creative and more physically
active than younger children. Recommended toys include craft
materials, jump ropes, puppets, books and sports equipment.
Children 8 and older can begin to use electrical and
battery-operated toys.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9 TO 14 These children can enjoy team sports and games that
demand increased dexterity, such as pick-up sticks and marbles.
Good toys include computers, microscopes, board games and sports
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For Web information about toy safety, see the sites at
http://www.safekids.org and http://www.saintfrancis.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping Late Is No Disadvantage
</P>
<P>
   A new study has found that Benjamin Franklin might have had it
all wrong when he advised being early to bed and early to rise.
Night owls, British researchers have found, are just as likely as
early-rising larks to be healthy, wealthy and wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found no evidence that following Franklin's advice about
going to bed and getting up early was associated with any health,
socioeconomic or cognitive advantage,'' Dr. Catharine Gale and Dr.
Christopher Martyn reported in the current issue of The British
Medical Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 1,229 men and women over 65, the researchers, from
the Environmental Epidemiological Unit at Southampton General
Hospital, found that owls were wealthier than larks. At least they
showed the largest mean income, the greatest access to a car and
the most indoor toilets.
</P>
<P>
   In the group surveyed, 356 were identified by their classical
circadian rhythms as larks, in bed before 11 p.m. and up before 8
a.m., and 318 as owls, turning in after 11 p.m. and getting up
after 8 a.m. The other subjects fell between. The numbers of men
and women were about equal in each group, but the owls tended to be
younger than either the larks or the others in the study.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that early risers somehow got more out of the day
``grew out of the need to make the best use of daylight,'' Dr. Gale
said, adding that many people have to alter their lark-owl
inclinations because of job demands.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gale, a definite lark, and Martyn, an owl, worked around
their different body clocks in compiling the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to compromise in writing the paper,'' Dr. Gale said.
``I feel at my most creative in the early morning, so I wrote the
results section then. My colleague feels at his peak in the late
afternoon and evening, so everything we wrote together was usually
put together between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY BETH JACKSON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1737EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
