<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1094 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-21 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOY WHO HATES DECEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - He's an 8-year-old American boy who plays baseball and
basketball, watches ``The Simpsons'' on TV, roams the neighborhood
on his bicycle and hates December.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, his teacher in second grade asked her class to
write an essay about the holiday season. In big tilted letters
printed on blue-lined paper, his began, ``I hate December because I
don't celebrate Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   It continued, ``Why I don't celebrate Christmas is because I'm a
Muslim. And Muslims don't celebrate Christmas. Instead they
celebrate Eid.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true what he wrote. But these are only the religious
technicalities.
</P>
<P>
   For Osman Chaudhry, a child born in the United States of America
in the decade before the new millennium, there are larger, more
complicated, more pressing concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas is about toys,'' he wrote. ``Eid is about prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Osman's mother, Mumtaz, mailed me his essay. ``I am writing this
letter to draw attention to the stress that all the non-Christian
children have to go through during the Christmas season,'' she said
in a note.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I spoke to her, she added, ``When you are new to a
country, you want to become a part of that country and still to
maintain your heritage. This is understandable to an adult but very
difficult for a little boy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kids don't understand &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Osman's parents emigrated from Pakistan in 1985. They have three
older boys for whom Christmas wasn't a difficult adjustment,
perhaps because they're closer to one another in age and formed
their own small support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osman is mostly with his friends from school,'' Mrs. Chaudhry
says. ``He sees all the commercials on television. And sees what
goes on in the stores. It is everywhere, the toys and gifts and
emphasis on what people are buying.''
</P>
<P>
   She wrote a letter to Osman's teacher, hoping she might explain
Osman's religious background to the other children. And she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher understands,'' Osman tells me. ``But the kids
still don't.''
</P>
<P>
   For Muslims, the holiest month of their year, Ramadan, begins in
December. From dawn to dusk, believers drink no water and eat no
food. This year, for the first time, Osman will join his family in
the fast.
</P>
<P>
   The end of Ramadan is Eid ul-Fitr. Gifts are exchanged then.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these are most often small things,'' Mrs. Chaudhry says.
``We do not wish to have the gifts outweigh the religious parts.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Protecting a tradition &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She's trying to protect a tradition, to preserve an identity. To
keep the American lifestyle from rolling over her immigrant family
like a tidal wave, washing away the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all our boys to know our traditions,'' she says. ``I
want them to know they are a part of something that is important
and goes back a long time. I feel if I do not do this then the
things we believe in will die out. But who can blame a child for
wanting what other children have? What his friends have?''
</P>
<P>
   To make it a little easier on their boy, the Chaudhrys will give
Osman his Eid presents early this year. Even sacred traditions, it
seems, must be altered in small ways to keep from being lost _ at
least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   `'Christmas is about toys,'' Osman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And it's true.
</P>
<P>
   What he can't imagine _ not because he's a Muslim but because
he's an American boy _ is that it wasn't always true. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
