<HEADER>
A1099 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEIMAN-GALLERIES-AZR &LR;      12-21 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIMAN-GALLERIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLERIES OF NEIMAN MARCUS A HAVEN FOR BIG SPENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Got a million dollars burning a hole in your pocket
and looking for a place to plunk it down for something nifty for
Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   The Galleries of Neiman Marcus might have what you're looking
for.
</P>
<P>
   The upscale retailer is testing the prototype home and gift
store in three locations nationally, including Biltmore Fashion
Park in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix store opened Saturday, offering an array of fine
jewelry, china, crystal and collectibles for shoppers who want to
spend seven figures, or just a few dollars. The new store carries
some knockout price tags but doesn't want to be just a haven for
big spenders.
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly has the capacity to max out a credit card.
Among its most expensive items: seven colored diamonds selling for
$1.4 million, and an emerald and diamond necklace, earrings,
bracelet and ring priced at $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the low end: A $10 candle in a coconut shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really all things to all people here,'' said Steve
Magner, vice president of Galleries of Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus is known as a high-end retailer that sells
expensive apparel in large stores, many of them in the
100,000-square-foot range. But the company is looking to take
advantage of the popularity of its hard good sales and also move
into new markets.
</P>
<P>
   At 12,000 square feet, the Biltmore store is much smaller than
Neiman's location at Scottsdale Fashion Square. Neiman picked
Phoenix for a Galleries so it could judge the impact of its sales
on a mainline store.
</P>
<P>
   Three Galleries stores are planned initially. One has opened in
the Cleveland area and the third is scheduled to open in Seattle
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do what we want them to do we will build 15 to 25,''
Magner said. ``This may be the venue that Neiman Marcus may use to
brand itself internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The store was designed by architect Richard Gluckman, who has
several museums to his credit, including the Georgia O'Keeffe
Museum in Santa Fe. Magner said it's intended to stand apart from
the mainline store, with a contemporary look that includes a
sandstone floor and sandstone walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merchandise is jumping out at you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Galleries isn't likely to intimidate the Biltmore's
well-heeled shoppers. The mall already has a reputation for
exclusive retailers that the Galleries will bolster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will add a level of merchandise and
sophistication we certainly have at the mall, but they will be the
centerpiece of all that,'' said Gary Doyle, the mall's general
manager. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glen Creno can be reached at glen.creno(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
