<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GATECH-UNC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cremins hopes for redemption against UNC
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Kentucky humiliated Georgia Tech in front of 23,614 in the
Georgia Dome on Saturday, Yellow Jacket coach Bobby Cremins
couldn't explain Tech's embarrassing performance. ``What can I
say?'' Cremins asked after watching his team lose 80-39.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning the veteran coach subscribed to the theory that
pictures were better than words. ``I showed them the first 20
minutes of the game,'' he said. ``No more needed to be said.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets get a chance at redemption tonight when they play
No. 7 North Carolina at Alexander Memorial Coliseum. The Tar Heels
have started 12-1 in what was supposed to be a rebuilding year.
Still, Tech's biggest challenge might be overcoming its Saturday
performance, more than anything it'll see from North Carolina in
the conference opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all embarrassed, all of us,'' Cremins said. ``We know
we can play a lot better. Our shot selection was poor, and when we
did get good shots, they just wouldn't go down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kentucky made us look bad and stupid, and we're neither of
those,'' he said. ``Offensively we were out of sync. We didn't play
together as a team. It was like five people out there playing, but
not together.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, despite its record, isn't as good as last year's
edition. Coach Bill Guthridge has said on several occasions that
his Tar Heels are over-rated. Gone are All-America selections
Antawn Jamison and Vince Carter, along with guard Shammond
Williams. Ed Cota injured his thumb against Louisville and didn't
play Saturday against Dartmouth. Another starter, freshman Jason
Capel, missed the game because of an illness in his family.
</P>
<P>
   Both are expected to play against the Jackets, along with
freshman guard Ronald Curry, who is through with his football
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year North Carolina was one of the most exciting teams
I've seen in our league,'' Cremins said. ``Bill Guthridge did a
wonderful job in winning the national coach of the year award. He
had my vote. If you lose two like they did (in Jamison and Carter),
it's hard for them to be as good. But Ed Cota has always been one
of the best point guards in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins refused to get too down on his team. ``Saturday against
Kentucky was a great setting with 23,000 in the stands, and we
didn't live up to the setting. We were playing well, but our last
game was a very poor showing. Our overall record is 7-2, and I'm
very pleased with that. We split with Georgia and Kentucky, and
that wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blowouts occur,'' he said. ''They're not very pretty, but they
happen to everybody. Remember when Nebraska beat Florida in
football a few years ago? I've seen it happen to a lot of good
programs like Duke and North Carolina. But against Kentucky, we
played brainless.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
