<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major matchups dot this week's schedule
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's only December, but tonight's Duke-Kentucky
matchup could have the intensity of an NCAA tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   The second-ranked Blue Devils (10-1) and third-ranked Wildcats
(10-1) will meet in the regular season for the first time since the
1988-89 season in tonight's second game of the Jimmy V Classic in
East Rutherford, N.J. The teams have met in two of the most
thrilling games in NCAA tournament history, Duke winning 104-103 in
overtime on Christian Laettner's buzzer-beater in the 1992 East
Regional final and Kentucky rallying from a 17-point deficit to win
86-84 in the South Regional final last season.
</P>
<P>
   Duke and Kentucky have been college basketball's premier teams
of the 1990s, and the winner could stake its claim as the top team
of the decade. Duke has won two NCAA titles and has four Final Four
appearances during the '90s, while Kentucky has advanced to the
title game the last three years, winning in 1996 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   However, both coaches are playing down the significance of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this game was for a national championship or a regional
title, then it'd fit into whatever equation you're using to
determine the top team of the 90s,'' Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski
said. Kentucky's Tubby Smith said,'' Any one game is not going to
determine the history of Kentucky basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   TONIGHT
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina at Georgia Tech, 8 p.m., Fox SS.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky vs. Duke, 9 p.m., ESPN
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
