<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-ECAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia falls on tough times with back-to-back losses
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Ron Jirsa's 39th birthday was Monday. In his
second season as Georgia coach, he hasn't had much else to
celebrate lately, with his Bulldogs losing two overtime games in a
row. Georgia, which fell to 7-3 with Saturday's loss to Fresno
State, is a team desperately needing some sort of spark heading
into tonight's home game against East Carolina. The Dogs might find
some new life in freshman guards Terrence Edwards and Shawn Fields,
who will make their debuts against the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll both play,'' Jirsa said. ``We'll see how much, but
they'll both play.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the younger brother of former Georgia tailback Robert
Edwards, now with the New England Patriots of the NFL, and Fields
officially joined the Bulldogs before the 86-82 loss to Fresno
State. They practiced for the first time on Sunday, followed by two
sessions on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has labored through its first 10 games with only three
guards _ seniors G.G. Smith and Ray Harrison and freshman D.A.
Layne _ after Adrian Jones suffered a season-ending foot injury in
the preseason. Smith has averaged 34.9 minutes per game, and
Harrison has averaged 32.8 in the eight games he has finished. He
played just six minutes against West Virginia and didn't play
against Furman with a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   East Carolina arrives in Athens with plenty of confidence after
stunning South Carolina 56-34 Saturday in Columbia. In that game,
the Pirates took an early 8-0 lead but then went more than nine
minutes without a field goal. But the Gamecocks managed only 13
first-half points en route to their lowest-ever scoring total in
Frank McGuire Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the lowest field-goal total, field-goal percentage,
first-half scoring and total points for South Carolina under
sixth-year coach Eddie Fogler. The Pirates used a 20-2 second-half
run sparked by three consecutive 3-pointers by freshman guard
Brandon Hawkins, to put away the Gamecocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``(East Carolina) plays good defense, and they play a lot of
people,'' Jirsa said. ``They play good defense, both man to man and
in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia struggled at East Carolina a year ago, needing forward
Badi Oliver's free throw with no time left for a 55-54 victory.
After Harrison tied the game with 35 seconds left, the Pirates'
Raphael Edwards missed a jumper. Georgia took over on an
alternate-possession jump ball. Oliver caught a full-court pass
from Larry Brown with 1.8 seconds left and was fouled by Edwards as
he turned to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
