</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons miss is Arizona's gain
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he held his breath early in the second round of the '97
draft, Arizona Cardinals vice president for player personnel Bob
Ferguson wondered if he would ever see a scene like the one that
transpired in Sun Devil Stadium on Sunday. Ferguson and Cardinals
coach Vince Tobin desperately wanted quarterback Jake ``The Snake''
Plummer, the local hero from Arizona State, in the second round.
With only the journeyman Kent Graham to develop at quarterback, the
Cardinals needed a savior, and preferably a box-office draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure Dan (Reeves) would take him in Atlanta
because the feeling was he wanted a young guy behind Chris Chandler
at the time,'' Ferguson recalled. ``But then the Falcons passed
twice on Plummer (taking defensive lineman Nathan Davis and
tailback Byron Hanspard) in the round, . . . and he was just
sitting there for us. Sometimes you've got to be more lucky than
good. Sometimes things just work out.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons had selected Plummer _ and, apparently, there was
no sentiment for him in the war room _ he'd still be sitting behind
Chandler. In Arizona, he got the chance to play, and Monday he
earned a four-year contract extension worth about $6 million per
year. The new contract came just a day after he authored a
brilliant last-minute rally to get the Cards to the brink of their
first postseason berth since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (contract) already was agreed to before Sunday's game,''
said Plummer, whose cool demeanor is often likened to that of Joe
Montana, ``but bringing us back like that, . . . I hope it showed
management here and the fans what they can expect.''
</P>
<P>
   No new Leaf
</P>
<P>
   San Diego veterans have answered the question why Chargers
lame-duck coach June Jones hasn't gone back to Ryan Leaf for a few
late-season starts. According to several players, the first-rounder
has been missing meetings and frequently falling asleep in the
sessions he's attended since being benched in favor or Craig
Whelihan.
</P>
<P>
   On the line
</P>
<P>
   If you still need convincing that the New York Jets' Bill
Parcells is the most brilliant coach of this era or that assistant
head coach Bill Belichick has one of the NFL's best defensive
minds, look no further than the makeshift front four the team used
to capture the AFC East. Left end Rick Lyle flopped in an earlier
stint with the Cleveland Browns and had just three sacks entering
the season. Right end Anthony Pleasant was a solid player early in
his career, but injuries marred his last two seasons, and he had a
half-sack for Atlanta in '97. Right tackle Ernie Logan personifies
the term journeyman, having played for four teams in seven seasons.
The left tackle is former Georgia star Jason Ferguson, who fell all
the way to the seventh round of the '97 draft after testing
positive for marijuana at that year's combine workouts. Exclusive
of incentives and bonuses, the four earn an aggregate $1.136
million in base salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Toe jam
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas training staff has informed coach Chan Gailey that
Deion Sanders is only a longshot to be able to play in the team's
first playoff game. Sanders continues to rehabilitate a sprained
big toe and still can't drive off his left foot. The feeling now is
that there is ligament damage. Sanders attempted to practice last
Wednesday and lasted only one play.
</P>
<P>
   Without a Hitch
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota defensive coordinator Foge Fazio went into this year's
draft hoping to select former Vanderbilt cornerback Corey Chavous
in the first round to replace the departed Dewayne Washington.
Instead the Vikings used their No. 1 pick on wideout Randy Moss and
traded for New England corner Jimmy Hitchcock. Like most
coordinators in the NFL, Fazio was skeptical of Hitchcock, who had
been inconsistent in three seasons with the Patriots and was
rendered expendable with the first-round addition of Tebucky Jones.
There are no such doubts now about Hitchcock. He has seven
interceptions and has returned three of them for touchdowns. ``He's
not blessed with tremendous ability,'' Fazio said Monday, ``but
Jimmy is a hard worker who studies tape like crazy and has turned
himself into a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Zebra time
</P>
<P>
   As commissioner Paul Tagliabue and aides continued to seek a
viable instant-replay system that does not include a coach's
challenge to trigger a review, game officials suffered through
another tough weekend. Buffalo's comeback bid against the Jets
ended on an interception by strong safety Victor Green that clearly
hit the ground. Bengals cornerback Artrell Hawkins clearly landed
out of bounds while making an interception of a desperation heave
by Pittsburgh's Mike Tomczak. The co-chairmen of the competition
committee, Green Bay coach Mike Holmgren and Tampa Bay GM Rich
McKay, seem ready to lobby for replay at the March owners meetings,
but they prefer a system that is not based on the coach making a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tops
</P>
<P>
   Plummer shares the honor with teammate Frank Sanders, who had 10
catches for 138 yards. The former Auburn wideout now has career
bests in catches (81) and receiving yards (1,039). Of his 10
catches Sunday, seven were for first downs, and three times he
converted third-and-long situations.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive best
</P>
<P>
   New England's Lawyer Milloy, arguably the best young strong
safety in the league, had 14 tackles and two pressures of Steve
Young in the Patriots' victory over San Francisco. Playing close to
the line of scrimmage, Milloy did a solid job of ``spying'' on
Young and rendered the bootleg play ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Truly special
</P>
<P>
   Dallas tight end Eric Bjornson, who doubles as the holder on
placement tries, ran seven yards for a touchdown on a fake
field-goal try. The first rushing attempt of Bjornson's four-year
career was the game's lone touchdown and secured the NFC East title
for the slumping Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing . . . .
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's game, Chicago first-year tailback James
Allen had carried just 13 times for 47 yards in his career. In the
Bears' 24-3 victory over Baltimore, the former Oklahoma standout
replaced an injured Edgar Bennett and rushed for 163 yards _ 135 of
them by halftime _ on 23 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Stat stuff
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Gary Anderson, who hasn't missed a kick all season,
has 153 points. That's two points more than the hapless
Philadelphia Eagles have scored as a team.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate for the worst decision of the year: Eagles quarterback
Bobby Hoying rejected a four-year, $20 million contract offer in
training camp. He might never see that kind of money again. . . .
Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie has earned more than $2.3 million
in bonuses since replacing Rob Johnson as the Bills starter. . . .
Green Bay tailback Dorsey Levens has regained much of his cutting
ability, but he still can't explode as well as he did before
breaking his ankle. . . . Despite the solid late-season performance
of Kent Graham, the Giants still want to add a veteran quarterback
during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's John Randle, who played at least three snaps at each
of the four defensive line positions, on Jacksonville rookie
quarterback Jonathan Quinn: ``After we hit him in the head a few
times, he probably thought he was seeing double. But, nah, that was
just me playing all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
