<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVITZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Levitz eliminating more jobs, closing stores
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Levitz Furniture Corp. is making another round of job
cuts and store closings as it tries to return to profitability. The
company announced Monday it will shut down more than a third of its
stores and cut 25 percent of its workers. About 1,000 of the
company's 4,000 workers will lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Levitz pulled out of the metro Atlanta market when it closed six
stores in February. The Boca Raton, Fla.-based company has been
operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since September
1997. The first wave of cuts closed 18 stores and laid off 300
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's No. 2 furniture retailer will close 27 more stores
in eight states in the South and Midwest while leaving open 63
stores on the east and west coasts and Minneapolis, said Edward L.
Grund, who became the company's chairman and chief executive in
November. Stores are being closed in Florida, Texas, Maryland,
Virginia, Indiana, Louisiana, Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Levitz also plans to consolidate its 65 warehousing operations
into 17 buildings. The company will use the proceeds from the sale
of closed stores, warehouses and inventory to reduce debt,
refurbish some existing stores and open new ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has no plans to reenter the competitive metro
Atlanta market. ``Our share of the market was too fragmented,''
said Mike McCreery, senior vice president and chief financial
officer. ``We're focusing on markets where we have a significant
presence that's profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitz has battled declining sales in recent years as a flood of
new competitors courted consumers with store formats that resembled
home interiors, rather than warehouses. As a result, the company
plans to open seven ``model'' stores that feature dining rooms and
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
