<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYPHOTOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO HAVE A PICTURE-PERFECT HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MEDA KESSLER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Admit it. Somewhere, there is a shoe box or two crammed with
blurry, overexposed holiday memories.
</P>
<P>
   You hang on to them, because, well, you can't just throw away
family photographs; they mean so much. So let's take a look at
them, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, here's one of your 5-year-old putting tinsel on the tree.
Except that she's so far away, you can't make her out from the
family dog _ which you think is also in the photo _ maybe.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another favorite of your husband opening up his
now-prized telescope you got for him a few years back. Except that
all you can see is the top of his forehead. Whoops.
</P>
<P>
   Oooh. And here's one of everyone standing rather stiffly in the
living room. My, doesn't Grandpa look happy to be there?
</P>
<P>
   OK. Stash these away. Now let's figure out how to take quality
photos that will actually make it into a real photo album. Or
frame. Or make a Christmas card for next year.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTS, CAMERAS, BATTERIES?
</P>
<P>
   These tips are addressed to those who use point-and-shoot
cameras. The manufacturers of these little gems have really worked
to make them quite user-friendly, but they are not totally
idiot-proof. There's always a way to put that finger in front of
the lens if you try hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   1. Stock up on film and batteries. It's very disheartening to
miss out on a great shot because a weak battery prevents the flash
from going off or you used the last roll on those carolers who
stopped by on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   2. Practice. If you've never used a camera before, take a few
practice rolls to see how it works, especially if you're using the
flash. Actually figure out which button you press to take the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   3. Delegate. If you've decided that it's physically impossible
for you to take a good photo, hand the camera off to someone else,
maybe one of the older kids home from college or your
brother-in-law. Arrange this ahead of time and have on hand a small
bag to hold film, batteries and anything else that person might
need. This also ensures that you might actually be in a few photos
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   SAY CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   1. Don't be afraid to get close to your subjects. These cameras
allow you to move in nice and tight _ about two to three feet _
without the flash overexposing the skin tones. Tighter shots mean
less clutter in the background.
</P>
<P>
   2. Try to avoid posed photos. The tree sparkles, the presents
are unwrapped and everyone is having a great time. Why ruin the
mood by insisting that everyone stop what they are doing to stare
uncomfortably in the camera? If you do want posed photos, set up a
small area in your home strictly for photo purposes. Pick out a
comfy chair and pull it away from the wall a bit to avoid harsh
flash shadows. Remove paintings or other wall objects. Drape the
chair with a neutral-colored piece of cloth so as not to clash with
your subjects' clothing. This will be the perfect place to get a
shot of the in-laws or of Grandma holding the new baby.
</P>
<P>
   3. Avoid big group shots. These little cameras just are not
meant for photographing large numbers of people. If you insist on
getting photos of everyone, try breaking them up in small groups.
(See No. 2.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Be aware of your surroundings. A perfect photo can be ruined
by that potted plant growing out of someone's head or those dirty
dishes stacked up in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   5. Be creative. Hand out disposable cameras to everyone and let
them chronicle the holiday events with their own eye. It's always
fun to see things from a kid's-eye view. Photograph everything.
There's more to Christmas than just unwrapping gifts. Have the
camera handy during the holiday dinner and the kids' nap time. Take
pictures of yourselves. Hold the camera out an arm's length away
and shoot fun couples snapshots of you and your new
daughter-in-law, or even you and the cat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
