<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND22-COX     12-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta mag's top nuts: Mayor, Mitch
 &HT;    By Don O' Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At a time of year when many magazines are trotting out
their best and worst lists, Atlanta ($3.50) has launched its first
Golden Goober Awards. There are no ``bests'' here. The magazine
proudly announces that it has compiled the pick of the crop of
1998's ``rogues, rascals, goofballs, doofuses, yahoos and clowns.''
An obvious Golden Goober goes to the U.S. Department of
Transportation for warning airlines that they must create
peanut-free buffer zones around passengers who are allergic to the
legume. Other notable recipients: Mayor Bill Campbell (concerning
that matter of computing crime statistics), Mitch Skandalakis (for
negative campaign ads), Ted Turner (for his overreaction to the
Tailwind scandal) and Ralph David Abernathy III (for his brushes
with the law and sloppy bookkeeping).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The year in Time: By now, we already know that President
Clinton and Kenneth Starr are Time's ($3.95) Men of the Year. But
the magazine also offers entertaining features on winners and
losers of 1998 as well as a fine profile of Mark McGwire. Winners
include Hillary Rodham Clinton, Jesse ``the Mind'' Ventura, Adam
Sandler and Rick Schroder. And there are no surprises on the losers
list: Clinton, ``Godzilla'' and Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beyond Clinton: Newsweek ($3.50) is packed with news of the
impeachment and impending Senate trial, but the magazine also has
an intriguing interview by author Doris Kearns Goodwin with Hillary
Clinton's former aide Lisa Caputo about the first lady's future.
Caputo predicts Mrs. Clinton will follow Eleanor Roosevelt's
example and enjoy a productive public life for years to come. And,
in a look at the year in literature, Malcolm Jones revisits the
debate over Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full.'' In response to charges
by Norman Mailer and John Updike that the novel was
``entertainment,'' not ``literature,'' Wolfe wonders why ``these
old men are rising off their pallets to condemn my book?'' The
answer, he says with his usual modesty, is ``because my book has
cast a very big shadow, and people like Mailer and Updike find
themselves in the dark. And what do you do when you find yourself
in the dark? You whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Wolfe, Entertainment Weekly ($3.50) anoints the
Atlanta-based novel the No. 1 book of the year in its Best &AMP; Worst
Issue. The worst book? ``Message in a Bottle'' by Nicholas Sparks,
a tear-jerker that is headed for the big screen with Kevin Costner
and Paul Newman. The magazine's picks for best and worst movies are
``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Simon Birch,'' respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winter writing: In a literary-heavy New Yorker ($3.95),
authors Richard Ford, Annie Proulx and others provide stories to
help the winter nights seem shorter. In ``The Blood Bay,'' Proulx
recasts an old Irish folktale in the plains of Wyoming during the
winter of 1886-87; filmmaker Ethan Coen recounts a man's encounter
with a large deer on a snowy road in ``The Buck Stops Here''; and
Ken Kesey's ``Otto the Bloody'' depicts New Year's Eve in 999.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Luxe ($8), a slick, very upscale marketing
magazine, profiles Virgin Group Chairman Richard Branson. The
founder of Virgin Records and Virgin Airlines operates with the
philosophy that if he wants it, then others will, too. . . .
Jezebel ($3.95), the Atlanta-based magazine, spotlights Southern
actress Lori Petty on the eve of her soon-to-be-released film
``Club Land.'' Also featured are ``Five Master Bedrooms to Die
For'' and a behind-the-scenes look at the Atlanta Channel on local
television.
</P>
<P>
   Don O' Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
