<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILWIND22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV Guide on CNN's Operation Tailwind
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first installment of a detailed four-part story in
TV Guide on CNN's Operation Tailwind fiasco has very little
significant new information. The report, which will continue over
the next three weeks, delves into the background of CNN's report,
which alleged that U.S. military forces used sarin nerve gas in
Laos in 1970. The report aired in June and was retracted in July,
and several lawsuits by veterans are pending against CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Part 1 of the report obviously relies heavily on April Oliver,
the former CNN producer who was fired for her role in the ``Valley
of Death'' report, but who still maintains it was true. (CNN has
never said the story was false.) TV Guide even reports Oliver's CNN
salary: $65,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide's report will probably be the most exhaustive on CNN
and Tailwind, at least until the first book is written, but it
follows by several months reports in Brill's Content and American
Journalism Review and does not, in Part 1, add anything that
changes what is already on the public record.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to talk to TV Guide about what is coming in parts 2, 3
and 4 were rebuffed. Editor Steve Reddicliffe was unavailable;
writer Mary Murphy was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
