<HEADER>
A1157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER22-COX     12-21 0222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report: TV dramas shortchange women
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study of TV dramas from 1994 to 1997 finds that ``despite
incremental changes, men still outnumber women (and) key minority
populations are chronically under-represented,'' with Hispanics the
most under-represented group on television. The study, commissioned
by the Screen Actors Guild, was conducted by George Gerbner of the
Annenberg School of Communications. It looked at characters on
prime-time dramas and daytime soaps.
</P>
<P>
   Among Gerbner's findings:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Men outnumber women two to one.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Male African-American characters have increased until they
outnumber their percentage in the actual population; female
African-American characters still lag.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Low-income wage earners are virtually invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``There has been a decline in the number of characters with
disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Women age faster than men, and as they age they become more
evil.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Seniors of both genders are greatly under-represented and
seem to be vanishing instead of increasing as (they are) in real
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerbner concludes: ``Television is frozen in a time warp of
obsolete and damaging representations.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
