<HEADER>
A1171 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-US-1222-COX     12-21 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-US-1222-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRAQ DOWNPLAYS DAMAGE FROM AIRSTRIKES; PROCLAIMS ITS STRENGTH,
EVEN WITH SADDAM'S REGIME ON EDGE
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ Even before the U.S. and British military airstrikes
began last week, there were signs that Saddam Hussein's regime was
edgy about its self preservation. Now that the bombing is over,
officials are emphasizing their strength.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz Monday announced figures for
military casualties of the airstrikes, stating that 62 soldiers
were killed -- 38 of Saddam elite Republican Guard -- and 180
wounded. He said that U.S. and British missiles largely hit empty
barracks that will be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, U.S. Marine Corps Gen. Anthony Zinni said U.S.
and British bombs and missiles struck 85 of the 100 targets
attacked and 74 were destroyed -- including barracks and command
structures of Saddam's Republican Guards around the country --
before strikes were halted early Sunday, Iraq time.
</P>
<P>
   Zinni told reporters at a Pentagon briefing that among the
targets hit was Saddam's Baath Party headquarters, where Iraqi
officials earlier this month refused to grant full access by U.N.
weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our friends in the region and others clearly look at
what happened to Iraq and realize that Saddam suffered a defeat,''
Zinni said when asked about Baghdad's claim that Saddam was the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair agreed in London that the
airstrikes have set back parts of Iraq's ``military infrastructure
several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz's announcement, however, attempt to show just the opposite:
That the Iraqi regime was still strong despite the barrage of more
than 400 missiles fired by U.S. and British forces.
</P>
<P>
   American President Bill Clinton has stated that he wants to end
the 20-year-reign of Hussein. Though U.S. officials said the four
days of airstrikes were aimed at setting back Hussein's weapons
operation, it is widely believed that they also hope to soften him
up for a coup from within his government or a rebellion from his
people.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz labeled these goals ``heinous intentions'' because the U.S.
has no business in internal Iraqi affairs. He said they will not
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought foolishly that when they sent a few hundred
missiles against Iraq, the people of Iraq would uprise against
their leadership. This is fantasy. This is Rambo-like fantasies,''
Aziz said. ``The Iraqi people strongly, genuinely support their
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hussein's regime has survived numerous larger calamities
in the past, from the 8-year war with Iran to its defeat in the
Gulf War in 1991. Assessing the impact of these recent airstrikes
will take more time.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure, observers say: From extra soldiers on the
streets to loyalty pronouncements in the press to a recent shake-up
of his military, Hussein and his allies are being extra careful.
What's not at all clear is whether these precautions are needed to
meet any threat or just Hussein's way of being cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Even in good times, Hussein's whereabouts are rarely known, he
makes few public appearances and only sparingly meets with foreign
officials -- who are often driven to remote, unknown destinations,
for the encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be in a small, closed society, you always feel in danger,''
said one foreign observer. ``The recent events have shaken the
(Hussein) family and the inner circle.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few reliable reports about damage from the bombings
and no way to confirm Aziz's casualty figures. Iraqis, who have
always kept a close eye on foreign journalists, is naturally even
more restrictive amid concern that its attackers not pick up
newspapers and read details of the condition of their targets.
</P>
<P>
   But, there were signs that even before the bombing Hussein was
seeking to tighten his grip on his own people.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the first attacks, Hussein divided the military
control of the country among four trusted allies and did so in a
public way. While the regime said the changes were needed to resist
the coming missile attacks, the move was likely done for internal
control.
</P>
<P>
   As Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan said, Iraq believes
the United States is trying to disrupt communications between
different areas of the country, such as the largely Shiite Muslim
south and the predominantly Sunni Muslim north of the country.
</P>
<P>
   By giving trusted military commanders a degree of autonomy in
each region, it makes it easier for them to crush any rebels who
try to take advantage of a damaged communications network.
</P>
<P>
   The move was announced publicly and two of the leaders made
public statements of loyalty to Hussein, perhaps to show that they
were no threat to supersede his authority in their regions.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Associated Press reported, based on information from
exiled Iraqi opposition leaders, that Hussein's cousin, a military
commander, recently executed several officers for disobeying
orders. The officers were in the southern region, the home of an
active opposition from Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said that Iraqi's ``laugh'' at the idea that they will rise
up against their president.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPY-NOVELS-ART-2NDTAK     12-21 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPY-NOVELS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: accounting mode.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most affected by the cooler market are the second-tier authors
who were writing in the genre, said Romanos of Simon &AMP; Schuster.
The well-known authors, he said, had a tougher time keeping their
audience, while ``the next level, the up-and-coming spy fiction,
began to shrink dramatically, so there's hardly any more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger thriller writers like Daniel Silva, 37, author of ``The
Unlikely Spy'' and ``The Mark of the Assassin,'' draw inspiration
from World War II, but ``going back to the Cold War would be a
little strange,'' he said. ``Instinctively it doesn't feel right.
There's not enough distance and drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Le Carre, a former British intelligence officer whose real name
is David Cornwell, can be viewed as a case study of shifting to new
themes while tinkering with publishing relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The author left his publisher of 20 years, Alfred A. Knopf,
changed literary agents and is poised to publish a new book,
``Single &AMP; Single,'' that continues his movement away from
espionage themes and the prosaic world of his weary and brooding
spy, George Smiley.
</P>
<P>
   His last book, ``The Tailor of Panama,'' involved an elaborate
plot to void the Panama Canal Treaties. His base of readers has
eroded and his past sales figured into his last advance from Simon
&AMP; Schuster, which dropped to $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Scribner, where marketing executives have a one-word view of
Cold War spy fiction (``Done'') the publishers are positioning le
Carre to reach a new generation of readers. Scribner is planning to
print 300,000 copies of the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Wark, a University of Toronto history professor who
specializes in the study of intelligence services and spy fiction,
said the espionage genre still had life but was ``going through a
difficult period when clearly new settings or scenes are
required.''
</P>
<P>
   In Search of a New Lode
</P>
<P>
   Instead of new spy settings, though, writers are switching to
new genres with the intrigue of politics or police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wait for the Cold War to be quaint as a little
Napoleonic war,'' said Charles McCarry, a former CIA intelligence
officer who has moved from novels about spies to books about
political intrigue like his best-selling ``Lucky Bastard.'' ``After
doing this for almost 30 years,'' McCarry said, ``what happens is
that you live your experience and eventually it runs out. So you
find another vein.''
</P>
<P>
   A contrarian view of the Cold War comes from Follett, who with
his departure this month from Crown for Dutton, an imprint of
Penguin Putnam, intends to write a historical novel based on a
failed launching of an American satellite amid Cold War tensions in
1958. He is careful, however, to correct any typecasting of the
book as a Cold War novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say it's a Cold War story,'' Follett said, ``people
will think it has a character like Smiley and involves a KGB person
and an FBI agent who are at loggerheads. And it isn't like that at
all. None of the principal characters are Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   Follett noted that he had avoided the spy genre in his last two
novels, the latter a contemporary thriller called ``The Hammer of
Eden,'' which centers on aging hippie eco-terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the golden age of the spy story is definitely
over,'' Follett said. ``But that doesn't mean that there aren't
going to be any good ones written. In order to do so, I've had to
set my story in 1958. I don't think it would work in 1998. We're
not afraid of the Russians anymore. You need someone to be afraid
of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
