<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-INMAN-BOS &LR;      12-21 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-INMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CHAIR SAYS SHE'LL STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Unhappy over Governor Cellucci's attempt to seize
control of the Republican State Committee, Chairwoman Jean Inman
Monday told Cellucci she would not seek another term as party
chief.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in another move that could have political
ramifications, Cellucci has settled on a career police officer from
New York City to be his secretary of public safety. Sources say
Cellucci will tap Jane Perlov, commanding officer of the Queens
Detective Borough, for that post.
</P>
<P>
   But that selection could create some ill will among both
Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator James Jajuga, a Democrat from Methuen, had hoped
for the job, as had outgoing Norfolk County District Attorney
Jeffrey A. Locke, the son of former Senate Republican Leader David
Locke.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Cellucci's move to quietly install his own operatives
at the state committee didn't work as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Inman, an Avon businesswoman, was upset Cellucci planned to
replace her six-member state committee staff with his own
operatives.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Cellucci had told Inman he wanted John
Brockelman, who served as his deputy campaign manager in the 1998
campaign, to take over operational responsibilities from Mark
DeCourcey, the committee's current executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sad day for me,'' said Inman. ``I wanted to stay on as
chairman, but as things changed, I reconsidered. I was comfortable
with the team we had here that worked so hard during the last
election cycle. They wanted to replace everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the news that Inman would not seek another two-year term
as chairwoman seemed to surprise the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she did a good job in the most recent (election)
cycle, and I was looking for a little stability with a little new
blood as a way to do an even better job in the 2000 election
cycle,'' Cellucci said. ``I think it would have been nice if Jean
had continued, but that's her decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One source close to Cellucci said two possible replacements were
being considered: Plymouth County Sheriff Peter Forman or state
Senator Richard Tisei of Wakefield. Both have years of experience
in Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   But another source said state committee members, unhappy over
Cellucci's attempt to take over the committee, might sponsor a
candidate of their own for the party's top post.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are unhappy all around,'' the source said. ``It all
depends on whether they turn that unhappiness into action by
fielding an alternative candidate.'' The 80-member state committee
is slated to meet Jan. 14 to chose a chairman for the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her decision not to run again, Inman said she remained a
strong supporter of Cellucci. ``I fully support the governor,''
Inman said. ``One of the things I am most proud of is how we pulled
the party together after an energetic primary and elected a
Republican governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Inman Monday won praise from Jim Rappaport, her predecessor as
Republican Party chairman. ``She came through in the clutch,'' said
Rappaport. ``I think she has been a very able chairwoman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
