<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGINEST SAYS HE'S BACK IN SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He has played football, a most violent game,
ever since he can remember, and has endured hits, collisions, and
pain unfathomable to the average Joe. He has conquered them and
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   But for weeks this season, the Patriots' Willie McGinest has
been derailed.
</P>
<P>
   His chiseled 6-foot-5-inch, 270-pound frame has been left on the
sideline with an injury to his upper groin that has caused him
excruciating pain.
</P>
<P>
   For one who makes his living chasing quarterbacks with quick
moves, cuts, and sudden bursts _ the reason he is paid $5 million
annually _ those acts became impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Game after game went by. Twice McGinest tried to return and
twice his body failed him. The frustration mounted. Then he heard
whispers from people who thought he wasn't tough enough to get back
on the field, and those comments felt like a knife through his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday McGinest finally seemed to be feeling relief and the
hope that his injury would no longer be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Though he never said, ``I'm playing Sunday vs. the Jets,'' he
did smile as he said, ``I'm going to surprise you (the media).'' He
added, ``I feel great. I feel like I'm full-speed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was able to run full tilt Monday, a day after
watching his teammates cut the legs out from under the surging San
Francisco 49ers, 24-21, to qualify for the playoffs for the third
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest owes his possible comeback to a specialist the team
sought for him who is trained in this type of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I'm strengthening the muscles around the groin
muscle,'' said McGinest. ``Those have to be stimulated so all of
the pressure isn't on the actual groin muscle. When I injured it,
the muscles around it weren't strong, so all the pressure was going
on that one muscle. If the muscles around it are strong I should be
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest said he spoke to Fox TV commentator and former Oakland
Raider Matt Millen, who told McGinest that he was out three months
with a groin injury. ``It's one of those injuries you have to let
heal,'' McGinest said.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that time has come. It was thought McGinest might sit
out the regular-season finale and then play in the playoffs, but
when asked if was taking the week off he said, ``I never take a
week off.'' He certainly sounded like a man who felt better than
he's felt in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the Patriots' pass rush had been abysmal. In
fact, in the seven games before Sunday's, New England had a total
of eight sacks. But Sunday that changed.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest finally saw a pass rush _ the Patriots had five sacks _
thanks to zone blitzing and tremendous push up front by Chad Eaton,
who sparred with crazyman Kevin Gogan all day. The Patriots were
able to get after the best passer on earth, Steve Young, at the
best possible moments.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest watched carefully and offered advice to young Greg
Spires, who was taking his ``elephant'' role, and even claimed a
part in the big sack Spires had late in the fourth quarter that
stopped the 49ers in their tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played good . . . well, he played all right,'' McGinest
said, catching himself. ``You never tell a rookie he played good.
He came up with plays when he needed to. He just did his
assignments. Right before he got his sack I told him they're gonna
try something, probably a boot(leg) to get outside on the edge. I
told him to stay outside. Sure enough, they try a boot and he stays
outside and he gets the sack. He's coming along. A lot of the young
guys who came in contributed.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest believes his return comes at the best possible time,
against Bill Parcells and the Jets. McGinest will get to see all of
his old mates, like Corwin Brown, Curtis Martin, Otis Smith, Keith
Byars, etc., in what has become a great rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we go against Corwin, Curtis, Dave Meggett, and
(coaches) Bill Belichick and Al Groh, we're always going to be
fired up against those guys,'' McGinest said. ``Bill and Al Groh
are brilliant. They've been together so long with the Giants and
here for a few years; they help each other and they do a great job
trying to stop the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest also was pleased to see that Chris Slade, his partner
in pressuring the QB for many years, returned to his normal level
of play after many weeks of struggling with leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, McGinest had his arm around Slade and was
talking to him about what was ahead. Slade responded with a sack
and nine tackles. He was flying around like the player who earned
All-Pro honors last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him that he was going to go out there and play for
the both of us because I couldn't be out there,'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's been tough the past few weeks because he's been
hurt and he hears people saying he's not playing at his level. They
don't know what's going on because they don't know about his
injuries and what they've done to him. They don't come close to
understanding the situation and that when you do what we do and
play this position you need your legs. Your legs are everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him to go out and play like Chris Slade.''
</P>
<P>
   Then McGinest offered his two cents about Pete Carroll vs.
Parcells. He said both have their special ways of motivating
players. McGinest still remembers Parcells benching him on third
downs because he had a poor game rushing the passer and how mad it
made him. He remembered how motivated he was to prove Parcells
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But he understands that Carroll, who has been perceived as being
not as tough on players, stepped into a tough situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to fill some big shoes,'' said McGinest. ``His
obligation and contribution to the team has been great. Any time
the level of the play of this team drops a little bit and
expectations aren't reached right away, it falls on the head man.
That's when all the comparisons start to creep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took pressure off his back by winning on Sunday . . .
finally winning the big game because everybody counted us out of
this game. He coached a good game and he should be satisfied. He
still has more to do this week vs. the Jets and then the playoffs.
But it gave him a little breathing room.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest said he grew up playing under coaches that were far
tougher than Parcells, ``so I knew where he was coming from. I
understood what he was trying to do.'' He remembers Parcells
walking out of practice to prove a point. He remembers before the
final game of the '96 season Parcells, in his pregame speech
``started crying in front of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, McGinest would like to make Parcells cry again, but
for different reasons. He'd like to have a hand in beating his old
coach. And now, he'll have a leg to stand on as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
