r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CLINTON-SPI &LR;      12-21 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLINTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERY OF TV MAY SAVE CLINTON PRESIDENCY YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Italics) 'Twas a week before Christmas and all through the
House
</P>
<P>
   An impeachment was stirring a rancorous joust.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were laid by accusers with care,
</P>
<P>
   In hopes that the Clintons would go on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The prez and his lady indeed did go live,
</P>
<P>
   But said they were staying, not taking a dive.
</P>
<P>
   (End italics)
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by what might have been the most politically astute
support group ever assembled, President Clinton tensed his jaw
muscles Saturday, looked straight into the camera and declared that
he's staying till ``the last hour of the last day'' of his term,
whether that last day comes in two months at the bidding of the
Senate or in two years at the bidding of his naturally chosen
successor.
</P>
<P>
   The last time impeachment escaped the high school civics class
to become a topic of cocktail party chitchat, a less media-savvy
president used television mainly as a conduit of information, first
to say, like Clinton, that he would never resign, then to tell us
he was, well, doing what he said he'd never do.
</P>
<P>
   The indelible images from that time a quarter-century ago are
Richard Nixon's awkward wave and silly grin as he prepared to board
the chopper to ignominy, which is not an island in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to avoid filing the same flight plan, Clinton has
used television more shrewdly _ as part of a strategy and not
simply as a means of responding to journalistic inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested the strategy was ill defined, but I'm not so
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Think what you will of his defiant ``apology'' last August.
Light on contrition, it will be remembered more for its hubris than
its humility. And what about the big lie? When Clinton went on TV
to say he had done nothing improper with ``that woman,'' he was
cheekier than all the ``Saturday Night Live'' spoofs of him.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Clinton has had his moments of introspection and regret _
all well documented _ but the ``defiant leader'' act is something
that wouldn't play nearly as well in print. As ABC's Sam Donaldson
pointed out Saturday, the Democrats who walked out of the Capitol
building to protest the impeachment vote and show their support for
the president weren't doing it for the benefit of newspaper
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Just as humor doesn't always translate well to the printed page,
fits of pique should be seen to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wants us to feel his pain, but he doesn't want
us to see him as the simpering victim. Victim, yes. Simpering, no.
</P>
<P>
   The president's narcissistic ego won't let him accept defeat, or
even allow him to accept that what he did was wrong, so he (and his
handlers) have gambled on a performance as embattled chief
executive, hoping that sympathy builds in his favor. It seems to be
working. Despite his impeachment, the president's approval rating
remains high.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the best performer the presidency has ever had,
Ronald Reagan's Hollywood credentials notwithstanding. As long as
he remains defiant on TV, right down to the flexing of those jaw
muscles, the message to Americans is clear: ``My enemies are out to
get me, but you and I are bigger than this petty partisan
squabble.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes for good theater of the absurd. And right now, with
apologies to Jon Lovitz, Bill Clinton remains the master Thespian,
because without television he might be in even bigger trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
