<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS YOUR COMPANY `COOL' ENOUGH TO KEEP PEOPLE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, CA 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: We just lost a promising employee who
told us the main reason she was leaving was because our company is
not ``cool,'' but she did not clarify what she meant. I am not an
out-of-touch manager, but I don't know what it means to be a cool
company. I have asked a number of people and gotten different
answers. What do you think? C.S.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The notion of cool companies has become a very hot
topic. Some people might say that if you have to ask if your
company is cool, then it's not. There are a number of key
characteristics that differentiate cool companies from uncool ones.
</P>
<P>
   For example, cool companies try to understand and respect their
employees as individuals and provide them with real opportunities
to be heard. They also provide opportunities to foster employee
learning, development and growth. These companies consider the
balance between work and life, and typically implement policies
with this in mind, such as flex time, on-site child care and
telecommuting.
</P>
<P>
   Cool companies act honestly and with integrity, and there is a
genuine respect for employee diversity. These companies have a real
appreciation of the value that diversity of backgrounds,
experiences and cultures can bring to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Such companies embrace the newest technological advances, and
they tend to have a more casual atmosphere, not only in terms of
attire but in terms of the physical and organizational structure.
In fact, their corporate structure is not a pyramid, but tends to
be rather flat.
</P>
<P>
   Research is already showing that turnover in cool companies is
relatively low, and that's pretty cool too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are some employees reluctant to ask questions? I have one
who usually does a good job, but he could do an excellent job if he
would just ask a question or two. I have encouraged him to do this,
but he won't. How can I change this? J.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Why employees refuse to ask questions is a very good
question. The best place to find the answer is to look carefully at
your employee and at yourself as his manager.
</P>
<P>
   There can be any number of personality traits that may be
holding him back. For example, perhaps he has some feelings of
insecurity over the mistaken belief that asking questions can be a
sign of ineptitude. Or, he may have had some negative experiences
that are now preventing him from daring to ask a question.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it may be helpful for you to look at your
leadership style and try to see if you are fully receptive to
employee questions. Is it possible that your potential response may
be preventing him from asking anything in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the most successful managers tailor
their leadership style to meet the individual needs of the
employees they supervise. If this employee needs to be encouraged
to ask some questions, and this can help turn him into an excellent
employee, then it makes unquestionable sense for you to encourage
him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My manager rushed into my office, accompanied by one of the
vice presidents, and said he needed a particular report
immediately. I'm usually quite good at accessing this type of
thing, but I couldn't find it. My manager gave me a dirty look and
they both stormed out. A few minutes later I found the report and
gave it to them, but they said nothing. Should I say something?
W.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Whenever anyone in management storms out of your office, it
is a good idea to do some follow-up to make sure that the storm has
indeed passed. But first, look at your performance history, as this
will set the context for the discussion. In a word, are you truly a
person who can access just about anything that ever crossed your
desk, or are you a person whose desk is the great abyss?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, you do not have to open the discussion with an
apology. In fact, you are arguably entitled to an apology from
anyone who storms out of your office. You should open by saying
that you wanted to discuss what happened the other day. Let your
manager talk, and then respond in kind. No matter how the
discussion goes, let him know about any steps that you are taking
to prevent this type of problem occurring in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If you have established a pattern of being a reliable employee,
this matter will most likely be written off as nothing more than an
isolated incident. However, if you have established a pattern of
being rather unreliable, this incident calls for a change in your
part, lest you be written off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
