<HEADLINE>
SENATORS WARN CLINTON AGAINST CHALLENGING HOUSE IMPEACHMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators from both parties warned President Clinton
Monday not to use the argument that the lame-duck House had no
right to impeach him as a way to delay a Senate trial on whether he
should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that is perceived as parliamentary maneuvering to get
out of this ... is going to be a serious mistake,'' Sen. John B.
Breaux, D-La., said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, also said that the White
House should avoid any legal maneuvers that would ``drag'' the
process out.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, they keep saying that this should be swift,
but at the same time, they're considering something that would
delay this for weeks or months,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart confirmed Monday that the
president's lawyers were considering a legal argument that was
first advanced earlier this month by Yale Law School Professor
Bruce Ackerman in testimony Dec. 8 before the House Judiciary
Committee, which was considering articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said it would be a ``big mistake'' for a House whose
members' terms were about to expire to vote on the articles.
</P>
<P>
   His argument was based on the 20th Amendment to the
Constitution, which in 1933 moved the start of the new Congress
from early March to early January after an election year.
</P>
<P>
   He and others have said the purpose of the amendment was to
abolish lame-duck sessions of Congress _ those held after an
election _ so that any measures passed are more accountable to the
most recent wishes of the people. This would mean that the
impeachment articles passed Saturday by the House of the 105th
Congress would need to be approved by the incoming House of the
106th Congress for the Senate to be able to consider them.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House decides to challenge the validity of the
impeachment vote, it could file a motion at the outset of a Senate
trial with Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who is charged by
the Constitution with presiding over such a trial. Or the White
House could to a file a motion in federal court, which could take
weeks or months to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever decision Rehnquist or the Supreme Court might hand
down, the Senate could overrule it by a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart maintained that ``no conclusions'' had been reached on
whether White House lawyers would press the strategy Ackerman
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, said it would be a ``real mistake'' if the
president started ``playing procedural games rather than dealing
with the substance of this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., also said Sunday that she
believes that the impeachment articles ``continue on through the
changes of sessions.''
</P>
<P>
   If the White House does choose to use the lame-duck Congress
argument to fight the validity of the perjury and
obstruction-of-justice articles approved by the House, it faces a
number of legal hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Many constitutional experts maintain that congressional
procedures and precedents make clear that impeachment is not like
any other legislation and will survive the demise of this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Research Service, which studied the issue
earlier this year, concluded that ``an impeachment proceeding may
be continued from one Congress to the next.'' The CRS noted that
one of the first impeachment cases _ of federal Judge John
Pickering in 1803-04 _ and one of the most recent _ of federal
Judge Alcee Hastings in 1988-89 _ carried over from one Congress to
the next, as did several impeachment cases in between.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Thomas Jefferson's ``Rules of the House,'' which is
used as a guide on Capitol Hill, says that ``an impeachment is not
discontinued'' by the end of a Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Ackerman acknowledged the previous impeachment
cases but noted that the House vote on them had occurred before
elections, not afterward, as in Clinton's case. He said the
Republicans' losses this year would give the impeachment vote the
flavor of a lame-duck Congress rushing through articles of
impeachment that might not pass in the new House, with its smaller
Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tushnet, a constitutional law professor at Georgetown
University, said Ackerman's argument was ``worthy of
consideration'' but would likely be thrown out by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a pure legal environment, the argument might have a chance
but in this case, the Senate is the final judge, and they (the
senators) seem pretty set against it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Senate opposition, Tushnet said, a White House
challenge could end up ``merely adding a few months onto the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the idea of a censure of the president appeared to be
gaining momentum as several senators made known that they would
consider the option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start the process of a trial,'' Hutchinson said.
``Whatever happens after that opens a lot of doors and a lot of
options _ including censure.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday former Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter
suggested a bipartisan censure resolution voted by the Senate and
accepted by Clinton. The proposal would require Clinton to admit he
lied under oath, something he has refused to do. Earlier this
month, Bob Dole, the 1996 Republican presidential nominee, proposed
that both houses of Congress approve a joint resolution of censure
that Clinton would be required to sign.
</P>
</TEXT>
