u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-FERTILITY-C     12-21 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-FERTILITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Multiple births can carry deadly danger for babies
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To women who have struggled to get pregnant, the
arrival of octuplets might seem to be a blessing, but multiple
births always cause alarm among doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Infertility treatments are becoming easier to take and more
popular, and multiple births are becoming more common, doctors say.
But their frequency doesn't diminish their danger.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their prematurity and their extraordinarily low birth
weight, the eight babies born to a 27-year-old Houston woman will
immediately face life-threatening dangers and won't be out of
harm's way for weeks. And aggressive infertility treatment will be
to blame if the octuplets _ one of whom was born two weeks ago _
don't survive these traumatic early years, experts said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is one baby,'' says Kaylen Silverberg, a physician
with the Texas Fertility Center in Austin. Any other outcome is
deemed less than successful, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But like Bobbi McCaughey, the Iowa woman who gave birth to the
first set of live septuplets in the United States last year, Nkem
Chukwu had more than one baby in part because of the fertility
drugs she was taking.
</P>
<P>
   Fertility drugs, which come in both pill and injectable forms,
stimulate the production of eggs in the ovaries and greatly
increase the chances of getting pregnant. Typically, women will
take the drugs for 8 to 12 days in a row, injecting themselves at
home.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what fertility medication Chukwu had been taking.
McCaughey took Pergonal, a drug that can be difficult and painful
to administer. The newest injectable varieties _ Fertinex,
Follistim and Gonal F _ are easier to use and can be more effective
than the older drugs, Silverberg says. But they must be
administered carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're using fertility drugs and you get eight fetuses,
it's not a success at the beginning,'' says Margaret Thompson, an
obstetrician at Renaissance Women's Group in Austin. ``In fact, I
think that would be viewed by most of us _ I hate to say failure _
it's not the desired result of fertility treatments. In most cases,
you would lose these fetuses.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Chukwu was remarkably lucky to carry seven of the
babies for 30 weeks, which is past the point in normal, 40-week
pregnancies when single babies would be considered dangerously
premature, Thompson said. The gestational age of a baby is the most
important factor in its development, though in this case the birth
weights will also be significant.
</P>
<P>
   The Chukwu octuplets ranged in size from 11 ounces to 1 pound,
11 ounces. Most babies born between the 28th and 30th weeks
typically weigh between 2 1/2 and 3 pounds, and the McCaughey
septuplets, who also were born in the 30th week, all weighed more
than 2 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say any babies born as small and as early as the Chukwu
octuplets face several threats to their survival. Their lungs will
struggle to function and could be injured by the machines used to
support them. Blood vessels deep in the babies' brains are fragile
and could spontaneously rupture, leading to serious neurological
problems, such as mental retardation and cerebral palsy. And their
intestinal tracts could become infected, causing inflammation of
the bowels. With the additional risk of infection, the octuplets
will need around-the-clock attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite everybody's best intention, you just can't do as good
a job of taking care of that many babies as you can with a lesser
numbers of babies,'' says Todd Scharnberg, chief of neonatology for
the Seton HealthCare Network in Austin. ``It's a huge concern,
because dealing with one baby at that gestation is a difficult
problem. Dealing with three or four or six or eight would strain
the capabilities of any intensive care unit in this country and
just make it more difficult to take care of the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Park writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
