<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABP-CHARGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABP wants to sell book publisher, grow elsewhere
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American Business Products said Monday it will sell
BookCrafters, its least-profitable division.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based ABP hired SunTrust Equitable Securities to sell
the short-run book printing company based in Chelsea, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is part of a move to enhance profitability, ABP said.
BookCrafters made a profit of $1.7 million on revenues of $50
million in 1997, a margin of about 3.3 percent, according to
Robinson-Humphrey, an Atlanta research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The division, one of five, generated revenue of about $45
million in the first 11 months of this year. No margins figures
have been released.
</P>
<P>
   ABP's shares closed Monday at $23.68 3/4, up 75 cents, on
above-average volume. BookCrafters will be counted as a
discontinued operation. ABP expects to record a material charge in
the fourth quarter of 1998 to account for the move.
</P>
<P>
   ABP employs 100 at its Atlanta headquarters, off Northside Drive
near I-285. Curtis 1000, an ABP subsidiary, employs 350 at a Duluth
manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   ABP is focusing its growth on its flexible packaging and custom
printing businesses, said Richard Smith, chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said ABP does not plan to sell Curtis 1000, its largest
division. Curtis is a digital printer of customized envelopes,
forms, labels, presentation folders and design services for small-
and medium-sized businesses. Starting in 1996, Curtis went through
an aggressive restructuring that closed 12 plants and expanded the
Duluth factory.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the company plans to use the proceeds from the
BookCrafters sale to develop and market new products and to
possibly acquire businesses in the industries in which its other
divisions compete.
</P>
<P>
   ABP's business supplies printing division includes Curtis 1000;
International Envelope, which makes Tyvek, a water resistant,
tear-free material used in envelopes and the backing for
self-adhesive postage stamps; Discount Labels; and Jen-Coat, which
makes special coatings for product labels and packaging materials,
such as Equal and Sweet'n Low.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he sees potential growth in selling alternative,
non-cardboard packaging to online and catalog retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ABP bought BookCrafters in 1972. The company typically prints
short runs, usually 1,000 to 10,000 books.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Smith, an analyst with Robinson-Humphrey, said the plans
were expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``BookCrafters had been slowing,'' he said. ``It didn't fit, and
it had the lowest return on asset of any business in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
