A1207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYNOVUS-FORTUNE-COX     12-21 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYNOVUS-FORTUNE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia companies rank high in Fortune's list
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fortune magazine says that two of the nation's best
employers are in a Georgia city that seldom gets out of the shadow
of image-conscious Atlanta. The magazine's Jan. 11 edition ranks
Columbus-based Synovus Financial and AFLAC in the top 15 of the 100
best companies to work for in America.
</P>
<P>
   Synovus, a banking and credit card processing company, took the
top spot in the annual ranking. AFLAC, an insurance company, ranked
13th in the magazine, which will be on newsstands beginning Dec.
28.
</P>
<P>
   The only other city with two entries in the top 15 was Dallas.
One Atlanta company broke the top 100: flooring company Interface
is ranked 96.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year when it was ranked number 11 by Fortune, Synovus
added a program giving all 10,000 of its employees stock options,
created a $1 million-year leadership training program for workers
and began offering a $5,000 assistance benefit to employees who
want to adopt a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recognition means a lot to our company, but the most
important thing is we know we still have to do a lot,'' said
Elizabeth ``Lee Lee'' James, who heads up Synovus Service Corp.,
the company's administrative arm. ``We focus on making sure every
person in our company knows that somebody cares about them.'' The
company pays up to 21 percent of salary annually toward employee
retirement, produces a magazine describing how it helps employees
who have faced personal tragedies, and purchased 3,200 bricks _
each with the name of employees _ for a new $100 million campus in
downtown Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Synovus has $10 billion in assets and owns 36 banks in the
Southeast. It also owns 80.7 percent of Total System Services, one
of the world's biggest credit and debit card processing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune said it polled more than 27,000 employees and
collaborated with best-selling authors Robert Levering and Milton
Moskowitz to come up with the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   AFLAC CEO Dan Amos said he competes for top employees with
Synovus, across town, and he wanted a boost when recruiting
out-of-state job candidates to Columbus. ``My main goal was to have
been in the top 100. To be the top insurance company is more than I
ever dreamed of in one year.''
</P>
<P>
   AFLAC began giving employees stock options this year, brought in
a service where employees can buy prepared dinners to warm up when
they get home, and created a walk-in medical clinic where employees
pay $10 for treatment of minor ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus business boosters and economic development recruiters
hope to capitalize on the double listing in Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to stretch it and get everything out of it we
can,'' said Mike Gaymon, the president of the Greater Columbus
Chamber of Commerce. ``I can see all kinds of wonderful marketing
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
