<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-DANGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIPLE BIRTHS CAN BE DANGEROUS SIDE EFFECT TO USE OF FERTILITY
DRUGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By T.J. MILLING 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Fertility drugs may be a godsend to couples desperate
to have children, but multiple births like the octuplets born in
Houston are a dangerous side effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human being was meant to have one baby,'' said Dr. Brian
Kirshon, a high-risk obstetrician/gynecologist who delivered the
octuplets Sunday at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital. ``When you get
up to these high-order pregnancies, it's so unusual to be able to
keep the babies alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The type of fertility treatment given to octuplet mom Nkem
Chukwu was similar to that given to the mothers in other recent
multiple births _ a septuplet mom in Iowa, a sextuplet mom from
Kingwood, Texas, and an octuplet mom in England who lost all her
fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's Hospital, where the Chukwu octuplets were delivered,
did not administer the fertility treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment is a combination of hormones, one that promotes
maturation of the ovarian follicle, and another that causes the
ovum to pop off the ovary and enter the fallopian tube where it can
be fertilized by sperm.
</P>
<P>
   After the administration of the first, the doctor can use a
scope to look at the ovary and see how many ovarian follicles _ the
structures that contain the ova, commonly called eggs _ are mature
enough to ovulate. The ethical question for a fertility doctor is
whether to administer the second hormone when he sees multiple
mature follicles that could lead to multiple fetuses and major
complications for mother and children.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting babies are commonly born premature, facing lung,
heart and metabolic problems, and an increased risk of developing
abnormalities like cerebral palsy. The mother has a high risk of
developing diabetes or high blood pressure or both.
</P>
<P>
   The ova can be removed and united with sperm in a test tube, a
process called in vitro fertilization, and then one to five
fertilized ova can be reimplanted in the uterus. Kirshon said
doctors generally are implanting lower numbers of ova, say one or
two, to avoid the problems of multiple births, but regardless there
cannot possibly be more fetuses than ova implanted.
</P>
<P>
   When the hormone cocktail is used with natural fertilization,
many ova can pop into the fallopian tube, be fertilized and
eventually roll down into the uterus for implantation.
</P>
<P>
   There is a process called reduction in which the doctor
selectively removes some of the implanted ova to give the others a
better chance of surviving. But many women object to that procedure
on religious or philosophical grounds, likening it to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshon said it is a difficult line for doctors to walk, trying
to give women enough treatment to get pregnant but not too much,
and all the while dealing with their desperate desire to have
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women will go to any lengths to get pregnant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
