<HEADLINE>
CROWDS FROM ALL NATIONS _ EXCEPT ONE _ ARE TRAVELING TO AND FROM
CUBA
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: This is the fourth in a series of four essays) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past two years, Cuba's leaders have made an energetic
effort to open up Cuban society to the outside world. Almost every
week the island has hosted an international gathering of one kind
or another.
</P>
<P>
   Since the highly celebrated visit of Pope John Paul II last
January, professional organizations around the hemisphere have been
scheduling conventions and conferences there. Fidel Castro
personally welcomes many of them when he is not making state visits
to other Caribbean, Latin American or European countries. His
speaking and traveling schedule this year has resembled that of an
U.S. politician running for his party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Last month in Portugal, Castro encountered King Juan Carlos of
Spain. He playfully reminded the monarch that the governor
general's palace in Havana, built in 1791, contains a throne
installed in expectation of a visit by a Spanish king, but one
never came. Cuba has preserved both the palace and the throne for
200 years as national historic treasures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you will come and see us,'' Castro teasingly beckoned
to Juan Carlos. ``We have your chair all ready for you.''
</P>
<P>
   As spokesman in chief for the island nation, the bearded leader
displays a freewheeling style. A few weeks ago, he welcomed U.S.
editors and publishers, answering their questions _ some at
unexpected length. At one point, the conversation turned to the
pennant-winning New York Yankees' stellar performer, Cuban
expatriate Orlando ``Duke'' Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Castro insisted that his country has many more where the Duke
came from. He promptly offered to field an entire big-league team
if the majors were interested. ``Why not?'' he pressed. ``Canada
has a big-league team.''
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian journalist interrupted to stress that Canada has two
major-league teams. ``Good point!'' replied Castro. ``We'll raise
you two teams!''
</P>
<P>
   The week I was there in November, Havana was entertaining a
conclave of artists and writers. The Cuban leader's speech to the
group was broadcast on nationwide television. Next only to
baseball, the fine arts claim the country's most devoted following.
</P>
<P>
   Around picturesque old plazas in the evenings echo the strains
of string instruments, with occasional bongo accompaniment.
Informal mariachi-style ensembles serenade diners at the little
bars and restaurants. At schools and village gatherings, amateur
artists are encouraged to perform.
</P>
<P>
   During my visit, the Cuban arts community was host to a
worldwide ballet festival featuring internationally prominent
performers from nine countries. Havana's ornate old Opera House was
jammed to capacity for each performance _ someone in every seat, a
vertical figure in every imaginable standing space. In Cuba, ballet
is not an elitist escape. Admission is only 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The overflow crowd at the Friday night finale rose in standing
ovation at the entrance in the balcony of Alicia Alonso, Cuba's
former prima ballerina. Now in her late 70s and blind, the
indomitable woman is considered a national treasure. She personally
choreographed one of the evening's numbers, insisting that even if
she can't see, she can feel the movement.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise of all was the tumultuous response of
the crowd to a multiracial, 13-member troupe of 10- to 15-year-old,
mostly inner-city kids from Los Angeles. They didn't attempt
classical ballet. They tap-danced.
</P>
<P>
   Their fresh-faced routine, performed to an orchestral
arrangement of ``It Don't Mean a Thing if It Ain't Got That
Swing,'' brought down the house at every performance. The North
American kids, judging by length of applause and audience-demanded
encores, were easily the most popular performers among a standout
cast of professionals. Whatever else this may say, it told me that
there's no popular animus here toward Americans _ certainly not
toward our children.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone looking for an ideological meaning in the audience's
preferences would have to be puzzled, however. The
next-most-applauded presentation was an innovative number by
Italian ballerina Carla Fracci, featuring her imaginative use of an
enormous scarlet veil.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of her energetic dance was performed to a
stirring accompaniment of the socialist anthem, the
``Internationale.'' Then, as the martial rhythm faded, the music
segued to a slow, clear-voiced operatic rendition of ``Ave Maria.''
The ballerina contrived at one point to shape the bright red scarf
into the form of a cross. The two themes blended into the heartily
cheered performance.
</P>
<P>
   We may be excused, perhaps, if curiosity prompts us to grope for
meaning. The enthusiastic audience reaction may have been saying,
as Lorenzo Albacete suggested in the Jan. 26 edition of ``The New
Yorker,'' that a new generation of Cuban Roman Catholics finds no
unbridgeable gulf between the social goals of the Revolution and
the social mission of the Church. Or all this may merely reflect
the universality of art. Or could it bespeak some inchoate yearning
for a reconciliation of the family of man?
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
