<SLUG> BC-FINFRONTS-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (lb) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR TUESDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted): &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Lede story)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks rose for the third straight session
Monday, powered higher by continued flows into popular large
capitalization issues and torrid demand for companies that do their
business on the Internet. Saturday's impeachment vote had virtually
no impact on investors, analysts and traders said. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-FEES (Charleston, S.C.) _ In the coming years, dozens of
plaintiffs' lawyers who were hired to represent states in their
claims against the cigarette makers will become multimillionaires.
But by all accounts, Joseph Rice, who negotiated the recent $206
billion tobacco settlement, and his law firm will be the biggest
winners of all. By Barry Meier.
</P>
