<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1231 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-2ndTake     12-21 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: family of man? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   International visitors have always been celebrated in Cuba, and
Ernest Hemingway may be the most beloved. The La Bodeguita
restaurant, on a narrow cobbled side street off Cathedral Plaza,
advertises itself as the famous novelist's favorite hangout.
</P>
<P>
   Memory has it that ``Papa'' Hemingway enjoyed sitting in the
crowded bar, where the names of ancient patrons in graffiti now
adorn almost every available inch of interior wall space. Here the
moody author would down Mojitos, an island drink concocted of sugar
cane, rum, lime juice and crushed mint. Then he'd stroll a few
blocks to the Floridita Bar, where he'd order daiquiris. After
satisfying his thirst, Hemingway would repair in good spirits to
his residence and continue composing whatever work absorbed him at
the time, perhaps ``The Old Man and the Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wall above the corner in the Floridita where the writer
so frequently sat regaling bartenders, there appears a framed
photograph of a white-bearded Hemingway talking with a youthful
Castro. The seat on his favorite bar stool has been removed, and
the upright pipe that supported it is chained off. This spot where
locals swear Hemingway took his last drink before going home and
shooting himself is permanently retired from occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   At the newly restored Hotel Nacional, Havana's premier hostelry
of bygone decades, tourists and conventioneers can see full walls
overprinted with mural photographs of Jack Dempsey, Errol Flynn,
Rita Hayworth, George Raft and a host of other popular American
performers who appeared there in the pre-Castro years when Havana
was a gambling mecca and local night life was dominated by mob
figures like Lucky Luciano and Meyer Lansky. Pictures of these,
too, adorn the wall of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   But tourists seeking richer history, dating back to Christopher
Columbus and Hernando De Soto, find it lovingly preserved in La
Habana Vieja, the Old City. Cubans take pride in the United
Nations' designation of their ancient capital as one of the world's
historic cities. They see it as a sanctuary from modernity's visual
and aural blights. In restoring their Hotel Row for tourists, they
make clear that they have in mind no mimicry of Las Vegas. ``And
the Caribbean doesn't need two Miami Beaches,'' one told me. Havana
has more in common, I'm thinking, with New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The city's seven plazas commemorate in art and statuary the
country's unique variety of cultural and historic heroes. Here is a
bronze statue to Santa Isabella _ De Soto's widow and the only
woman ever designated governor of Cuba. There is one to Jose Marti,
independence martyr of the war against Spain. And the Plaza de
Armas, built on the site of Fulgencio Batista's former military
headquarters, features displays of the 1959 Revolution. There's
even a 1950s vintage armored tank, from which (popular legend has
it) Castro himself shot and sank one of the landing boats at the
1961 U.S.-backed Bay of Pigs invasion attempt.
</P>
<P>
   To the west of the city, past the duty-free zone with its
industrial assembly park, a road follows the shoreline curve
through lush foliage and ends at a seaside medical resort dedicated
to long-term treatment of children's diseases. Here I saw a softer
side of Cuban life.
</P>
<P>
   Two formal hospital wards, several playground areas and 45 large
guest houses for patients and parents sprawl in a natural grassy
setting that slopes off to the sea. Here a group of specialists
provides treatment and a therapeutic recovery environment for young
people suffering from malignancies and leukemia, chronic kidney and
renal ailments, and various psychosomatic disorders.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of youngsters greets our small party's arrival. Some
want their pictures taken with us. A tow-headed 10-year-old boy has
spots of baldness. His hair is just returning after chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Julio Medina, physician in charge, explains that treatment
is free for Cuban youth and selected others who come as ``guests of
the Cuban people.'' The facility, for example, has provided
treatment and rehabilitative services for about 300 young
Ukrainians afflicted by the nuclear accident at Chernobyl a decade
ago. Some have discovered delayed symptoms only in the past year or
so.
</P>
<P>
   I talked with Dr. Gennady L. Korneinko of Kiev, who helps raise
money in Ukraine to transport these young patients to Cuba. No
comparable treatment is available, he assures us, anywhere in
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   A Ukrainian father, here with his 15-year-old daughter, tells me
she has been given ``a second chance for life.'' He is full of
gratitude to the Cuban people.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts like these have helped Cuba win respect from other
nations. No longer a social pariah, it now maintains friendly
diplomatic and trade relations with almost every nation except our
own. An estimated 1 million to 4 million tourists visited the
island this year, spending close to $2 billion there. More are
expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond doubt, our continued economic embargo has hurt the Cuban
economy and its people. Considerable economic recovery has occurred
in spite of it. But the embargo has made recovery slower,
identifiably more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The great irony is that the purpose of our sanctions was to
convince the Cubans to overthrow Castro. In reality, they've had
the exact opposite effect. For years they gave Cuba's hard-liners
an excuse for economic failure.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Dominguez, Harvard's resident Cuba expert, wrote in 1993:
``The Castro regime endures in part because its enemies unwittingly
help it to survive.'' The sanctions provide a convenient and
creditable scapegoat on which to blame shortages and high prices of
almost any sort, say longtime observers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, three former U.S. secretaries of state and a
bipartisan group of senators called on President Clinton to appoint
a blue-ribbon commission to recommend a new approach to U.S.-Cuban
relations. One hundred years have passed since the Spanish-American
War, 38 since the Bay of Pigs invasion attempt, and 36 since the
missile crisis. Our lease on Guantanamo Bay will expire in 2002. It
does seem time for a fresh approach.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
