<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX'S FINOVA ON `BEST TO WORK FOR' LIST  
 (ADV: LIST OF TOP 12 FIRMS AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Rick Baker has three kids in college, but he didn't
have to write out any tuition checks this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The $6,600 tab for the 98-99 school year was picked up by his
employer, Finova Group Inc. The Phoenix commercial finance company
will pay the bills until they graduate. Any employee is eligible
for up to $3,000 per child per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cashing in on the current three and the next one,'' the
52-year-old assistant vice president said with a laugh. `'I figure
I'll have 11 years of (college) expenses paid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Future Leaders Grant Program, as the new tuition plan is
called, is one of the many perks and programs that earned Finova a
prime spot on ``Fortune'' magazine's second annual ``100 Best
Companies to Work for in America'' list. The rankings were
announced Monday and are included in the Jan. 11 issue, out next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly traded company, which was spun off from the old
Dial conglomerate in 1992, ranked No. 12 in its debut on the list,
and was the only Arizona-based company to make a showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're certainly one of the best companies that we looked at
in terms of how little perks and little benefits'' add up, said
Robert Levering, workplace author and co-founder of the Great Place
to Work Institute, which produced the list in collaboration with
``Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Levering singled out the college tuition plan as among the most
unique and generous he's seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of too many other companies that do anything like
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most tuition programs cover a limited number of employees'
children, usually those at the top of the class. Under Finova's any
employee's child is eligible as long as they have the grades to get
into an accredited institution, whether its DeVry or Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely unusual,'' Levering said.
</P>
<P>
   Also unusual about Finova, Levering and his colleagues found:
the high regard employees have for Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer Sam Eichenfield.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the research for the ``Fortune'' list is a random
employee survey, and Finova employees gave their boss top marks for
everything from leadership to personal birthday cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's spoken of very, very warmly by so many people,'' Levering
said. ``It's definitely one of the more notable things about the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the gushing about the CEO is not as extreme as at
Southwest Airlines, last year's top winner and No. 4 this year, but
``it's certainly right up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichenfield, a 62-year-old down-to-earth executive who joined
the company in 1987 when it was known as Greyhound Financial, was
pleased with the recognition by ``Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me because we think the company has a role
in society and a role for its people and it's nice to see that you
can be successful in taking care of both of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finova decided to submit its name for consideration after it
looked at the benefits offered by last year's winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that we did most of things that they do and in many
cases I felt that we do more,'' said Bill Roche, senior vice
president of human resources. ``And, I know how our employees feel
about the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who works in Finova's portfolio policy and analysis
department and has been with the company for 11 years, said it's
the whole package, from the concierge service that got him tickets
to a sold out Celene Dion concert to the company's extensive ``Care
and Share'' charity program, of which he's on the board.
</P>
<P>
   He's worked at big-name compa nies such as IBM and Dun and
Bradstreet and says ``nothing compares to this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you send in your resume for a high-paying job at Finova _
the average salary in the Phoenix area is $57,000 plus a bonus of
$10,300, excluding excluding senior executives _ keep in mind that
the company doesn't have big hiring plans. While it's growing at a
good clip, much of the growth is from acquisitions or cross-selling
to existing customers. Also, turnover is a relatively modest 10
percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   Roche said Finova will probably hire just 30 to 40 people _
around the country _ in the first half of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business conditions could change that as well as an
acquisition, but otherwise we are fairly steady,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the word is already out about the company.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said every time there was a job opening in his former
department a few years ago ``we'd get like 80 to 100 resumes.''
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the ``Fortune'' ranking, a company had to be
at least 10 years old and have a minimum of 500 employees. The
magazine said 206 companies participated in the entire selection
process. Employees of the eligible companies had to complete the
survey, which were designed to evaluate trust in management, pride
in work and camaraderies, among other factors. The companies had to
submit company newsletters, employee handbooks and videos. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE LIST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top 12 companies on ``Fortune'' magazine's 100 Best
Companies to Work For in America list. The list will be published
in the Jan. 11 edition.
</P>
<P>
   1. Synovus Financial
</P>
<P>
   2. TD Industries
</P>
<P>
   3. SAS Institute
</P>
<P>
   4. Southwest Airlines
</P>
<P>
   5. Scitor Corp.
</P>
<P>
   6. PeopleSoft
</P>
<P>
   7. Goldman Sachs
</P>
<P>
   8. Deloitte &AMP; Touche
</P>
<P>
   9. MBNA
</P>
<P>
   10. Hewlett-Packard
</P>
<P>
   11. Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   12. Finova Group Inc. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at 444-8617 or
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
