<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FOCUSES ON JOB AS SENATE TRIAL LOOMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For President Clinton, Monday was a day to help the
poor, mourn the victims of terrorism, and play host to the
capital's hungry media.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a time to dwell on the fact that as of Saturday he
stands as only the second president in U.S. history to be impeached
by the House and now faces a Senate trial on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The president left to others, including spokesman Joe Lockhart
and Vice President Al Gore, the task of blasting impeachment
advocates and fleshing out his strategy for dealing with the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers noted that his climbing approval ratings are
due to the view by the public that he continues to deal with their
problems and has not let the impeachment issue distract him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public understands that this president has
remained focused on the job they sent him here to do and they
approve of the job he's done,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore that perception, the president and first lady
devoted the early afternoon to making lasagna for the homeless and
needy at a kitchen run by a nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few blocks from the Capital building where two days ago
House Republicans rammed through the impeachment vote, the first
couple donned aprons and ladled sauce over noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the Senate could expect from his defense team
regarding impeachment, the president tersely replied, ``a few days
to celebrate the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he have a holiday message for Congress and the country? ``I
hope everyone in the country will take some time to think about
other people and do something in the spirit of the season like
this,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Clintons traveled to Arlington National Cemetery
where they helped lead the 10th anniversary memorial service for
the victims of Pan Am flight 103 that exploded over Lockerbie,
Scotland, as a result of a terrorist bomb.
</P>
<P>
   At the outdoor ceremony, which commenced at the exact moment
that the airplane exploded, bells tolled for two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the 270 victims were read by relatives. And Clinton
assured them that his administration was doing everything possible
to bring the perpetrators, believed to be sheltered by Libya, to
justice.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony the president and first lady laid a wreath at
the memorial cairn built in honor of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons then returned to the White House where preparations
were under way for the annual Christmas party for the hordes of
journalists, pundits and columnists who have relentlessly covered
the president's travails this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a large tent set up on the White House South Lawn, members of
the normally adversarial national press, dropped their professional
duties for a few hours to be the guests of the impeached president.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before Christmas, Clinton is expected to continue
his strategy of staying above the impeachment fray.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled Tuesday to do his annual Christmas reading to
children and Wednesday will visit Baltimore with Secretary of
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo to highlight housing issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
