<HEADLINE>
EARLY BIRDS GET THE PASSPORTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Dec. 27. Do you know how old your passport is? Or where it
is? January, when business is slow at the passport office, is a
good time to renew if the passport expires anytime in 1999 and you
plan to travel outside the country. Many countries will not admit
travelers with passports that have less than six months' validity
left.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, mail is the way to go for renewal. It is fastest
at this time of year. The official estimate is that getting a
passport by mail takes 25 working days, starting from the time the
government receives the material until it is back in the
applicant's hands. A little time can be saved by enclosing a
request for an express return by mail, Federal Express or other
services, plus payment for the extra cost.
</P>
<P>
   But you might do even better right now. Do not dally until
March: the pace picks up radically and continues at fever pitch
until September.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year ended in October, 6.4 million passports were
issued; in 1995, the number was 5.3 million. There are 45 million
valid passports in the country now, a State Department spokeswoman
says, compared with 33 million in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   One more statistic. In 1995, more than two-thirds of passports
were issued to new applicants, a reversal of the situation the year
before. This trend is continuing: new applications _ many of them
from newly naturalized citizens eager to revisit the home country _
numbered 4.9 million, and renewal applications totaled 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the opening in 1992 of a huge passport factory in
Portsmouth, N.H., service by mail has been growing as passport
demand has expanded beyond the capacity of downtown offices. Vistas
of young people in sleeping bags outside passport offices are
becoming part of the banished folkways of the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, the New York Passport Agency flabbergasted its
constituency by saying it would not start the passport process for
people who arrived on its doorstep unannounced. The agency had
already said it would serve those applying in person only if they
had air tickets for travel within 14 days. But in 1996, to cut the
jam-up further, it began to require phone appointments.
</P>
<P>
   The by-appointment, immediate-travelers-only system has been
adopted by three other agencies this year: Miami, Los Angeles and
most recently Washington (in November). The automated numbers for
appointments are: Miami, (305) 539-3600; Los Angeles, (310)
575-5700 and Washington, (202) 647-0518. The numbers work only with
touch-tone phones.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the other regional offices would eventually also refuse
to accept walk-ups, a spokeswoman for the State Department, Maria
Rudensky, said that the pressure was not equally great nationwide;
New Orleans and Seattle, for example, have lower demand. There are
also regional offices in Boston, Chicago, Honolulu, Houston,
Portsmouth (site of the mail-order fulfillment house),
Philadelphia, San Francisco and Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Passport Agency is now at 376 Hudson St. on the
corner of West Houston St. People with tickets for departures in
the next 14 days, or who are traveling soon but need some extra
time to get visas, can make appointments within the next 14
calendar days by calling (212) 206-3500. This line also provides
general information on getting a passport.
</P>
<P>
   A new adult passport costs $60. An adult renewal costs $40, but
people going to the appointment-only agencies for a new or renewed
passport will pay $35 more for the expedited service. Information
and forms to be printed out may be found on the Internet at
travel.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Applications may be mailed to the National Passport Center, Post
Office Box 371971, Pittsburgh, Pa. 15250. These are taken directly
to Portsmouth. Those sent to regional centers may be worked on
there or relayed to Portsmouth if the local offices are jammed up.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department last month began phasing in passports with
digitized pictures and other added security features. The old
requirements for the photos you must supply, two identical
photographs 2 by 2 inches (color or black and white), still apply,
despite the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman, James P. Rubin, the computer-generated
photograph of the bearer makes the passport much less vulnerable to
alteration by criminals. Rubin said 15,000 United States passports
were stolen abroad in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1999, all domestic passport agencies will be
equipped to issue these new versions, although replacements issued
by embassies or consulates overseas will continue to be the
old-fashioned kind. Because adults' passports are valid for 10
years, and may be renewed for two years after that, it will take 12
years before all passports issued in the United States will have
been created by the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   If the desired effect is achieved, passports should be less
attractive targets for thieves because their resale value will
decline. Until then, having a digitized passport provides no
particular benefit to the holder.
</P>
<P>
   The first machines to produce the new passports were installed
in Portsmouth, but not all the machines there have been replaced,
so there is no way to guess whether you will get a new model if you
mail your application this early.
</P>
<P>
   A reader, A. Lawrence Katzman of New York, wrote about an
experience he and his wife, Shirley, had with visas in Turkey that
may guide others traveling there. The Katzmans had visas put into
their passports at the consulate in New York in August for a cruise
they were taking from Istanbul later that month. They paid $45 each
for what proved to be single-entry visas, which were stamped on
their arrival in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned from the cruise, they were required to get
second visas, again paying $45 each. They then learned that for the
same $45 they could have bought multiple-entry visas good for three
months, all they needed. The Katzmans said they were not told this
initially, although a spokesman for the Turkish Mission to the
United Nations said they should have been.
</P>
<P>
   An information sheet provided by the Consulate General of
Turkey, 821 United Nations Plaza, New York, N.Y. 10017, says: ``If
you are going to Turkey on a cruise line and leaving with the same
cruise line (a) visa is not required.'' This, of course, applies
only to travelers who board a ship elsewhere and make Turkey a stop
on the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   As to the $45 fee, Penar Palti at the Consulate said it was
adopted in February, a rise from $20, after the United States
raised to $45 from $20 the fee for applying for a United States
visa. ``And if the United States raises its fee again, so will
we,'' Ms. Palti said.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of back-and-forth has been going on for a few years.
However, the United States fee covers only the application; there
is no guarantee a visa will be granted. If it is, no further
payment is needed; if not, the fee is forfeited. ``It's the cost
just to play the game,'' Ms. Rudensky said.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, Turkey is more liberal. It sells visas to
tourists at the port of entry for the same $45.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
