<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS QUESTION FAIRNESS OF TEXAS' CLEMENCY PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Attorneys for two death row inmates, including a
Canadian whose case has attracted international attention, argued
before a federal judge Monday that Texas' clemency process is
unfair and shrouded in secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers maintain that the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
should be required to hold a public meeting on a condemned inmate's
clemency request and provide reasons for denying or granting it.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the 17 board members vote by fax or phone and don't
explain their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks stayed the
executions of Stanley Faulder, a Canadian citizen, and Danny Lee
Barber on grounds that Texas' clemency process should be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the evidence will show that Mr. Faulder did not
receive meaningful review by the board,'' attorney Sandra Babcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks adjourned Monday's hearing for a day to allow the
inmates' attorneys more time to review state documents before
closing arguments. He also hinted that attorneys for the state
might want to reconsider their decision not to call any witnesses
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's surprising to me the state would rest without any
evidence,'' Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make a determination,'' he noted, adding he will
base his decision on the evidence presented, rather than on the
burden-of-proof theory in which the inmates' attorneys would bear
the greater responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's hearing, Victor Rodriguez, chairman of the
pardons and paroles panel, defended the clemency process, saying
board members take their job very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every piece of information that is sent to us is reviewed,''
Rodriguez said when one attorney asked if board members really have
enough time to properly handle clemency requests. ``We make time
for these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he did not believe board members ought to be
required to disclose publicly their reasons for denying or
recommending clemency for an inmate because of possible court
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe whatever reason we give, it would not be good
enough for the attorneys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In making a decision, board members review documents submitted
by the inmate. They also can launch an investigation, but Rodriguez
said members have not done so in recent years because they didn't
think it was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The board decides whether to recommend clemency to the governor.
Gov. George W. Bush can commute a death sentence to life in prison
only if the board recommends he do so.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1995, when Bush took office, the state has
executed 77 people. Only one person was spared: Henry Lee Lucas.
Bush said he accepted the board's recommendation to commute his
death sentence to life because there was doubt Lucas committed the
1979 slaying of a woman near Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder, 61, was convicted of killing an East Texas woman in
1975. His case has generated controversy in Canada, where there is
no death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Barber, 43, was sentenced to death for the beating death of a
woman more than 19 years ago in Balch Springs, a Dallas suburb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1920EST &QL; 
