<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
accepts the inevitablity of his government's downfall, striking a
deal with the political opposition to hold new elections sometime
next spring. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Roundup on impeachment developments: Vice
President Gore calls for censure. Some Clinton advisors want a
trial instead. McConnell says there has to be a trial. In a signal
that Senate Democrats would maintain some distance from the White
House, Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia warns that the White House
should not expect to control the terms of a censure resolution. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENT (Beijing) _ By sentencing two of the country's
most prominent democracy campaigners to lengthy prison terms, China
takes its harshest steps yet in its current crackdown on organized
political opposition. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS (Houston) _ The two sons and six daughters of Nkem
Chukwu remained in critical condition at Texas Children's Hospital,
sedated, incubated and all eight of them together weighing just a
breath over 10 pounds. By Rick Lyman. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BANANA-TRADE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration announces
that in retaliation for Europe's refusal to open its market to
bananas shipped by two U.S. companies _ Dole Food Co. and Chiquita
Brands International, which is controlled by Carl Lindner, a major
contributor to both political parties _ it will impose 100 percent
tariffs on a variety of European-made products. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-PAY (Washington) _ Mid-career officers who have been
quitting military service in droves will receive a 10 percent pay
increase under a Department of Defense proposal that calls for the
largest increases in pay and pensions for military personnel since
1982. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLOON (Undated) _ Faced with a choice between a crash
landing in the Himalayas or the possibility of being forced down by
China's armed forces, three balloonists seeking to circle the world
nonstop pressed on into Chinese airspace, hoping for a last-minute
change of heart by the Beijing government. By Malcolm W. Browne.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks rise for the third straight session,
pushed higher by continued flows into popular large-capitalization
issues and torrid demand for companies that do business on the
Internet. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MYLAN-SUIT (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission charges
that Mylan Laboratories, the nation's second biggest maker of
generic drugs, has violated antitrust laws, and the government says
it will seek $120 million in refunds for consumers of two widely
used anti-anxiety medications. Attorneys general from 10 states,
including New York, Connecticut, Florida, Illinois and
Pennsylvania, are filing a similar lawsuit. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SPY-NOVELS (Undated) _ Like cashiered spies groping for a
mission, veteran literary spy masters are coming out of the Cold
War into a new world order that is hard on current sales and
indifferent to their old-fashioned trench-coat espionage fiction.
By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
