<HEADLINE>
HIGGINBOTHAM'S LEGACY TO THE AGES CITED AT FUNERAL RITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Civil rights legend Rosa Parks, a constellation of
legal luminaries, and hundreds whose lives he touched celebrated
the legacy of A. Leon Higginbotham Jr., saying the prominent
jurist's courageous voice will echo down the generations.
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham, a former chief justice of the US 3d Circuit Court
of Appeals and winner of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, died
last week after a series of strokes. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   But during services at Peoples Baptist Church in Roxbury which
were alternately poignant, inspirational, and hilarious,
Higginbotham's spirit danced before an overflow congregation that
included Supreme Court Justice Stephen G. Breyer and NAACP
President Kweisi Mfume.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us he was a Herculean giant, who marched for freedom and
equality with presidents and kings,'' said Stephanie
Franklin-Suber, Philadelphia's city solicitor and a former law
student of Higginbotham.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us he was a living legend, who traveled the corridors of
history in search of social justice and human rights,'' she said.
``To us he was a force of nature. . . . As is fitting, he finally
sits on the high court of history.''
</P>
<P>
   There were tributes read from President Clinton and South
African President Nelson Mandela. There were testimonials from
fellow judges and former students. And there was a reverential
silent standing salute to Parks, who walked slowly along the front
of the church just before the service began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really interested in people who needed help and needed
work,'' Parks, 85, said of Higginbotham after the memorial service.
``I think he really had a great idea that we are all equal
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks's refusal to give up her seat to a white passenger led to
a boycott of Montgomery buses in 1955 by the city's black residents
and, ultimately, the desegregation of public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a turning point in the fight for civil rights _ a
movement to which Higginbotham, the son of a Trenton, N.J.,
domestic, would dedicate his career.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Brown III, who grew up with Higginbotham and later
practiced law with him, recalled that when his lifelong friend
enrolled at Purdue University, after graduating high school at age
16, he wanted to become an engineer. But like his childhood dream
to pursue a career in firefighting, Jim Crow stood in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no room at Purdue's inn for black students,'' said
Brown. ``Leon and his fellow black Purdue classmates were forced to
reside in an unheated attic in a house off of campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was racism that prevented Leon from becoming a fire
commissioner and perhaps even the CEO of IBM. However, it is clear
that no matter what career path Leon traveled, he would eventually
rise to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``While he did not become a firefighter,'' said Brown, ``he
helped dampen the fires of discrimination. While he did not become
a civil engineer, he did become a social engineer through his
decisions as a trial judge.''
</P>
<P>
   When President Lyndon Johnson appointed him a federal district
court in 1964, Higginbotham, at 35, became the youngest appointee
to the federal bench in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham was a professor at Harvard University's John F.
Kennedy School of Government at the time of his death. And his
colleagues and law students talked of his relentless drive and his
ability to juggle many demanding jobs at once.
</P>
<P>
   In a written tribute from the White House, President Clinton
hailed Higginbotham's career and thanked him for his testimony
earlier this month before the Judiciary Committee in which the
former judge pronounced the president's actions, which Republicans
deemed perjury, not impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He backed up his heartfelt commitment with action,'' wrote
Clinton, who awarded Higginbotham the nation's highest civilian
honor, the Presidential Medal of Freedom, after his retirement from
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a brilliant mind and eloquent voice and a tenacious
spirit, he became a champion of civil rights and the rule of law.
As a lawyer, scholar and distinguished jurist Judge Higginbotham
strived throughout his career to ensure that America lives up to
its promise of justice for all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript which read, ``I will never forget how he spoke
up for me,'' Clinton underlined the word ``never.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, in his written condolences to Higginbotham's family,
called the former judge ``a powerful voice of the voiceless, a
tireless defender of the oppressed and an unparalleled champion of
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In the memorial's emotional apex, Higginbotham's daughter, Dr.
Karen Higginbotham, a clinical psychologist, painted a loving
portrait of her father _ the man who took her to Washington to
listen to Martin Luther King's landmark ``I Have a Dream Speech''
and taught her to respect those on the lower rungs of life's
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouses where he worked, she said, his children
learned the names of every security guard and every person in
housekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Then she told the story of a woman who approached her father one
night when he was dressed in black tie. Higginbotham was the
keynote speaker, but the woman mistook him for a waiter and ordered
a glass of whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned to the woman and said: `Is that on the rocks or with
water?' '' Karen Higginbotham said. ``And then he got her the drink
_ with a napkin.''
</P>
<P>
   When the woman, visibly embarrassed, later approached him, his
daughter recalled, Higginbotham answered with aplomb: ``I knew you
were thirsty. I knew you just wanted a drink.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
