<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-FEES-ART-2TAK     12-21 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-FEES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER REAPS RICH REWARD FROM TOBACCO SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Miss., N.Y., S.C., Texas, Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rl) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Joseph Rice, a plaintiffs' lawyer here who
negotiated the recent $206 billion tobacco settlement, was feted by
state attorneys general at a hotel dinner this month in Coral
Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of their efforts, Rice and two other lawyers _
his partner, Ronald Motley, and Richard Scruggs, from Pascagoula,
Miss. _ received rather unusual mementoes: wood-lined cigar boxes.
But a few hours earlier, they had been pondering far weightier
matters. The three men had met on Scruggs' yacht, anchored in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., to discuss how to divide an unparalleled windfall
in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   In coming years, dozens of plaintiffs' lawyers nationwide, all
hired to represent states in claims to recover health care costs
from cigarette makers, will become multimillionaires. And by all
accounts, Rice and his firm _ Ness, Motley, Loadholt, Richardson &AMP;
Poole _ will be the biggest winners of all. Out of a total pie
estimated at anywhere from $10 billion to $30 billion, the firm is
guaranteed $1 billion _ just for starters. Rice's cut will easily
be in the tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is already set to get a share of the money paid to
lawyers for nine of the 12 states that recently resolved fee claims
through arbitration or negotiation, including the $8.2 billion that
went on Dec. 11 to lawyers who represented Florida, Texas and
Mississippi. From those three states alone, Rice and his firm will
collect about $1 billion in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   But that is just a down payment. The firm also worked for 23
other states, including giants like New York, whose settlement is
worth $25 billion over 25 years. Rice estimates that his firm,
depending on which state is involved, will get from 3 percent to 50
percent of the total legal fees in each state it represented.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a tall, slightly paunchy 44-year-old, said it is a payday
well earned. His firm, he said, invested thousands of hours and
spent $20 million to $30 million to sue tobacco companies on behalf
of states, a gamble that looked shaky when the state lawsuits
started in 1994. And he said he was convinced that the deal would
save lives and that the lawyers involved should get paid as well as
the tobacco executives are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the lawyers who carried the burden and led the
fight not be paid like a chief executive officer of a
corporation?'' Rice asked.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy employed by Rice's firm may qualify it as one of
the business world's most successful franchise operations. After
getting a toehold in the first state tobacco lawsuit, filed in 1994
by Mississippi, Rice and other Ness, Motley lawyers fanned out
around the country offering regulators in state after state
essentially a package deal that could be used in pursuing cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   Included were thousands of coded and computerized tobacco
industry documents, testimony from dozens of expert witnesses,
legions of lawyers and battalions of researchers. In return, state
officials signed contracts guaranteeing Ness, Motley and affiliated
firms 15 percent to 25 percent of any recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Ness, Motley also activated a network of law firms nationwide
with which it had existing ties. It advanced those lawyers millions
of dollars to pay costs ranging from salaries to new desks to
computer equipment. And when Christine Gregoire, the attorney
general for the state of Washington, ran low on money, Rice says
his firm also kicked in, advancing that state $150,000 a month to
finance its lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Rice played a central role in negotiating the $368.5
billion tobacco settlement plan that collapsed in Congress this
spring. But by then, a new round of secret talks had begun, and
Rice became the chief negotiator in the talks that led to the
latest deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe clearly sat in the No. 1 seat in the state settlement,''
said Phil Carlton, a lawyer who served as one of the tobacco
industry's principal lobbyists and negotiators. ``You get yourself
in a real good bargaining position when you can deliver 20
settlements instead of one.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a custom-made role for Rice. Unlike the free-wheeling
Scruggs, who joined Mississippi Attorney General Michael Moore in
filing the first state action, Rice prefers operating behind closed
doors. And when tobacco lawyers insisted that Scruggs not be told
about the new talks because they feared he would disclose them to
the media, Rice obliged, even though Scruggs represented many of
the same states that Ness, Motley did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that if Dickie were here, people were going to read
about them,'' said Rice, referring to Scruggs.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said his relationship with Scruggs was ruptured for a time.
But all those involved in the tobacco talks _ state officials,
industry lawyers and anti-smoking advocates _ agreed that Rice was
a tough, tenacious negotiator who pressed to get the best deal he
could for state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Myers, a lawyer with the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids
in Washington, said he disagreed at times with Rice because Rice
refused to simply walk away from talks when cigarette makers would
not budge. But he was impressed by Rice's determination and
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He squeezed out every possible cent,'' Myers said. ``He
wouldn't give up just because he failed in a single approach.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Rice got along well with outside negotiators hired
by cigarette makers like Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds because
he, like those lawyers, was focused on forging a deal, rather than
going to court. One industry lawyer, Meyer Koplow of New York, had
previously worked with Rice to settle thousands of asbestos claims
brought by Ness, Motley.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's style, however, might not fit that well in corporate
suites. His office, in a six-story building in Charleston's
historic downtown district, is decorated with a statue of a bucking
bronco, pictures of horses and other mementoes of a ``Texas
wannabe,'' which Rice happily admits that he is. He owns a large
weekend home on the nearby Intracoastal Waterway, where he keeps 20
horses, and his idea of a good time is to go riding with his wife
and 14-year-old daughter or to go on cattle drives.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's firm had used the same type of legal roundup that it did
in the tobacco cases in suing asbestos producers, which is where it
made its reputation and its wealth. In those cases, as with
tobacco, its efforts to control litigation by dominating as many
cases as possible also led critics to charge it with conflicts of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   While the firm has profited from asbestos litigation for more
than a decade, last year the Supreme Court threw out one landmark
case, a $1.3 billion class-action settlement between asbestos
producers and plaintiffs' lawyers, including Rice, that not only
settled claims by existing asbestos victims but restricted the
legal options of people who might be sickened by asbestos in the
future. Opponents of the deal charged that lawyers like Rice
effectively sold out the legal rights of future victims so they
could reap hundreds of millions in fees by settling their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought what they were doing was unethical and illegal,''
said Brian Wolfman, a lawyer with Public Citizen, an advocacy group
in Washington that opposed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ness, Motley rejected any suggestion of conflict.
But at one point in the tobacco cases, the firm represented both
states and smokers in separate lawsuits, a problematic position
because the groups might have vied for settlement funds. It
withdrew from cases brought by smokers, but it now finds itself in
a similar position after signing up to represent New York state,
New York City and Erie County because state and local officials are
fighting for their share of New York's payout.
</P>
<P>
   A part of that fight will also involve lawyers' fees going to
Ness, Motley, said one lawyer involved in the New York case who
insisted on anonymity. And Rice also has some unfinished business
with Scruggs, the Mississippi lawyer. When Ness, Motley and
Scruggs' firm, Scruggs, Millette, Lawson, Bozeman &AMP; Dent, joined
forces on state tobacco cases, they had no written agreement on how
to split up fees.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said no decision had been made, but that Ness, Motley had
far more lawyers working on the tobacco cases than Scruggs' firm
did. And Rice said his firm had additional fee-sharing agreements
with other law firms involved in state tobacco cases to be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   While the tobacco industry is limiting its payouts through
arbitration to plaintiffs' lawyers to $500 million annually, some
$94 million of that first installment is likely to go to Ness,
Motley this year. Producers will continue to pay lawyers until all
the claims are resolved, so Rice's firm will be getting similar
paychecks for decades.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Rice, who recently bought a $1.5 million yacht, says he
does not have any immediate plans for his cut. Nor does he intend
to stop working, though an end to round-the-clock junk-food-filled
negotiations with tobacco industry lawyers has let him trim eight
pounds from his waistline.
</P>
<P>
   As he strolled around his office, he pointed out a newspaper
cartoon that a colleague had taped to his office. It shows a group
of fat lawyers with lighted cigars and raised glasses holding
bulging sacks of cash representing the take in Florida, Mississippi
and Texas. The caption of the cartoon, which ran in The Florida
Times-Union of Jacksonville, reads: ``To The Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a lot of money,'' Rice said. ``But nobody gave us a
chance in hell when we started out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
