<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1255 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-HNS &LR;      12-21 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS DISCUSS CENSURE AS ALTERNATIVE PUNISHMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican and Democratic senators indicated Monday
that some form of censure could be considered as an alternative
punishment for President Clinton when they take up the articles of
impeachment against him early next month.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and television appearances, most seemed to be open
to the idea of a bipartisan compromise like censure to avoid the
removal of the president from office or the possibility that he
could get off without any punishment for his conduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, at some point, censure certainly is going to be one
of the options,'' Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, told Cable
News Network.
</P>
<P>
   But she warned the White House, as did several Democratic
senators, not to play politics with the issue and to tone down the
rhetoric aimed at averting a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sentiment I'm hearing (from colleagues) is that we
need to start the process of a trial. What happens after that
starts opens a lot of doors and a lot of options,'' Hutchison said.
``All of us want to have a strong bipartisan solution that people
can rally around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said there must be no ``deal''
between the White House and the Senate. He said a negotiated
settlement would undermine the seriousness of the historic task the
Senate is expected to take up almost immediately after it convenes
Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders hope that impeachment proceedings can be wrapped
up by Jan. 19, when Clinton is scheduled to deliver his State of
the Union address. But they caution a Senate trial could drag on
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said he is open to a bipartisan solution as long as it is
worked out among senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether there is a trial or whether there is some other
solution, that decision must be made by senators, and it must be
bipartisan or it will have absolutely no credibility with the
public,'' Byrd said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators' comments came after former Presidents Carter and
Ford proposed Monday that the Senate adopt a bipartisan resolution
declaring that Clinton lied under oath rather than drag the country
through what could be a lengthy and sordid public trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow we must reach a conclusion that most Americans can
embrace and that posterity will approve,'' Democrat Carter and
Republican Ford wrote in an opinion piece published in The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake, the judgment of history does matter. It
matters profoundly,'' the two continued, adding that the
``impeachment by the full House has already brought profound
disgrace'' on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter-Ford proposal would require Clinton to admit that he
lied under oath, something that he has not been willing to do for
fear he might be indicted on perjury charges when he leaves office
by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. The Carter-Ford proposal,
however, would prevent Clinton's admission from being used against
him in a future trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., said the proposal was worth
examining. But he raised concerns that it could be viewed as ``a
pardon'' along the lines of the one Ford gave Nixon in Watergate
and the amnesty Carter granted to those who sought to avoid the
Vietnam draft.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials stopped short Monday of endorsing the
Carter-Ford suggestion. But Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart said the
president was willing to look at any ``reasonable ideas'' that
would bring the ordeal to a swift conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said he hopes the Senate will ``forge a
fair, bipartisan compromise to end this matter promptly _ and to
end it in a way that will respect the will and the wisdom of the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued to insist that Saturday's vote on impeachment in
the House ``was wrong ... for our Constitution and wrong for
America.'' He said he hopes the Senate will ``rise to the moment''
and ``be the voice of reason, deliberation and healing that America
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the president's lawyers will continue to prepare
``a whole series of legal and constitutional'' arguments against
impeachment in the event there is a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's view is that we need to work hard to find a
bipartisan solution to put this behind us,'' Lockhart said. ``But I
think the president's lawyers, as is their obligation, will prepare
an effective and persuasive defense if it does move to a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats warned the White House to back off any legal
challenge that might question whether the Senate has the right to
begin a trial based on impeachment articles drawn up by the
current, lame-duck 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., suggested that such actions could
backfire by eroding support for Clinton in the Senate and also with
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anything that is seen as parliamentary maneuvering to
get out of this is not going to be accepted by the American
public,'' Breaux told CNN. ``It's going to have to be out front. It
is going to have to be fair. I think if we try and solve this on
parliamentary maneuvering, it is going to be a serious mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., called for a ``a cooling off period''
over the holidays to give parties on both sides of the issue time
to reflect on what could lie ahead as the Senate prepares to take
up the two articles of impeachment accusing Clinton of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have the ball, I think it's up to us to handle it
coolly, objectively and with dignity,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   He called on the White House and the public ``to let us do our
jobs'' without the influence of public opinion polls, the latest of
which shows Clinton's job approval rate rising to a record 73
percent in the aftermath of his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls also indicate that two-thirds of the American
people favor a compromise rather than Clinton's removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be hard to avoid the beginning of a trial, some
senators who do not like the idea of removing a popularly elected
president from office hope to force a vote to dismiss the case. If
that vote fails, they'll move to censure Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those ... fail, then, presumably, we would move on to a
trial,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D. If it goes to trial, it
would take a two-thirds vote by the Senate to convict.
</P>
<P>
   About the only option not being considered as a way out of the
impeachment quagmire is resignation, even though some former
Clinton aides have suggested that his conduct has left him unfit to
govern.
</P>
<P>
   Former Press Secretary Mike McCurry has told the British
Broadcasting Co. he has ``enormous doubts because of the
recklessness of his (Clinton's) behavior. The nature of this
particular affair, and then the way he did conceal it, really does
raise some very profound, troubling matters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-HNS &LR;      12-21 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS DISCUSS CENSURE AS ALTERNATIVE PUNISHMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican and Democratic senators indicated Monday
that some form of censure could be considered as an alternative
punishment for President Clinton when they take up the articles of
impeachment against him early next month.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and television appearances, most seemed to be open
to the idea of a bipartisan compromise like censure to avoid the
removal of the president from office or the possibility that he
could get off without any punishment for his conduct in the Monica
Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, at some point, censure certainly is going to be one
of the options,'' Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, told Cable
News Network.
</P>
<P>
   But she warned the White House, as did several Democratic
senators, not to play politics with the issue and to tone down the
rhetoric aimed at averting a trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sentiment I'm hearing (from colleagues) is that we
need to start the process of a trial. What happens after that
