<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, DECEMBER 21
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections appeared in The New York Times on Monday.
Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission by the
New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by NYT
clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SATURN-APPOINT-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 12,
about the General Motors Corporation's appointment of Cynthia M.
Trudell as chairwoman and president of its Saturn division
misstated the dates of her service at G.M.'s transmission factory
in Ypsilanti, Mich. She was a manufacturing engineering manager and
later an operations manager there from 1987 to 1990, not 1981 to
1990. From 1981 to 1987, she was a manager at G.M.'s transmission
factory in Windsor, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   BC-U.S.-IRAQ-AID-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 15,
about Voices in the Wilderness, an American group that opposes
sanctions on Iraq and has received a warning from the United States
Government about goods it has taken there, misidentified the
Government department that operates the Office of Foreign Assets
Control. It is the Treasury Department, not the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TATE-GALLERY-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 1,
about the building of the new Tate Gallery of Modern Art in London
misspelled the surname of a British artist who is becoming
internationally known. She is Gillian Wearing, not Waring.
</P>
