<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RISK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Low-weight multiple-birth babies often must put up fight
to survive
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Chukwu octuplets face a fierce fight for their
lives in the next weeks _ and probably other challenges in the
years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple births are notoriously risky because the babies tend to
be significantly lower in weight and underdeveloped at birth. The
smaller they are and the more prematurely they are born, the more
medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Those surviving infancy may suffer health problems ranging from
learning disabilities to cerebral palsy because of neurological
damage. Such damage is caused by bleeding in the brain or the
inability of the babies' underdeveloped lungs to deliver sufficient
oxygen to their brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are drugs you can give for these premature babies to
reduce the respiratory distress syndrome, to mature their lungs,''
said Dr. Joe Massey of Reproductive Biology Associates of Atlanta,
the state's largest infertility clinic. ``But it can only be
incompletely effective at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Massey predicts problems are more likely with the Chukwu
octuplets than with the McCaughey septuplets, born 13 months ago to
Bobbi McCaughey of Iowa. The McCaughey babies, born in the 30th
week of gestation, were all at least 2 pounds at birth. The normal
gestation period is 40 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Chukwu babies are much smaller. One girl was
born Dec. 8 at 28 weeks, followed Sunday by the remaining seven at
30 weeks. The largest weighed 1 pound, 10 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   In multiple pregnancies, each baby has at least a 10 percent
risk of experiencing neurological handicaps, Massey said, compared
to 1 percent or less for a single baby born at 40 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Multiples are also much more likely than ``singletons,'' or
single babies, to die in infancy. In 1995, multiple babies
comprised less than 3 percent of all U.S. births, but 16 percent of
neonatal deaths, according to the National Center for Health
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the McCaugheys' success has encouraged some mothers
to be more confident about multiple pregnancies, Massey said.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductive Biology patients deliver twins at least monthly and
triplets five to 10 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there still are occasional losses of triplets,'' Massey
added, pointing out that Nkem Chukwu, who conceived via fertility
drugs, miscarried triplets earlier this year. ``Those are very sad
stories. People who have triplets or quadruplets and lose them at
five months, you don't hear about.''
</P>
<P>
   Reduction, selectively aborting some fetuses, is an option for
multiple pregnancies. But Reproductive Biology doctors don't advise
patients one way or the other, only warn them of the risks and
discuss reduction as one option.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reduction) doesn't clearly prolong the pregnancy as well as
we thought it would, but the babies are a little bigger,'' Massey
said. ``It probably reduces the risk. It's the worst decision our
patients ever have to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
