<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves might miss playoff
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves, who had heart bypass
surgery eight days ago, will not help prepare for this Sunday's
final regular-season game against Miami and could miss the team's
first playoff game on Jan. 9 or 10.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 54, was re-admitted to Piedmont Hospital on Sunday
afternoon after experiencing an accelerated heart rate a few hours
before the Falcons' game at Detroit. Atlanta defeated the Lions
24-17 to clinch the NFC West title and earn a bye through the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' condition is stable, but he will stay at Piedmont at
least until Wednesday. Doctors and team officials said he was not
getting enough rest at his Buckhead home after being discharged
last Friday, four days after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after his hospital release, Reeves and his
doctors predicted a part-time role for him this week and a full
return for the playoffs. Instead, he's in a private room where even
visits by family members are limited.
</P>
<P>
   He will not speak by phone with his assistants this week,
including Rich Brooks, the assistant head coach and defensive
coordinator serving as interim coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He overdid it,'' Brooks said about Reeves, who apparently
fielded too many phone calls, took too many visitors and wore
himself out with a Saturday morning trip to team headquarters to
address the team. ``He is not to be in contact with us at all this
week _ doctor's orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have no involvement in the upcoming game. We don't
know what the return schedule will be. The doctors will determine
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Reeves miss the first playoff game? ``It's conceivable,
yes,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Kauten, the heart surgeon who operated on Reeves,
would not comment specifically about Reeves but said an irregular
heart rhythm is common among bypass patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, it will occur post-op between 10 and 30 percent of
the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the irregularity is unknown, but doctors think it
probably is a combination of patients being on a heart-lung machine
during surgery and post-operative dehydration. It can be resolved
with medicine given for two or three months after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons team internist Dr. Charlie Harrison, who was talkative
last week, issued only a brief statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not feeling well and felt that something was, 'Not
right.' We decided to bring him back into the hospital in order to
run some tests and adjust his medication,'' the statement said.
``He remains in . . . good spirits and thrilled about his
championship team.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who had angioplasty procedures to clear heart blockages
in August 1990 and January 1991, began experiencing similar
symptoms after a 27-17 victory at New Orleans on Dec. 13. He
mentioned them to Harrison. The next morning, after an angiogram at
Piedmont, he was in surgery within a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves had four bypasses to circumvent blockages in three heart
arteries. He was walking and talking the next day and held an
emotional news conference after his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he really needs is rest, and what he didn't get last week
was rest,'' said Brooks, who is getting his information from team
physician Andrew Bishop. ``That's part our fault, part (the
media's) fault and part his fault. Dan needs to take care of
himself right now, and we need to take care of the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor is going to make sure he doesn't overdo it again,
and if that means missing the first playoff game, he'll miss the
first playoff game. It's obviously a hell of a lot more important
that he regain his health and get strong than a football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Lillian Lee Kim contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
