<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-CASUALTIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQIS COUNT DEAD, SCOFF AT BOMBINGS' EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD _ Iraqi officials say US and British air raids had
killed 62 soldiers, and had wounded 180.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also asserted Monday that civilian casualties were
``much, much higher,'' but they refused to offer details on that
death toll, which the Iraqi United Nations ambassador, Nizar
Hamdoon, had said on Sunday was in the ``thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   The official Iraqi military casualty count is impossible for a
tightly controlled press corps to confirm here.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Iraqi Health Ministry had said that 42
civilians had been killed in the attacks, and about 100 were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqi leaders also acknowledged that the four days of
sustained missile attacks, which ended Saturday, had demolished
missile factories and had severed telephone communication between
the north and south of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But they scoffed at the notion that splitting the predominantly
Sunni Muslim northern part of the country and the Shiite Muslim
south would lead to a revolt against Saddam Hussein. They dismissed
the idea as an American ``Rambo-like fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz added that the United States
and Britain had failed to harm seriously the Iraqi government or
military. ``They boasted of great success,'' he said. ``They
lied.''
</P>
<P>
   General Anthony Zinni of the Marine Corps said in Washington on
Monday that the strikes had hit 85 percent of their targets, 74
percent of them successfully. He said that damage assessment from
cruise missile and bombing attacks probably will take a few more
days.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq says the missiles also targeted civilians in colleges, post
offices, dormitories, a museum and an oil refinery. ``This is a
policy of hatred,'' Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi authorities have refused foreign journalists access to
sites where they say significant civilian casualties were recorded.
</P>
<P>
   But Aziz offered a complete breakdown of the military
casualties. He said the elite Republican Guard, a primary target of
the attacks, especially in the south, had lost 20 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen soldiers of the Special Republican Guard, whose duties
Aziz refused to describe, and 24 soldiers in other branches of the
military, were also killed, and 180 soldiers were wounded. But most
of the strikes hit empty barracks, Aziz said, adding, ``These
barracks could be and will be rebuilt.'
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Aziz directly addressed what some analysts
see as a US strategy to divide the north and the south to
destabilize Hussein's regime. ``They thought foolishly that the
people of Iraq will uprise. This is a fantasy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Shiites in the south rose in rebellion after the Gulf War of
1991. That uprising was crushed by troops loyal to Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Western observers in Baghdad say, the regime appears to be
showing some concern about a possible rebellion, and thus has taken
steps to tighten its grip on the military.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein divided Iraq into four military districts Wednesday
after the US and British air raids began. The observers say that he
appointed loyal military commanders to direct the regional
quadrants to thwart possible civilian uprisings.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi opposition groups in London and Cairo say that Hussein's
cousin, former Defense Minister Ali Hasan Al-Majid, was named the
commander in the sensitive southern region. The opposition claims
that Al-Majid ordered the executions of several officers in the
south immediately after he took control.
</P>
<P>
   The Western observers also offered an explanation why the Iraqi
military offered so little resistance during the fighting. They
surmised that Iraq withheld its surface-to-air missiles, which
could have been used to defend against the attacks, to avoid
targeting by allied forces.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
