<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-ART-NYT &LR;      12-21 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTUPLETS' BIRTH NO CAUSE FOR CELEBRATION, DOCTORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ga., Ala., N.Y., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The two sons and six daughters of Nkem Chukwu remained
in critical condition at Texas Children's Hospital Monday, sedated,
incubated and all eight of them together weighing just a breath
over 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   While news of the birth of the Chukwu octuplets _ which the
family had tried to keep private but which had leaked out to
Houston media outlets on Sunday _ had drawn dozens of reporters and
television crews to the hospital and was being greeted by many
Monday as a cause for celebration, it was raising deep concern
among leading reproductive specialists around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not be a cause for celebration,'' said Dr. Mark
Perloe, director of reproductive endocrinology at the Atlanta
Reproductive Health Center. ``The cost of caring for these babies
and the pregnancy will run into the millions of dollars. The risk
of death still exists. And there is a significant risk that they
will have lifelong health problems. I think this is a wake-up call
for the medical profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Increases in the use of the same kinds of fertility drugs that
had been given to Ms. Chukwu have caused a surge of multiple births
in the last decade, specialists said. ``If you look at the
statistics, you see that there is a growing increase in the number
of multiple gestations,'' said Dr. Benjamin Younger, executive
director of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine, based
in Birmingham, Ala. ``Some of it is due to in-vitro fertilization,
some is due to an expanded use of the medications but some of it is
just because we are seeing the results of the baby boomers who
delayed in having their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a situation has led many aging and childless couples to
demand the types of aggressive fertility therapies more likely to
produce multiple births.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish this couple well and I hope the babies do well, but
this scares me,'' said Dr. Alan Copperman, director of reproductive
endocrinology at Mt. Sinai-NYU Medical Center and Health System in
New York. ``It seems there is almost an acceptance these days of
quads or quints or even more, and the outrage gets less and less as
we hear about more and more of these cases. The fact is that the
vast majority of these cases end in disaster, sometimes for the
mom, most often for the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Chukwu babies are the only known living octuplets in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a successful octuplet pregnancy in the
history of mankind,'' said Dr. Mark Evans, chairman of the
department of obstetrics and gynecology at Wayne State University
in Detroit. ``Although these babies were born alive, the odds are,
unfortunately, that there will not be happy outcomes for at least
several of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, nine infants were born to a mother in Sydney,
Australia, but all subsequently died. And there have been three
other cases of octuplet births in the last 13 years, one in Spain,
one in Britain and one in Turkey, but in each case at least some of
the infants soon died.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a case comes along like that of Ms. Chukwu _ or Bobbi
McCaughey, who gave birth to seven babies in November 1997 in
Carlisle, Iowa, all of whom still survive _ some desperate couples
become more willing to take greater risks, Copperman said. ``It's
almost like an arms race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chukwu children all maintained a fragile hold on life
Monday, doctors said, and the next three days will be the most
critical, as it becomes clear whether the infants' lungs, hearts,
brains and internal organs are developed enough to keep them alive.
Even after that, doctors said, dangers remain from infections or
metabolic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chukwu, 27, was born in Nigeria but is now an American
citizen living in the Houston area. The hospital declined to
release any personal information about the couple, at their
request, though The Houston Chronicle identified her husband, Iyke,
as a respiratory therapist.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had been trying to conceive for several years and Ms.
Chukwu had lost triplets earlier this year, doctors said, so she
entered her most recent pregnancy with a solemn determination. At a
news conference at the hospital on Sunday, Dr. Patti Savrick
described the new mother as unusually tall and ``very serene, a
very spiritual woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The fertility drugs Ms. Chukwu was receiving, hospitals
officials said, were pure FSH, which stimulates ovulation, and HCG,
or human chorionic gonadatropin, which is normally produced by a
healthy placenta to maintain pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chukwu was admitted to St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital in
early October as she and doctors struggled to forestall the birth
of the fetuses until they were old enough to survive. She gave
birth to her first daughter on Dec. 8, 15 weeks premature, but
doctors were able to delay the other births until Sunday morning.
It was not until after the first birth that a sonogram revealed
there were seven more living fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chukwu remained confined to her hospital bed for the two
weeks following her initial delivery with her pelvis raised above
her head, to remove pressure on her cervix, and was administered a
trio of drugs (magnesium sulfate, terbutaline and indomethicin) to
delay the birth of the remaining fetuses, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining seven children were born during a 45-minute
Caesarian section at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital early Sunday and
ferried to the adjacent Texas Children's Hospital by a team of more
than two dozen doctors. The family immediately asserted its
privacy, refusing to give interviews, to appoint a family spokesman
or to allow photos of the tiny infants, forcing journalists to set
up camp outside the hospital, which by Monday was giving no more
press briefings and simply releasing updates every six hours on its
Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   The premature Chukwu children remained unnamed Monday at Texas
Children's Hospital, where they were being referred to as babies
A-through-H. The largest of them was 26 ounces, the smallest 10.3
ounces. Exact measurements were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1268 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-ART-2NDTAKE     12-21 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOUSTON: were unavailable. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The smallest one, Baby E, is small enough to fit in a woman's
hand, as small as a beanie baby,'' said Laura Floyd, a hospital
spokeswoman. All of the babies were in incubators and under
sedation, and seven remained attached to ventilators to aid their
underdeveloped lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, their mother had to undergo further surgery Monday
morning to correct internal bleeding, which doctors described as a
``generalized ooze'' in her abdomen. ``It was something not
anticipated,'' said Dr. Brian Kirshon, a specialist in high-risk
births who delivered the Chukwu children.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said they expected Ms. Chukwu to be well enough to go
home in about a week, though the infants, if they survive, would
likely remain hospitalized for many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshon and other members of the medical team involved in the
Chukwu births told reporters on Sunday that, of course, bearing
octuplets was not the desired result of fertility treatments. ``The
human being was meant to have one baby,'' Kirshon said. It had
happened, in this case, both because the fertility drugs which had
made Ms. Chukwu's pregnancy possible had also led to the
fertilization of so many eggs and because the family, when given
the option early in her pregnancy to stop the growth of some of the
fertilized embryos, a procedure called selective or multi-fetal
reduction, had declined to allow it.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is highly controversial and some patients and
doctors consider it unethical, a form of early abortion. Proponents
argue that, while it is not the ideal outcome, the procedure does
provide a potentially better chance for the remaining embryos to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every single patient that undergoes treatment with these
fertility drugs I discuss the dangers and I discuss multi-fetal
reduction,'' Copperman said. ``If they say yes, they will allow
reduction, it perhaps allows you a little more leeway to give
fertility drugs. With others, say they can't emotionally or
religiously or ethically tolerate the procedure, you have to be
more careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Such issues only come into play in procedures involving these
fertility drugs, doctors say. In those cases where in-vitro
fertilization is used, under 10 percent of all cases, the number of
eggs implanted into the mother can be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``With in-vitro, you have a tremendous amount of control, but
with these fertility drugs, when you don't use in-vitro, you can
cause the woman to make a lot of eggs and you don't have quite as
much control,'' Copperman said.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes, in some extreme cases, a bit of a guessing game, and
not all doctors administering the fertility drugs have as much
training as they might need, said Perloe. ``There are no
restrictions on who can use these drugs. A gynecologist with four
weeks training during his residency has just as much access as
someone who has done a fellowship and trained two to three years,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, Younger said, is that prospective parents
sometimes must pay for their own fertility procedures when medical
insurers decline to cover them. ``And since they're paying for it,
and it is very costly, they often demand the most aggressive form
of therapy and they get into a situation of unnecessary risk
taking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Younger said, the federal government has
steadfastly refused to allocate money for reproductive research,
largely because ``the issue inevitably always becomes entwined with
the abortion debate.'' Conservatives in Congress have expressed
concerns over research involving the use of human embryos, Younger
said, choking off funding both for that kind of research and for
other fertility research, even if it doesn't involve the use of
embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The end result, he said, is that during the same years when the
use of such fertility drugs was going up and the demand was
increasing from aging, childless couples, very little research was
being done in the United States on the proper use of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd been doing the research, we might have looked to
develop some protocols on how to best use these drugs, protocols
that would have lessened the likelihood of something like this
happening,'' Younger said. ``The dearth of research has left a
great void in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   On the brighter side, doctors in the field have become much more
scrupulous about warning patients of the dangers involved, he said.
The problem is that the patients, desperate to get pregnant, don't
always listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients develop what we call selective hearing,'' Younger
said. ``They just filter the warnings down to a lower level and
concentrate on the part about getting pregnant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
