<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HUMMER-REEVES-COX     12-21 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HUMMER-REEVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Respite is in order for Reeves
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mostly, Monday's injury report for the Falcons was
unremarkable, encouraging. With one large exception:
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves _ out (strained patience).
</P>
<P>
   Rich Brooks, the undefeated interim head coach of the Falcons,
is no doctor, but his diagnosis of the reversal that landed Reeves
back in the hospital Sunday afternoon was expert enough for our
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much, too soon,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't you see it coming? Wasn't it obvious with his teary
news conference Friday _ just four days after heart bypass surgery
_ and his insistence upon visiting the team at Suwanee on Saturday
before it left for Detroit that Reeves was pushing it? His mind was
making too many promises that his body couldn't fill.
</P>
<P>
   The coach needed one more lesson on being a good patient, and it
came in the form of a racing heartbeat before the Falcons had taken
the field in Detroit. His body was calling for a time-out; and you
only get a limited amount in this life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You worry about (Reeves rushing back),'' team president Taylor
Smith said. ``It's almost was like he felt he was letting everybody
down. I think he needs to be relieved of that pressure for a while,
(to) get well. And he will.''
</P>
<P>
   The treatment, they say, is to get as far away from professional
football as possible. May we suggest a week in Charlotte?
</P>
<P>
   Failing that, Reeves will be cloistered away from the team, its
fans and the media, just as the celebration over the NFC West title
begins to peak. He is in strict medical exile, which seems to make
a lot more sense than the original plan to jump back into the fray.
One prognosis had him being able to help game-plan for the Dolphins
this Sunday, which always did seem more hopeful fantasy than
medical possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know his return schedule,'' Brooks says now.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it is to say, the Falcons might as well proceed
from here under the assumption that Reeves is lost for the season.
The realistic approach is to press on into the playoffs, without
expectation that their coach will show them the way.
</P>
<P>
   We all tried to fool ourselves that he would be able to shake it
off and be fit for the Falcons most promising postseason run in 18
years. More than anyone, Reeves is the man who rightfully should be
leading this parade. But that doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Players miss seasons to breaks and tears. Good heavens, a week
ago the coach had his chest cracked like a walnut while surgeons
constructed a little I-285 around his heart. Yes, he can get a
written doctor's excuse to sit down during the playoffs, maybe
watch them from a booth.
</P>
<P>
   How hard will it be to rein in Reeves now that the reality of
his situation is more plain? ``For a little while, not too hard,''
Brooks said. ``As he starts feeling stronger, then it will be
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in the time of Falcons plenty, the architect of it all is
asked to partake in none of it. That has to be nearly as painful as
any incision.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to face the truth that for the next month Reeves
can't lead as he has. This very well might hurt the Falcons. But
racing back to the sidelines before he is truly able does no one
any good.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Email: steve(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
