<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SHRUG OFF IMPEACHMENT; DOW UP 85 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fallout from political turmoil at home or military action
abroad often rains down on financial markets. Not so for the first
impeachment of a US president since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Monday pushed the Dow Jones industrial average up
85.22 points to close at 8988.85 in the first day of trading since
the House of Representatives' bipartisan vote Saturday to impeach
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The gain _ for a third consecutive day _ brought the Dow closer
to its 9374.27 high reached on the Monday before Thanksgiving.
Despite a volatile year, the Dow is up a respectable 13.66 percent
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A bull market in dark political times seemed to be testament to
investors' blind and determined optimism about the economy and its
prospects _ no matter what is unfolding in Washington, D.C., or how
many bombs are falling in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complacency of the market is outstanding,'' said Kathleen
Camilli, chief economist for Tucker Anthony Inc. in New York.
``Corporate America has been so successful increasing the wealth of
average Americans, does it really matter what happens in
Washington? It doesn't really affect us that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has a history of reacting to political events only
when they have a direct impact on the economy, analysts said. For
example, the 1990 bombing of Iraq by President Bush triggered a
market drop. But, the economy at the time was sinking into
recession, and there was a fear retaliation against Iraq's
oil-producing neighbors would worsen it.
</P>
<P>
   Bombings in Iraq have become almost familiar since. Meanwhile,
analysts said, Wall Street views Clinton's troubles as either a
largely Republican attack on the Democratic president, or destined
to come to a screeching halt when a more temperate Senate takes
over and possibly votes for a censure of the president, for his
behavior in the investigation of an affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day for the country and clearly a sad day for
the Clintons, but it's not clear what the economic impact'' of
impeachment is, said James Weiss, deputy head of equities for State
Street Research &AMP; Management Co. ``So, at the moment it's not
affecting the market.''
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look at the market reveals what appears to be
irrational hopes are investors whose decisions are tinged with
wariness. Investors have restricted much of their confidence to the
large high-tech company stocks, which are pulling along a market
that, otherwise, is in the doldrums, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the 12 best performing stocks in the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 accounted for just over half the index's total gain of
22.5 percent for the year through Dec. 18, according to an analysis
by BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Microsoft Corp. has more than doubled in price
since January, rising 2 5/8 Monday to close at 140 7/16. Other Blue
Chip computer giants also gained: Lucent Technologies up 5 1/2,
closing at 103 7/8; Cisco Systems rose 4 1/4 to 94 11/16; Intel
added 2 11/16 to 122 11/16; and Dell Computer Corp. climbed 4 1/16,
to 71 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fab Five _ Cisco Systems, Microsoft, Lucent, Dell, and
Intel _ are clearly providing the leadership for the market as they
have been for the last couple of months,'' said Ned Riley,
BankBoston's chief investment officer.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``When the average investor looks at his or her mutual fund
holdings, the question automatically asked is, `Why didn't my funds
do as well as the S&AMP;P?' '' he said. ``Because their mutual fund
didn't hold Microsoft at the same weighting as the S&AMP;P or Intel,
which was up 71 percent through last Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Many investors have money in growth funds invested in small
stocks, which have not performed well this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Parke, who heads the equity group for Massachusetts
Financial Services, agrees gains are ``concentrated in the
fast-growing blue chip technology companies,'' while ``the rest of
the market was left in the dust for the past few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small stocks is down 8.05 percent for
the year. And blue chip companies such as Gillette Co. have
languished, because they don't give investors what they want:
strong earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   The razor and consumer products company's stock has dropped from
highs of around 62 a share in April and in July as profits fell
below expectations. Gillette's stock dipped 5/16 Monday, closing at
43.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that wants earnings certainty, and it's
willing to pay for any company with earnings certainty. Therefore,
the rich stocks just get richer,'' Parke said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets have been further fortified by successfully
shaking off the turmoil _ and fears of recession _ triggered by
disasters in Asia and Russia last summer. And though economists
predict US growth is expected to slow, interest rate cuts by the
Federal Reserve, copied by European central banks, also reassured
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Events in the political world could have consequences in 1999,
however, if the Senate is forced to move ahead with a full trial
and conviction of President Clinton. But investors ``presume the
Senate will not move forward with a trial'' of the president,
Camilli said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, investors ``are finding a very safe haven in the middle
of this herd,'' said BankBoston's Riley. ``As long as the herd
continues to pour money into the biggest and most successful tech
stocks, they will feel comfortable. But . . . if the leaderhip
shift takes place, it could be very traumatic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
