<SLUG> BC-ZAMBIA-COPPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SAYS THERE'S NO DEAL YET FOR COPPER MINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Anglo American Corp. of South
Africa said Monday that reports coming out of Zambia this weekend
that it had agreed to buy three of Zambia's most important copper
mines are ``premature.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nchanga, Nkana and Konkola mines are the richest prizes of
the state-owned copper company, and their sale is crucial to the
country's privatization program.
</P>
<P>
   News reports from Lusaka quoted Zambia's finance minister, Edith
Nawakwi, as saying a deal had been reached for Anglo American to
take over the mines for $10 million in royalties and a commitment
to spend $1.1 billion upgrading them. Negotiations to sell them to
another consortium went on for two years, with the sale price
regularly falling with copper prices.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo American said Monday that its negotiating team had signed
``a non-legally binding memorandum of understanding'' with the
Zambian government. But it said the document would become effective
only when ratified by both the government and the board of the
Anglo American subsidiary that already owns a 27 percent interest
in the mines.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are continuing, Anglo American said.
</P>
<P>
   A protocol officer for the finance minister said she was in an
urgent Cabinet meeting and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
