<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-F22-COX     12-21 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-F22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pentagon OKs Lockheed fighter
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Pentagon has approved initial production of
Lockheed Martin's F-22 fighter, a milestone for the program headed
at the company's Marietta, Ga. plant.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts worth $761 million passed final review by a top
Pentagon panel. One, for $571 million, will fund two production
test planes. Another, for $190 million, includes advance payments
on six more of the state-of-the-art warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a favorable review,'' Gloria Cales, an Air Force
spokeswoman, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts still must be signed by Defense Secretary William
Cohen, a formality expected within days.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft covered by the contracts are the first of 339 F-22s
the Air Force plans to buy over the next 16 years for up to $41
billion, plus $19 billion in development costs.
</P>
<P>
   Final assembly is to be done in Marietta, where Lockheed
Martin's Aeronautical Systems unit oversees the F-22 program.
Boeing Co. is a major partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This moves the program to the production phase from the
development stage we've been in for the last few years,'' said Tom
Burbage, vice president and general manager of F-22 programs at the
Marietta plant. ``It's a nice way to end the year.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Lockheed Martin has produced three F-22s, two for flight
tests and one for ground tests.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract funds two planes, called Production
Representative Test Vehicles, to be built in 1999. They'll be used
to certify assembly line processes and, unlike the existing test
planes, will later go into service.
</P>
<P>
   Full funding for the next batch of six planes would be awarded
late next year, assuming the program receives continued support
from the Pentagon and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After that, production would ramp up to 24 planes annually by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 of the Marietta plant's 9,400 employees work on the
F-22. Burbage said that number will stay fairly constant, as
employment on the engineering side drops while production manpower
rises.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, F-22 flight testing fell behind schedule,
prompting the General Accounting Office to recommend delaying the
program. But the plane in November met the Pentagon's requirement
for 184.4 test hours _ 4 percent of the total planned _ before
initial production was approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the program is very solid technically,'' Burbage said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
