<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COX     12-21 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheap oil prices keep holiday visitors on the road
 &HT;    By Marcus Franklin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There is good news for holiday travelers:
Gasoline prices are down, despite U.S. military airstrikes against
Iraq last week and tensions between the United States and other
Middle Eastern countries, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently there has not been any real jitter for a disruption
(of the flow on oil to this country),'' Keaton said. ``Refiners are
still operating at 92 percent to 96 percent of their capacity. It's
all very dependent on how much the war might escalate.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the average price of self-serve regular unleaded gas
decreased this month to $1 a gallon, down about 3 cents since
November, according to AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Travel experts anticipate that a record 45.2 million people will
travel 100 miles or more from home during the Christmas and New
Year's holidays, a 2 percent increase over last year's 42.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 million will go by automobile and nearly 10 million by
airplane, train or bus, according to AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dallas-based Greyhound carried 1.25 million people
around the nation to be with loved ones for the holidays. This
year, the company expects its ridership to increase by at least 5
percent, according to company spokeswoman Katherine Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Those who travel by airplane should be prepared for delays
because of the recent U.S. airstrikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you plan to fly and take a present to your
nephew in Florida this week, don't gift wrap it. If you do, airport
security people will unwrap it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the same level of security we've been on since the
Persian Gulf war,'' said John Sears, a spokesman at Dayton
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Sears said the only change is that last year's Federal Aviation
Administration ``advice'' to unwrap packages at security
checkpoints this year is a directive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
