<SLUG> BC-EIGHT-BIRTHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTUPLETS STRUGGLE FOR LIFE, WORLD WRESTLES WITH IMPLICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first surviving set of octuplets, born of modern
chemistry and their mother's persistence, clung to life Monday
under plastic blankets and the eyes of a world left to wonder about
the boundaries of science.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Texas Children's Hospital were taking
``minute-by-minute'' care of Nkem Chukwu's six daughters and two
sons, who collectively weighed just over 10 pounds, or the
equivalent of a single large newborn.
</P>
<P>
   Although statistically they had an 85 percent chance of
survival, all remained in critical condition and two appeared to be
struggling somewhat Monday, said chief neonatologist Dr. Leonard
Weisman. All face two to three months of intensive care at an
anticipated cost of $250,000 each, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven were born Sunday by caesarean section, 13 weeks before
their normal due date; one was delivered vaginally 12 days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Their 27-year-old mother, who had taken fertility drugs, had
surgery Monday to repair damage from the extreme measures she took
to keep her babies growing inside her, which included spending
weeks nearly upside down to minimize pressure on her midsection.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said the babies were being monitored for
life-threatening disorders common among premature infants. ``Our
main concern is that we get through the first few days, which we
usually associate with breathing or heart problems,'' he said in an
interview. ``The next phase will be nutrition, focusing on whether
we are giving them enough fluids, sugar, proteins, fats.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Monday, a media horde had assembled and pledges of
donations were streaming into St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital, where
the children were born before being whisked to the neonatal
intensive care unit at adjacent Texas Children's.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pledges were a lifetime supply of diapers from an
anonymous donor; a lifetime supply of wipes and disposable training
pants from the Drypers Corp.; a one-year supply of baby formula
from Mead Johnson Nutritional; and a year's supply of groceries
from Randall's, a Houston supermarket chain, said Marianne Dwyer,
assistant director of health care philanthropy at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous callers also offered financial help, and the hospital
was in the process of setting up a trust fund for the family, she
said. A load of toys, flowers and balloons also was en route to the
Chukwus.
</P>
<P>
   The seven babies born Sunday were all breathing with help from a
ventilator Monday. The first baby was taken off the ventilator and
was only receiving supplemental oxygen. She had begun feeding
through a tube in her mouth, while her siblings were receiving
intravenous fluids with dissolved sugar and salt. All remained
under the warmth of artificial light and plastic blankets designed
to help them retain fluid.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly two-week gap between births was possible because each
baby grew inside its own amniotic sac; after the first girl was
born Dec. 8, doctors gave Mrs. Chukwu drugs that ceased labor and
helped her cervix to close, giving the remaining babies added time
inside the womb, Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Kirshon, a high-risk obstetrician, said Mrs. Chukwu
underwent surgery Monday to control abdominal bleeding caused by
those measures. He called the surgery successful and said Mrs.
Chukwu might go home by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Chukwus, Nigerian-born US citizens living in southwest
Houston, had not told hospital officials of their decisions about
baby names, and so each was designated with a letter, a system that
used up one-third of the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   The largest was Baby G, a boy who weighed 1 pound and 10 ounces
at birth; the smallest was Baby E, a girl who weighed just over 10
ounces. Weisman said it appeared Baby E had been ``crowded'' by her
siblings, and her diminutive size made her prospects unclear. The
smallest of the septuplets born last year to an Iowa family, the
McCaugheys, weighed in excess of a half-pound more than the largest
Chukwu octuplet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the largest among the octoplets face uncertain futures. By
two weeks of age, each baby will be tested to see if there is
bleeding into the brain; beginning at six weeks, each will be given
regular eye tests because impaired vision is common among premature
infants. Infections are an ongoing concern, and doctors will
continually monitor their physical and emotional development, which
might be delayed or impaired, Weisman said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He defended the cost of the babies' care _ more than 25 times
the expense of eight uneventful, single births _ contrasting it
with the amount of money spent on geriatric patients near the end
of their lives. ``If a baby gets a quarter-of-a-million dollars in
care and lives to be 83, when you consider the number of years of
productive life, it's not that much. From our perspective, we think
these costs are worthwhile,'' Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors knew Mrs. Chukwu was carrying multiple fetuses, but
learned exactly how many only after the Dec. 8 birth. They kept it
a secret until Sunday at the request of her and her husband Iyke, a
physical therapist at a Houston hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had discussed aborting one or more fetus to give the
others more room to grow, but the Chukwus declined, citing their
religious beliefs. The Chukwus had long sought unsuccessfully to
have children before taking fertility drugs, and she suffered a
miscarriage of triplets earlier this year while also taking the
drugs, Kirshon said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hurdles that remain, the births were nothing short
of a medical marvel and a testament to Mrs. Chukwu's fortitude.
Hospitalized since October and confined to bed for six weeks, she
was fed intravenously to shrink her stomach and give her babies
room to grow. She spent the days leading up to the caesarean tilted
nearly upside down to keep pressure off her lower body.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was determined to give these babies the best chance
possible by trying to prolong the pregnancy,'' Wiseman said.
``Imagine putting a 25- to 30-pound bowling ball on your belly and
lying upside down for two weeks. Anything she could do, she did.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest recorded multiple birth was nine babies in Sydney,
Australia, in 1971, according to the Guinness Book of World
Records. All the children died. Three other cases of octuplets have
been recorded in the past 13 years. In two cases, all the babies
died, but in 1996 a Spanish woman delivered six healthy babies
after two fetuses died in utero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
