<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-HNS &LR;      12-21 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PARLIAMENT GIVES INITIAL APPROVAL FOR EARLY ELECTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's Parliament rejected Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's peace policies Monday and then took the first step
toward dissolving itself and holding early elections.
</P>
<P>
   The action is likely to put the brakes on peacemaking with the
Palestinians for several months.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 81 of the 120 members of the parliament, the Knesset,
voted to dissolve the body and hold elections, including several
from Netanyahu's coalition and his own Likud Party. The preliminary
vote took place just minutes after the packed assembly defeated the
prime minister's plan calling on the Palestinians to fulfill
specific peace commitments before Israel would agree to cede more
West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting slumped in his seat and looking dejected, Netanyahu cast
his vote in favor of the bill, brought by the opposition Labor
Party, after making a last-ditch call for a national unity
government. The offer was rejected immediately by Labor's leader,
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The victory of the new elections bill represents a blow to
Netanyahu, who had hoped that he could instead muster enough votes
to pass his plan for peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   His plan would have required commitments from Palestinians to
renounce all claims to statehood and Jerusalem; stop violence and
incitement to violence; seize illegal arms; and accept Israel's
terms for release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote, Netanyahu said he was confident that a majority
of the Israeli public backed his tough peace policies for the
Palestinians. But should the Knesset vote for early elections, he
predicted, he would be re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced that people want peace with reciprocity and
Jerusalem as Israel's capital,'' Netanyahu said. ``We will fight
for our opinions and if there will be new elections, we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Netanyahu's plan, approved by his right-wing
Cabinet on Sunday, was defeated by a vote of 56 to 48. Then the
bill for early elections passed its first reading. It must pass two
more readings, which may take place as soon as next week, before it
becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he would not fight the bill's second and third
readings, and Israeli press reports predicted that elections would
be set for sometime between March and June of next year, about a
year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Knesset, it seemed that election season had already
begun.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the vote, Barak chided Netanyahu for leading
Israel down a path of stalemate in negotiations with the
Palestinians and promised Israelis that his Labor party would be
able to deliver in peacemaking where Netanyahu had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got another road to offer,'' Barak told the packed
Parliament in a speech broadcast on Israel TV. ``We want to get
this country back on track, invest in education, not in the
(Israeli) settlements (on the West Bank and Gaza).
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the peace process, and we are going to change
Israel into a better place for all of us,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote ended two weeks of frantic maneuvering by Netanyahu to
save his crumbling coalition, which began when members of Labor and
Meretz, a smaller left-wing party, proposed the bill for early
elections.
</P>
<P>
   To buy time then, Netanyahu asked a coalition partner to attach
a no-confidence motion to the bill, which postponed the vote for
one week, according to Knesset rules. But the vote was held up for
two weeks to accommodate President Clinton's visit to Israel and
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the no-confidence motion was withdrawn, leaving the
Parliament to vote on Netanyahu's peace plan and the bill for early
elections only.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians blasted the prospect of months of campaigning,
which likely will divert attention from peacemaking and make it
virtually impossible for Israel to carry out more land-transfers
and other obligations made in the U.S.-brokered Wye River peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a bad signal if Israel stops the peace process,'' said
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat. ``In my view, this is the
greatest violation of the Wye agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials refrained from commenting on Israel's internal
politics, but said they expected the Wye agreement to be carried
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of the United States is that the Wye River
memorandum should be implemented as signed and without new
conditions,'' said State Department spokesman James Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians have worked hard to implement many of their
commitments under the agreement, including annulling clauses in the
Palestine National Charter and stepping up the fight against
terror,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Monday's vote, Netanyahu appeared to be in trouble
with Israel's voters. A poll taken last week concluded that 80
percent of Israelis supported the Wye agreement, 53 percent were
unsatisfied with Netanyahu's handling of the peace process and 63
percent wanted to see former army chief-of-staff Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak, touted as a favorite to beat Netanyahu, enter
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Up until the last minute, Netanyahu portrayed himself as a tough
negotiator who could get the best deal possible in negotiations
with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise you that Arafat is the first person who thinks any
alternative is better than Netanyahu,'' Netanyahu said. ``The whole
world understands this. Every Palestinian understands this. And
most of the nation understands this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
