<SLUG> BC-BOOZY-LUNCHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASUAL DRINKING HURTS WORK PERFORMANCE, STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a season of holiday office parties and year-end boozing,
Boston researchers have offered surprising new evidence on who is
responsible for most alcohol-related problems in the workplace: Not
the classic ``problem drinkers'' but the majority of workers who
occasionally imbibe too much on weeknights or have a drink with
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The new view, which upsets a half-dozen assumptions about
alcohol and job performance, emerges from surveys of almost 14,000
managers and hourly workers in seven Fortune 500 companies. The
surveys were conducted by researchers from Harvard and Boston
Universities and the Boston consulting firm of John Snow, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis found that 77 percent of workers who occasionally
drink to excess the night before a workday, or have any alcohol
with lunch, account for almost 60 percent of productivity problems
_ absenteeism, coming late to work or leaving early, poor work
performance, and workplace strife.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take classic hangover symptoms such as nausea and
headache to lower productivity, noted Jonathan Howland of Boston
University School of Public Health, one of the study authors.
``Excessive alcohol use which upsets sleep and decreases
concentration can affect the employee, and productivity goes
downhill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are based on questionnaires mailed to the homes of
managers and workers from 130 US work sites. First researchers
sorted respondents into levels of alcohol use, classifying about
one-fifth as alcohol-dependent, 61 percent as non-dependent
drinkers, and 20 percent as abstainers.
</P>
<P>
   The high level of workers considered alcohol-dependent is based
on a fairly broad, but generally accepted, definition that includes
individuals who answer ``yes'' to two or more questions such as:
``Have you ever felt the need to cut down on your drinking?'' or
``Have you ever felt guilty about your drinking?''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the yearly rate of work performance problems among the
three groups, researchers not surprisingly found that
alcohol-dependent workers ranked highest, with nearly seven
episodes of work performance problems a year, compared to about
four episodes among abstainers. Nondependent drinkers were
intermediate, with 5.4 episodes on average.
</P>
<P>
   However, because there were so many more non-dependent drinkers,
they accounted for a larger fraction of workplace productivity
problems _ 59 percent, versus 41 percent for the classic problem
drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for American firms, the researchers said, is
that companies are ignoring the largest source of their
alcohol-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provocative new study raises interesting questions about
our understanding of the alcohol problem in America,'' said Dr.
Steven A. Schroeder, president of the Robert Wood Johnson
Foundation, which funded the study. ``It tests conventional wisdom
and offers insight into the nature of the harms caused by alcohol
in the workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors, drawing on several years of research, say their
findings justify a new look at workplace policies focussed for
decades on counselling and treating (or firing) the obvious
alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   Citing recent revisions of societal thinking about drinking and
driving, college binge drinking, and cigarette smoking, the
researchers said it ``may now be time to revisit workplace alcohol
policies and practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed, but some cautioned against management preachments
that intrude into employees' personal lives, lest that produce
resentment rather than behavioral change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study is a wakeup call,'' said Bruce Davidson, manager of
employee assistance and work life programs at Compaq Computer
Corporation in Maynard, Mass. ``But you shouldn't cross the magic
line that separates the workplace from what people do in their
private time, or you'll get a backlash. Nobody likes to be told
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason why heavy-handed management pronouncements might
not work, the study suggests, is that managers do more than their
share of daytime drinking with adverse consequences on their own
productivity. The study found that managers were three times more
likely than hourly workers to drink during working hours _ usually
at lunch or at company-sponsored functions.
</P>
<P>
   But one alcohol researcher said there is accumulating evidence
that nondependent drinkers may give up ``risky drinking'' behavior
quite readily, in contrast to those who are classic alcohol
addicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news on this story is there is 20 years of research
and 40 to 50 clinical trials around the world showing that what we
call `risky drinking' can be reduced in many cases by as little as
five minutes of simple advice to people,'' said John Higgins-Biddle
of the University of Connecticut Medical School. ``When we tell
them about the negative consequences of their drinking and suggest
simple things people can do to cut down, people tend to get the
point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
