<SLUG> BC-OHIO-VOIONOVICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voinovich ready to deal with Senate trial
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ohio Gov. George Voinovich on Monday treaded gently
on the topic of President Clinton's up-coming impeachment trial in
the Senate, but said he doesn't think a trial can be avoided by
striking a plea deal that punishes the president with a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich, a Republican from Cleveland, will join the Senate in
January as that 100-member body prepares to deal with two articles
of impeachment against Clinton that were approved by the House of
Representatives last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me from what I've read, that in order to end a
process, you have to begin the process,'' Voinovich said. ``A trial
has to start.''
</P>
<P>
   But Voinovich also said many options are being discussed to
resolve the Clinton crisis and said, ``I'm not closing my mind to
any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Clinton became the second president in American
history to be impeached by the House of Representatives. The
closest America has come to impeaching a president since Andrew
Johnson 130 years ago was when President Nixon resigned before the
drafted articles of impeachment could be approved on a floor vote
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved two articles of impeachment against Clinton.
The first charges him with committing perjury in front of a grand
jury when he was questioned about his affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. The other article charges him with
obstruction of justice for a host of alleged acts including
tampering with witnesses and concealing evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment charges have been forwarded to the Senate for a
trial in which the outcome is determined by a two-thirds vote and
Chief Justice of the Supreme Court William Rehnquist presides. But
scholars and politicos have been debating whether the Constitution
will permit the Senate to dodge the unpopular prospect of a trial
by censuring Clinton and perhaps assessing a fine.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine, a Republican from Cedarville, issued a
statement Monday saying he will remain impartial as a ``juror'' for
the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich, who replaces retiring Democrat John Glenn, also
steered clear of offering any opinions on the evidence against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly speaking, I'm really not going to have a lot to say on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
