<HEADLINE>
IRAQ CHALLENGES U.S. ASSERTION OF `HIGHLY SUCCESSFUL' BOMBINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The confrontation with Iraq shifted from bombs to
words Monday, with the U.S. military touting the accuracy and
destructiveness of air strikes against Saddam Hussein's military
infrastructure, while Iraq claimed the onslaught killed mostly
innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Corp. Gen. Anthony Zinni, field commander of bombing
campaign, said the massive operation destroyed 74 percent of its
intended targets. Among them were Iraqi military barracks,
communication stations and facilities where chemical and biological
weapons were being constructed, Zinni said.
</P>
<P>
   He displayed black and white pictures of a bombed out airfields
and facilities that he said housed Iraq's elite Republican Guard
troops, the defense ministry and the headquarters of Saddam's Baath
Party.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 cruise missiles were fired and 600 bombs dropped
during Operation Desert Fox, and 85 percent of the targets were hit
at least once during the four-day assault that ended Saturday. The
campaign also involved more than 600 sorties _ including 300 at
night _ and more than 40 ships in strike and support roles, Zinni
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen called the bombing campaign
``highly successful,'' saying the operation set Iraqi weapons
development back at least one year. Cohen also repeated warnings
that the United States would resume attacks if the Iraqi leader
continued to threaten his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to make it more difficult for Iraq to use deadly
chemical and biological chemicals against its neighbors,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz challenged the U.S.
claims, saying the bombing campaign focused not on his nation's war
making capability but on civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
   Civilians were killed in hospitals, homes and schools, the same
targets U.S. bombs struck during the 1991 Persian Gulf War, Aziz
said, calling such attacks ``the American way of making war.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz conceded that Republic Guard barracks were hit, killing 62
soldiers. But he said the number of civilian deaths was even
greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four days of intensive bombings with all the smart missiles
and bombs, the high-tech precision weapons, these are the real
results,'' Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows what these people are in reality,'' he added,
referring to U.S. military leaders. ``They lie. They boast. They
disinform and misinform their peole and the whole world in order to
justify a criminal policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But authorities in Iraq did not follow the past practice of
taking foreign journalists to areas of heavy civilian casualties,
leading to speculation that the number of civilian deaths was not
high.
</P>
<P>
   Zinni said the most surprising aspect of Desert Fox was the
``complete lack of resistance'' from the Iraqi military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hesitate to make a judgment why other than to say I
think that the Iraqi military is fully aware what could happen if
they reacted in any way,'' Zinni said. ``Obviously, if you turn on
a radar, react in any way, we're prepared to handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the U.S. military ``a force of stability in the
region,'' Zinni said U.S. forces remain ready to attack again
should Saddam persist with trying to build weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those in the region view him as a threat and those in
the region appreciate us being there providing a counter and a
deterrent to that threat,'' said Zinni, who heads the U.S. Central
Command, which oversees the U.S. military's Middle East operations.
``I think Saddam may have learned from this, and if he's smart, he
wouldn't want to see a repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain launched the operation after
United Nations weapons inspectors reported that Iraqi forces barred
them from entering some facilities suspect in the production of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the bombing focused
solely on legitimate Iraqi military targets and successfully
undermined Saddam's war-making capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can take it from me that, along with the air
defense systems, the missile production capability, the
command-and-control system of the whole army, the special
Republican Guard were targeted particularly,'' Blair told Cable
News Network. ``And they were badly hit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
