<HEADLINE>
MOTHER SAYS FAGAN SHOULD BE TRIED IN '79 KIDNAP OF DAUGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the first time Monday, Middlesex County District
Attorney Thomas F. Reilly and his successor, Martha Coakley, met
with Barbara Kurth in part to determine if she was willing to allow
her former husband to plead guilty to kidnapping their two
daughters 19 years ago in exchange for his avoiding jail.
</P>
<P>
   But Kurth wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob M. Atwood, the Boston attorney who represents Kurth, said
his client told prosecutors that she believes Stephen Fagan must be
punished for having taken their daughters, then 5 and 2 years old,
away from her to Florida and raising them under an assumed identity
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, however, the two daughters, Rachel, 24 and Lisa,
21, met for about an hour with the same prosecutors to make the
case on Fagan's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was expected that the young women would urge the
prosecutors to agree to the plea deal, Brian Heffron, a spokesman
for Reilly's office, declined comment on the discussions or whether
any decisions have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said that Reilly, Coakley, and assistant district
attorney Lynn Rooney did not ask Kurth her reaction to a plea
bargain. But Atwood said that Kurth opposes such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes he should be punished for what he did, but she
believes it is up to the judicial system to decide what that
punishment should be,'' Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' meeting with Kurth, which lasted for more than
an hour, was their first with her since Fagan was arrested last
April 16 at his Palm Beach mansion and charged with kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth felt that her 75-minute meeting with the prosecutors was
``productive'' in that it provided Reilly and Coakley, who takes
over as Middlesex district attorney next month, an opportunity to
gauge her potential credibility as a witness in the case, Atwood
said.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the trial but a previously scheduled
hearing is set for Dec. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan has maintained that he took his daughters from their
mother's home in North Adams after a weekend visit because Kurth
was an alcoholic and neglectful of the children. Kurth has denied
that she had a drinking problem and insists that she took good care
of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Reilly's office reportedly was exploring the
possibility of reaching a plea agreement with Fagan. Heffron
declined to say whether Reilly's office had scheduled the separate
meetings with Kurth and the daughters to explore such a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   In prior discussions, Richard M. Egbert of Boston, Fagan's
lawyer, has told the prosecutors that he is confident that he can
defend Fagan successfully but is willing to engage in plea bargain
negotiations to avoid a trial. Egbert declined comment on any
discussions Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
