<SLUG> BC-STATES-BILLS22C-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        CLINTON'S LEGAL DEFENSE FUND GETS STEADY DONATIONS, BUT
LEGAL FEES GROW   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 21, -- The impeachment process could not only
cost President Bill Clinton his job, but also a small fortune in
legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons already owe $7 million and counting in lawyer's
bills from the Paula Jones sexual harassment case and Whitewater
land deal investigation, according to Tony Essaye, executive
director of the Clinton Legal Expense Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone with those kind of legal fees would be
incredibly concerned,'' said Essaye, who oversees a trust of
private donations collected to help pay for the Clintons' legal
costs. ``We are doing the best we can to meet this enormous
potential burden to the Clintons. We are cautiously optimistic
about what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust had raised only $2.2 million as of August, the last
time numbers were made available.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the White House and Essaye said they didn't know
yet how much the impeachment process has cost Clinton in personal
legal fees. They also could not estimate the cost of a Senate
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In his official capacity, Clinton is represented by the White
House counsel, which is paid for by taxpayers, Essaye said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton must pay fees to his private lawyer, David Kendall,
whom he hired to assist the White House counsel in defending him,
Essaye said.
</P>
<P>
   The government will wind up paying most costs related to the
impeachment process. But if the $900,000 the House Judiciary
Committee spent pursuing Clinton in the impeachment inquiry alone
is any indication, he will have to pay plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's insurance policy paid off the $850,000 settlement in
the Paula Jones case, according to a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the presidential legal bill was $6 million. The trust
had collected $2.2 million dollars and paid out 1.25 million to the
president's lawyers, Essaye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president would have to pay any amount leftover from what
we could not pay,'' Essaye said. ``Of course, the president could
always make money doing lectures and appearances when he leaves
office. But I think there is a better use of his time.''
</P>
<P>
   During the impeachment process, the trust has received a
``steady flow of donations,'' from individuals allowed to
contribute up to $10,000 a year. Essaye said the trust received
calls from folks concerned with Clinton's bills.
</P>
<P>
   Essaye would not release information about how much money has
been raised since August and said the next figures would be made
available in February.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the trust, Richard M. Lucas, said he was
confident the donations would ``substantially'' reduce the amount
owed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's approval rating has been high and people want
to help him,'' Lucas said. ``There have been no peaks or valleys in
donations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said he didn't think Clinton's impeachment battle needed
publicity. The direct mailings soliciting donations for Clinton's
legal bills don't mention it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donors are well aware of what they [the Clintons] are going
through.'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
