<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-RESTRAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL TO URGE REVAMP OF CHILD-RESTRAINT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Eight months after a teenager died while being subdued
by workers in a group home, a panel of law enforcement and human
service professionals has found state policies on restraining
children and adolescents to be ``almost devoid of any standard of
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday a task force will call on Massachusetts officials to do
a much better job of monitoring and guiding children's residential
programs on the use of restraints.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary William D. O'Leary convened
the task force in response to the death on April 29 of Mark Soares,
16, of Hyde Park. A spokesman for O'Leary said the secretary will
carry out the task force's recommendations, which are meant to cut
down on the use of restraints and injuries resulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make Massachusetts a leader nationally on the issue
of restraints,'' said Larry Swartz an aid to O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   However, Michael Weekes, director of the Massachusetts Council
of Human Service Providers, said the focus of the task force was
too narrow, failing to examine the forces that have fueled the use
of restraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have become more violent and staff are less trained,''
said Weekes.
</P>
<P>
   State regulations will be revamped next spring to allow mental
health, mental retardation, juvenile justice and social service
programs to use physical force to temporarily immobilize children
only in instances when the children are endangering themselves or
other people. Current regulations also allow children to be subdued
if they are causing property damage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the programs will have to begin filing quarterly
reports with the state, detailing how often restraints were applied
and resulted in injuries. The state also will conduct formal
reviews if a child or worker is repeatedly involved restraints to
ensure the child is in the appropriate program and the worker has
been properly trained.
</P>
<P>
   Up to this point, programs have only had to report to the state
instances where the use of restraints led to injuries requiring
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years the state has confirmed 20 instances when
children and adolescents were hurt while being placed or held in
restraints. Most suffered bloody noses, bruises and broken limbs
and noses. Three of them died, including Soares.
</P>
<P>
   A medical examiner ruled that Soares died of neck injuries he
sustained while be restrained by workers at the Wayside Carriage
House, a Marlborough group home for troubled youth under contract
with the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a judge who presided over the inquest into the death
of Soares concluded the workers, Jason Childs and Michael Comforti,
had not acted with ``criminal negligence'' as they struggled to
control Soares.
</P>
<P>
   But the inquest report by Judge John S. McCann revealed a series
of troubling events leading up to Soares' death.
</P>
<P>
   After Soares punched and head-butted Childs, Childs wrapped his
arm around Soares' neck, periodically lifting the teen off the
floor as he pushed him back toward a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Although the headlock was prohibited by Wayside and has been
barred by O'Leary, the judge believed Childs had no other way to
try to control Soares at that point.
</P>
<P>
   The headlock lasted only ten to 30 seconds, but was applied with
enough force to damage the neck artery leading to Soares' head,
causing the teen's blood pressure to drop. He was able to speak,
but had only minutes left to live unless he received medical
attention.
</P>
<P>
   After Childs wrestled the teen onto the floor face-down, the
worker placed his upper body on Soares' back and ``hyperextended''
his neck by holding his head about eight inches off the floor.
Although Childs did not realize it, those two moves, which impeded
the teen's breathing, in combination with the neck injury proved
fatal, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   During the restraint, Childs and other workers had a discussion
about whether Soares was breathing, with Childs concluding the teen
was playing possum.
</P>
<P>
   Before falling silent, Soares cried in an increasingly weak
voice, ``I can't breathe...I can't breathe...Please stop.'' But
Childs, who was lying on top of him, did not hear the cries,
according to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   While the task force did not examine the specific circumstances
of Soares' death, it called on residential providers to train their
staff on how to properly monitor a child's breathing during
restraint and to treat distress as a medical rather than behavioral
issue.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 different types of restraint techniques are in use
in Massachusetts, some widely recognized, others the creation of
individual programs. The panel urged the state to consult medical
specialists to find out which techniques are dangerous, and to hold
annual conferences to inform providers about safe restraint
techniques and methods for preventing the need for restraints in
the first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
