<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COACHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaching carousel spins on
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was 1989 when Steve Spurrier first realized that
being a lame-duck coach was for the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before leading Duke into the All-America Bowl, Spurrier
told his players that he had accepted an offer to return to
Florida, his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mistake,'' Spurrier said. ``A big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   During the game, Spurrier caught one of the Blue Devils loafing
and gave the guy an earful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just looked at me and smiled,'' Spurrier said. ``I could
see it in his eyes. `Hey, I don't have to listen to you. You're not
my coach anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Spurrier gave Gators assistant coaches Bob Stoops and
Carl Franks his blessing earlier this month when they were hired as
head coaches at Kansas State and Duke, respectively. They offered
to remain longer and contribute to Florida's preparation for the
Jan. 2 Orange Bowl against Syracuse, but Spurrier said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them that they needed to concentrate on their new
teams,'' he said. ``We have plenty of good coaches around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier's problem has become an all-too-familiar one in college
football this time of year. The bowl preparation time of December
is also the time of greatest movement of coaches from one job to
another. With less than a month before a bowl game, schools find
themselves without key assistants or, in some case, no head coach.
It puts both the schools and the coaches in an uncomfortable
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, at least most of them, want to do right by their old
employer, particularly if that school is playing in a big bowl
game. But the new employer usually is offering a significant salary
increase and wants the new coach on the road recruiting and
rebuilding the program.
</P>
<P>
   In this season's national championship game, No. 1 Tennessee
(12-0) plays No. 2 Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4.
without its offensive coordinator. David Cutcliffe resigned after
the SEC championship game on Dec. 5 to become the new coach at
Mississippi. Running backs coach Randy Sanders, 33, has received
the job on a permanent basis. Having to replace a coordinator on
the eve of one of the biggest games in school history should be a
stressful proposition, but coach Phillip Fulmer insists that it
will not be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy played quarterback at Tennessee and has been coaching
running backs and wide receivers ever since, so he knows our
system,'' Fulmer said. ``I may get a little more involved in
special situations now, but I have complete confidence in Randy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer was a little miffed that Ole Miss hired Cutcliffe on the
eve of the SEC championship game, but he understood that he would
not have his good friend for the Fiesta Bowl. It is the nature of
the profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that sooner or later David would become a head coach,
because he was ready,'' Fulmer said. ``We will miss him, but in
this case all we can do is wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Orange fans might not be so gracious should Tennessee be
unable to move the ball against Florida State, which wields the
nation's No. 1 defense. Tulane (11-0) will not be playing for a
championship when it takes on BYU in the Dec. 31 Liberty Bowl. But
the Green Wave will be going for its first undefeated season since
1931, which is a big deal for a school that has struggled as much
as Tulane. But Tulane will be without Tommy Bowden, who left to
become coach at Clemson. Assistant head coach Rich Rodriguez, the
offensive coordinator, was the choice of players and some boosters,
but athletics director Sandy Barbour picked Georgia assistant head
coach Chris Scelfo, a native of New Iberia, La.
</P>
<P>
   Since being tapped for the job on Dec. 7, Scelfo has been
scrambling to assemble a staff, get them out recruiting and prepare
the current team to play one of the biggest games in school
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough, because our kids have been through a lot in
just a few days,'' said Scelfo, whose brother, Frank, already was a
member of the Tulane staff. ``There's no question that this whole
thing is disruptive, and the ones who get hurt the most are the
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The recruiting calendar is one of the pressures causing coaches
to move in December. Coaches can begin direct contact with recruits
on Dec. 1, and the pressure is tremendous on new coaches to hit the
road recruiting for the new school immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Once a new coach is in place, it creates a domino effect
throughout the coaching profession as he tries to assemble a staff.
</P>
<P>
   Help may be on the way. Grant Teaff, the executive director of
the American Football Coaches Association (AFCA), says his group is
working on a plan that would keep coaches on campus more in
December, when their teams need them most. The AFCA hopes that the
result will be that schools won't feel pressured to hire a new
coach immediately. The goal is for schools to wait until after the
bowls before raiding the staffs of other schools. ``There's too
much pressure on the school and certainly too much pressure on the
coaches,'' Teaff said. ``It's not healthy for the profession. We
hope to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaff's group plans to submit its proposal to the NCAA early
next year. Given the current legislative structure of the NCAA, any
meaningful change is probably a year away.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the coaching merry-go-round continues. Each
opening filled creates an opening somewhere else, where another
group of players will be disappointed and maybe even disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's part of the profession, but sometimes our players
get caught in the shuffle in this thing,'' Scelfo said. ``All of us
need to remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
