<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: P.D.Q. BACH RETURNS; O'NEILL SOCIETY HONORS
PRODUCER; THE LIEBERMANN BANDWAGON; FREE ADMISSION AT MOMA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to spreading seasonal cheer, Santa
Claus isn't alone. As he has annually since 1985, this is the time
of year when Peter Schickele sets up satirical shop at Carnegie
Hall in the guise of the zany professor who unearthed the works of
P.D.Q. Bach, ``the oddest of Johann Sebastian Bach's 20-odd
children.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's concert is titled ``Songs My Mother Wouldn't Teach
Me the Words To'' and is scheduled for two performances, at 2 p.m.
Sunday and 8 p.m. next Tuesday. The program features the ``leeric''
tenor Archie Worley, the New York Pickup Ensemble, the
``semi-conductor'' Kenneth Jean, and such P.D.Q. masterworks as
``Einstein on the Fritz'' and ``The Abduction of Figaro.''
</P>
<P>
   Honor Bound
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Theodore Mann, who joined with Jose Quintero to
restore the reputation of Eugene O'Neill with their Circle in the
Square revival of ``The Iceman Cometh'' in 1956, will receive the
O'Neill Society's medal for his ``monumental contributions'' to the
playwright's work. With Circle in the Square, Mann produced 14
O'Neill plays.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony will take place when the society meets for four
days beginning on Jan. 7 in Bermuda, where representatives of 10
countries will deliver scholarly papers, see performances and hear
music associated with the Nobel Prize-winning playwright. Another
medal will be awarded, to Joy Bluck Waters, who owns and restored
Spithead, the Bermuda house where O'Neill worked on ``Strange
Interlude,'' ``Lazarus Laughed'' and ``Marco Millions'' in the
mid-1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Music Man
</P>
<P>
   The good times are rolling for the 37-year-old New York-born
composer Lowell Liebermann. Last week, in announcing its 1999-2000
season, the New York Philharmonic set the dates May 25 through 27
for the world premiere of his Concerto for Trumpet and Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5, the Florentine Opera in Milwaukee will present the
North American premiere of Liebermann's first opera, ``The Picture
of Dorian Gray,'' based on Oscar Wilde's novel. James Galway's
latest CD, ``Galway Plays Liebermann,'' is devoted to the
composer's work.
</P>
<P>
   Free Expression
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thanks, New Yorkers. That's the word from the Museum
of Modern Art, which is offering free admission Wednesday in
gratitude for public support. Wednesday is one of two full days and
two evenings being added to the museum's schedule to accommodate
public demand to see its current exhibitions, including the Jackson
Pollock retrospective on view through Feb. 2. Normally closed on
Wednesday, the museum will be open from 10:30 a.m. to 6 p.m.
Wednesday and on Dec. 30. The museum, which normally closes at 6
p.m. on Thursdays, will also be open until 9 on Jan. 14 and 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
