<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-BOS     12-21 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MODERATES COULD HOLD KEY TO SHIFT TO CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's prospects of avoiding a lengthy
impeachment trial improved slightly Monday as a senior Republican
senator from New England expressed preliminary support for a
censure alternative that could cut short the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that some other moderate GOP lawmakers from the region
might follow, Senator John H. Chafee of Rhode Island said in an
interview that censure ultimately could ``be a very attractive
alternative'' to a protracted Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee's comments came after Senator James M. Jeffords,
Republican of Vermont, expressed reservations over the weekend even
about trying Clinton on the House-approved impeachment charges of
perjury and obstruction of justice stemming from his sexual affair
with the former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With formal impeachment proceedings all but certain to begin
next month in the Senate, Chafee and Jeffords are critical to the
White House goal of gaining enough support to strike a censure deal
to resolve the crisis short of a full trial.
</P>
<P>
   If all 45 Senate Democrats united behind a censure plan, they
would need only six Republicans to forge a majority that could
dismiss the House articles and end the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, who served as Navy secretary under President Richard M.
Nixon before he entered the Senate in 1976, stressed that there is
no alternative to starting the impeachment proceedings. But, he
said, ``It may well be that as we go along that censure would be a
very attractive alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as Senate officials prepared for the
historic proceedings, the White House pondered its public relations
and legal defense strategies, and Vice President Al Gore appealed
to his former Senate colleagues to strike ``a fair, bipartisan
compromise'' to censure the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his first full business day as the only impeached
president since 1868 by consulting with Senator Edward M. Kennedy,
one of the most influential Democrats on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agenda was Kennedy's concern about advancing
education, health care, and New England fisheries interests in the
administration's budget for the next fiscal year, the conversation
turned to impeachment during the 30-minute meeting at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senator emphasized his intention to do all that he could
to see that the Senate deals with this issue fairly and
expeditiously,'' according to sources familiar with the
conversation. The sources would not discuss the president's private
comments to Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential support from Chafee and Jeffords for a
censure plan, the White House suffered a widely anticipated setback
Monday when Senator Robert C. Byrd, the Senate's senior Democrat,
voiced his opposition to any censure proposal involving White House
participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the good of our nation, there must be no `deal' involving
the White House or any entity beyond the current membership of the
US Senate,'' Byrd said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a former Senate majority leader, will be a pivotal figure
in the impeachment proceedings because senators in both parties
consider him the leading constitutional scholar in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take my cues from Senator Byrd,'' said Senator
Mitch McConnell, a Kentucky Republican who will control much of the
proceedings as chairman of the Senate Rules Committee. ``I think
he's the expert,'' McConnell said of Byrd on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said: ``Whether there is a trial or whether there is some
other solution, that decision must be made by senators, and it must
be bipartisan or it will have absolutely no credibility with the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, buoyed by a joint call for censure Monday by
former Presidents Gerald R. Ford and Jimmy Carter, stepped up its
pursuit for the alternative resolution, even as Clinton's lawyers
weighed a wide of range of defense strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main focus is trying to bring this to a bipartisan closure
promptly,'' said James Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House
counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gore continued to expand his role as a chief
advocate for Clinton's censure despite the prospect of fallout from
the Lewinsky matter tainting his bid for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do hope that the United States Senate will rise to this
moment, as it so often does, to be the voice of reason,
deliberation, and healing that America needs,'' Gore said in
appealing for a censure alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the Senate will, therefore, forge a fair bipartisan
compromise to end this matter promptly and to end it in a way that
will respect the will and the wisdom of the American people,'' said
Gore, who served in the Senate from 1984 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refrained from commenting publicly on his impeachment
crisis, focusing instead on budget meetings, commemorating the 10th
anniversary of the Pan Am 103 disaster, and visiting a Washington
soup kitchen to promote community service.
</P>
<P>
   But the president continues to consult regularly with former
Senator George S. Mitchell of Maine about strategies to resolve the
impeachment proceedings, according to White House spokesman, Joseph
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The two current Maine senators, Olympia J. Snowe and Susan M.
Collins, are moderate Republicans who are central to the White
House strategy to forge a bipartisan compromise. But neither has
taken a public position on censure, and both declined comment
Monday about the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords appears to have made the strongest statement of any
Senate Republican about the preference for censure. ``I would hope,
perhaps, we could reach consensus so that a trial wouldn't be
necessary,'' Jeffords told the Sunday Rutland Herald. ``It seems to
be an awful low bar for impeaching future presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry said he is ``certainly open to a
reasonable approach.'' But Kerry indicated he is focusing on
challenging the impeachment charges within the Senate proceedings.
``It seems to me we should consider right up front whether we can
have a motion for summary judgment,'' or dismissal, he said. ``In
other words to determine up front whether these facts at their
worst rise to the level of an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton received surprise support for censure from
four House Republicans who voted for impeachment: Representatives
Sherwood L. Boehlert and Benjamin A. Gilman of New York, Michael N.
Castle of Delaware, and James C. Greenwood of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, the four
wrote: ``We urge you to allow the Senate to consider strong censure
as a remedy. We are not convinced, and do not want our votes
interpreted to mean that we view removal from office as the only
reasonable conclusion of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Louise D. Palmer contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
