<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS &LR;      12-21 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT SEEKS TO INSURE UNSOLD SEAT LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Connecticut is shopping worldwide for an insurance
policy to cover as much as $13 million annually in unsold luxury
seats the state has guaranteed at the planned New England Patriots
stadium in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The state's insurance agent is soliciting competitive bids for a
policy that could cost as much as $5 million a year for financial
protection on vacant club seats and luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an inquiry from the state that said we have this
exposure, can it be insured,'' said the agent, Fred Tanguay, a vice
president at the Hartford-based R. C. Knox &AMP; Co. ``I went out into
the market, and I am still out in the marketplace, talking to
numerous companies. In fact, there is a certain level of interest
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there is no deadline and no urgency for the state
seeking proposals. However, although the target date for the $375
million stadium opening is 2001, a decision to purchase a policy
must be made well before then.
</P>
<P>
   If there are indications corporate support for suites is soft,
potential underwriters may smell more of a risk and increase the
premium prices. In simpler terms, it would be like looking for an
insurance policy after the car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the insurance capital of the world, it would not be
unusal that one of the domestic companies here would have an
interest,'' Tanguay said. ``But it being of a competitive bidding
nature, it's going to be best price, best coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The otherwise unlikely confluence of insurance and sports is
becoming less so in Hartford, home to some of the largest and most
well-known insurers in the world _ including Travelers and Aetna.
The city even has the chairman of Pheonix Mutual Home Life
Insurance Co. heading up the $1 billion Adriaen's Landing urban
redevelopment project, of which the stadium would be part.
</P>
<P>
   But while the state has insured halfcourt prize shots at
University of Connecticut basketball games, this could be one of
the more complicated and interesting policies ever taken out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most unusual,'' Tanguay said.
</P>
<P>
   The premium range, likely between $1 million and $5 million,
will depend on whether the policy offers full coverage and what the
deductible is set at. Anything costing more than $5 million would
not be prudent for the state, Tanguay said.
</P>
<P>
   Potential underwriters are looking at National Football League
market analyses from seven other areas to evaluate the price of
club seats, how many are sold, economic demographics, population,
wealth, corporate vibrancy.
</P>
<P>
   To make a decision, insurers will have to weigh the probability
of selling 6,000 club seats at $4,000 apiece and as much as 150
luxury suites at $100,000 a piece, given all those factors in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the type of things that go into it,'' Tanguay added.
``It's not a typical type of exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, only one company is publicly known to be negotiating for
the policy. That is General Star Indemnity, based in Stamford,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an insurable interest and there's the potential for
an unexpected and unintended loss, then you can generally insure
it,'' said Kevin Brooks, president of General Star, which insures
hole-in-one golf contests, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Tanguay said the policy would be some form of a contingent
liability, meaning all or part of the state's exposure would be
covered if the seats are not sold.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the popular parlance of Hartford, he added: ``The
discussions are along the lines of terms, conditions, deductables,
co-insurance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
