<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN INMATE'S CASE CHALLENGES LEGALITY OF TEXAS BOARD'S
CLEMENCY PROCEDURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Defending the procedures of the State Board of
Pardons and Paroles, Chairman Victor Rodriguez sparred verbally
with a death row lawyer in federal court Monday and was admonished
by the judge to give ``yes or no answers'' and to avoid ``making
speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   One exchange came when Rodriguez was being questioned by Sandra
Babcock, attorney for Joseph Stanley Faulder, a 61-year-old
Canadian who has been on death row since 1977. Does the board
conduct investigations to verify the truthfulness of information
that goes into an inmate's clemency petition file, she asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to ask you something,'' Rodriguez responded. ``What
do you mean by investigation? Before I leave the courtroom, I'd
like to have some idea what you mean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the witness, I'm the lawyer,'' Babcock said. ``You
don't get to question me.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks, who issued a temporary
restraining order two weeks ago that stayed the execution of
Faulder and another inmate, weighed in on her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't question the lawyers,'' he told Rodriguez, who has
appeared testy at times in the past few weeks as the parole board
has been bombarded with lawsuits challenging the legality of its
clemency procedures.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, state District Judge Paul Davis, ruling in a
class-action lawsuit filed by condemned prisoners, found that the
parole board's procedures violate the state constitution and the
Open Meetings Act. He ordered the board to begin holding public
meetings to deliberate clemency petitions, to vote in public and to
record the reasons for their votes.
</P>
<P>
   When that order was blocked by the state Supreme Court,
attorneys for Faulder, who was convicted of murdering an elderly
East Texas woman in 1975, and Danny Lee Barber, 43, who was
sentenced to die for beating and stabbing to death a Dallas-area
woman in 1979, challenged the state's clemency process in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder and Barber were scheduled to die on consecutive days
early this month, but were spared by Sparks, who ruled that it is
``difficult to determine what the Texas (clemency) law is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the court knows for certain is that the plaintiff filed a
petition for clemency and the board voted against clemency. The
record is void of any reason for the board's action. The board
identifies no procedures to avoid arbitrary and capricious
determinations of clemency decisions that otherwise fail to comport
with due process. It is unclear how the board can document that its
procedures are not arbitrary if it does not document its procedures
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, the 18-member parole board had not held
meetings to discuss clemency actions. The petitions are sent by air
express and fax to each member, who cast a ballot by fax.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, two state courts have ruled that failing to
record votes and the reasons for them violated the state
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock, arguing that it is also a violation of the U.S.
Constitution's guarantee of ``minimal due process,'' questioned
Rodriguez about the board's refusal to record the reasons for its
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Turning combative once more, Rodriguez said, ``We do give a
reason for the decision. We tell you that we did not recommend
clemency because a majority of the board members would not vote to
recommend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, Sparks interrupted the testimony and drew muffled
laughter when he invoked recent presidential testimony:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give that answer again,'' he said. ``To me, that is like
asking what `is' is or what `alone' means.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was on the witness stand for less than an hour before
the noon recess. Before leaving the bench, the judge instructed him
to give ``yes or no answers'' when his testimony resumed and to
avoid making speeches in response to the attorneys' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Through the day, Sparks frequently interrupted lawyers who filed
the lawsuit to remind them that the hearing was concerned with only
one issue: Did Faulder and Barber receive ``minimal due process''
from the parole board?
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that until last March, clemency was an executive
prerogative, not a judicial matter, but the law changed with a
Supreme Court opinion in a lawsuit brought by an Ohio inmate
against that state's clemency process.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no constitutional right to clemency, the high
court ruled, ``some minimal procedural safeguards apply to clemency
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks will hear another day of testimony Tuesday and then
decide whether to issue a preliminary injunction against the parole
board.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, there is a growing belief in the Capital
that the way the parole board operates will be altered by
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Elliott Naishtat, who had filed two bills to reform
the board's procedures, attended part of Monday's hearing and
predicted that the system will become more open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pardon and parole board is an established government body
that should comply with existing state law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
