u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CERULEAN-COX     12-21 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERULEAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge says Blue Cross windfall must be more widely shared
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The for-profit conversion of Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Georgia was turning into a windfall for 70,000
policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   If WellPoint Health Networks' acquisition of Blue Cross were to
be approved early next year, as expected, the 70,000 policyholders,
at no initial cost, would have a choice of taking $4,000 or the
equivalent in WellPoint stock.
</P>
<P>
   Now the value of that freebie may be cut to about $1,850.
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court judge in Richmond County has ruled that an
estimated 74,000 more policyholders at the time of the conversion
also are entitled to the same five shares in Cerulean, the parent
company of Blue Cross, that the original 70,000 received.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, favoring the plaintiffs in a class-action lawsuit,
is expected to delay the closing of the acquisition of Cerulean by
California-based WellPoint. The deal was to close in the first
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross said Monday it might appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But WellPoint and Blue Cross said the acquisition price, $500
million, would remain the same. ``It won't have any impact on the
terms of the deal,'' said WellPoint spokesman John Cygul.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Harman, a Blue Cross vice president, added: ``Cerulean
and WellPoint remain committed to the merger and the closing as
soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The original 70,000 stockholders had individual Blue Cross
policies, or were members of Blue Cross employer plans that aren't
self-insured. After a mailing to about 144,000 policyholders that
qualified in those two categories, 70,000 signed up to receive the
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Harman said the purpose of the signup offer was to tell
policyholders about a possible tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge J. Carlisle Overstreet's ruling requires all those
eligible _ including those who didn't sign up _ to receive the
shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Cerulean shares were offered as a result of Blue Cross'
controversial 1996 conversion from a nonprofit to a for-profit
company.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders still must approve the WellPoint-Blue Cross merger.
</P>
<P>
   A date for the shareholder meeting has not been set. Blue Cross
is awaiting the final Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission's approval
of the proxy.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear what effect, if any, the judge's ruling would have
on a July settlement agreement reached between Blue Cross and
several consumer groups that had filed a lawsuit over the
conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, Blue Cross agreed to endow a health care
foundation with shares and warrants that had an initial value of
about $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
