<HEADER>
A1373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-OCTUPLETS-COX     12-21 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-OCTUPLETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World's first surviving set of octuplets in critical condition
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The world's first surviving set of octuplets remained
in critical condition Monday, but their pediatrician sounded
optimistic that all eight could live to see their first Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Nkem Chukwu, a 27-year-old Houston woman, gave birth to five
girls and two boys Sunday morning by Cesarean section at St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital, two weeks after the first of the octuplets, a
girl, was born in a normal delivery. The first baby born fifteen
weeks prematurely, is breathing on her own while her siblings, born
13 weeks early, will remain on ventilators until at least Thursday,
hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, who used fertility drugs to get pregnant, was in good
spirits Monday following early morning surgery to control internal
bleeding, said Dr. Patti Savrick, the babies' pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seemed very happy this morning,'' Savrick said, adding
that the exhausted mother wants to recover more before making any
statement to media which had descended on the hospital from around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at St. Luke's and at the adjoining Texas Children's
Hospital, where the babies were taken immediately after birth,
still refer to the unnamed infants as babies A through H. All eight
weighed less than two pounds at birth.
</P>
<P>
   But it is baby E, the tiniest of the eighth, that has doctors
most concerned. Weighing just 10.3 ounces, she had been carefully
watched in the womb after doctors detected reduced blood flow to
her body through her umbilical chord.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Chukwu went into labor around 5 a.m. Sunday, ``We
were really concerned that this baby may not survive much longer,''
said Dr. Brian Kirshon, who delivered the octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them are still critically ill, but she's the most
critically ill,'' Savrick said, adding that baby E, like her
siblings needs a ventilator and oxygen to help her undeveloped
lungs function.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people up in the (neo-natal intensive care unit) are
working very hard on each baby individually, monitoring every
aspect of vital signs and fluid and oxygen level... on literally a
minute by minute basis,'' Savrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the infants could be in hospital for up to two
months, while their mother may be released within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshon said Chukwu and her husband, Iyke, a respiratory
therapist at a Houston hospital, rejected the idea of ``selective
reduction,'' a technique in which doctors abort some fetuses so
that the others have a better chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally out of the question,'' to the deeply religious,
Nigerian born couple, Kirshon said.
</P>
<P>
   After Chukwu went into labor Sunday, medical teams from both
hospitals sprung into action.
</P>
<P>
   At about 7 a.m. _ roughly two hours after her contractions began
_ doctors had given Chukwu an anesthetic to numb her from the waist
down.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of the end of a grueling pregnancy. She had
spent the previous six weeks in bed, the last two inclined with her
head tilted toward the floor to take pressure off her abdomen.
Kirshon said Chukwu had not slept the night before and got only
about two hours of sleep a night in the days leading up to the
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   She also stopped eating and was fed intravenously to give the
babies more room.
</P>
<P>
   With teams from the Children's Hospital waiting in the hallway
to stabilize each infant, Kirshon performed the Cesarean Section in
a jammed packed delivery room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine _ one baby after the next _ its like a
factory, a conveyor belt,'' Krishon said. He said Chukwu was able
to see her newborns about an hour after the delivery as staff
members filed past her with the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked at the babies and she smiled. She was excited,''
Kirshon said.
</P>
<P>
   So was nurse Kasie Clark, 25, who helped coordinate the eighteen
to twenty people who crowded the delivery room at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that I may never personally see again in my
career,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   People and businesses from Houston and beyond responded quickly
Monday with gifts for the city's newest celebrities. One anonymous
donor pledged a lifetime supply of diapers; the Drypers Corp.
pledged a lifetime supply of baby wipes and disposable training
pants; Randall's Food Market donated a one-year supply of
groceries; Mead Johnson Nutrionals offered a one-year supply of
formula; and Holt Educational Outlet donated educational toys.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers at the hospital said multiple births have become more
common as more women opt for fertility drugs. Last month a woman
delivered sextuplets at the hospital_five survived_and as of
Monday, 36 babies from multiple births were being cared for at the
Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Now doctors are waiting for the Chukwu's to replace their babies
letters with names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to have some names because it would be easier to
keep track of the babies,'' Savrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
