<HEADER>
A1382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYLAN-SUIT-NYT &LR;      12-21 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYLAN-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKER OF GENERIC DRUGS ACCUSED OF ANTITRUST VIOLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Fla., Ill., Minn., N.Y., N.C., Ohio, Pa., W.Va.,
Wis.)  (rl) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission charged Monday that
Mylan Laboratories, one of the world's biggest makers of generic
drugs, had violated antitrust laws, and the government said it
would seek $120 million in refunds for consumers of two medications
widely used to treat symptoms of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general from 10 states planned to file a lawsuit
making similar accusations this week.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said Mylan had entered illegal agreements with
one of its suppliers to eliminate competition in the market for the
two generic drugs. Doctors write more than 21 million prescriptions
a year for the medications.
</P>
<P>
   Mylan denied all the charges. Milan Puskar, chairman of the
Pittsburgh-based company, said the commission's action was
``radical, rushed and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Mylan's shares dropped $3.3125, to $26.75, in New York Stock
Exchange trading after the accusations were announced.
</P>
<P>
   The government asserts that after locking up the supply of raw
materials, Mylan was able to raise prices to an astounding degree.
In January, the agency said,Mylan raised the wholesale price for
one drug, clorazepate, to $377 for a bottle of 500 tablets, up from
$11.36 for the same quantity. And in March, it said, the wholesale
price for the other drug, lorazepam, went to $190, from $7.30, for
a bottle of 500 tablets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mylan's outrageous price increases have cost consumers at
least $120 million in higher prices,'' said William Baer, director
of the agency's bureau of competition. Patients, many of them
elderly, take these drugs for long periods, and it may be dangerous
for them to halt treatment suddenly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baer said Mylan's price increases had generated ``a tremendous
number of consumer complaints,'' more than any other issue in the
last four years, as well as a large number of protests from members
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the generic drugs cost much less than the
brand-name versions, even after the price increases. But he said
the lawsuit was justified as a way to preserve competition among
makers of generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The brand-name version of lorazepam is Ativan, made by the
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories unit of American Home Products Corp. The
brand-name version of clorazepate, Tranxene, is made by Abbott
Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Arquit of Rogers &AMP; Wells, a lawyer for Mylan, said,
``Mylan's prices for the generic drugs are less than half of the
prices for the brand-name products, which are therapeutically
identical.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted 4 to 0 Monday to sue Mylan in federal
court. The complaint will name four defendants: Mylan; Profarmaco,
an Italian company that supplies raw materials to Mylan; the
Cambrex Corporation of East Rutherford, N.J., which is the parent
of Profarmaco, and Gyma Laboratories of America, based in Westbury,
N.Y., a distributor for Profarmaco.
</P>
<P>
   In demanding refunds, the commission is testing a relatively new
enforcement strategy. The agency often seeks injunctions requiring
violators of the antitrust laws to halt their illegal conduct, but
it has rarely tried to force companies to surrender what the
commission regards as ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   Mylan said its agreement with Profarmaco had a legitimate
purpose: to guarantee an adequate, uninterrupted supply of
chemicals. But, it said, in the last few weeks it decided not to
enforce provisions of the contract under which Mylan was to receive
all the output of certain chemicals made by Profarmaco.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest annual report, Mylan said that it had taken ``a
very aggressive position and raised prices'' on many products.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Hovenkamp, a University of Iowa professor who wrote a
leading treatise on antitrust law, said a court order requiring
consumer refunds was ``an aggressive remedy'' for the FTC to seek
at the start of an case.
</P>
<P>
   Baer said the complaint would charge that Mylan had violated
Section 5 of the Federal Trade Commission Act of 1914, which
outlaws ``unfair methods of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission is accusing Mylan of restraint of trade,
monopolization and conspiracy to monopolize the markets for the two
generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has often won refunds in cases that involve
direct mail or telemarketing fraud that enticed consumers to invest
in get-rich-quick schemes or to buy lottery tickets or vacation
trips. Typically, the government or the company establishes a pool
of money, reviews claims and pays refunds to consumers. But that
sort of remedy is unusual in FTC antitrust cases.
</P>
<P>
   Baer said the price increases by themselves would not have been
illegal. ``What's unlawful,'' he said, ``is for companies to get
together and conspire to exclude rivals and raise price. By
cornering the supply of raw materials _ even if you don't corner
100 percent of the supply, if you corner a substantial percentage
of it _ that gives you market power, the power over price. When
Mylan went to Profarmaco, it knew that if it was able to achieve an
exclusive agreement, it would be able to raise price, and that's
exactly what it did.''
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report, Mylan stated that it was losing money on
41 of 97 generic products in December 1997, and that it ``faced a
business decision: raise prices on the specific products or stop
manufacturing them altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   The states that said they would join in a lawsuit against Mylan
are New York, Connecticut, Florida, Illinois, Pennsylvania,
Minnesota, North Carolina, Ohio, West Virginia and Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
