<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARYLOU LUTHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; No Rest on 7th Ave. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When American designers announced that they would show their
fall 1999 women's wear in February, two months earlier than usual,
there was a collective gulp on Seventh Avenue: The new schedule
meant the fashion industry's long year-end vacations might be cut
short.
</P>
<P>
   Now the holiday season has arrived and Marc Jacobs is in Paris,
working through the holidays on his collection for Louis Vuitton.
In New York, where Jacobs' office has usually been closed from
Christmas to New Year's, his business partner, Robert Duffy, will
keep the lights on.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Marc could take a couple of weeks off in November
after the women's opening,'' Duffy said. ``This year, we started
the fall women's collection before we opened spring.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Badgley Mischka. ``Basically, we knew our schedules would
change, so we started working on fall earlier than usual,'' James
Mischka said. His partner, Mark Badgley, added, ``We've been going
crazy, but we will be in Los Angeles with our families for
Christmas and then on to Palm Beach, so I can get used to my new
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan will manage to take a holiday, ``but not with a lot
of peace of mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be going from the mountains to the beach over the
holidays,'' she said, ``but I don't know how much I can relax,
knowing that I'll be opening menswear January 12 in Milan, DKNY
here on February 14 and the collection on February 19.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bartlett, whose Italian offices were closed for two weeks
last year, had planned a vacation in South Africa this year. But
between getting his Byblos menswear ready for a Jan. 8 opening in
Milan, Italy, along with preparing for the moved-up showing of his
John Bartlett collection of men's and women's wear in New York, he
has cut back to a three-day vacation with his family in Cincinnati.
``Cape Town will have to wait,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yeohlee Goes Home &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yeohlee Teng, whose clothes are in the ``Cubism and Fashion''
exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, will celebrate the
turning of the century as the featured designer in a clothing and
architecture exhibition in her native Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   She and the architect Ken Yeang will show what they call
environmentally responsive clothing and architecture, first in
Kuala Lumpur in March 2000, and later that year in Penang. The
designer said she would also try to link fashion and art in the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Met show opened my eyes to fashion as art,'' said Ms.
Teng, whose label is called Yeohlee. ``I see fashion as art with a
function attached to it. It is an art form that only succeeds when
it works as clothing.'' She cited her cubist black-and-white
one-size-fits-all silk jacquard cape in the Met show as wearable
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``While art has emotional content, it doesn't have a real
function,'' she said. ``It may lift your soul, but it doesn't
necessarily keep you warm.''
</P>
<P>
   The cape will keep you warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Rainbow of Silks &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In what promises to be one of the most colorful spring seasons
in years, it will be possible to wear Easter-egg colors during the
Easter season. Shalini, a New York designer, is making the most of
fashion's new coalition with the rainbow by offering several
designs in an astonishing 60 shades. That's the number of colors
offered by one of her suppliers, Taroni Mills of Italy, a prominent
silk maker, for specific fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   The designer gives retailers the Italian mills' color swatches,
they show them to customers and Shalini delivers the outfit four to
six weeks later. Shalini, whose full name is Shalini Kumar, has a
spring collection priced from about $600 for pants and skirts to
$1,200 for jackets. They will be available in January at Saks Fifth
Avenue stores in New York and elsewhere, and at Ultimo in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
