<HEADER>
A1402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOVING-OBIT-COX     12-21 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVING-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neal V. Loving defied gravity, prejudice
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Neal V. Loving, who became an aviator despite
racial prejudice and kept flying long after a glider accident
resulted in the amputation of his legs, died Saturday at
Springfield Community Hospital. The retired research aerospace
engineer from Yellow Springs, Ohio was 82.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an extremely nice man _ you couldn't find a better
one,'' said Robert Cavanagh, who worked with Loving at the Flight
Dynamics Laboratory. ``His accomplishments _ you almost stood in
awe.''
</P>
<P>
   If, as he said in an interview with the Dayton Daily News last
year, ``success is loving what you do,'' Mr. Loving was a very
successful man.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Detroit on Feb. 4, 1916, Mr. Loving was smitten by
aviation after seeing his first airplane in 1926. A Detroit high
school principal told him in 1931 that there was ``no place for
colored people'' in aviation, and he learned that his race
disqualified him for the Army Air Corps, but that didn't stop him
from learning to fly. He built his first aircraft, a glider, in
1936.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, Mr. Loving's glider nose-dived 100 feet and crashed at
65 mph. Doctors had to amputate both of Mr. Loving's legs, and
while he was in the hospital, his mother died and his fiancee
backed out of their engagement.
</P>
<P>
   He resumed flying after his recovery, and started his own flying
school in 1946. He also continued to design and build full-sized
aircraft. One of his planes, a racer called ``Loving's Love,'' was
donated to the Experimental Aircraft Association's Air Education
Museum in Oshkosh, Wis. The plane's name became the title of his
autobiography, published in 1994 by the Smithsonian Institution
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Loving flew Loving's Love in 1953 to Jamaica, where he met
Clare Barnett, who became his wife in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, at the age of 40, Mr. Loving started work on a college
degree in aeronautical engineering. He became an engineer with the
Flight Dynamics Laboratory at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in
1961, remaining there until his retirement in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Loving continued to fly planes until 1991. His many honors
include the George ``JR'' Wedekind Award at the United States Air
Show, and the EAA Major Achievement Award, both presented in 1995.
In 1997, the Aviation Trail presented him with the Trailblazer
Award, given to Miami Valley residents who have made a significant
contribution to aviation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neal has been recognized as quite a figure in aviation
circles, overcoming all the obstacles he had,'' said, Wedekind the
president of Aviation Trails and one of the original organizers of
the United States Air and Trade Show. ``We're of course saddened by
the loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Loving is survived by his wife, his son, Paul, and his
daughter, Michelle.
</P>
<P>
   Donations can be made in Mr. Loving's memory to the EAA's Young
Eagles Program, P.O. Box 3086, Oshkosh, Wis. 54903-3086
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
