<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ-MILITARY, IRAQ-SCENE, IRAQ-INSPECTORS)
</HEADLINE>
  
 U.S. URGED TO EASE CALL TO INSPECT ATOMIC ARMS  (Eds: See also(mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Clinton administration, under pressure to
make some concession to other Security Council members after the
bombing of Iraq, may be willing to consider closing the file on
nuclear inspections, diplomats and independent arms control experts
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Security Council assembled Monday morning to
begin what was expected to be weeks of assessing where the United
Nations goes next on Iraq, it was apparent to diplomats that the
United States would have to compromise on something if other arms
inspections _ of biological, chemical and missile systems _ were to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   American officials would not speculate on what step the United
States might be prepared to make, saying the topic was being
discussed in Washington. They said Samuel Berger, the national
security adviser, was planning to clarify policy on Iraq in a
speech on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said Monday that closing the nuclear option seemed to
be the most palatable of limited choices for Washington as the
Council begins to negotiate a compromise plan to deal with Saddam
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is resisting strong pressure to replace
Richard Butler as head of the U.N. Special Commission. Again
Monday, the Russians insisted that Butler remained an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't trust him,'' said Yuri Fedotov, deputy Russian
representative on the Council.
</P>
<P>
   Other members say the Russian opposition to Butler is gaining
some support, if only as a way to remove a stumbling block for
dealing with the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has not resolved the nuclear issue, which is
sensitive. A spokesman for the National Security Council, David
Leavy, said Monday, referring to the International Atomic Energy
Agency: ``The nuclear file is closer to being closed than the
others. And when the IAEA says to close it we'll agree to close it.
But the U.S. government's position as of Monday stays the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts who say they believe that the question might
be closed say the Energy Department is stepping up efforts at its
nuclear laboratories at Los Alamos and Livermore to develop more
sophisticated sensors for environmental monitoring of Iraq, the
system that the United Nations would have to rely on after most
spot inspections had ended.
</P>
<P>
   For a year the atomic agency has been reporting that it cannot
find evidence of a nuclear-weapons program in Iraq. That finding
would allow the Security Council to end a period of intrusive
inspections that began in 1991 and shift to long-term monitoring.
The United States has blocked all Council efforts to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and Britain flatly oppose removing
Butler from the special commission, which oversees the inspections
of biological, chemical and missile systems. Washington also
opposes calls to reorganize the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing, Iraq has ruled out any further cooperation
with weapons inspectors. But it is willing to have the IAEA run its
monitoring from inside Iraq. The agency insists that its monitoring
can detect nuclear activity.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Leventhal, president of the independent Nuclear Control
Institute in Washington, who opposes closing the books on Iraqi
nuclear work, said in an interview Monday that the administration
appeared to believe that agreeing to close the nuclear file would
save the special commission. He added that in view of the pressures
on Butler and Iraq's determination not to work with him or his
commission, it may not be possible to keep the old inspection
system intact. All the inspectors have left Iraq.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Nuclear Control Institute has recommended that the
commission be given control of nuclear inspections, because,
Leventhal said, the International Atomic Energy Agency has been
``bamboozled'' by the Iraqis and let Saddam's government off too
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least the IAEA should be held accountable for its
nonalarmist assessment of Iraq's nuclear-weapons program,''
Leventhal said. ``The IAEA trivializes all missing information.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article to be published this week in Arms Control Today,
the journal of the independent Arms Control Association in
Washington, two other experts say, ``Essentially all of Iraq's
pre-gulf war nuclear facilities and equipment have been eliminated
or converted to nonproscribed purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the article finds that Iraq has continued intensive research
to solve problems that the bomb program had encountered earlier.
The article was written by David Albright, president of the
Institute for Science and International Security in Washington, and
Khidhir Hamza, an exile Iraqi nuclear scientist who was formerly in
charge of developing a nuclear weapon for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The article said, ``Iraq could make a nuclear device within two
to 12 months after deciding to do so, assuming it acquired
sufficient fissile material.''
</P>
</TEXT>
