A1405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-HNS &LR;      12-21 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESPECTED MILITARY LEADER SHAHAK A FAVORITE TO BECOME ISRAELI PRIME
MINISTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ He is a respected military leader, a charismatic
speaker and a nimble peacemaker whom the late Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin entrusted to negotiate peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, 54, a former military chief of
staff, also became a favorite for prime minister of Israel after
the Knesset gave preliminary approval to a bill to dissolve the
parliament and hold early elections.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had been expected to pass, because Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu virtually endorsed early elections last
week. On Monday, the measure flew through the legislature with
support from both coalition and opposition members.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all eyes are on Shahak, a popular war veteran. Speculation
of his impending entry into Israeli politics underscores the
emergence of a new political center _ one that is gaining momentum
among a sector of the population greatly dissatisfied with the two
major parities.
</P>
<P>
   Soon to become a private citizen, the general hasn't formally
entered the political fray, and it remains to be seen whether he'll
be able to for the upcoming election. According to Israeli law, a
retired high-ranking army officer must wait 100 days after leaving
the service before he can formally enter politics.
</P>
<P>
   But, already he's being touted as the Israeli most likely to
beat Netanyahu and opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak. An
opinion poll conducted earlier this month showed Shahak trouncing
Netanyahu by 52 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another poll taken this month found that 63 percent wanted
Shahak to enter politics, 32 percent as the head of a new centrist
party and 50 percent as Barak's No. Two in the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's kind of the Colin Powell of Israeli
politics,'' said Mark Heller, an analyst with the Jaffee Center for
Strategic Studies at Tel Aviv University who was referring to the
retired U.S. general.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Shahak) hasn't been in Israeli politics so he's seen as a
kind of white arrow, a straight neck, and that's what makes him
popular,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 and 1995, Shahak led Israel's negotiating team during
talks that produced the Cairo Agreement, better known in Israel as
Oslo II, a huge, meticulously negotiated document that fleshed out
the details of land-transfers to the Palestinians, security
arrangements and civilian questions referred to more broadly in the
initial agreement negotiated in Oslo, Norway, in 1993. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; As a result, he earned a reputation for being pro-Oslo, even
though as an army officer, he refrained from making political
statements. Today, he still hasn't disclosed in public his stand on
peacemaking with the Palestinians _ or any other issues of Israeli
politics. But he once said that Israel should not run the lives of
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The same poll in which 63 percent of Israelis wanted Shahak to
enter politics found that 73 percent did not know what his views
were on any of the important questions on the national agenda.
</P>
<P>
   With new elections on the horizon, there will be increasing
pressure on Shahak to say what he believes in. But the fact that he
is immensely popular without staking out a political platform is
telling commentary on a public that both implicitly trusts military
leaders and searches for someone who can carry Rabin's torch in
peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Barak held this image when he first took the helm of the Labor
Party last year. But unlike Shahak, he lacks charisma, often coming
across intelligent but lifeless on television, an image that has
hurt him in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak hasn't come through very well,'' said David Kimche, an
author and former director of Israel's Foreign Ministry. ``He lacks
experience with the media. (Shahak) has a better chance of beating
Netanyahu than Barak does today.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming months, Barak's deadpan image may change. He's hired
U.S. spin-meisters James Carville and two others to help him
repackage himself. But Barak's supporters are still worried.
Rabin's widow, Leah, asked Shahak to join Labor instead.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the general has refused and insisted instead on forging
a new centrist party, possibly with Likud moderate Dan Meridor, one
of Netanyahu's former ministers who resigned months ago in protest.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect has Netanyahu worried that Shahak will beat Barak
in a three-way race and leave Netanyahu to face him in a runoff.
Some of Netanyahu's advisers are counseling the prime minister to
resign so that elections would be held in 60 days _ a tactic that
would prevent Shahak from running because of the 100-day
no-politics rule military officers must observe.
</P>
<P>
   Other Netanyahu advisers say he should stave off elections as
long as possible, both to allow the excitement over Shahak to
dissipate as his political views become known and to wait for
Israel's sagging economy to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, said Kimche, Shahak is the man to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a man who is still very clean as far as politics are
concerned,'' he said. ``He's fresh out of the army, with a very
good record in the army, and considered by the people to speak
clearly about the need for the country, so people look to him as a
way out of the country's morass.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Kimche added, ``it depends on what his election platform
will be. It's still very early.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
