</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-NUTCRACKER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS FOR A TROUBLED TROUPE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: One photograph of Donald Byrd will move. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The future looked bleak for Donald Byrd and his
modern-dance company, Donald Byrd/The Group, this time last year.
``The Harlem Nutcracker'' was a critical and popular success, but
the company's national tour of the lavish production was
foundering. As costs climbed, bills went unpaid. Some performances
had to be canceled. It looked as if the group might go under.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Byrd and his troupe are well on their way to
financial recovery. His faith in ``The Harlem Nutcracker,'' a
nine-year labor of love that begins a two-week engagement Tuesday
at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, has paid off. The company has
whittled down a debt of ``one-point-something million'' dollars
connected with the production, as Byrd put it recently, to
$400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company has an accumulated debt of about $250,000
that is not associated with ``The Harlem Nutcracker,'' it finished
its fiscal year with a surplus of several thousand dollars, a rare
occurrence in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Duke Ellington-Billy Strayhorn ``Nutcracker
Suite,'' to which it is partly set, the reworking of the classic by
Byrd places the narrative in modern-day Harlem, where a black
grandmother reminisces about her youth. The production represented
a step up the ladder for the small, experimentalist New York
troupe, which seemed poised for major success.
</P>
<P>
   The company extended its five-city tour this winter to eight
weeks from five. ``We are planning next year to send out two
companies,'' said Benjamin Mordecai, the theatrical producer and
assistant dean at the Yale School of Drama, whom Byrd brought in
last year as executive producer of ``The Harlem Nutcracker.'' ``We
have enough interest to fill up about eight weeks for each company.
And we're hoping to go to more cities, ideally 10 altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   A 16-member jazz ensemble made up of senior Ellington musicians
has replaced the quartet that toured with the company. The choirs
that were hired in each city, in addition to 27 local child
performers, are now gospel choruses. ``The Harlem Nutcracker'' now
features a cast of more than 80 dancers, singers and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd has tinkered with the production, too, rechoreographing and
recostuming some parts that had disappointed him, streamlining the
physical production and rehearsing his dancers even harder than
usual. ``It is exciting to see disciplined bodies working,'' he
said. ``With a rigorousness of approach, with authenticity and
honesty, the experience is being recreated every evening as if it
were the first time the dance is being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Streamlining the ballet's technical requirements helped get the
scenery up faster, said Mordecai, now a consultant to the company.
``Before I became involved, it took three days. Now it takes 10
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The producer also has made better deals with presenting
theaters, Byrd said. ``Ben asked for fees appropriate to what we
were doing,'' he said. ``We had been underselling the production
because of our desire to run it as a community-based operation.
Presenters made money before, but we lost. We've had to think a
little more commercially.''
</P>
<P>
   Another important factor in the production's resurgence has been
the involvement of Aetna. In addition to the sponsorship fee, Aetna
is involved in setting up community events like opening-night
benefits for local community organizations in tour cities. Aetna
has contributed $250,000, according to Willard I. Hill, vice
president and head of emerging markets for Aetna Retirement
Services, the division sponsoring the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sponsorship is tied into a new business operation I am
creating and managing, targeting the high-growth segments of the
African-American, Latino and women business-owners markets,'' Hill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ``Nutcracker'' debacle, the company has been able to
continue touring a new full-evening piece, ``Jazz Train.'' Byrd is
at work on several one-act dances in celebration of the centenary
of Ellington's birth next year, for a New York season in March. But
Byrd admits to a lingering worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me a little nervous that dance doesn't just need to
be interesting, it needs to be an event,'' he said. ``Has American
dance caught up with the rest of American culture and become a
commodity? We had to be mindful of that trend and use some of the
methods other media use. I still have to remember that artistic
quality matters. If work is not very good, then people won't
come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
