<HEADLINE>
LATE SEASON SHOPPERS GIVE MERCHANTS PLENTY TO CHEER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- If the weekend was any indication, area retailers
will finish this holiday shopping season with fuller cash registers
than they did last year, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Business was brisk at stores and malls in Southern California
throughout the weekend, the season's last big weekend before
Christmas. It was particularly so Saturday, when last-minute
shoppers rushed retailers in crushing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But just because the parking lots were full over the weekend,
don't expect any relief in the last three shopping days before
Christmas. Retailers and analysts say the days leading up to
Christmas are as busy, if not busier, historically than the last
Saturday before the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Based on anecdotal evidence, retail analyst Richard Giss on
Monday stuck with his earlier prediction that Los Angeles area
merchants will see an average 4.5 percent to 5 percent increase
compared to last year's holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense was that (this weekend) was a little busier than last
year, and I think last year people were waiting for the sales,
which hit pretty late,'' said Giss, a partner with the trade retail
services group of the accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Millman, general manager of the Burbank Media City
Center, said foot traffic through his mall was higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday was as busy here as I've seen it in the five seasons
I've been here,'' he said. ``I'm really looking forward to this
week. (Monday was) very, very busy and ... I think it's going to be
very, very busy all the way through the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the number of bags and packages customers carried,
it appeared that shoppers were buying and not just looking. Though
Millman did not yet have weekend results, the mall's merchants have
so far reported 5 percent to 7 percent sales increases compared to
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were a lot of transactions going on,'' Millman
said. ``At this point in the season, it's no longer browsing.
People are here to make purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   Other centers also reported healthy crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The car count at the Camarillo Premium Outlets center in Ventura
County was ahead in the ``double digits'' compared with last year,
according to general manager Terri Cameron. The center has,
however, about 15 more stores than it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our stores were ahead of last year and the car counts
were up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An arctic storm brough chilly weather to Southern California,
where the temperatures were in the 80s just a week before, but that
didn't stem the tide. Actually, the cold added to the Christmas
feeling, retailers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather had everyone all bundled up,'' Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   Giss, who confessed to being among the weekend's hordes of
shoppers, said parking lots were full and lines were long at the
centers he visited. The shoppers, if not exactly in the merriest of
spirits, were quietly focused on the task at hand _ buying gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles area should end the season well compared to
other parts of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very busy. I think that the numbers in our area
continue to be strong,'' he said. ``The East Coast, however, is
suffering from the warm weather. Although the sales are brisk,
they're still behind in the apparel category.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
