A1429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAULDER-DEATH-ROW-COX     12-21 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAULDER-DEATH-ROW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sparks challenges Texas' clemency process
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A visibly irritated U.S. District Judge Sam
Sparks admonished state officials Monday over Texas' secretive
clemency process, challenging their refusal to hold hearings or
make public any aspects of their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the horror of a hearing, since a majority of the other
states require a hearing?'' Sparks asked several times during the
opening day of the most significant court challenge in several
years to the controversial clemency process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not understand the resistance. For God's sakes, (you)
don't want to have a hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, when Parole Board Chairman Victor Rodriguez
insisted that to make the closed system more public might invite
more lawsuits by convicts and that there was no problem with the
current process, Sparks appeared to bristle again, quizzing him at
length about the need for such total secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   And when Rodriguez seemed to repeatedly dodge questions from
him, as well as from attorneys for condemned convicts Joseph
Stanley Faulder and Danny Lee Barber, Sparks warned: ``The next
speech might cost you a little of your salary,'' hinting of a
possible fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to give a speech you can do it out in front of the
TV cameras,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony is expected to resume this morning. Sparks could rule
as early as today on whether Texas' clemency system meets
constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Faulder and Barber two weeks ago challenged the
secrecy of the clemenary process as illegal. They insisted that
they were denied their due process rights guaranteed under the U.S.
Constitution because Texas' clemency system operates under rules
that are not publicly available and board votes are conducted in
secret and without explaination.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the argument was raised in an appeal seeking to save
his life, Barber was less than an hour from being executed at a
Huntsville prison. Faulder was to be executed the next day. Sparks
halted both executions pending Monday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Babcock, Faulder's attorney, and Kurt Sauer, representing
Barber, argued that the secrecy of Texas' current system illegally
denies due process to condemned criminals. ``A decision cannot be
arbitrary . . . but how are we to know whether a decision was
arbitrary if no reason is given?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Brent Hornsby, who supervises all clemency
paperwork, both testified how convicts' petitions, supporting
documents and filings by police, prosecutors, victims' families and
other relevant officials are forwarded quickly to parole board
members.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said board members are supposed to review the filings
before making their decision. Babcock suggested they may not even
read the documents.
</P>
<P>
   In Faulder's case, she said, parole board records show that 14
of the 18 members voted before a letter from U.S. Secretary of
State Madeline Albright, who wrote on behalf of Canadian expressing
concern that an international treaty may have been violated because
Faulder, a Canadian, had never been given the opportunity to call
his country's consulate when he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer argued that it was impossible for parole board members to
review all the paperwork in a dozen or more execution-clemency
cases a year, 400 other general clemency cases, 59,000 parole
requests and 29,000 parole revocation cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do review each of these cases. We make the time,''
Rodriguez said. ``We take this job very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also testified that parole board members never seek to
verify the information given them. As proof, Babcock cited a
protest letter written by a Gregg County sheriff which she said
contained inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   But underscoring the secrecy of the process, the letter was
entered in evidence Monday under seal and kept confidential by
Sparks at the insistence of state officials. So were more than a
half-dozen boxes of official files on the two cases, which were
brought to the courtroom after Sparks demanded they be surrendered,
when state officials did not produce them as requested Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorneys General Reed Lockhoof and Dewey Helmcamp
insisted that Texas' system is both legal and fair. ``The inmates
and their attorneys want one more shot to retry their case with the
board, and that's not what clemency is all about,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   But, based on his questions throughout the hearing, Sparks
appeared unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that a recent U.S. Supreme Court opinion ruled that ``due
process in clemency procedures is a constitutional right,'' Sparks
told state officials, ``if the state's procedures are not too
clear, then every single execution'' will end up for review in
federal court, like the Faulder and Barber cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine a state being dumb enough to do that (operate
with unclear procedures), but there are a lot of things I don't
understand,'' Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is an extremely politically conservative state,''
Lockhoof told Sparks, attempting to explain why lawmakers have left
the system unchanged for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to stay at the bottom of the 35 states?'' Sparks
shot back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his sometimes pointed questioning , Sparks also made it
clear he intends to decide only the legal issues raised in the
Faulder and Barber cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a legislator. . . I do not intent to establish Texas
law,'' he said. ``My interest is only did these two people have
full constitutional protections.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close of Monday's hearing, Sparks expressed surprise that
state officials ended their presentation without presenting any
evidence to bolster their assertions about the legality of Texas'
system.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Attorney General Dan Morales in a published
interview had questioned whether Texas' clemency system was fair. A
spokesman said Monday that Morales' personal opinion has no bearing
on the presentation of the case before Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
