<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-FOLO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON OCTUPLETS REMAIN IN CRITICAL CONDITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trims included) 
 
By T.J. MILLING 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first known set of surviving octuplets remained in
critical condition Monday as a team of specialists worked to help
their tiny bodies adjust to life outside the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday morning, their mother underwent surgery to stop
internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   The infants _ know as babies A through H because their parents
have not yet named them _ were being cared for by the 10 physicians
and three nurse practitioners in the neonatal intensive care unit
at Texas Children's Hospital. The babies were moved there from St.
Luke's Episcopal Hospital after seven were surgically removed from
Nkem Chukwu's womb Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth was delivered naturally Dec. 8, but the others were
kept in the womb to allow them to mature further, which increases
their chances of survival. The infants, six girls and two boys,
weighed from 11 ounces to 1 pound 11 ounces at birth, but their
weights are expected to drop slightly before rebounding in a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ```Out of the woods' will probably be two or three weeks away,''
said Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology at Texas Children's.
``Each week the problems change a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, who conceived after a fertility drug therapy, was
returned to surgery to stop internal bleeding about 3 a.m. CST
Monday, a St. Luke's spokeswoman said. She was in stable condition
in St. Luke's late Monday, but she was still in the intensive care
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hurdle for the newborns now is lung development,
Weisman said. The 2-week-old, a girl, was breathing on her own, but
the other seven were on mechanical ventilators, though only two
were on pure oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Premature infants' lungs are deficient in a chemical called
surfactant, which is produced by cells in the alveoli, the
microscopic terminal sacs where gases diffuse into the blood.
Surfactant, a viscous fluid, keeps the sacs from collapsing,
allowing maximum gas exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Respiratory failure was a major killer of premature babies until
surfactant treatment was developed in the 1980s. An additional
steroid treatment given to the pregnant mother to stimulate
surfactant production in the fetus was also developed, and, Weisman
said, the two methods used together have greatly reduced infant
mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Another medical advance that helps the octuplets' chances is
caffeine. Used in neonatology for about 15 years, caffeine
stimulates the infants' respiratory systems and allows them to
breathe on their own sooner, Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   A third improvement was a drug that prevents the ductus
arteriosus from staying open, Weisman said. While the fetus is in
the womb getting oxygen from its mother's blood, the duct shunts
blood around the fetal lungs. It normally closes at birth, when the
infant starts breathing but can remain open, especially in
premature infants.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said ventilation technology and nutrition have improved
also, but the lung treatments made the biggest difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surfactant makes all the others pale by comparison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The octuplets were also on antibiotics as a precaution, and
sedatives, Weisman said. They were being given dopamine, a
vasoconstrictor, to raise their blood pressure, and tucked under
plastic blankets and kept warm with heaters.
</P>
<P>
   Premature babies have a greater risk of developing such
abnormalities as cerebral palsy, but an ultrasound view of the
2-week-old showed no such problems, Weisman said. The others will
be scanned in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Companies have pledged to provide free groceries, free baby
formula and free diapers for a year. St. Luke's was also setting up
a bank account for the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of calls,'' hospital Director of
Development Katy Gill said. ``We're trying to figure out what they
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Prado, a neighbor of the octuplet parents, said Chukwu and
the father, Iyke Paul Louis, 41, were ``good neighbors and good
people.'' He said Louis was a respiratory therapist and some-time
real estate agent, but neither Prado nor other neighbors knew the
couple well.
</P>
<P>
   Louis was not present at the Sunday birth, hospital officials
said, and it was not clear whether he had visited since.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu miscarried a set of triplets earlier this year before
becoming pregnant with the octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   How she came to be on fertility drugs has not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors offered to reduce the number of fetuses in her womb in
order to improve the remaining ones' chances of survival, but
Chukwu declined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fertility specialists say multiple births are not a medical
miracle, but a medical mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman is in danger of losing one or more of these babies.
The babies may face a reduced quality of life,'' said Dr. Ronald
Young, director of gynecology at Baylor College of Medicine. ``I'm
praying that they all go to Harvard, that they all do well, but
there is inherent danger in patients using these drugs by
themselves or untrained physicians using them.''
</P>
<P>
   The drugs Chukwu used, according to the obstetrician who began
caring for her after the drugs were administered, were a pair of
hormones. One stimulates the development of ova on the ovary, and
the other causes them to pop off the ovary and enter the fallopian
tube where sperm can fertilize them.
</P>
<P>
   After administration of the first hormone, the doctor can use a
scope to inspect the ovary for the presence of mature follicles,
the structures that contain the ova. He may choose not to
administer the second hormone if there are many mature follicles,
which could lead to multiple fetuses. But even if the second
hormone is not administered, the woman should be ordered to abstain
from sex, said Dr. Larry Lipshultz, a Baylor professor of urology.
All the mature ova eventually will enter the fallopian tube, where
they could be fertilized.
</P>
<P>
   Lipshultz said in vitro fertilization, in which a few mature
eggs are removed from the ovary, fertilized and then replaced in
the womb, allows much better control of the number of fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are safe drugs if properly used and properly
monitored,'' he said. ``We just don't have the whole story. We
don't know if she took too much drug or what. We have to wait to
get that information before we can comment on what happened. We
just have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The same fertility treatment has lead to numerous multiple
births. The five surviving infants from a set of sextuplets, born
Nov. 11 to Chris Collins in nearby Kingwood, are still at Texas
Children's.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in Carlisle, Iowa, Bobbi McCaughey gave birth to the
only known surviving septuplets, about nine weeks premature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the Guinness Book of World Records, the largest
multiple birth was nine babies in Sydney, Australia, in 1971. Six
of those children survived.
</P>
<P>
   Three other octuplet births have been recorded in the last 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Rosario Clavijo, 31, of Huelva, Spain, became
pregnant with the aid of fertility drugs and gave birth Dec. 5,
1996, to six healthy babies _ four boys and two girls. Two children
died.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, a 32-year-old British woman, Mandy Allwood,
rejected medical advice to abort some of her eight fetuses. Her
pregnancy and her decision to have all the babies aroused
controversy after she hired a publicist for a tabloid newspaper,
which paid for her story based on how many live births she had.
Four months into pregnancy, she lost all the fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-year-old woman from Imzir, Turkey, gave birth to octuplets
Dec. 20, 1985, but six died within 12 hours. The five boys and
three girls were delivered by Caesarean section, 12 weeks
premature. The mother, Sevil Capan, had been taking fertility
drugs. The remaining two babies died within three days of their
birth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
