<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Spend wisely, Sharp warns
</P>
<P>
   By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some state lawmakers and agency officials might
have visions of billions of dollars dancing in their heads, but
Comptroller John Sharp says someone needs to step up and be the
budget grinch next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp will leave office in January after an unsuccessful bid for
lieutenant governor. On Monday he said state lawmakers face the
tough challenge of keeping a cautious eye on the state's checkbook
even though there's likely to be more money that can legally be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, a former state representative and senator, called the
next session a dangerous time for the Legislature ``because they
are flush with money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to be thinking about paring back and storing
their nuts for the winter,'' he said. ``Somebody's got to be the
bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   According to preliminary estimates from Sharp's office, the
state could have $3.7 billion left over when the two-year budget
cycle ends Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Growth in the state's economy could kick in another $2.6 billion
for the next budget cycle.
</P>
<P>
   And the state's settlement with tobacco companies over Medicare
spending will add $1.8 billion during the biennium.
</P>
<P>
   But legislative budget leaders already have warned that a
constitutional spending cap will prevent them from spending a chunk
of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The cap prevents the state budget from growing faster than the
economy even if there's money to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Growth in schools, prisons and other state services will eat a
good share of the surplus, legislative leaders have said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said now is not the time to become complacent in the
effort to hold down state spending, especially while there are
uncertainties in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're now not your own economy,'' Sharp said of Texas.
``You're a national economy. If the national economy goes up, you
do great. If the national economy goes down, you go down with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of uncertainty out there,'' he added. ``There is
a lot of euphoria without reason and a lot of flux. Now ought to be
the time that you really watch your spending. If you don't do that,
then you pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan B. Elizondo Jr. writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
