<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL22-COX     12-21 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New ad campaign helping company make its strong points clearer
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Recovering from a bumpy start, Dell Computer
Corp.'s national television advertising campaign is up and running
in the company's first major effort to strengthen the Dell brand.
</P>
<P>
   The $70 million campaign is designed to raise Dell's profile
among business executives, information-system managers, even
college students. Unlike commercials that include details about
products and prices, the TV spots are designed to prompt viewers to
add Dell to their list of potential PC suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are considered, we are one of the industry's best at
closing deals,'' said Scott Helbing, Dell's vice president of
corporate brand strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Dell executives believe that the straightforward commercials,
which were produced by the global agency BBD&AMP;O, convey the
company's direct style better than an aborted campaign by the J.
Walter Thompson agency.
</P>
<P>
   That effort ended up in court this fall, when the agency sued
Dell and Dell countersued.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texans might be surprised to learn that the world's
fastest-growing major PC company and the region's largest private
employer remains an unknown to many corporations, businesses and
consumers. Dell's blue logo with the askew ``e'' is a long way from
having the global or even national recognition of Nike's swoosh,
Apple Computer's multicolored apple and Coca-Cola's label.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's own research found that many potential customers haven't
heard of the company or, if they have, are confused about what it
does. For example, Dell executives say a surprising number of
people believe the company is a Texas mail-order business.
</P>
<P>
   The BBD&AMP;O campaign targets those weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   The spot aimed at consumers features a college music major who
says that with Dell she was able to configure the exact notebook
computer she needed, with features she couldn't find elsewhere. A
second spot features a British engineer whose responsibilities
include maintaining his large employer's computer system.
</P>
<P>
   In the third of the 30-second spots, an airline industry
executive praises Dell for delivering solutions when people all
around him are coming to him with problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's problems with J. Walter Thompson started only two months
after work began on the initial campaign last December. Dell
executives were unhappy with the quality of the work that the huge
agency was producing, according to a lawsuit Dell filed this month
in Williamson County.
</P>
<P>
   That suit followed the agency's suit in New York alleging that
Dell broke payment contracts with J. Walter Thompson. The agency
claims Dell owes it more than $6 million in fees and bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   In its countersuit, Dell says the agency failed to forward
Dell's payments for air time to at least one TV station, and that
its performance forced the delay of the campaign, which originally
was to launch in the United States in April and worldwide a short
time later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a single, acceptable broadcast spot was ever delivered,''
Dell's suit says.
</P>
<P>
   That spot starred a mouse, drawn in animation, who donned
sunglasses and bombed a maze that separated it from a large wedge
of yellow cheese. The point was that Dell's direct model eliminates
obstacles to success, such as middlemen. That was the message Dell
wanted to convey.
</P>
<P>
   But the 30-second spot had the potential to confuse viewers,
Helbing said.
</P>
<P>
   He was recruited to Dell in February after about 11 years in
advertising, including two years with Tricon Restaurants
International, the PepsiCo spinoff that owns Pizza Hut, Kentucky
Fried Chicken and Taco Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I the mouse?'' Helbing asked, imagining how a viewer might
have reacted. ``And why did he burn it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to picture someone saying, `That's a cute little
mouse. I think I'll go buy a multimillion-dollar system from those
people.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Helbing said the BBD&AMP;O campaign is more direct, which fits
Dell's style.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse commercial ran in major U.S. markets for four weeks
beginning last June, even though Dell Chairman Michael Dell and
other top executives had lingering doubts about it. In early
August, Dell told J. Walter Thompson that it had asked BBD&AMP;O to
create its version of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''It got to the point where we had to find a solution,'' Helbing
said.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for J. Walter Thompson was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapid turnaround for a campaign of that size, BBD&AMP;O had new
commercials ready by mid-November, including filming in Austin, San
Antonio, New York, London and Paris, Helbing said.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin shots include Metric 12, Dell's pace-setting
manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   Those ``bricks-and mortar'' glimpses convey that Dell is
substantial, much more than a mail-order house, Helbing said.
</P>
<P>
   The spots will air during select events, the relatively rare
times executives watch TV. That includes during college football
bowl games and NFL games and on cable news programs such as MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Versions of the commercials will run in Japan and Europe early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Until data is available about the effectiveness of the spots,
Dell is relying largely on gut feelings of senior executives,
especially chief executive Michael Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really close to who we are as a company, because
Michael should have a better feel for who this company is than
anybody else,'' Helbing said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
