<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HALL-COX     12-21 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President serves up holiday cheer at soup kitchen
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton demonstrated his holiday spirit
on his first day at work since being impeached.
</P>
<P>
   And he invited U.S. Rep. Tony Hall to join him.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton, Ohio Democrat joined Clinton and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton on Monday at the D.C. Central Kitchen, where they
helped the massive facility prepare more than 2,700 holiday meals
for almost 100 charity organizations around the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons worked on a pan of lasagna and Hall teamed with
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman to frost a Christmas cake.
During the event Clinton offered an olive branch to the Congress
that last Saturday made him the first elected president to be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they have a merry Christmas,'' Clinton said. ``I hope
everyone in the country will take some time to think about other
people and do something in the spirit of the season _ something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who has campaigned against hunger both at home and abroad,
said Clinton was ``trying to lead by example'' at the soup kitchen
where Hall has volunteered many times before.
</P>
<P>
   Hall spoke by telephone with Clinton on Saturday before the
impeachment vote, and then again Sunday night. He said Clinton
hopes the up-coming Senate trial ``isn't a long, drawn-out thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of Clinton's state of mind: ``At least as far as what he
says and how he looks, he seems OK. He's been down lately, but he's
staying in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall has steadfastly advocated a compassionate and forgiving
resolution to the crisis that has dogged Clinton all year.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor during the debate, Hall argued against a clause in
the impeachment articles that would bar Clinton from ever again
holding any public office in the future. ``The House doesn't have
the moral authority to judge that the president is forever
unredeemable,'' Hall said at the time
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Hall said that the day at the D.C. Central Kitchen
was good, and that he remained impressed with Hillary Clinton's
graciousness and strength.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cake decorating, Hall reported mixed success. He
struggled to write out ``Merry Christmas'' and sign his name in
pink frosting, but did better working in straight lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I did was the borders.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
This story includes information from the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
