<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/21/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ALPINE, Ariz. -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- WOLF-RELEASE-PROGRAM,
12-21 -- Newly reintroduced after ranchers exterminated them half a
century ago from the high timberlands of eastern Arizona, today's
wolves wear radio collars that allow them to be tracked by
biologists. Bobby Fite, a cattle rancher in Alpine, says one of the
newly returned wolves had entered his property. Fite tends about 40
Herefords. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- CHINA-LIU, 12-21 -- Liu
Nianchun, right, released from a Chinese labor camp on medical
grounds, criticizes Beijing at a press conference in New York. With
him are his brother, Liu Qing, and Xu Jin, daughter of another
activist, Xu Wenli. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS-2, 12-21
-- A Labor politician, Haim Ramon, right, with Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, a Likud member, as Parliament meets Monday in
Jerusalem to dissolve Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
government. Netanyahu on Monday accepted the inevitability of his
government's downfall, striking a deal with the political
opposition to hold new elections sometime next spring. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- HARLEM-NUTCRACKER, 12-21 --
Donald Byrd, the modern-dance choreographer. His faith in ``The
Harlem Nutcracker,'' a nine-year labor of love that begins a
two-week engagement Tuesday at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, has
paid off. The company has whittled down a debt of
``one-point-something million'' dollars connected with the
production, as Byrd says, to $400,000. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- KAZUKO-FASHION-3, 12-21 --
Kazuko, dressed in her trademark white clothing, wears necklaces
she calls ``floating wires,'' strung with a spectrum of stones,
priced from $100 to $250. You may admire Kazuko's work, but don't
call her a designer. ``I don't design,'' she says emphatically. ``I
make things.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- KAZUKO-FASHION-2, 12-21 --
Vest of antique lace with seed pearls, $1,975; cell phone pouch on
gold wire with pearls and stones, $1,875. ``I totally believe in
fashion,'' says Kazuko, the designer. ``Fashion is like Zen. What
we put on our body is as important as what we eat and breathe.''
(Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- KAZUKO-FASHION-1, 12-21 --
Choker of mixed stones, including aquamarine and tourmaline, on
gold wires by Kazuko, $3,985. Her jewelry has earned her a loyal
following in the 10 years it has sold at Barneys New York stores,
but the newer note cards and fabric pieces have created the impetus
for an exhibition of Kazuko's work planned for spring at the Holly
Solomon Gallery. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LOS ANGELES -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- LA-HOMELESS-2, 12-21 --
Janice Foster walks with her children (from left: William, 14,
Shayla, 4, and Dion, 3) in downtown Los Angeles. The family is
spending its nights at the Union Rescue Mission shelter, one of the
few in Los Angeles that will allow a family with a boy age 13 or
older to stay together. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- LA-HOMELESS-1, 12-21 --
William Foster, 14, plays with a yo-yo in the hallway of the Union
Rescue Mission, a homeless shelter. There are not many other
shelters for a family to go and stay together in Los Angeles, and
even fewer that will take in a boy - like William - who is 13 years
or older. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, 12-21
-- Rep. Robert Livingston and his wife, Bonnie, stand outside the
Capitol on November 6 after announcing he would run for speaker of
the House. Even though Livingston had a number of affairs while
gaining power in Congress, he said during a recent interview that
he shrugged off an advertisement asking women to come forward with
information about affairs with members of Congress. ``I didn't
consider the power of a million dollars,'' says Livingston.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- IRAQ-MILITARY, 12-21 --
U.S. Marine Gen. Anthony C. Zinni, the commander who led the air
attack against Iraq, right, and U.S. Navy Capt. Mike Todd, listen
to Secretary of Defense William Cohen, foreground, during a press
briefing on the results of Operation Desert Fox on Monday at the
Pentagon. Zinni said American forces had hit 85 percent of their
targets and that there were signs that Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein was losing some of his control over the country. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- PARADE-BROWN-2, 12-21 --
Brent Carver, as Leo Frank, and Carolee Carmello, as his wife, in
``Parade,'' with music and lyrics by Jason Robert Brown. Although
critical reaction has been decidedly mixed, the play arguably
represents the most ambitious new work of the season, given that
large-scale original musicals rarely come along these days, and
that ``Parade'' deals with such weighty subjects. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- PARADE-BROWN-1, 12-21 --
Jason Robert Brown, with ``Parade'' props. For Brown, writing the
music and lyrics for ``Parade'' was hard because he wanted to bring
to life Leo Frank - the man at the center of the play, a New York
Jew working as a superintendent at a pencil factory in Atlanta in
1913 - but the character eluded him. ``I couldn't find a lot of
personal resonance,'' says Brown. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LONDON -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- SPY-NOVELS, 12-21 -- Ken
Follett signing copies of his latest novel, ``The Hammer of Eden,''
in London recently. In the last two months, writers like Follett
and Robert Ludlum have left their publishing houses for new ones,
moves that often reflect polite differences about advances or sales
expectations that publishers do not consider promising enough to
justify the generous contracts of flush days. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS, 12-21 --
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu listens to a debate in
the Knesset on Monday about early elections. The Israeli Parliament
rejected Netanyahu's peace policies on Monday, then gave initial
approval to a law calling early elections. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- SCI-AIDS-MINORITIES, 12-21
-- A forum in Harlem sponsored by the Rev. Al Sharpton and his
National Action Network showcased alternative views on AIDS. ``I
don't agree with everything they may say, but I think people should
hear it,'' says Sharpton. (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NORTHBORO, Mass. -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- ISLAMIC-SCHOOLS-BOS,
12-21 -- Asama Ahmed, in third grade, listens to her teacher during
a class at the Al-Hamra Academy in Northboro. The school was
founded four years ago as the first Islamic elmentary school in
Massachusetts. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- FASHION-COLUMN-BOS, 12-21 --
Johnnie Evers shows Stephanie Lugin the finished results following
a makeup session. More than ever before, there are male makeup
artists everywhere giving hands-on advice to women about their
looks. ``We make people feel good about themselves,'' Evers says of
his job. ``We're not judgmental. At the end of the day, I can go
home and feel good because I made someone else feel good.'' (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- SCI-FITNESS-CHILD, 12-21 --
Pushing a stroller while jogging seems safe, one expert says, but
the stroller should be sturdy and stable. ``Don't trade safety for
savings,'' says Dr. Bryant Stamford. ``Expect to pay over $200.''
He also suggests choosing a model with a deep seat and a seat belt,
and wearing a safety wrist strap to prevent the stroller from
getting away from you. (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- IMPEACH-HASTERT, 12-21 --
Rep. Dennis Hastert, chief deputy whip, left, meets with Rep. John
Boehner, the House majority whip, in a conference room at the U.S.
Capitol in June. Hastert, who has suddenly gone from being an
anonymous middle-level legislator to the presumptive speaker of the
House, has a reputation among his GOP colleagues as someone who can
reach out to Democrats. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) M0NTERAY, Calif. -- Dec. 21, 1998 --
SCI-DEEPSEA-AQUARIUM-2, 12-21 -- Mushroom soft coral uses tentacles
to catch food. Miles beneath the turbulent waters of California's
Monterey Bay, research biologists equipped with a giant robot
submersible, advanced sensory equipment and stomachs almost of
steel are collecting some of the rarest sea creatures known to man.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- SCI-DEEPSEA-AQUARIUM-1, 12-21
-- Researchers lift a giant robot submersible after a deep dive to
collect sea animals for a Monterey Bay exhibit. If the biologists
manage to keep these bizarre animals alive after bringing them back
from the abyss, as they say they can, the researchers plan a public
exhibit of more than 40 species early next year the largest such
display of living deep-sea life ever. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
