<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prosecutors, Fagan: Still no deal
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Stephen Fagan's daughters and his
ex-wife met separately with prosecutors Monday, each airing sharply
different views of the man charged with kidnapping his children two
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and Fagan have not reached a plea deal, which
sources said has been under discussion for about two weeks. A
preliminary hearing is scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan took daughters Rachael and Lisa, then 5 and 3, in 1979
during a Massachusetts custody battle with ex-wife Barbara Kurth.
Fagan fled to South Florida with his daughters days later and
created a fictional life as Dr. William Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth has not seen her daughters since the October 1979
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, she met with Middlesex County District Attorney Tom
Reilly to discuss the case and state her opposition to a plea deal.
Less than an hour after that meeting, her daughters met with Reilly
to plead for his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who is leaving office in two weeks to become
Massachusetts Attorney General, was joined by his successor, Martha
Coakley. Coakley gained national attention last year prosecuting
Louise Woodward, the British nanny convicted of killing a baby in
her care.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth's attorney, Jacob Atwood, said Coakley wanted to meet
Kurth and size her up as a potential witness if the case goes to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't go into what they said, but from our side it was a
positive meeting,'' Atwood said. ``They were clearly impressed by
Barbara's resilience and her demeanor, and I think they have a good
feeling now about what kind of a witness she'll be.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, who has opposed any plea deal that keeps Fagan out of
jail, said his client won't interfere with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara doesn't want to impose her views on the judicial
system, and she doesn't want to do anything that would put a
further wedge between her and the kids,'' Atwood said. ``Any
reasonable prosecutor will look to discuss a plea, and there's
still room for that. But after the meeting Barbara doesn't have any
feeling that they are going to sell her out.''
</P>
<P>
   John Holland writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
