<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- SCI-FITNESS-CHILD, 12-21 --
Pushing a stroller while jogging seems safe, one expert says, but
the stroller should be sturdy and stable. ``Don't trade safety for
savings,'' says Dr. Bryant Stamford. ``Expect to pay over $200.''
He also suggests choosing a model with a deep seat and a seat belt,
and wearing a safety wrist strap to prevent the stroller from
getting away from you. (Chris Maynard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- IMPEACH-HASTERT, 12-21 --
Rep. Dennis Hastert, chief deputy whip, left, meets with Rep. John
Boehner, the House majority whip, in a conference room at the U.S.
Capitol in June. Hastert, who has suddenly gone from being an
anonymous middle-level legislator to the presumptive speaker of the
House, has a reputation among his GOP colleagues as someone who can
reach out to Democrats. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) M0NTERAY, Calif. -- Dec. 21, 1998 --
SCI-DEEPSEA-AQUARIUM-2, 12-21 -- Mushroom soft coral uses tentacles
to catch food. Miles beneath the turbulent waters of California's
Monterey Bay, research biologists equipped with a giant robot
submersible, advanced sensory equipment and stomachs almost of
steel are collecting some of the rarest sea creatures known to man.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Dec. 21, 1998 -- SCI-DEEPSEA-AQUARIUM-1, 12-21
-- Researchers lift a giant robot submersible after a deep dive to
collect sea animals for a Monterey Bay exhibit. If the biologists
manage to keep these bizarre animals alive after bringing them back
from the abyss, as they say they can, the researchers plan a public
exhibit of more than 40 species early next year the largest such
display of living deep-sea life ever. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
