<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1462 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SECRETARY-STATE-C     12-21 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SECRETARY-STATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No sneak-peeks into Secretary of State's digs for Florida's
Harris
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Some transitions are smoother than others.
</P>
<P>
   Before his Dec. 12 death, Gov. Lawton Chiles let successor Jeb
Bush join him in picking a Supreme Court justice. Bush, who will
name other appointments today, is expected to move into the
governor's mansion several days ahead of his Jan. 5 inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of State Sandra Mortham, who lost to Katherine
Harris in a Sept. 1 GOP primary, has refused to let Harris into her
office early even to measure the drapes or plug nail holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Katherine Harris takes office, she can do all the
decorating she wants,'' said Mortham spokesman David Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Harris aides say they got the message when they saw the
transition office they were assigned by Mortham on the Capitol's
19th floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a 12- by 9-foot room with a card table,'' one aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mortham, the first incumbent Cabinet member to lose in a primary
in nearly three decades, also refused to put any Harris transition
people on her payroll, which the aides said is often done as a
courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   Harris declined to criticize ally-turned-rival Mortham, saying
with a shrug, ``She just doesn't believe it's a good use of
taxpayer dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Mortham, who will take a job as a lobbyist for the Florida
Medical Association next month, is just following the rules, Bishop
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the swearing-in, Sandra Mortham is still the Secretary
of State,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
