<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-RAILROAD-COX     12-21 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RAILROAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush names GOP counsel to oil panel
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, whose re-election campaign
included an unprecedented outreach to minorities, Monday named
Michael Williams the first African American on the Texas Railroad
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 45, will replace Republican Carole Keeton Rylander,
who is giving up her seat to become state comptroller next month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Williams, general counsel to the Republican Party of
Texas, is ``a smart, capable individual who brings a blend of
legal, policy and regulatory knowledge'' to the agency that
regulates the oil and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   Williams acknowledged that one thing he doesn't bring is
experience in the oil and gas industry. His lack of experience is
not unique for railroad commissioners, whose interest in the job is
frequently more political.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he views his new job as ``a great challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a kid who grew up in Midland, and I understand the
significance of the energy industry in the state's economy and the
culture of the state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who plans to run for the seat when it's on the ballot
in 2000, beat out a contender who has oil and gas experience and
who did Bush a political favor this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Holzheauser, R-Victoria, was a leading GOP candidate
for election to the three-member commission this year. He withdrew
when Tony Garza, a Bush appointee as secretary of state, abandoned
his race for state land commissioner and instead ran for the
Railroad Commission. Garza will succeed Barry Williamson, who ran
an unsuccessful race for attorney general instead of seeking
re-election to the Railroad Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Holzheauser, chairman of the House Energy Resources Committee,
wanted the appointment to replace Rylander. He said he was told
late Sunday that he would not get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got a fair hearing on my abilities, and I'm
satisfied that the governor's staff was diligent in their
evaluation of the candidates,'' said Holzheauser, offering not a
hint of ill will. ``In politics, nobody owes you anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, general counsel for the Richardson-based Wilkins Group
Inc., a telecommunications firm, said Bush approached him about a
job shortly after the November election. They discussed secretary
of state and railroad commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently named Secretary of State Al Gonzales to the Texas
Supreme Court. His replacement has not been named, but Clark Kent
Ervin, an African American and No. 2 man at the secretary of
state's office, is a top contender.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Williams means the GOP probably will have an
African American on its statewide ticket in 2000. The only other
African American to win a GOP statewide nomination was Louis Sturns
of Fort Worth, who ran an unsuccessful campaign in 1990 after being
appointed to the Court of Criminal Appeals by then-Gov. Bill
Clements.
</P>
<P>
   By appointing Williams, Bush put his longtime friend on the
first rung of what has become a popular ladder to higher office.
Many commissioners have fueled those races with campaign
contributions from oil and gas interests they regulate.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said ``it would be inappropriate to suggest race played
no role'' in his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine it did, and, in a way, I would hope that it
did. I think it is important that in this kind of arena that we
indicate a desire for participation by a wide range of people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' ties to Bush go back to their days in Midland, where
Williams was raised. They served as co-chairmen of the city's
United Way campaign in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   From 1980 to 1984, Williams was a federal prosecutor
specializing in police brutality and hate crime cases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he ran for Midland County attorney and lost in the GOP
primary. Bush was his campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, President George Bush appointed Williams assistant
secretary of education for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
