<HEADER>
A1469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEEDEES-BOULEZ-NYT     12-21 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEEDEES-BOULEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICAL CDS: BRIGHTENING SOME DARK CORNERS  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boulezian Pierrot
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, Pierre Boulez has been going around the world
recording for Deutsche Grammophon the music that means most to him
_ music that in some cases has been with him throughout his life as
a musician.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg's ``Pierrot Lunaire'' was one of his early loves.
What he found in its piano part _ ``a considerable density of
texture and violence of expression'' _ influenced his own writing
for the instrument in his first published works; the crucial
achievement of his late 20s, ``Le Marteau Sans Maitre,'' was partly
a homage to ``Pierrot.'' When he started conducting, Schoenberg's
score was one of the first he recorded, in the early '60s, and he
made another version in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   His new recording (on DG 457 630) accordingly reflects, in some
respects, half a century of study and performance. It is deeply
Boulezian in its justness of instrumental tuning and balance, its
clarity of detail and, more occasionally, its vividly energized
motifs, its bursts of musical lightning.
</P>
<P>
   But much has changed, too. The piano part no longer sounds so
very dense and certainly not so very violent: violence, perhaps,
happens when the score is not being very well played, and the
performance here by members of Boulez's Ensemble Intercontemporain
is consistently beautiful and secure.
</P>
<P>
   No longer an expressionist nightmare, the work has also ceased
to be the ``superior cabaret'' Boulez once called it. Christine
Schaefer, the vocalist, interprets the speech-song notation in a
very tuneful way: She does not sound very different when fully
singing one of the other Schoenberg pieces on this CD, the
miniature, spectacularly high-flying song ``Herzgewaechse.'' Humor
and acid have given way to exquisite delicacy and exactness.
</P>
<P>
   With the instrumental music so fine and appealing, one can
understand why ``Pierrot'' had such an impact on Ravel. As it
sounds here, it could almost have been written by him. Listen to
the pretty flurry that follows what one might have thought the
threatening news that Pierrot is attacking his friend Cassander
with ``a cranium driller.''
</P>
<P>
   This is altogether a magical performance, full of musical light
and worrisome only to the extent that magic and light do not seem
the work's most essential qualities. Boulez even finds charm in
Schoenberg's later piece of chamber music with recitation, the
``Ode to Napoleon,'' where David Pittman-Jennings brings brisk
effectiveness to the tricky solo part.
</P>
<P>
   A Caring Bluebeard
</P>
<P>
   In another newly released recording, of Bartok's opera
``Bluebeard's Castle'' (DG 289 447), Boulez provides a delectable
treatment of the score, again with some of his old musical
characteristics intact: he leaps at the chopped rhythm and the
xylophone-plus-wind sound of the arpeggios that depict the armory
behind the second of the castle's seven doors _ doors that Judith
has her new husband, Bluebeard, open. (Because these seven openings
are almost the only action, ``Bluebeard'' is a perfect opera for
the ears alone.)
</P>
<P>
   Jessye Norman as Judith is an unusual choice: The part suggests
a lighter voice, if one with the power to penetrate. But, a few
slips and slides apart, Ms. Norman proves the value of ripeness. As
Bluebeard, Laszlo Polgar _ who sang this role again for Boulez at
Aix this summer _ proves the value of understanding the language.
He is magnificent: careworn and caring in his responses to his
young bride, always easy in his vocal delivery and fully in touch
with what the orchestra is doing. The playing, by the Chicago
Symphony, is wonderful throughout, and here magic and light tell
much more of the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
