<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Giving Stock to Kids or Charity  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I have owned some shares in a stock for five years, with
an original cost of about $1,000. The current market value is about
$9,000. What are the tax consequences if I give the stock to my
son? What are the tax consequences if I give the stock to charity
instead?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  First of all, congratulations on your investment
acumen. A ninefold price increase in five years? You can manage my
money anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Because the stock is worth less than $10,000, you can give it to
your son without paying gift taxes if he is at least 18 years old.
If he is younger than 18, you can avoid the gift tax only if you
deposit the money for his benefit in a Uniform Trust to Minors
account, which you can open at almost any financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   You won't have to pay a capital-gains tax on your $8,000
investment gain. However, your son will have to pay the tax after
he sells.
</P>
<P>
   If he does sell, he must use your $1,000 cost basis in
determining the size of the gain. He also will use your purchase
date in determining whether it is a long-term gain _ which it is in
this case because you have held the stock for five years. (One year
would have been enough to qualify.)
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller suggests that
you dig up the confirmation slip you received from your broker when
you bought the stock and give it to your son so that he can
document the cost and purchase date if the IRS audits him after he
sells.
</P>
<P>
   If you give the stock to charity, you can claim the full current
market value of the stock on your income tax as a charitable
deduction. Again, you don't have to pay the capital-gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   You are allowed to deduct whatever the stock was worth on the
day the company entered the transfer of ownership on its books.
This might not happen until days or even weeks after you tell your
broker to deliver the stock to the charity.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your broker or the company's transfer agent when the change
of ownership became official. Also ask for the stock's high and low
trading prices on that day. Take the midpoint, multiply it by the
number of shares, and that is how much you can deduct.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Treasuries
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in T-bill investing, which seems much safer
than the stock market. How do I go about it?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: If you have access to the Internet, go to the U.S.
Treasury Department Web site at  &LR; www.treasurydirect.gov. &LR;  It tells
you how to open an investment account directly with the government,
and explains the rules governing purchases and sales of Treasury
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can call the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco at
(415) 974-2330 and order a free investor kit.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy Treasuries in person, by telephone or on the Web
site after you have established an account. All purchases are
commission-free. However, if you sell before the issue matures, you
must pay a $34 transaction fee.
</P>
<P>
   The government will keep track of your assets, collect your
interest income and maintain your account free of charge if the
assets total no more than $100,000. Above that, you pay a $25
annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   You also can buy and sell Treasuries through your broker, who
will charge you commissions.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy Treasury bills (which expire in 13 to 52 weeks),
notes (two to 10 years) or bonds (30 years) for only $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Although Treasuries certainly are safer than stocks, they return
less than stocks over the long term. The current annual interest
rates range from about 4.3 percent for shorter-term issues to 5
percent for 30-year bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The interest you earn on Treasuries is exempt from state and
local income taxes. However, you will have to pay the federal tax.
</P>
<P>
   Young Investor
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am 22 years old and recently took a full-time job with
Oracle Corp. My company offers a 401(k) and a stock-purchase plan.
What disturbs me is all the recent negative financial news. Do you
have any investment suggestions for people my age?
</P>
<P>
   A: An investor your age should worry far less about current
financial conditions than someone who is middle-aged or approaching
retirement. One way or another, the U.S. economy always manages to
prevail in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, most experts advise young people to invest
almost entirely in a diversified portfolio of stocks or equity
mutual funds, which have a superior long-term growth record.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have returned an average of about 10 percent annually
(including reinvestment of dividends) during the past several
decades. At that rate, every $1,000 you invest today would be worth
$60,000 when you are ready to collect Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   You probably can piece together a sound portfolio by investing
whatever you can afford in your company's 401(k) plan and also
putting up to $2,000 per year in a Roth Individual Retirement
Account, where your investments grow tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Investing in Oracle through its stock-purchase plan certainly
would have been a great idea in the past. The stock is selling for
more than 25 times what it cost 10 years ago. On the other hand,
the price is still below the highs reached in the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember that staking the bulk of your funds on one stock
is extremely risky _ even though it has paid off so far for your
boss of bosses, billionaire Larry Ellison.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
