<HEADLINE>
TV FAILS TO REFLECT SOCIETY, ACTORS UNION STUDY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Television continues to present a distorted
picture of real life with significant underrepresentation of women,
seniors, the poor and most minorities, a report released Monday
showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of television seems to be frozen in a time warp of
obsolete and damaging representations,'' asserted George Gerbner, a
Temple University professor of telecommunications and author of the
study, which was commissioned by the Screen Actors Guild. ``Through
changes in ownership, management, stars and styles, the cast of the
world of television is much as it was in 1993 or, for that matter,
in 1969.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerbner, who reviewed 9,000 characters in 645 episodes between
1994 and 1997, found that women consistently played one out of
every three roles in prime time and only 48 &UR;  &LR; percent of all
characters on daytime shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They age faster than men and as they age they are more likely
to be portrayed as sexless and evil,'' he noted. ``Mature women
seem especially hard to cast _ and hard to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Seniors have nearly vanished, the study found, with old men in
0.4 &UR;  &LR; percent of roles and women in 0.2 &UR;  &LR; percent in prime time. By
ignoring seniors, television is saying that ``as characters age,
they lose importance, value and effectiveness,'' Gerbner said.
</P>
<P>
   In the study's single positive note, Gerbner found
African-American characters represented 12.3 &UR;  &LR; percent of all TV
characters, a figure generally equivalent to their percentage in
the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   But Latinos, representing more than 10 &UR;  &LR; percent of the actual
population, are cast in 2.6 &UR;  &LR; percent of prime time roles and
3.7 &UR;  &LR; percent of daytime; Asian-Americans and Pacific Islanders,
representing 3.4 &UR;  &LR; percent of the populace, are much less visible in
prime time at 1.4 &UR;  &LR; percent and 0.4 &UR;  &LR; percent in daytime. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
