<HEADLINE>
UMA ON STAGE 
ROGER'S RHYME TIME 
BEJEWELED SINGERS 
REDUNDANT BUTLER
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH JESSE MCKINLEY  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nicole Kidman, who bares all in the David Hare play
``The Blue Room'' at the Cort Theater, is not the only Hollywood
star who likes the idea of making her way across a New York stage.
Uma Thurman _ whose most recent off-camera role was new mother _
will appear in Martin Crimp's adaptation of Moliere's
``Misanthrope'' next month at the Classic Stage Company in the East
Village.
</P>
<P>
   Acting in front of an audience rather than a camera may pose a
challenge, but the role itself should not: Ms. Thurman will portray
a young American actress in a play that has been modernized from
top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Angell
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New Yorker magazine is Tina-less but not
Angell-less this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown resigned as editor in July to start a magazine
venture with Miramax. But Roger Angell, who usually contributes a
full-page rhyme built around well-known names for the year-end
issue, was back in his accustomed place on the last page,
mentioning Sen. John Glenn (``the senior flyer'') in almost the
same breath as Danny Meyer, owner of the Union Square Cafe. Angell
skipped last year's issue after the deaths of his former wife and
his brother. (``I wasn't feeling very Yule-y,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   This time around, for an issue that went to the printer the day
before the House voted to impeach President Clinton, Angell used
the word ``unimpeachable'' in the fourth line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rarely as timely as this,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And no, he did not insert the word at the last minute. He said
he decided to allude to the constitutional drama in Washington
about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it would be in the air, and I wanted to get the
whole thing over with at the beginning of the poem so people
wouldn't be looking for sly references to Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewel Song Sans Faust
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Never mind how the three singers sound at the New
York Philharmonic on New Year's Eve. The advice from one of them,
the soprano Deborah Voigt, is ``Be sure to check out the jewelry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A singer friend said to me, `Get yourself some fancy
jewelry,''' she said. ``So I had Breslin's office call up Van Cleef
&AMP; Arpels, and they said they'd be happy to send some over.''
(``Breslin's office'' refers to her press representative, Herbert
Breslin.)
</P>
<P>
   What happened next sounded like a real-life version of the Ethel
Merman standard ``Anything you can do, I can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the other sopranos got wind of it,'' Miss Voigt said,
``and she's trying to get some too.'' She said she did not know
which of the two others _ Angelica Kirchschlager, a mezzo-soprano,
or Noemi Nadelmann, a coloratura _ had also asked for jewelry. But
someone familiar with the onstage and offstage preparations (and
who spoke on the condition of anonymity) said it was Miss
Kirchschlager.
</P>
<P>
   Butler Available
</P>
<P>
   In London on Monday, Paul Burrell was described as having been
``made redundant.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Burrell _ the former butler to Diana, princess
of Wales, and the man she once called ``my rock'' _ had been let go
by the Diana, Princess of Wales Memorial Fund, a charity set up
after her death in a car crash last year. Burrell, 40, had
coordinated fund-raising events for the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph said he had been given a month's notice and
would leave his $59,000-a-year post on Jan. 18, having ``accepted
redundancy'' because his job was being phased out. There was no
answer at his home in Wrexham on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will contemplate my future in the new year,'' Burrell told
The Telegraph.
</P>
</TEXT>
