</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-POOL-LANES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES COUNTY DEFENDS CAR-POOL LANES AS NECESSARY TOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Calling car-pool lanes key to traffic relief, the
Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors voted unanimously Monday to
oppose legislation that would open the diamond lanes to all
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good tool. The whole point of the lanes is to get
people to share instead of having single-occupancy vehicles,'' said
Supervisor Don Knabe. The car-pool lane ``is a very integral part
of this whole integrated transportation system we're trying to
create'' countywide, Knabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Tom McClintock, a Republican who represents Greater
Los Angeles' northern suburbs, predicted the supervisors'
opposition won't matter in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are thinking like bureaucrats,'' he said. ``We've had 25
years of experience with these diamond lanes. Every scrap of
information we have shows they cause congestion.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate comes as the California Department of Transportation
plans to double the number of car-pool lanes from 305 miles to 680
miles by 2015 in Los Angeles, Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino and
Ventura counties.
</P>
<P>
   On an amendment by Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich, the board
unanimously agreed not to oppose Caltrans studying the opening up
the diamond lanes to all traffic on Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock contends the state effectively stopped building
freeways 30 years ago, ``while politicians like Don Knabe poured
billions of dollars down these transportation rat holes like
diamond lanes.''
</P>
<P>
   McClintock said only 7 percent of traffic uses car-pool lanes,
but Caltrans senior engineer Dawn Helou said that amount represents
15 percent of people on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock said he bases his conclusions on the experience of
New Jersey, which in November reopened its car-pool lanes to all
traffic on two interstate highways. The car-pool lanes covered only
about 30 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went from bumper-to-bumper congestion to free flow in all
lanes,'' McClintock said.
</P>
<P>
   In an extensive study, New Jersey officials found the diamond
lanes did not boost car pooling but instead worsened traffic
congestion, were plagued with cheaters who endangered others by
darting in and out of the car-pool lanes, and didn't improve air
quality as expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981221.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-21 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS &LR;      12-21 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The job this week for the National Basketball Players
Association is sealing the cracks in its vaunted unity.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks? Try exposed fault lines. Karl Malone's statement that
the owners' most recent collective-bargaining proposal, mailed to
each NBA player last week by commissioner David Stern, was ``fair''
and that a deal is ``almost done'' measured on seismographs on both
sides of the labor war.
</P>
<P>
   So the union spent Monday, Day 174 of the lockout, in an
``informal'' meeting with its negotiating committee, coming to the
conclusion that the offer was not substantive enough to warrant a
vote of the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Avery Johnson, a member of that rank and file, felt otherwise.
When asked if he believed the owners' latest proposal would go
before the union membership for a vote, Johnson said, ``Yes. Billy
(Hunter, the union executive director) has been doing a good job of
gauging how we feel about everything that's on the table, so I
sense something is going to happen in the next couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if you listen to the union's negotiating committee, which
discussed the issue with approximately 100 members on a conference
call Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just caught up and talked over some things,'' said Danny
Schayes. ``Out of the conference call from last week, we had talked
over the viability of voting on their (the owners') proposal. We
voted unanimously in our group not to vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then the players on our weekly conference call (Monday)
voted unanimously not to as well. The response was that they liked
the job we were doing. They're desirous of a fair deal, and they
won't even consider voting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not right now, but the day may be fast approaching when
the players call for a vote. The season will be canceled if a deal
isn't reached soon, and Stern, who is vacationing in Colorado, has
refused to specify the exact date when the league will be shut
down. It has been 10 days since the negotiating committees from
both sides sat down to bargain, and no new talks are on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Stern mailed a copy of the owners' latest collective-bargaining
proposal to every player in the league, perhaps hoping for a few
players to speak in favor of accepting the deal. It was a move no
doubt prompted by Hunter's assertion that he would not put an
``unacceptable'' offer up for a vote of the union rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone thought the deal was only in need of tweaking before
he considered it acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, that deal (the owners' offer) is fair,''
Malone said at Saturday's charity all-star game in Atlantic City,
N.J. ``It just needs some minor changes. I think the deal is
decent. To me, I feel the deal is almost done.''
</P>
<P>
   Union president Patrick Ewing disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That deal is the same deal we've been going over for the last
two or three weeks _ maybe even longer,'' he said. ``They haven't
changed their position one iota. All they did was make the numbers
look great, but it's not a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Schayes cited non-economic issues like cap restrictions that are
the biggest stumbling blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Schayes pointed out the owners' new definition of the cap hold
as one. In previous years, the salary for a Larry Bird-exception
free agent counted 150 percent against the team's salary cap.
Whatever space remained under the cap when signed players and
unsigned Bird-exception free agents were totaled was how much a
team could offer another's free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But under the new proposal, the cap hold would rise from 150
percent to perhaps 400 percent, meaning teams would have
significantly less room under the cap to go out and sign another
team's free agent _ which translates into less freedom of movement
for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the economic issues, we are fairly close,'' Schayes said.
``On the percentage (of basketball-related income to be divided),
we're at 57 (percent) and they're at 52. That's pretty close. On
the escrow number (on how much of their salaries the players should
contribute to protect against salary overspending), they're at 15
(percent); we're at 10. On the (maximum salary) increase, they're
at 12.5 and 7.5 (percent); we're at 13 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then they have a laundry list of 20 other things, other
issues that relate to freedom of movement _ things like trying to
slip in an increased cap hold. There are a lot of those things that
chip away at the value of the Larry Bird exception and free agency.
We may be farther apart on those things than on the economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we can meet between Christmas and New Year's and
hopefully get some action. Let's make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' Eddie Johnson thinks something will happen within
the next week to 10 days _ but it won't be a vote on the owners'
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Stern) will come up with a proposal that will
pique our interest,'' Johnson said. ``I think that right after
Christmas he will lay out a proposal that he's had in his pocket
all along, a last, best offer. I think it'll be one that doesn't
really divide the union, but it's going to be where half think it's
good and half doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll give us a short period of time to make a decision on it,
maybe five days or so, so the players will be antsy and anxious to
get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery Johnson said that as doomsday approaches, the union should
consider the fact that the owners have all the leverage and that
after fighting the good fight, it may be time to consider accepting
an offer from the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thinking has always been that when it gets to the point
where it's the last possible date that we can make a deal or this
thing is over (the season is canceled), (that the union leadership
must be) really be mindful of the middle-class guys,'' Johnson
said. ``The big guys are always going to get their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they don't make it on the court, they'll make it off
the court (in endorsements). So just really be mindful of the 300
or so middle-class guys that we have in the league and make your
decision based on those guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 2302EST &QL; 
