<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURBY-THEFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEFT PROMPT POLICE TO ISSUE FIRST FURBY ALERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTROSE, Calif. _ Thieves broke a hobby store window and
snatched two Furbys, leaving behind other valuable collectibles,
police and the store owner said.
</P>
<P>
   The theft prompted police Monday to warn store owners to move
their Furbys out of view from store windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something that's popular and a novelty should probably be put
somewhere else,'' said Sgt. Matt Wojnarowski of the Glendale Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest desperate measure in the rush to own one of the
6 1/2-inch-tall interactive _ and apparently irresistible _ toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that people kind of lose perspective about what
the holidays are all about,'' said Lana Simon, spokeswoman for
Furby maker Tiger Electronics Ltd., based in Vernon Hills, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Wojnarowski said this was the first Furby burglary
they had heard of since the toys became the Christmas rage.
</P>
<P>
   But Simon said she has heard of some people even dyeing the fur
on the microchip-minded toys in an effort to dress them up as rare
Furbys. The stolen ones from Crescenta Valley Hobby and Craft, in
the suburbs north of Los Angeles, included a white-haired,
blue-eyed one with a $500 price tag and a gray-haired Furby with
brown eyes priced at $200.
</P>
<P>
   As for the store owner, Fred Farias, he won't miss the pair of
Furbys that have sent teen-agers into temper tantrums because they
so desperately wanted their parents to buy this season's hot toy
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I'm Furby-free,'' Farias said Monday as he
continued cleaning up broken glass from his store. ``We don't have
to worry. ... I don't have to be held up (at gunpoint) for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Farias was trying to sell the two toys on consignment as a favor
for two loyal customers who purchased the popular items at retail
prices after waiting in line for three hours at a toy store in a
mall.
</P>
<P>
   Farias already purchased two replacement Furbys from a friend _
at the going rate of $100 apiece, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have never put them in the window,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Farias is thankful the thieves didn't get away with other
items _ like a $400 model train engine and a Hot Wheels set for
$180.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what a Furby was until yesterday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just aggravating,'' another store employee said. ``It
seems like most people are buying them to resell them. It's like
scalping tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The furry animals with bulging eyes and an O-shape mouth retail
for $30-$35 but are going as high as several hundred dollars in
underground trade in classified ads, online auction sites and even
from people's garages and car trunks. Police valued the two toys at
$100 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The thieves stole the Furbys sometime between 10:30 p.m.
Saturday, after the owner closed shop, and 6 a.m. Sunday when a
passer-by noticed the broken glass, Farias said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to wait until after the holiday rush, there's
no need to purchase Furbys underground, Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty into 1999,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 2328EST &QL; 
