<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-CSUNSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN ALUMNI STRIVE FOR BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Sidebar to CSUN baseball story) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adam Kennedy, Eric Gillespie and Robert Fick were
the core of Cal State Northridge's best baseball team, the 1996
squad that won 52 games and came within a win of the College World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three of us were the best,'' said Fick, a catcher and the
fifth-rated prospect in the Detroit Tigers organization. ``It
didn't matter we were Cal State Northridge. We were the best.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gillespie has battled injury in the Angels organization,
Kennedy and Fick have parlayed their CSUN experience to the
precipice of the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Both are expected to contend for major-league jobs when spring
training begins, and right-hander Rob Crabtree, the most dependable
pitcher on that '96 CSUN team, could begin the season as a set-up
man for the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, Crabtree, Fick and Kennedy, a second baseman in St.
Louis' organization, should begin the season at Triple-A. But the
chance of a promotion by summer is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Fick's hitting has impressed the Tigers. He batted .420 his last
season with the Matadors and last season hit .318 with Double-A
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's despair to find a catcher, coupled with Fick's season,
earned him a September call-up to the Tigers, where he hit .364
with three homers in 22 at-bats. It pushed him into contention for
a major-league roster spot _ along with Paul Bako, Joe Siddal and
journeyman catcher Bill Hasselman, who signed with the team last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert is ready to hit at the major-league level, but the
thing to consider is what's best in continuing his development,''
Tigers general manager Randy Smith said. ``It's probably catching
at the Triple-A level. The biggest thing with him is his throwing.
For him to be a front-line major-league catcher, he's got to
improve his throwing. It's a combination of footwork and arm
strength. He does a great job blocking the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kennedy's presented with a different challenge. The
St. Louis Cardinals switched Kennedy from shortstop to second base,
a move that should benefit the 22-year-old since the Cardinals
recently acquired Edgar Renteria from the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kennedy's offseason work program was altered in October
when he separated his left shoulder diving back to first in the
Arizona Fall League. He's hoping to return to the batting cage this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the minor leagues (changing positions) is hard to swallow,
but when you stop and think they're doing it for a reason, then
you're excited about it,'' said Kennedy, who batted .398 with CSUN
in '96. ``I know they think I can play in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second base, it's not simple, but if you can play shortstop
you're not going to have too much of a problem at another
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, 26, has uncanny control and deception, which makes up
for his average major-league fastball. It was at the urging of
Giants director of player personnel Dick Tidrow that Crabtree was
added to the 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   In the Arizona Fall League, the top winter league for prospects,
Crabtree struck out 41 and walked four in 28 innings of relief.
It's why the Giants view Crabtree as a perfect middle-relief guy
who could find himself setting up for closer Rob Nen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see him pitching in the big leagues at some point,''
Tidrow said. ``He can hold runners, field his position, hit spots
and control his pitches. The five pitches he throws, he has control
of each one, and he has guts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-21-98 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
