<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASD-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT CANDIDATES ELECTED TO SECURITIES DEALERS BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two of the four members of an independent slate
representing small broker-dealer firms have been elected to the
National Association of Securities Dealers' 35-member board in the
first contested election in NASD history, the association said at
its annual meeting in Washington Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD is the parent of the Nasdaq-Amex Market Group and NASD
Regulation Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The two newly elected board members are Alan Davidson, president
and founder of Zeus Securities in Jericho, N.Y., and LaRae
Bakerink, vice president and director of compliance of SK
International Securities in La Jolla, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The membership has spoken,'' Davidson said. ``The days of
uncontested elections at the NASD are over.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Davidson has argued that small brokerage firms are
overregulated and underrepresented by the association. There are
roughly 5,500 NASD member firms, each of which has one vote;
approximately 3,500 members voted in the election.
</P>
<P>
   The election was held to fill 12 vacancies on the association's
board. Three open seats were designated for members representing
the brokerage industry; four for candidates outside the industry,
and five for so-called public members. Two of the three vacant
industry seats went to the independent candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson and Ms. Bakerink defeated two NASD nominees, E. David
Coolidge III, chief executive of William Blair &AMP; Co. and a member
of the NASD board since 1996, and James Dimon, who recently
resigned from his position as president of Citigroup. The only
winning NASD industry nominee was Richard Romano, president of
Romano Brothers &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Two independent candidates lost Monday. They were Bill Singer,
an industry candidate who is a partner at the law firm of Singer
Frumento in New York, and a nonindustry candidate, Dan Jamieson,
editor in chief of Registered Representative magazine, a brokerage
industry trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that the NASD serve the balanced
interest of the membership, the issuers and investors, and
ultimately not forget that members pay the bills,'' Davidson said.
``We have to work together to create one membership, not
constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, the association's chairman, said, ``Our board has a
unique governance structure that assures representation to diverse
industry, nonindustry and public members. We welcome diversity and
inclusiveness as a strength in serving the investor and our many
constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members elected to represent the public were:
</P>
<P>
   Former President Gerald Ford, for a term of one year.
</P>
<P>
   For three-year terms:
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Chao, distinguished fellow, the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Duberstein, chairman and chief executive, Duberstein
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kirk, executive-in-residence, Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   John Markese, president, American Association of Individual
Investors.
</P>
<P>
   New nonindustry board members who will serve three-year terms
are:
</P>
<P>
   H. Furlong Baldwin, chairman of the Mercantile Bankshares Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Isenberg, chairman and chief executive of Nabors
Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Rock, principal, Arthur Rock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   James Rothenberg, president, Capital Research and Management Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
