<SLUG> BC-NJ-RADIUM-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE ORDERS WATER SYSTEMS TO REDUCE RADIUM LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ State officials Monday ordered nine public water
systems to take steps to remove radium from the water supply after
new testing methods found radium levels that exceeded federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the elevated levels of naturally occurring radium
did not pose an immediate health threat, but that long-term,
chronic exposure could increase the risk of certain types of
cancer, particularly bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the water systems serve about 60,000 people in Atlantic
and Cumberland Counties in southern New Jersey. The two other
systems are in Sussex County and provide service to about 128
people in a mobile home park and an apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   The elevated levels were found by a new way of testing for
radium 224. Because New Jersey is the first state to use the new
testing method, state and federal officials said that they do not
know how the radium levels here compared with those in other
states. Federal officials are now using the same method on public
water systems in 27 other states. After reviewing the results,
federal officials may consider imposing new regulations requiring
such tests for all public water systems.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey began testing all of it 615 public community water
systems in 1997 after scientists noticed discrepancies in test
results of water sampled from the Toms River section of Dover
Township. Officials were testing the water for contaminants that
may have contributed to a higher incidence of some childhood
cancers in the area. (Researchers have not yet determined the cause
of the unusual cancer rate.)
</P>
<P>
   Because radium 224 has a very short half-life, 3.7 days,
officials determined that they needed to test water samples within
48 hours of being collected. Federal guidelines do not require
testing within a particular time frame, so this radioactive element
decayed before it could normally be detected.
</P>
<P>
   Barker Hamill, chief of the state's Safe Water Division, said
the state has completed sampling at 70 percent of the 615 systems.
Of those systems tested, 413 comply with safe drinking water
radiological standards, and 29 are being closely monitored, in
addition to the nine systems that have been ordered to take action
to remove radium. He said that testing at the remaining 164 systems
will be completed by July.
</P>
<P>
   Hamill said corrective steps include closing contaminated wells
and drilling new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The state's testing did not include private wells. Officials
have previously urged homeowners with private wells to test for
radioactivity and consider adding a water softener or take other
measures to remove the radium.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Evenson, district chief of the U.S. Geological Survey, said
that there were several factors contributing to the elevated levels
in the aquifer in southern New Jersey. Those factors include high
acidity, which strips metals, like radium, and releases it into the
water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
